00:01:22.640 --> 00:01:24.720
-Very well?
-Decently well.

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:28.360
We made a plan to catch up last week,
but we couldn't. So, I've never met her.

00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:29.800
Yeah.

00:01:30.920 --> 00:01:31.920
Never met her.

00:01:32.600 --> 00:01:33.840
Actually, I never met Shantanu also.

00:01:33.920 --> 00:01:35.840
-No, we've only interacted on WhatsApp.
-Yeah.

00:01:35.920 --> 00:01:38.320
-Her brand is doing really well.
-Yes.

00:01:38.400 --> 00:01:39.840
Like, crazy well?

00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:43.440
She is just launching, if I'm not wrong,
in Sephora, US.

00:01:43.520 --> 00:01:45.560
She's doing very well in Sephora, UK.

00:01:45.640 --> 00:01:47.320
She's doing very well in India.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:50.560
So, she's gotten the right markets,
I think.

00:01:50.640 --> 00:01:52.320
Her strategy for, like...

00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:56.640
And, I think, which is great
for, like, any new founder also is...

00:01:57.400 --> 00:02:00.480
She focused very clearly
on, like, one product.

00:02:00.560 --> 00:02:03.240
-Which is?
-Which is her Champi Hair Oil,

00:02:03.320 --> 00:02:06.800
which, I think, is easily, like,
50-55% of her sales.

00:02:07.920 --> 00:02:09.320
What's the price point?

00:02:09.400 --> 00:02:13.200
I think it's about 1,200 to 1,300 rupees,
the big one.

00:02:15.800 --> 00:02:18.280
The big size, I think, the 100ml.

00:02:18.360 --> 00:02:21.320
And then, it's about, I think,
900 for the smaller one.

00:02:21.400 --> 00:02:23.840
-Oil is a tricky market.
-You know? But she...

00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:25.320
Hair oil is a tricky market.

00:02:25.400 --> 00:02:28.000
Her storytelling also has been
really, really good.

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:30.160
Ready? Start.

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:32.040
Is it the crew I know?

00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:33.480
Where are they?

00:02:33.560 --> 00:02:35.880
No, never mind. No, all good.

00:02:37.200 --> 00:02:38.320
Yeah?

00:02:39.120 --> 00:02:40.880
So, I know Bhakti a bit already.

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:42.520
-Because of Bangalore, Bangalore.
-Yeah.

00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:44.280
-The Bangalore connection.
-Yeah.

00:02:44.360 --> 00:02:46.400
Her husband is also a friend.

00:02:46.480 --> 00:02:48.520
He's also a very talented musician,
by the way.

00:02:48.600 --> 00:02:49.600
Yes.

00:02:49.680 --> 00:02:54.080
And he's in a band which practices, like,
200 metres away from my apartment.

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:56.360
-Oh, God.
-And I've been to their jamming sessions.

00:02:56.440 --> 00:02:57.520
-No way!
-Yeah.

00:02:57.600 --> 00:02:59.040
What's his name? What does he do?

00:02:59.120 --> 00:03:00.760
Tejas Goenka,

00:03:00.840 --> 00:03:06.520
and he is currently managing director
of Tally Solutions.

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:10.640
So, it's a family-run,
family-founded company.

00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:14.120
His granddad and his father founded it.

00:03:14.200 --> 00:03:16.000
And it's a software company.

00:03:16.080 --> 00:03:22.720
So, I think India's--
Any small and medium business in India

00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:27.000
will, you know, do all their invoicing,
all their inventory on Tally, right?

00:03:27.080 --> 00:03:29.080
-So, I think--
-We all use Tally.

00:03:29.160 --> 00:03:30.480
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

00:03:30.560 --> 00:03:32.880
It's just... it's become a household name.

00:03:32.960 --> 00:03:37.760
And yeah, I think it's great to see
because I come from a family that's,

00:03:37.840 --> 00:03:42.400
you know, where I've seen my father work
in a professional environment.

00:03:42.480 --> 00:03:45.680
And then, you know,
you kind of get the exposure to see

00:03:45.760 --> 00:03:49.440
someone on the other side, to see how,
you know, you can carry on family legacy.

00:03:49.520 --> 00:03:50.720
And, you know,

00:03:50.800 --> 00:03:53.520
build it into something
that's modern, that's current,

00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:57.120
and also transcend different perspectives.

00:03:57.200 --> 00:03:59.520
Yeah. So, I think-- He's an engineer.

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:04.040
We met in college,
University of Pennsylvania.

00:04:04.120 --> 00:04:07.880
And we were friends,
friends for very long.

00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:09.800
And then, yeah, we got together.

00:04:09.880 --> 00:04:12.440
So, yeah.

00:04:12.520 --> 00:04:14.040
So, he took this on.

00:04:14.120 --> 00:04:15.520
What do you mean "got together"?

00:04:18.600 --> 00:04:21.520
I think we decided that we could do...

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:26.040
we could be a lot more than friends
at another common friend's wedding.

00:04:26.120 --> 00:04:28.040
-So I think that--
-Is it Tally in real life?

00:04:28.120 --> 00:04:29.520
Did you get the parents involved?

00:04:29.600 --> 00:04:31.080
I think the pen-pen connection worked,

00:04:31.160 --> 00:04:32.920
and, yeah,
our parents know each other as well.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:34.720
-So, that was a bonus.
-[Diipa] Cute.

00:04:34.800 --> 00:04:37.000
But it was not a setup.

00:04:37.080 --> 00:04:41.160
So, I like to say that loud and clear.

00:04:41.240 --> 00:04:43.200
And, yeah, so, I think, one day,

00:04:43.280 --> 00:04:46.320
we decided that we've been friends
for long enough.

00:04:46.400 --> 00:04:49.040
-And, yeah.
-We met him in Amsterdam.

00:04:49.120 --> 00:04:51.760
Yeah, I was just telling Nikhil.

00:04:51.840 --> 00:04:54.520
Bhakti and I know each other
from Amsterdam,

00:04:54.600 --> 00:04:56.040
and that's it, we'll stop there.

00:04:56.120 --> 00:04:58.520
-Nothing happened.
-Nothing else happened.

00:04:58.600 --> 00:05:00.520
Nothing else happened.

00:05:00.600 --> 00:05:02.040
Now we have to know. What happened?

00:05:04.120 --> 00:05:06.560
I made them too curious.
Honestly, nothing happened.

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:08.040
We just had a really good time.

00:05:08.120 --> 00:05:11.400
-And we saw Diipa's beautiful home.
-On our boat.

00:05:11.480 --> 00:05:13.400
-And we just had fun.
-Yeah.

00:05:13.480 --> 00:05:14.640
Girls' time.

00:05:14.720 --> 00:05:17.040
How did you get to Amsterdam?
Where did you begin?

00:05:17.120 --> 00:05:18.480
Start with you,

00:05:18.560 --> 00:05:21.520
because I know them, I know her,
but I'm going to get to know you.

00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:23.320
I'm the new kid on the block.

00:05:23.400 --> 00:05:25.840
Yes, Amsterdam.
Okay, let's just, backwards.

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:28.920
So, Punjabi family, born in Delhi.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:31.280
And then, Mom and Dad
were both working very hard,

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:34.320
so, at one point,
they put us in boarding school in Ooty.

00:05:34.400 --> 00:05:36.520
I went to this fantastic...

00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:38.600
I was just talking on the way here as well

00:05:38.680 --> 00:05:40.400
that boarding schools
have a pretty bad rep.

00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:42.600
-Yeah.
-I had the best time.

00:05:42.680 --> 00:05:44.680
And I feel like anybody
who comes to boarding school,

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:46.680
ask them, they've had the best time.

00:05:46.760 --> 00:05:50.680
So, boarding school kid,
it was an international school.

00:05:50.760 --> 00:05:53.400
I didn't speak English, actually,
when I got into the boarding school.

00:05:53.480 --> 00:05:56.960
Hindi was my main language.
And then, now, my Hindi sucks.

00:05:57.600 --> 00:05:59.040
English is the main language.

00:05:59.120 --> 00:06:01.520
I never thought you were
originally from India.

00:06:01.600 --> 00:06:05.000
Yeah, but this boarding school
is literally like Harry Potter.

00:06:05.080 --> 00:06:07.280
You should look it up once.
It's called Hebron School.

00:06:07.360 --> 00:06:10.000
-Okay.
-Do you know the main garden of Ooty?

00:06:10.080 --> 00:06:15.120
You take one side road
and you enter into this insane world.

00:06:15.200 --> 00:06:17.600
And I know maybe I'm, like,
romanticising it now.

00:06:17.680 --> 00:06:22.040
But it, literally-- Our dining hall
had long tables like Harry Potter.

00:06:22.120 --> 00:06:25.240
And we had prefects,
and it was this very British school.

00:06:25.320 --> 00:06:29.760
My teachers were from New Zealand
and Korea and the US.

00:06:29.840 --> 00:06:32.600
And it was this fantastic upbringing.

00:06:32.680 --> 00:06:36.840
So, after that, my mom and dad
started doing business.

00:06:36.920 --> 00:06:39.720
Like, every Punjabi has
a textile business.

00:06:39.800 --> 00:06:43.560
So, we had a textile business,
where we were making ski outfits

00:06:43.640 --> 00:06:46.720
for companies in Switzerland
and in Netherlands.

00:06:46.800 --> 00:06:50.880
And so, when we finished school,
they were like, "Okay,

00:06:50.960 --> 00:06:53.760
"if you want to study anywhere abroad,
it has to be the Netherlands."

00:06:53.840 --> 00:06:57.120
And I'm like,
"Where on earth is the Netherlands?"

00:06:57.800 --> 00:06:59.880
And then, did a little bit of research.

00:06:59.960 --> 00:07:01.560
I'm like, "Oh, my God,
it looks like a sin city.

00:07:01.640 --> 00:07:03.360
I don't know if I want to go there.

00:07:03.440 --> 00:07:06.200
Do they speak English there?
Like, what's going on?"

00:07:06.280 --> 00:07:08.160
Mom and Dad were like,
"No, we have a base there.

00:07:08.240 --> 00:07:09.840
So, if you want to go, you can go there."

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:15.520
Did a little research, found an amazing
Bachelor's kind of university there.

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:21.000
And turned out
it was a really fun experience.

00:07:21.080 --> 00:07:24.760
And as, kind of, you know,
closed off and Christian

00:07:24.840 --> 00:07:28.080
and very rule-abiding
my boarding school was,

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:30.760
Amsterdam was the other opposite.

00:07:30.840 --> 00:07:33.760
So, I always look at my life
in these three phases, almost.

00:07:33.840 --> 00:07:35.560
Like, phase one of me
being a really, like,

00:07:35.640 --> 00:07:37.960
Indian-Indian girl, went to KV.

00:07:38.040 --> 00:07:40.320
Like, spoke Hindi was as, like,

00:07:40.400 --> 00:07:43.280
you know, with the plaits
and oil in my hair type.

00:07:43.360 --> 00:07:44.600
Like, typical.

00:07:44.680 --> 00:07:48.320
Then phase two was basically in Hebron,
where this international world,

00:07:48.400 --> 00:07:50.600
like, just exploded, opened up to me.

00:07:50.680 --> 00:07:53.120
But still, narrow-minded in a way.

00:07:53.680 --> 00:07:56.320
And then, phase three
was Amsterdam, where...

00:07:57.200 --> 00:08:01.960
just every walk of life, every culture,
every open-minded philosophy.

00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:04.840
And I met my husband there,
who you've met, of course.

00:08:05.560 --> 00:08:08.440
And then, I moved to London
to do law for my master's.

00:08:09.560 --> 00:08:13.240
But my husband and I,
at that point, boyfriend, got together.

00:08:14.240 --> 00:08:17.840
And then,
while I was finishing my law school,

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:22.880
Instagram, this world of content creation
or whatever,

00:08:22.960 --> 00:08:24.640
back then, it didn't even have a term.

00:08:24.720 --> 00:08:26.680
It was blogging, I think.

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:30.840
And Instagram was just starting,
that that path kind of found me.

00:08:32.040 --> 00:08:37.440
And then, I decided, very difficultly
in an Indian family, to stop law

00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:40.360
and start "blogging".

00:08:40.440 --> 00:08:43.640
-How long back was this?
-And my mom was like... ten years ago.

00:08:43.720 --> 00:08:46.560
Eleven years ago,
and my mom was like, "Absolutely not.

00:08:46.640 --> 00:08:49.920
What is blogging?
You're an academic student, straight As.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.920
You're not going to get
into this Instagram thing."

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:56.320
And I was like, "Mom, trust me.
The media landscape is changing.

00:08:56.400 --> 00:08:59.040
I can see something in the future
is going to happen here.

00:08:59.800 --> 00:09:01.400
This is the right time, right place.

00:09:01.480 --> 00:09:04.760
I need to be the first mover here.
This is going to be big."

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:09.000
And this was like, heydays of, like,
just beginning Instagram.

00:09:09.080 --> 00:09:10.520
Instagram, yeah.

00:09:10.600 --> 00:09:12.880
-It was literally ten years ago, 2015.
-Yeah.

00:09:13.560 --> 00:09:16.760
And, indeed,
it was right time, right place.

00:09:16.840 --> 00:09:20.840
And I became kind of the first desi
who was globally doing it.

00:09:21.720 --> 00:09:23.960
Made some insane campaigns,

00:09:24.040 --> 00:09:26.880
the face of Maybelline,
the face of Kerastase.

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:29.160
Was on Piccadilly Circus, Times Square.

00:09:29.240 --> 00:09:31.520
Like, every big beauty partnership
happened.

00:09:31.600 --> 00:09:34.720
And then, the pandemic happened.

00:09:37.040 --> 00:09:39.960
And I think I realised
I want more from this journey.

00:09:40.040 --> 00:09:42.600
By then, I'd done it for six years or so.

00:09:42.680 --> 00:09:44.640
Or seven years,
this whole Instagram world.

00:09:45.440 --> 00:09:47.320
As an academic, I was bored.

00:09:47.400 --> 00:09:50.960
I'm like, "Okay, I'm done.
I've taken as many photos as one can

00:09:51.600 --> 00:09:53.720
and done as many videos as one can.

00:09:53.800 --> 00:09:55.360
I need the next challenge."

00:09:55.440 --> 00:09:59.680
And always knew I was going
to get into business, always did.

00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:02.640
Like, Punjabi family, Dad put it in early.

00:10:02.720 --> 00:10:06.120
Like, "You have to get into business.
That's what we do."

00:10:06.200 --> 00:10:07.920
But I think I had it in me, too.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:10.760
Like, at age 12,
I started my first business.

00:10:10.840 --> 00:10:12.400
I can't call it a business.

00:10:12.480 --> 00:10:16.360
But my first little endeavour
was friendship bracelets,

00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:20.760
where I would get my entire class on it,
and we would make friendship bracelets.

00:10:20.840 --> 00:10:23.920
And I would kind of market it,
and they would make it.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:25.920
And so, back then,

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:28.680
already, I knew this was
going to become something,

00:10:28.760 --> 00:10:31.960
this business mind of mine, one day.

00:10:32.040 --> 00:10:34.040
-And now, here we are.
-Nice.

00:10:34.120 --> 00:10:36.520
-Yeah.
-What did you start first?

00:10:36.600 --> 00:10:39.520
-What do you mean?
-In terms of business?

00:10:39.600 --> 00:10:41.960
indē wild is my first business.

00:10:42.040 --> 00:10:45.080
Well, I can consider
the personal brand a business

00:10:45.160 --> 00:10:48.320
in the way of how big the team is,
and how we kind of lead it.

00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:51.520
But I would say indē wild
is my first business.

00:10:51.600 --> 00:10:54.240
-And how long has it been?
-Three and a half years.

00:10:54.320 --> 00:10:55.880
-Nice.
-Yeah, it's been three and a half years.

00:10:55.960 --> 00:10:57.800
What's the first product? Like, the first?

00:10:57.880 --> 00:11:01.000
The first products were our two skin SKUs.

00:11:01.080 --> 00:11:05.480
We had the AM and the PM Serum,
which is basically 12 serums in one.

00:11:05.560 --> 00:11:07.760
And the PM is eight serums in one.

00:11:07.840 --> 00:11:10.800
I call it, like, the T-shirt and jeans
of your skincare,

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:13.800
where you don't need
the 12-step skincare routine.

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:15.680
One product does it all.

00:11:16.920 --> 00:11:21.280
And then, the third one we launched,
which is now the crazy, viral one...

00:11:21.360 --> 00:11:24.520
-I did a little PR for you.
-Yeah.

00:11:24.600 --> 00:11:29.280
...is the Champi Hair Oil,
which has become the household product.

00:11:29.360 --> 00:11:32.280
And what percentage of your business
is India versus outside?

00:11:32.360 --> 00:11:35.000
Yeah, so, that has been crazy.

00:11:35.080 --> 00:11:37.400
So, when we launched
in the first nine months,

00:11:37.480 --> 00:11:42.280
indē wild it became the first brand
to launch in the US, UK, and India.

00:11:42.360 --> 00:11:44.400
Like, that had never been done before.

00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:47.480
And was your content background
a big, like a big steroidal push,

00:11:47.560 --> 00:11:50.480
-to taking it off?
-100%. 100%.

00:11:50.560 --> 00:11:54.800
I always say that having
a community of 2.5 million

00:11:54.880 --> 00:11:56.760
-was the trampoline jump.
-Yeah.

00:11:56.840 --> 00:12:00.640
It gave the boost,
but it's not obviously everything.

00:12:00.720 --> 00:12:01.880
Product matters, yeah.

00:12:01.960 --> 00:12:04.240
And you also built your community,
I think, authentically.

00:12:04.320 --> 00:12:06.040
-Yes. Yes.
-It took that time.

00:12:06.120 --> 00:12:07.600
'Cause you were in the beauty space,

00:12:07.680 --> 00:12:11.280
so I think that's another
fun buzzword, "community".

00:12:11.360 --> 00:12:13.800
Community is everywhere now.

00:12:13.880 --> 00:12:15.800
-And, yeah.
-I really hope my investors hear this.

00:12:15.880 --> 00:12:17.640
They're like,
"Why do you do this podcasting?"

00:12:17.720 --> 00:12:19.840
I'm like, "It really helps.
No one talks about shaving.

00:12:19.920 --> 00:12:22.280
So, I need to be in the centre
of conversation, in some way."

00:12:22.360 --> 00:12:24.800
Because you started
after the business started, right?

00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:26.280
-Yeah, much later.
-Yeah.

00:12:26.360 --> 00:12:28.040
So, they're like,
"Oh, this is like a hobby thing."

00:12:28.120 --> 00:12:31.320
"Are you even serious about..."
I don't have the media budgets

00:12:31.400 --> 00:12:33.280
of a Gillette or a Philips or whatever.

00:12:33.360 --> 00:12:35.240
-Yeah, of course.
-So I need to be centre of conversation.

00:12:35.320 --> 00:12:36.800
This is the lowest thing.
Like, unlike beauty.

00:12:36.880 --> 00:12:39.120
-Absolutely.
-My business has zero conversation.

00:12:39.200 --> 00:12:42.120
When was the last time
you spoke about your razor to anyone?

00:12:42.200 --> 00:12:44.440
Unless it's an investment. No one, no,
men don't talk. Women talk.

00:12:44.520 --> 00:12:46.280
Maybe you should shave
and then people will talk about it.

00:12:47.400 --> 00:12:49.360
Me? I have trimmers and shavers.

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:51.440
So I need to do everything
in this real estate.

00:12:51.520 --> 00:12:53.280
I shave my head and I trim my beard.

00:12:53.360 --> 00:12:56.960
No, but I think the founder face,
the creator face,

00:12:57.040 --> 00:13:00.240
has become such a common thing
in beauty now.

00:13:00.320 --> 00:13:02.680
Like, even Charlotte Tilbury
was just a makeup artist.

00:13:02.760 --> 00:13:05.480
And then, she literally became
the face of her brand.

00:13:05.560 --> 00:13:07.800
And that changed the marketing completely.

00:13:07.880 --> 00:13:10.160
You know, Rihanna, of course, we know.

00:13:10.240 --> 00:13:12.440
Celebrity brands, obviously,
is the face of the brand.

00:13:12.520 --> 00:13:15.040
But even in the US now,

00:13:15.120 --> 00:13:18.120
brands exploding where, their founders,

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:21.120
after starting the brand,
become public people

00:13:21.200 --> 00:13:22.800
and start posting content.

00:13:22.880 --> 00:13:23.920
How could you, like--

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.960
How much of your public persona
has helped Zerodha?

00:13:27.040 --> 00:13:29.280
Especially in an increasingly
competitive world, right?

00:13:30.040 --> 00:13:33.080
Are you seeing, like,
a podcast does well?

00:13:33.160 --> 00:13:36.560
You suddenly get like a ton of views
and then sign-ups go up or...

00:13:37.360 --> 00:13:38.800
I don't know
if there's a direct correlation.

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:40.800
You never thought about it?

00:13:40.880 --> 00:13:45.280
I've thought about it,
but have I been able to measure it? No.

00:13:46.240 --> 00:13:48.280
I hope it goes up.

00:13:48.360 --> 00:13:50.280
-What's your hypothesis?
-Isn't it doing really well already?

00:13:52.240 --> 00:13:56.120
Yeah, podcast is very, like,
non-monetary in nature.

00:13:56.200 --> 00:14:00.800
We don't have advertising
or sponsorship or any of that.

00:14:00.880 --> 00:14:03.000
In fact, I take money
from people who are guests,

00:14:03.080 --> 00:14:05.800
and we do a charity project
at the end of it.

00:14:05.880 --> 00:14:09.680
So, it's the opposite
of a capitalistic venture.

00:14:09.760 --> 00:14:11.720
The outcome,

00:14:11.800 --> 00:14:15.800
we're very much going after
that we want to elicit is,

00:14:15.880 --> 00:14:19.160
somebody goes and starts a business
in what we speak about.

00:14:19.240 --> 00:14:22.440
So, today, for example,
beauty and skincare.

00:14:22.520 --> 00:14:26.280
I hope when this is out,
some young kid or a few of them

00:14:27.880 --> 00:14:29.960
pick up something that you said
and start a business.

00:14:30.040 --> 00:14:31.400
So, today's about that.

00:14:34.240 --> 00:14:38.680
If we can lay out a road-map
of what the opportunity is

00:14:38.760 --> 00:14:41.240
in this industry that is growing
very fast.

00:14:42.200 --> 00:14:48.280
And we will figure out how to give them
the tools they require to solve

00:14:48.360 --> 00:14:51.960
for a bunch of things that you guys
have very successfully solved for.

00:14:52.040 --> 00:14:54.280
Bhakti can help most of all.
She can just sell their product.

00:14:54.360 --> 00:14:55.800
Yeah.

00:14:55.880 --> 00:14:58.760
Right? So, we'll put her phone number
and email at the end of it,

00:14:58.840 --> 00:15:01.280
so thousands of people
can reach out to her.

00:15:01.360 --> 00:15:03.280
-Absolutely.
-Launch them.

00:15:03.360 --> 00:15:05.760
Launch them. Please come, enlist.

00:15:06.360 --> 00:15:08.280
But tell us about you next.

00:15:09.160 --> 00:15:12.480
No, first of all, thank you
for having me here. And, you know...

00:15:12.560 --> 00:15:15.400
So much to learn from all three of you
in very different ways.

00:15:15.480 --> 00:15:16.720
Grew up between...

00:15:16.800 --> 00:15:19.880
So, born in the US, my dad was in IT.

00:15:19.960 --> 00:15:22.560
He was at TCS for many years, and then...

00:15:23.840 --> 00:15:27.640
So, grew up in the US,
Pune, Bangalore, Trivandrum, Pune.

00:15:28.360 --> 00:15:32.400
So, Pune is where I was
from 5th grade to 12th.

00:15:32.480 --> 00:15:34.400
Very cookie-cutter approach to life.

00:15:34.480 --> 00:15:39.480
I went to engineering school in Nagpur,
business school in IIM, Lucknow.

00:15:40.840 --> 00:15:42.720
So, 2005-2011 education,

00:15:42.800 --> 00:15:47.160
joined McKinsey as a consultant in 2011
in the Bombay office.

00:15:47.240 --> 00:15:50.520
-'11 to '16, I was at McKinsey.
-Long working hours?

00:15:50.600 --> 00:15:53.120
Yeah. It was the best first job, man.

00:15:53.200 --> 00:15:54.280
It was the best first job.

00:15:54.360 --> 00:15:57.200
-Is consulting dying?
-Oh, 100%.

00:15:57.280 --> 00:16:00.720
"Dying" is a strong word,
but if you don't evolve...

00:16:00.800 --> 00:16:03.280
What I did ten years back
is completely irrelevant today.

00:16:03.360 --> 00:16:05.160
What can they evolve into?

00:16:07.440 --> 00:16:11.600
I think consultants
were hired for two things.

00:16:11.680 --> 00:16:13.960
And even today,
those two things remain true.

00:16:14.040 --> 00:16:17.280
One is a bottom-up strategic understanding

00:16:17.360 --> 00:16:19.640
of a complex problem
that any business has.

00:16:19.720 --> 00:16:21.640
So, for Tira, for example,
you can say I need to know,

00:16:21.720 --> 00:16:25.520
for example, what's an inventory
versus marketplace model.

00:16:25.600 --> 00:16:27.280
What are the SKUs? What's the growth rate?

00:16:27.360 --> 00:16:31.000
You'll have really sharp analysts,
and they'll probably have AI to help them.

00:16:31.080 --> 00:16:32.520
But you don't need that anymore, right?

00:16:32.600 --> 00:16:33.760
-You do.
-You think?

00:16:33.840 --> 00:16:36.000
-I think so.
-AI doesn't solve for that?

00:16:36.080 --> 00:16:39.000
I don't think AI can help you
frame problems yet.

00:16:39.080 --> 00:16:41.160
A business needs to know
how to frame the problem

00:16:41.240 --> 00:16:44.360
and evolve the framing
of the problem constantly.

00:16:44.440 --> 00:16:46.000
You can't just let them free
for six months.

00:16:46.080 --> 00:16:47.120
Give me a for-instance.

00:16:48.880 --> 00:16:50.080
Let's say Diipa's brand.

00:16:51.840 --> 00:16:53.080
Am I saying that right, Diipa?

00:16:54.080 --> 00:16:57.520
Yeah, it's just because of "I-I-P-A"
name, numerology, my parents.

00:16:57.600 --> 00:16:59.000
Okay.

00:16:59.080 --> 00:17:01.800
Let's say Diipa's brand,
let's say indē wild,

00:17:01.880 --> 00:17:06.520
has to launch a men's business in India.

00:17:06.600 --> 00:17:08.000
Okay.

00:17:08.080 --> 00:17:10.760
And she's like, "Hey, I think
I'm only serving half the market.

00:17:10.840 --> 00:17:14.560
And I think there is a certain amount of

00:17:14.640 --> 00:17:18.440
institutional capability that I can do
to expand into the other half."

00:17:18.520 --> 00:17:20.520
For example, I'm just making this up.

00:17:20.600 --> 00:17:22.840
"I need someone to help me
figure this out."

00:17:22.920 --> 00:17:24.640
So, there's a market expansion.

00:17:24.720 --> 00:17:27.160
Now they'll come back
with, let's say, one-week answer.

00:17:27.240 --> 00:17:29.680
Usually, at McKinsey, it's like, oh,
one-week answer, a two-week answer,

00:17:29.760 --> 00:17:32.520
where you put all the information together
and put a hypothesis.

00:17:32.600 --> 00:17:35.360
At that point,
she has to start helping the team.

00:17:35.440 --> 00:17:38.080
Or her team will have to start
helping the team, figuring out, "Okay,

00:17:38.160 --> 00:17:40.000
we're going to double-click here
because this makes sense."

00:17:40.080 --> 00:17:42.520
But what part of their answer
will be useful to her

00:17:42.600 --> 00:17:45.520
-that she can't find herself online?
-And what can I not do in AI?

00:17:45.600 --> 00:17:48.000
-Yeah.
-Yeah. Like, market research, I can do it.

00:17:48.080 --> 00:17:49.360
For example, I don't know,

00:17:49.440 --> 00:17:51.000
I have not been a consultant
for ten years.

00:17:51.080 --> 00:17:53.600
-Really hard.
-You're putting him on the spot.

00:17:53.680 --> 00:17:55.920
But, for example, I will-- At McKinsey,

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:59.000
we would immediately know the 20 times
this has happened in the world.

00:17:59.080 --> 00:18:03.520
Immediately. We'll get five partners on
the phone from Germany, Amsterdam,

00:18:03.600 --> 00:18:05.520
Brazil, Australia, whatever.

00:18:05.600 --> 00:18:07.880
Play it out like you're enacting it.

00:18:07.960 --> 00:18:09.560
Say, I'm Diipa, I call you up.

00:18:09.640 --> 00:18:14.520
I want to launch a men's brand,
Shantanu calls who and asks what?

00:18:14.600 --> 00:18:19.040
I will find the ten biggest
men's brands expansions,

00:18:19.120 --> 00:18:20.520
like Dove For Men.

00:18:20.600 --> 00:18:23.040
For example, I'll know the guy in Unilever

00:18:23.120 --> 00:18:26.480
who would've done
the Dove to Dove Men expansion

00:18:26.560 --> 00:18:28.760
and spoken to him about,
"How did it work in China?

00:18:28.840 --> 00:18:31.520
How did it work in India?
What are the ten insights you found?

00:18:31.600 --> 00:18:32.960
What were the consumers going through?

00:18:33.040 --> 00:18:34.720
Then I'll come back to Diipa
or I'll come back you and say,

00:18:34.800 --> 00:18:36.760
"Hey, here are the big five things."

00:18:36.840 --> 00:18:41.520
What manufacturing
or supply chain or marketing...

00:18:41.600 --> 00:18:43.000
-So, it's network then?
-...strengths--

00:18:43.080 --> 00:18:45.040
So, the network is a bit.
So, that's the thing.

00:18:45.120 --> 00:18:47.000
There is one part of it which is,

00:18:47.080 --> 00:18:49.960
like, very bottom-up
information gathering and analysis.

00:18:50.040 --> 00:18:54.160
The second part is a counsellor who is

00:18:54.240 --> 00:18:57.160
just someone who is very senior,
who will help you think through things.

00:18:57.240 --> 00:18:58.640
I have seen that happen a lot.

00:18:58.720 --> 00:19:01.360
But generally, not a specialist
and a generalist, right?

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:04.520
'Cause he has never built
a skincare brand.

00:19:04.600 --> 00:19:07.520
-Who?
-Whoever at McKinsey she's talking to.

00:19:07.600 --> 00:19:10.480
No, they've not. Obviously,
never done it themselves,

00:19:10.560 --> 00:19:12.360
but they're close enough
to many people to have...

00:19:12.440 --> 00:19:14.360
It's like a venture capitalist
or an investor, right?

00:19:14.440 --> 00:19:17.000
You have done enough and you're smart
enough to do pattern recognition.

00:19:17.080 --> 00:19:20.560
But if somebody were--
Maybe I invested in a skincare brand,

00:19:20.640 --> 00:19:22.920
but if someone were to ask me
what should I do,

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:24.520
I would be the last person
they should take--

00:19:24.600 --> 00:19:26.600
But if you have invested in
15 skincare brands

00:19:26.680 --> 00:19:28.520
across three fund cycles,
you'll probably have the right answer.

00:19:28.600 --> 00:19:30.320
But then why can't I get this answer

00:19:30.400 --> 00:19:33.360
from my board member
from Unilever Ventures?

00:19:33.440 --> 00:19:34.600
-You know what I mean?
-Yeah.

00:19:34.680 --> 00:19:38.840
That board member,
if she would contact her list of people,

00:19:38.920 --> 00:19:42.000
they would have the same contacts,
they would have the same insight.

00:19:42.080 --> 00:19:45.720
So, math to math,
a board member who's from Unilever,

00:19:45.800 --> 00:19:49.160
would probably cost the same
as a McKinsey team for three months.

00:19:49.240 --> 00:19:51.360
You mean how much
we give away in equity?

00:19:51.440 --> 00:19:53.000
Intellectually, someone's giving you the--

00:19:53.080 --> 00:19:54.520
How much does it cost?
I've never used a consultant.

00:19:54.600 --> 00:19:56.520
But McKinsey doesn't give me money.

00:19:56.600 --> 00:19:58.160
Unilever has given her money.

00:19:58.240 --> 00:20:01.440
No, but, for example,
that's probably what it would cost.

00:20:01.520 --> 00:20:02.640
Like, we think about the--

00:20:02.720 --> 00:20:04.640
Equity returns you're creating
for that individual

00:20:04.720 --> 00:20:06.200
would probably be the same.

00:20:06.280 --> 00:20:07.840
Probably more. He's more invested.

00:20:07.920 --> 00:20:11.000
-Couple of crores a month for a good team.
-Yeah?

00:20:11.920 --> 00:20:14.520
Irrespective of my company size?

00:20:14.600 --> 00:20:15.960
It depends. So, for example,

00:20:16.040 --> 00:20:18.520
-a lot of it...
-How big is your company, Diipa?

00:20:18.600 --> 00:20:20.280
-In?
-Sales?

00:20:20.360 --> 00:20:24.400
So, we're gonna cross 100 crores in net.

00:20:24.480 --> 00:20:25.640
And I need to talk in net,

00:20:25.720 --> 00:20:28.000
because I think there's a lot of stuff
in the press

00:20:28.080 --> 00:20:31.000
with GMVs and ARRs and everything else.

00:20:31.080 --> 00:20:33.800
-What do you mean by "net"?
-Net sales after everything is taken out.

00:20:33.880 --> 00:20:35.520
So, net of discounts, returns,
and cancellations.

00:20:35.600 --> 00:20:37.000
It's what the accountant
will say is her revenue.

00:20:37.080 --> 00:20:39.000
Net of what you pay
a distributor, for example.

00:20:39.080 --> 00:20:40.480
-No.
-[Shantanu] Yes.

00:20:40.560 --> 00:20:42.480
-Yeah, yeah, yes.
-Yes. It's the invoice value.

00:20:42.560 --> 00:20:44.160
-Invoice value.
-[Bhakti] Invoice value.

00:20:44.240 --> 00:20:47.400
Back to my story,
I was at McKinsey for five years.

00:20:47.480 --> 00:20:50.320
-Started Bombay Shaving Company in 2016--
-Also, before I forget, another question.

00:20:50.400 --> 00:20:55.840
What are multiples in a business
like this or that today?

00:20:55.920 --> 00:20:58.120
-Is it 4x, 5x? Yeah.
-Valuation multiples?

00:20:58.200 --> 00:20:59.720
So, this is a good part, right?

00:20:59.800 --> 00:21:03.920
Four to five times revenue
if you're growing 40% year on year?

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:05.000
If you're growing 20%?

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:07.520
-Three to four.
-Really?

00:21:07.600 --> 00:21:09.520
-No, I think it's...
-I've heard differently.

00:21:09.600 --> 00:21:11.880
Yeah, it can be anywhere between...

00:21:11.960 --> 00:21:15.440
It really depends on what category
you are in as well because...

00:21:15.520 --> 00:21:18.280
So, in beauty, personal care?
There is a...

00:21:18.360 --> 00:21:21.680
There is-- The moment of transition
is when you become profitable.

00:21:22.360 --> 00:21:24.840
When you start going from
four times revenue, five times revenue,

00:21:24.920 --> 00:21:27.440
to 40 times forward EBITDA.

00:21:27.520 --> 00:21:29.880
-I've heard of cases...
-That's the transition.

00:21:29.960 --> 00:21:33.920
...with, like, five to six times on ARR.

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:36.440
Five to six times on revenue
is very common as well right now.

00:21:36.520 --> 00:21:37.520
But what's the growth rate?

00:21:37.600 --> 00:21:39.240
You won't value...
Who gets valued at that?

00:21:39.320 --> 00:21:40.440
How much is Emami valued at?

00:21:40.520 --> 00:21:41.840
How much did Minimalist get valued at?

00:21:41.920 --> 00:21:45.440
Hailey Bieber just... Hailey Bieber
just got her company valued at that.

00:21:45.520 --> 00:21:47.440
Hailey Bieber was at four, though.

00:21:47.520 --> 00:21:49.440
-She was at four and a half, five.
-No, babe.

00:21:49.520 --> 00:21:50.920
Minimalists was a very unique case.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:52.160
-She made 200 million.
-[Bhakti] Yeah.

00:21:52.240 --> 00:21:54.400
-And then, she only got 800 now, right?
-And then, one billion.

00:21:54.480 --> 00:21:55.840
No, her growth was valued at one billion.

00:21:55.920 --> 00:21:57.920
The other one is going to be
in three years, I think.

00:21:58.760 --> 00:22:00.000
Overall, got valued at one.

00:22:00.080 --> 00:22:01.080
-[Diipa] Overall.
-Okay. Yeah.

00:22:01.160 --> 00:22:04.920
So, but it is between 4x and 5x of...

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:06.080
-Revenue.
-Yeah.

00:22:06.160 --> 00:22:09.440
And I would imagine India is a bit more
because the beauty industry is exploding.

00:22:09.520 --> 00:22:11.360
Exploding, and it's also smaller, right?

00:22:11.440 --> 00:22:13.360
When you're at smaller scale,
you can grow faster...

00:22:13.440 --> 00:22:15.440
-[Diipa] Exactly.
-...and you will get a higher multiple.

00:22:15.520 --> 00:22:17.960
And to your question, Minimalist,

00:22:18.040 --> 00:22:20.440
don't quote me on this,
but I think seven or eight.

00:22:20.520 --> 00:22:22.920
You're on a podcast.
You're going to get quoted for sure.

00:22:25.520 --> 00:22:28.000
-Quote me on them, I think.
-No, but it's public information.

00:22:28.080 --> 00:22:30.400
There were 480 crores top-line,
3,000 crores net value.

00:22:30.480 --> 00:22:32.920
-Unilever really wanted that business.
-Yeah.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:34.440
And there are...

00:22:34.520 --> 00:22:36.000
I was reviewing their business
to invest, you know.

00:22:36.080 --> 00:22:38.440
And I negotiated with them so hard.

00:22:38.520 --> 00:22:39.920
At what stage?

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:41.320
-Like, a year before this deal.
-[Bhakti] Wow.

00:22:41.400 --> 00:22:42.600
A year and a half before this deal.

00:22:42.680 --> 00:22:44.240
So that was not a...
Like, it would not have been...

00:22:44.320 --> 00:22:46.440
The venture capital is not super happy
with the outcome.

00:22:46.520 --> 00:22:49.440
-No, it was a 40% markup from there.
-Yeah.

00:22:50.480 --> 00:22:53.040
-Yeah. Which is still something. 40-50%.
-Of course. Of course.

00:22:53.120 --> 00:22:54.920
50% in one year is great.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:57.640
But I still couldn't digest the valuation
when---

00:22:57.720 --> 00:23:01.680
I spent, I think, two, three days
with them on the phone,

00:23:01.760 --> 00:23:04.440
but I couldn't make my...
make up my mind to...

00:23:04.520 --> 00:23:08.320
See, there, at least my view outside in,
there is a lot of things at play, right?

00:23:08.400 --> 00:23:11.200
Unilever is struggling to premiumise.

00:23:11.280 --> 00:23:14.920
All of their brands, Dove, Ponds,
Fair &amp; Lovely, everything is mass.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:16.760
-But Minimalist is not premium.
-Very premium.

00:23:16.840 --> 00:23:18.680
-Premium?
-Compared to their portfolio?

00:23:18.760 --> 00:23:20.920
No, it's... Minimalist is masstige.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:22.200
-Like it's... It's masstige.
-Masstige.

00:23:22.280 --> 00:23:24.920
Compared to their portfolio, compared
to the average Unilever price point...

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:27.920
-Why? Lakmē?
-Lakmē is a very smart buy, right?

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:29.440
Okay, another good question for you guys.

00:23:29.520 --> 00:23:31.400
Yeah, but if you're talking about
beauty per se,

00:23:31.480 --> 00:23:33.440
this falls between the purview
of beauty and...

00:23:33.520 --> 00:23:36.680
Yeah, it is kind of between
L'Oréal and Unilever,

00:23:36.760 --> 00:23:38.480
so it was up for Unilever.

00:23:38.560 --> 00:23:43.440
And new CEO wanting to get into this--

00:23:43.520 --> 00:23:46.720
-I felt it was... It was one of those...
-What is premium?

00:23:46.800 --> 00:23:48.440
What is mass-premium?

00:23:49.200 --> 00:23:50.920
I think Bhakti is a good one
to answer that.

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:56.440
I think anything over 1,000 rupees is...
1,000 to 1,500 is premium.

00:23:56.520 --> 00:23:58.920
-Anything over 2,300...
-Luxury?

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:03.440
2,300 to 2,500 is prestige/luxury.

00:24:04.480 --> 00:24:06.440
And everything below?

00:24:06.520 --> 00:24:07.920
Everything below is mass.

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:10.880
-Which is so crazy because...
-Between mass and masstige.

00:24:10.960 --> 00:24:12.080
-Yeah.
-So, you can take

00:24:12.160 --> 00:24:15.840
anything between 700-1,000 as masstige

00:24:15.920 --> 00:24:21.000
and varies about plus-minus 100 rupees on

00:24:21.080 --> 00:24:24.120
different categories,
and then anything below that is mass.

00:24:24.200 --> 00:24:26.720
So, we're still playing
very, very value...

00:24:26.800 --> 00:24:28.440
-Heavily, yeah.
-Heavily in value.

00:24:28.520 --> 00:24:30.920
And we're talking skincare plus cosmetics.

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:32.280
So, how we...

00:24:32.360 --> 00:24:35.240
Just plainly
how we would categorise beauty

00:24:35.320 --> 00:24:37.680
is just four key main categories.

00:24:37.760 --> 00:24:41.840
Skincare, fragrance, hair-care,
and makeup.

00:24:41.920 --> 00:24:44.080
-Colour cosmetics.
-Okay.

00:24:44.160 --> 00:24:48.480
So, these are four key beauty categories,
and then everything else is personal care.

00:24:48.560 --> 00:24:51.920
So, soap, you will classify
as personal care,

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:55.920
but shower gel and shower oil,
again, you will classify as...

00:24:57.280 --> 00:24:59.440
You'll put it in beauty.

00:24:59.520 --> 00:25:01.440
And skincare is the largest?

00:25:01.520 --> 00:25:03.480
No, actually, colour cosmetics
is always the largest.

00:25:03.560 --> 00:25:04.920
-Colour is largest.
-Always.

00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:06.920
But, you know,
they're going kind of neck and neck.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:09.760
-It's going neck and neck.
-Because the lines are also blurring.

00:25:09.840 --> 00:25:11.920
I think, in the past,
colour has always been the biggest.

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:13.440
Always dominated. Yeah.

00:25:13.520 --> 00:25:14.920
Because it's the Estées
and L'Oréals of the world.

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:16.920
-Exactly.
-The lipsticks, the mascaras.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:18.280
It's always been the biggest.

00:25:18.360 --> 00:25:21.800
-Skincare, I think, has been a recent...
-Dark horse. Yeah.

00:25:21.880 --> 00:25:24.520
Recent one where, I think...

00:25:24.600 --> 00:25:27.120
I think maybe Glossier might have
started that trend, in a way,

00:25:27.200 --> 00:25:28.640
of, like, really skinifying.

00:25:28.720 --> 00:25:31.920
Just to qualify, when I think skincare,
I'm thinking moisturiser, sunscreen.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:33.280
-Correct.
-We're talking about that, right?

00:25:33.360 --> 00:25:35.080
This is a very... so, I'm very curious.

00:25:35.160 --> 00:25:37.760
So, for example, for men,

00:25:37.840 --> 00:25:39.920
these numbers are very different
for the categories I operate in.

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:41.600
No, I think we'll stick to women first

00:25:41.680 --> 00:25:43.880
because I'm guessing
majority of the market is that.

00:25:43.960 --> 00:25:45.440
Right? Like, 80%?

00:25:45.520 --> 00:25:47.920
-Yes, but changing.
-But changing. But changing.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:49.440
-Yeah.
-[Bhakti] Yeah.

00:25:49.520 --> 00:25:53.480
So, I think skincare is maybe... the past

00:25:54.520 --> 00:25:58.400
seven, six, seven years
really took a, like, upward trend.

00:25:58.480 --> 00:26:03.000
I think, yeah, the last 7-10 years
has been very good on skincare.

00:26:03.080 --> 00:26:05.680
And I think the way we define beauty

00:26:05.760 --> 00:26:10.880
has also really changed the concept
of, you know, adoption of skincare, right?

00:26:10.960 --> 00:26:12.960
Because I think beauty...

00:26:13.040 --> 00:26:14.800
Beauty has gone through this journey

00:26:14.880 --> 00:26:19.680
where it was all about
looking good, external validation.

00:26:19.760 --> 00:26:23.960
You know, we've all seen the ads,
where you put on a red lipstick

00:26:24.040 --> 00:26:26.760
or you put on Fair &amp; Lovely,

00:26:26.840 --> 00:26:30.400
and then you go get the next guy,
get the best guy, get the best job,

00:26:30.480 --> 00:26:32.840
you win a reality TV show,

00:26:32.920 --> 00:26:35.880
and then that was all about
really dominating makeup, right?

00:26:35.960 --> 00:26:39.760
Because it was about enhancing
or making yourself look better.

00:26:39.840 --> 00:26:41.480
So, it was not really...

00:26:41.560 --> 00:26:44.400
It was about getting external validation
and also telling yourself that,

00:26:44.480 --> 00:26:46.840
"I need to have all of this
to become better."

00:26:46.920 --> 00:26:49.200
Then it went on, like,

00:26:49.280 --> 00:26:51.320
I think, the space that...

00:26:51.400 --> 00:26:54.920
When skincare really took off
was all about, you know,

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:56.800
taking care of your skin,

00:26:56.880 --> 00:26:59.600
making sure that, you know,
you want to take care of yourself.

00:26:59.680 --> 00:27:00.840
And we're kind of there.

00:27:00.920 --> 00:27:03.600
But now, we've moved
into the self-expression zone.

00:27:03.680 --> 00:27:08.440
So, beauty is all about self-expression
and whatever that means to you.

00:27:08.520 --> 00:27:09.920
-Right?
-That comes in the makeup.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:13.280
That is where the journey
from makeup, you know,

00:27:13.360 --> 00:27:14.840
makeup dominating beauty when...

00:27:14.920 --> 00:27:18.080
Whenever, you know,
even when we do work with ad agencies,

00:27:18.160 --> 00:27:23.320
a lot of them,
they only look at beauty as makeup.

00:27:23.400 --> 00:27:25.880
Like, that's how it went hand in hand.

00:27:25.960 --> 00:27:30.040
And you kind of started, you know,
you ignore all the other categories.

00:27:30.120 --> 00:27:35.200
If you look at the services industry,
on the other hand, it's all about hair.

00:27:35.280 --> 00:27:38.400
So, skin and makeup services are not huge.

00:27:38.480 --> 00:27:40.440
-70%.
-Wait, that comes under this?

00:27:40.520 --> 00:27:44.440
So, services is also beauty, right?
Like hair services.

00:27:44.520 --> 00:27:46.920
-A salon...
-[Bhakti] Like a salon.

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:49.440
70% is all about hair. But when you're...

00:27:49.520 --> 00:27:51.920
Well, I wouldn't consider salon
under the beauty pyramid, would you?

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:55.280
Yeah. I mean, it's still--
you're still selling...

00:27:55.360 --> 00:27:57.320
you're still selling product there, right?

00:27:57.400 --> 00:27:58.440
Like a Kerastase.

00:27:58.520 --> 00:28:00.440
You're talking about
the products sold at a salon.

00:28:00.520 --> 00:28:02.440
-[Diipa] Not the treatment.
-No, not the treatments.

00:28:02.520 --> 00:28:03.920
But it's still consumption, no?

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:06.920
But it's still consumption
on how people think differently.

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:09.920
Is that a big part of consumption? Salons?

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:11.680
-Salons is huge.
-[Diipa] Used to be. Used to be, I think.

00:28:11.760 --> 00:28:13.720
In India, particularly,

00:28:13.800 --> 00:28:17.560
all professional haircare brands
have started in salons.

00:28:17.640 --> 00:28:19.520
If you look at Kerastase,

00:28:19.600 --> 00:28:23.440
they do majority of their business
still through salons because...

00:28:23.520 --> 00:28:27.440
And what does it take to crack a salon?
Like, if I am a new brand like Kerastase?

00:28:27.520 --> 00:28:31.720
So, India is very fragmented
even on the salon space.

00:28:31.800 --> 00:28:35.680
So, you will have, like,
eight to ten big brands

00:28:35.760 --> 00:28:38.880
that are dominating
different markets, right?

00:28:38.960 --> 00:28:42.480
Like the North or the West or the South,

00:28:42.560 --> 00:28:46.480
and you have to actually
be able to strike a deal.

00:28:46.560 --> 00:28:49.120
For example, and it's...

00:28:49.200 --> 00:28:52.040
A Kerastase, if they go into any salon,

00:28:52.120 --> 00:28:55.920
they don't allow
any other brand to be there.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:29:00.440
Is it like in a pharmacy
where you pay rent to get shelf space?

00:29:00.520 --> 00:29:01.840
It's a lot more than that.

00:29:03.640 --> 00:29:06.760
You have to give them products
that you can use on a service.

00:29:06.840 --> 00:29:09.840
So, you basically craft
an entire treatment menu

00:29:09.920 --> 00:29:11.440
with your product,

00:29:11.520 --> 00:29:14.440
and then that's how you
actually sell your product.

00:29:14.520 --> 00:29:16.960
Because it's all about
the after-sales service

00:29:17.040 --> 00:29:18.560
and after-sales purchase, right?

00:29:18.640 --> 00:29:23.600
So, if I like a product,
if I go to my hair stylist who I trust,

00:29:23.680 --> 00:29:25.440
because, again, beauty is all about trust

00:29:25.520 --> 00:29:28.600
and, you know, believing in someone
who you believe is an expert.

00:29:28.680 --> 00:29:31.280
So, when I go to them,
and, you know, my hair stylist says,

00:29:31.360 --> 00:29:34.080
"Your hair is falling,
why don't you use this serum,

00:29:35.240 --> 00:29:39.080
and let me let me use it
after I shampoo your hair before blow dry.

00:29:39.160 --> 00:29:40.200
This is how you use it.

00:29:40.280 --> 00:29:43.520
And, oh, you know,
the weather is really dry outside.

00:29:43.600 --> 00:29:46.560
So, maybe you should try
this shampoo that's moisturising

00:29:46.640 --> 00:29:50.920
and that will make your hair,
you know, hold well in this weather."

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:55.440
And then, at the end of it,
he's used all of that on me.

00:29:55.520 --> 00:29:57.760
And then he'll be like,
"Listen, do you want to buy it?"

00:29:57.840 --> 00:29:59.720
And I'm like, "Oh, I really like my hair."

00:29:59.800 --> 00:30:02.440
'Cause, again,
then it goes back to validation.

00:30:02.520 --> 00:30:06.200
Does a salon optimise
for best quality product

00:30:06.280 --> 00:30:08.440
or the highest kickback or margins?

00:30:09.760 --> 00:30:13.360
Definitely.
I think it's a mix of both, right?

00:30:13.440 --> 00:30:16.680
Because you also want people
to keep coming back to you.

00:30:16.760 --> 00:30:17.920
So, it's the--

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:20.920
But if it's like you said,
a brand just takes over

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:22.440
and says no other brand,

00:30:22.520 --> 00:30:24.520
then I guess you're only serving
the client one brand.

00:30:24.600 --> 00:30:27.120
And that's why, now,
a lot of salons are also saying,

00:30:27.200 --> 00:30:30.040
"No, we don't mind
having three or four brands

00:30:30.120 --> 00:30:32.720
because they cater
to all different kinds of products.

00:30:32.800 --> 00:30:34.240
Like curly hair.

00:30:34.320 --> 00:30:36.160
It's huge,
but we never speak about curly hair.

00:30:36.240 --> 00:30:39.720
Like, it's a whole segment in itself,
booming segment in itself.

00:30:39.800 --> 00:30:43.320
And it's just been started
getting addressed now.

00:30:43.400 --> 00:30:47.240
So, that pattern is breaking out.
And I think that's great.

00:30:47.320 --> 00:30:51.920
Like, I've discovered a lot of brands,
even international brands, through salons,

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:53.520
because they come in
through a distributor.

00:30:53.600 --> 00:30:55.720
So, you can work with the distributor

00:30:55.800 --> 00:30:58.920
who'll have all the best
salon connections.

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:01.920
Go to them saying,
"Listen, I want to distribute my brand."

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:03.720
They'll probably connect you to...

00:31:03.800 --> 00:31:05.680
If it's a small one, to ten salons,

00:31:05.760 --> 00:31:08.200
if it's, you know,
your brand is growing bigger,

00:31:08.280 --> 00:31:10.440
then to a chain of salons.

00:31:10.520 --> 00:31:13.800
So, I think my experience
has been a little bit different.

00:31:13.880 --> 00:31:17.280
Obviously, indē wild's hair products
are our best-selling.

00:31:17.360 --> 00:31:19.600
We're number one on Nykaa,
number one on Tira,

00:31:19.680 --> 00:31:25.960
and we're beating out salon brands
like Kerastase, like Olaplex, like others,

00:31:26.040 --> 00:31:30.200
I don't know the names of all of them,
that really are salon-first brands.

00:31:30.280 --> 00:31:31.840
And I think there is a change,

00:31:31.920 --> 00:31:35.200
and I'd say, specifically,
double-clicking into Gen Z,

00:31:35.280 --> 00:31:38.600
where they want that
salon experience at home.

00:31:38.680 --> 00:31:41.720
They want it fast, they want it quick,
they want to do it themselves,

00:31:41.800 --> 00:31:48.240
but they want the level of that expertise
and ingredients and salon-like feeling,

00:31:48.320 --> 00:31:49.960
but to be able to do it themselves.

00:31:50.040 --> 00:31:51.840
And so, when you notice,

00:31:51.920 --> 00:31:54.600
even if you look at the new shampoos
that are coming out,

00:31:54.680 --> 00:31:56.600
everything is so intelligent now.

00:31:56.680 --> 00:32:01.520
Everything has to be bond repair
and peptides and proteins,

00:32:01.600 --> 00:32:04.120
and ingredients-led
that the customer feels like,

00:32:04.200 --> 00:32:08.640
"Why would I go to a salon and spend 4,000
on getting the hair done first,

00:32:08.720 --> 00:32:10.200
then get fed these thingies,

00:32:10.280 --> 00:32:14.080
when I can get it quickly from Tira
by the next morning?

00:32:14.160 --> 00:32:16.560
And it claims to have all the same things,

00:32:16.640 --> 00:32:19.040
plus the influencer
who's talking to me about it

00:32:19.120 --> 00:32:22.120
has said you get the same effects,
I can see the before and afters."

00:32:22.200 --> 00:32:24.520
I feel like consumers...

00:32:24.600 --> 00:32:27.880
Maybe the salon is still very important
for, maybe, the millennials,

00:32:27.960 --> 00:32:30.920
and perhaps our aunties
and our moms and stuff.

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:33.040
Yeah, the older generation, absolutely.

00:32:33.120 --> 00:32:34.920
But Gen Z is a lot more like,
"I need it now."

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:36.920
-Instant gratification.
-Yeah, exactly.

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:38.440
They want it now, they want it all.

00:32:38.520 --> 00:32:41.640
I also think salons are good for sampling.

00:32:41.720 --> 00:32:44.520
So, the thing that makes brands work
in salons,

00:32:44.600 --> 00:32:46.920
and I think L'Oréal
is a fantastic example of this,

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:50.280
is they're able to get a SKU assortment,
which is larger.

00:32:50.360 --> 00:32:52.440
So, they'll do like 500mls and one litres

00:32:52.520 --> 00:32:55.360
and shaving foams, they'll do, like,
a two-kilo pack, stuff like that.

00:32:55.440 --> 00:32:57.080
VI-JOHN will do a good job with that.

00:32:57.160 --> 00:32:59.200
The customer
and the consumer are different.

00:32:59.280 --> 00:33:01.720
So, the customer is the stylist.

00:33:01.800 --> 00:33:03.440
The consumer is the person
he's doing it on.

00:33:03.520 --> 00:33:06.280
So, the consumer probably gets it done
the first time

00:33:06.360 --> 00:33:07.760
and then will come to a Tira
and say, "Okay..."

00:33:07.840 --> 00:33:09.320
-As a second purchase.
-Exactly.

00:33:09.400 --> 00:33:10.960
-Go on YouTube and say "how to do this".
-Yeah.

00:33:11.040 --> 00:33:12.880
"How much is it on Tira?"
And then they do it themselves.

00:33:12.960 --> 00:33:15.440
Do they look for the same brand
when they're on Tira?

00:33:15.520 --> 00:33:19.120
Often-times. The second thing that
I think really good salon-first brands do

00:33:19.200 --> 00:33:21.440
is they invest a lot in training.

00:33:21.520 --> 00:33:22.920
-Training.
-[Bhakti] Yes, training.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:25.160
They do a lot of, like, these...
they'll have massive teachers,

00:33:25.240 --> 00:33:27.160
they'll go into these academies.

00:33:27.240 --> 00:33:29.000
They'll call 50 stylists in one go,

00:33:29.080 --> 00:33:31.440
keep them for a week,
like, take them through it.

00:33:31.520 --> 00:33:34.960
So, now, there's a product
which is assorted for a salon,

00:33:35.040 --> 00:33:37.080
then there is a stylist
who's trained to use that product

00:33:37.160 --> 00:33:39.120
to the optimum performance.

00:33:39.200 --> 00:33:41.400
Then the consumer leaves the salon saying,
"Hey, that was fucking amazing."

00:33:41.480 --> 00:33:42.920
-Exactly.
-"Now, I want to come and see

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:44.440
how much it is for it."

00:33:44.520 --> 00:33:46.920
And then, the repeat goes on
to, you know, any platform,

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:49.960
they go on to a Tira and they're like,
"Okay, now, we keep buying it."

00:33:50.040 --> 00:33:52.120
And again, going back
to what Diipa said, right?

00:33:52.200 --> 00:33:54.920
I think the Gen Zs are
a lot more comfortable

00:33:55.000 --> 00:33:56.280
figuring it out for themselves.

00:33:56.360 --> 00:33:59.440
I think the millennials
and, you know, all the...

00:34:00.240 --> 00:34:02.960
everyone older than that
is very used to getting it done.

00:34:03.040 --> 00:34:05.000
So, they feel
a lot more comfortable saying,

00:34:05.080 --> 00:34:07.200
"Okay, my stylist has said this,
so, I'll get it." You know?

00:34:07.280 --> 00:34:08.440
"Now, I feel comfortable."

00:34:08.520 --> 00:34:10.440
And I think who we look
as experts has changed.

00:34:10.520 --> 00:34:11.520
Exactly.

00:34:11.600 --> 00:34:14.440
Like, I think millennials look at experts
as the trichologists,

00:34:14.520 --> 00:34:16.640
dermatologists, like, salon...

00:34:16.720 --> 00:34:18.800
-Yes.
-...hairdressers.

00:34:18.880 --> 00:34:20.440
And the Gen Z is looking at influencers...

00:34:20.520 --> 00:34:23.920
-KOLs.
-...you know, KOLs as their experts.

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:26.200
-What is KOL?
-Key Opinion Leaders.

00:34:26.280 --> 00:34:30.040
Would you want your brand
to be in salons at some point?

00:34:30.120 --> 00:34:32.040
Have you thought about, like,
a salon range?

00:34:32.120 --> 00:34:33.760
I think, I mean,
indē wild is such a, like,

00:34:33.840 --> 00:34:38.000
wellness, Ayurvedic,
like, I can see that happen,

00:34:38.080 --> 00:34:40.200
especially I think
our Champi Hair Oil, like, you know,

00:34:40.280 --> 00:34:43.880
reinventing the champi
in this really cool hair treatment way.

00:34:43.960 --> 00:34:47.080
I can see it, but I think, at this point,

00:34:47.160 --> 00:34:51.520
we're good with our online
and, like, our retailers,

00:34:51.600 --> 00:34:55.840
and I think next step, perhaps,
could be more spa-led first, perhaps,

00:34:55.920 --> 00:34:58.440
and then the phase after that
could be salon.

00:34:58.520 --> 00:35:01.640
-Diipa has really nice hair.
-Thank you.

00:35:01.720 --> 00:35:03.920
You need to get my oil.
I need to send it to you.

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:05.440
I will send you my oil.

00:35:05.520 --> 00:35:07.920
-Do you oil every day?
-No. That would be crazy.

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:09.440
[laughter]

00:35:09.520 --> 00:35:11.840
I oil, usually, once a week.

00:35:11.920 --> 00:35:14.200
We call it Sunday champi.

00:35:14.280 --> 00:35:16.440
That's kind of the thing
we've made with our brand,

00:35:16.520 --> 00:35:19.120
where, every Sunday,
our community champis with us.

00:35:19.760 --> 00:35:22.120
Girls go to Pilates
with oil in their hair.

00:35:22.200 --> 00:35:23.920
Girls go to groceries
with oil in their hair.

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:27.920
I've worked out with her
Champi Hair Oil on a Sunday.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:30.520
-And you keep it on all day?
-No.

00:35:30.600 --> 00:35:32.960
You keep it on for an hour, two hours,
and then you wash it out.

00:35:33.040 --> 00:35:36.160
It's almost, honestly,
it has become a movement of sorts

00:35:36.240 --> 00:35:40.080
with the Gen Z because this thing,
the champi, the hair oiling,

00:35:40.160 --> 00:35:42.160
was a PTSD to all of us growing up.

00:35:42.240 --> 00:35:44.720
-Yes.
-I mean, I hated it.

00:35:44.800 --> 00:35:47.280
Like, you would have
to go to school with it.

00:35:47.360 --> 00:35:49.920
-It would stink. It would be heavy.
-Plait your hair, yeah.

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:52.720
You just didn't like
the experience of oiling your hair.

00:35:52.800 --> 00:35:55.600
And especially if you go abroad with it,
you would be made fun of.

00:35:55.680 --> 00:35:57.920
So, Indians abroad, Indians in India,

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:02.640
all of us together have this
really bad experience of hair oiling.

00:36:02.720 --> 00:36:05.920
And what indē wild did
is we took that very same experience,

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:08.160
turned it on its head, and made it cool.

00:36:08.240 --> 00:36:10.840
And now, there's this clean girl aesthetic

00:36:10.920 --> 00:36:13.960
where it's all about slick back
and up-dos.

00:36:14.040 --> 00:36:16.080
-Do it with the Champi Oil.
-That's--

00:36:16.160 --> 00:36:17.320
Yeah. And so, it's become like...

00:36:17.400 --> 00:36:19.320
Instead of using a wax or a gel,

00:36:19.400 --> 00:36:22.320
use this oil
that is really good for your hair

00:36:22.400 --> 00:36:24.960
while you do a cool style with it.

00:36:25.040 --> 00:36:28.240
And then, really treat your hair
every Sunday,

00:36:28.320 --> 00:36:30.480
and the before and afters
speak for themselves.

00:36:30.560 --> 00:36:34.920
We were ideating a jewellery brand
recently with lab-grown jewellery,

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:36.880
lab-grown diamonds,

00:36:36.960 --> 00:36:39.680
and two people we were consulting,

00:36:39.760 --> 00:36:42.000
Kishore and Santosh Biyani.

00:36:43.560 --> 00:36:46.920
They were talking about
how the youth is buying,

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:49.680
not a new product altogether,

00:36:49.760 --> 00:36:53.480
-but they're buying re-imagined old.
-[Shantanu] Yeah.

00:36:53.560 --> 00:36:55.240
Is that something
that's working for Champi,

00:36:55.320 --> 00:36:57.000
and do you agree with that analysis?

00:36:57.080 --> 00:36:59.680
I think, 100%, for the brand, as a whole.

00:36:59.760 --> 00:37:03.600
indē wild, I think,
really resonates with the new India

00:37:03.680 --> 00:37:08.480
because we just take
age-old Nani's remedies,

00:37:08.560 --> 00:37:11.280
scientifically back it,
make it super cool,

00:37:11.360 --> 00:37:13.040
and bring it out again.

00:37:13.120 --> 00:37:19.320
And I think it's definitely that
nostalgic element that our products give

00:37:19.400 --> 00:37:22.520
while it being something really cool
to show off to your friends.

00:37:22.600 --> 00:37:26.000
Like, our Dewy Lip Treatments,
they're our lip balms, Bhakti loves them.

00:37:26.080 --> 00:37:29.080
-The Rose.
-Yeah, the Rose.

00:37:29.160 --> 00:37:30.840
They basically have ghee in it.

00:37:30.920 --> 00:37:33.400
Could you ever imagine
a lip balm with ghee in it?

00:37:33.480 --> 00:37:35.200
And it is the talk of the town.

00:37:35.280 --> 00:37:39.040
Like, you go to Soho House,
every girl has it on her table.

00:37:39.120 --> 00:37:42.000
They have it locked to their bags.
They have it locked to their jeans.

00:37:42.080 --> 00:37:44.480
-Really?
-And it's ghee in a lip balm.

00:37:44.560 --> 00:37:46.360
But it's so funny
because when I was growing up,

00:37:46.440 --> 00:37:47.920
my mom would tell me, "Eat a date,"

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:50.760
and she would put ghee inside it.

00:37:50.840 --> 00:37:52.360
And she's like,
"Eat it, and whatever's left,

00:37:52.440 --> 00:37:54.480
just put it on your lips."

00:37:54.560 --> 00:37:58.080
And I've grown up, literally, with that.

00:37:58.160 --> 00:38:00.480
Like, you know, put ghee on your lips
so they don't chap.

00:38:00.560 --> 00:38:02.960
-Yeah, exactly.
-Can we establish market size?

00:38:03.040 --> 00:38:05.120
You said skincare,
makeup, hair, and fragrance.

00:38:05.200 --> 00:38:07.000
How big is this market in India now?

00:38:07.680 --> 00:38:10.680
-You said premium is 1,000 bucks.
-[Bhakti] Yes.

00:38:10.760 --> 00:38:14.200
Luxe and prestige is 2,300 bucks.
Mass is below that.

00:38:14.280 --> 00:38:16.360
-Women are majority of the market.
-[Shantanu] Yeah.

00:38:16.440 --> 00:38:20.480
How big is the market and who is buying?
Overall. In India.

00:38:20.560 --> 00:38:22.880
I think beauty personal care,
at this point,

00:38:22.960 --> 00:38:25.160
In 2024, was 21 billion,

00:38:25.240 --> 00:38:28.240
which is so funny
because our first investor deck

00:38:28.320 --> 00:38:30.400
had something
from McKinsey and Bain saying,

00:38:30.480 --> 00:38:34.480
"In 2025, the Indian beauty market
would be 20 billion."

00:38:34.560 --> 00:38:36.000
-We've already beaten it.
-Yeah.

00:38:36.080 --> 00:38:38.760
So, it's going faster
than anybody expected.

00:38:39.560 --> 00:38:42.000
If you double-click
on beauty itself, I think...

00:38:42.080 --> 00:38:45.000
-40 to 45% of the market.
-Yeah.

00:38:45.080 --> 00:38:47.440
When you say beauty, you mean
skincare, makeup, hair, and fragrance?

00:38:47.520 --> 00:38:48.920
Correct. Yeah.

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:51.920
Do Indians still buy
the Western narrative?

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:54.400
-That's such a good question.
-Yes.

00:38:54.480 --> 00:38:55.920
[Diipa and Bhakti] Yes and no.

00:38:56.000 --> 00:38:57.920
-Yeah. Yes and no.
-Explain.

00:38:58.000 --> 00:38:59.400
You start.

00:38:59.480 --> 00:39:01.360
I think that...

00:39:02.560 --> 00:39:04.800
there was a time when a lot of the...

00:39:04.880 --> 00:39:07.480
Particularly when MAC entered, right?

00:39:07.560 --> 00:39:11.040
I think they came,
they had first-mover advantage,

00:39:11.120 --> 00:39:14.440
entered the market,
and really took it by storm.

00:39:14.520 --> 00:39:16.480
There was no Indian brand,

00:39:17.480 --> 00:39:19.680
there was no global brand
other than Maybelline.

00:39:19.760 --> 00:39:26.320
And Lakmē, as we all know,
has changed the game in the mass segment.

00:39:26.400 --> 00:39:29.920
But MAC came in and kind of--
We were all--

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:34.640
I think the millennial generation
was the first one that started, you know,

00:39:34.720 --> 00:39:36.840
travelling and going out

00:39:36.920 --> 00:39:38.800
and getting a little bit of the taste

00:39:38.880 --> 00:39:43.880
of what beauty was
in the Western countries.

00:39:43.960 --> 00:39:47.200
And I think that when that
MAC phenomena began,

00:39:47.280 --> 00:39:50.560
we were all, you know,
"Oh, wow, this is made in Italy,

00:39:50.640 --> 00:39:51.960
it's made in France,

00:39:52.040 --> 00:39:54.240
it's come from the UK,
it's come from the US."

00:39:54.320 --> 00:39:57.920
There was that whole enigma
to, kind of, you know,

00:39:58.000 --> 00:39:59.960
want and just be that, right?

00:40:00.040 --> 00:40:01.560
So, it was... whether it was in looks,

00:40:01.640 --> 00:40:05.640
whether it was in how we believed
what we wanted to be,

00:40:05.720 --> 00:40:10.160
just dressing,
everything was kind of aping the West.

00:40:10.240 --> 00:40:16.600
Now, as brands started really coming in
and the consumer mindset started moving,

00:40:16.680 --> 00:40:18.960
one, consumers believed

00:40:19.040 --> 00:40:23.160
that when brands are coming
from a country like France

00:40:23.240 --> 00:40:25.200
or they're coming
from a country like Italy,

00:40:25.280 --> 00:40:28.760
where they're known to have
really, really good quality ingredients,

00:40:28.840 --> 00:40:31.720
they want product that is very, very good.

00:40:31.800 --> 00:40:37.240
But I think when it comes to a brand
and storytelling

00:40:37.320 --> 00:40:39.080
and who they identify with,

00:40:39.160 --> 00:40:41.800
that identification
has changed very beautifully.

00:40:41.880 --> 00:40:46.400
They realised that they were not
seeing people who represent them.

00:40:46.480 --> 00:40:49.160
So, I think when it comes to
what they expect

00:40:49.240 --> 00:40:53.720
from a quality perspective, yes,
there is a want to emulate the West,

00:40:53.800 --> 00:40:57.000
in product standard, in quality,
in transparency,

00:40:57.080 --> 00:41:00.120
in how they talk about claims
in, you know...

00:41:00.200 --> 00:41:02.280
I think Europe has the highest standards

00:41:02.360 --> 00:41:06.480
when it comes to safety
and ingredients and transparency.

00:41:06.560 --> 00:41:10.160
And the consumers today, in India,
demand exactly that.

00:41:10.240 --> 00:41:14.880
Do they want to see
the same kind of brand storytelling,

00:41:14.960 --> 00:41:18.960
the same kind of, you know...

00:41:19.040 --> 00:41:22.480
They want to see
who they are on a global brand as well.

00:41:22.560 --> 00:41:24.720
So, I think that when you...

00:41:24.800 --> 00:41:26.920
Global brands are alienating...

00:41:28.480 --> 00:41:30.280
you know, alienating Indian consumers

00:41:30.360 --> 00:41:32.800
when they don't see someone
who looks like them in India.

00:41:32.880 --> 00:41:36.520
So, that's, I think,
any time a brand is coming in,

00:41:36.600 --> 00:41:38.000
I always tell them this, that,

00:41:38.080 --> 00:41:40.280
"Make sure... you may not get a face,

00:41:40.360 --> 00:41:42.960
but you make sure
that you are being able to see--

00:41:43.040 --> 00:41:46.520
Your brand has something
that connects to the Indian consumer.

00:41:46.600 --> 00:41:49.800
There's something
that speaks to their unique journey.

00:41:49.880 --> 00:41:53.480
That's something that's dear to them
and their values."

00:41:53.560 --> 00:41:57.000
So I think that...
that is something that has changed.

00:41:57.080 --> 00:41:58.800
And what's not changed,
I think, is the standards.

00:41:58.880 --> 00:42:01.280
But, traditionally,
the opposite worked, right?

00:42:01.360 --> 00:42:05.160
-Yes.
-I think, in India, like, growing up here,

00:42:05.240 --> 00:42:07.280
I think we had a colonial hangover.

00:42:07.360 --> 00:42:09.640
-I think everything was...
-Don't we still?

00:42:09.720 --> 00:42:11.160
I would argue, less.

00:42:11.240 --> 00:42:14.280
Or perhaps, for many people,
also not, because I think...

00:42:14.360 --> 00:42:17.280
And specifically in the premium
and prestige categories?

00:42:17.360 --> 00:42:18.880
What about mass categories?

00:42:18.960 --> 00:42:20.280
I'll get to that in a second.

00:42:20.360 --> 00:42:23.360
But I think the Eurocentric ideals
of beauty,

00:42:23.440 --> 00:42:24.800
the colonial hangover,

00:42:24.880 --> 00:42:26.520
I think we, like... Like you said,

00:42:26.600 --> 00:42:30.280
anything that came from the West
was just way better, way superior.

00:42:30.360 --> 00:42:33.280
India could never.
Because, look, look at our backyard.

00:42:33.360 --> 00:42:35.080
Look at how dirty everything is.

00:42:35.160 --> 00:42:40.400
But I think in... as time went by,
and in recent years, there's this pride.

00:42:40.480 --> 00:42:45.040
There's this nationalistic Indian pride
that I have seen in myself.

00:42:45.120 --> 00:42:46.800
I think when I first went abroad,

00:42:46.880 --> 00:42:50.080
I myself would be like,
"Oh, yeah, I've studied--

00:42:50.160 --> 00:42:52.400
I have cousins from America
or, like, I've studied."

00:42:52.480 --> 00:42:56.200
And now,
so proudly do I say I'm from India.

00:42:56.280 --> 00:42:58.800
And I think it's been a conglomeration
of so many different--

00:42:58.880 --> 00:43:00.880
But still marry a white guy
and live in Netherlands.

00:43:00.960 --> 00:43:02.520
But love, I can't choose, right?

00:43:02.600 --> 00:43:05.280
I happened to fall in love
with a white guy.

00:43:05.920 --> 00:43:07.000
Kill me for that.

00:43:07.080 --> 00:43:08.880
-You ran straight into that.
-I know.

00:43:08.960 --> 00:43:10.800
You know what happened?
Actually, when I got married,

00:43:10.880 --> 00:43:12.880
and I posted these
beautiful wedding photos,

00:43:12.960 --> 00:43:15.800
some Indian men literally were like,
"Didn't we have enough men in India?"

00:43:16.440 --> 00:43:20.400
I'm like, "Guys, you don't choose
who you fall in love with."

00:43:21.360 --> 00:43:23.200
But, no, back to this story.

00:43:23.280 --> 00:43:27.600
So, I think now, you know,
with everything that India is doing,

00:43:27.680 --> 00:43:29.680
like the Global South is where it's at.

00:43:29.760 --> 00:43:32.440
India is the epicentre
of beauty in our industry,

00:43:32.520 --> 00:43:35.400
but also in so many other things.
It's where it's going to be.

00:43:35.480 --> 00:43:37.800
But we're still buying more Estée Lauder.

00:43:37.880 --> 00:43:39.800
We're not.
But that's what we're arguing. We're not.

00:43:39.880 --> 00:43:41.840
-Majority.
-I feel like...

00:43:41.920 --> 00:43:43.440
I think we'll get to that.

00:43:43.520 --> 00:43:45.080
-L'Oréal and Estée Lauder.
-I think there's a shift.

00:43:45.160 --> 00:43:49.280
There's a significant shift
in home-grown brands dominating.

00:43:49.360 --> 00:43:52.600
-Exactly.
-Minimalist being a big one, right?

00:43:52.680 --> 00:43:55.800
And something to be said about timing.

00:43:55.880 --> 00:43:58.840
Can you give a percentage to this?
Say, five years ago,

00:43:58.920 --> 00:44:02.360
how much market share
did L'Oréal and Estée Lauder have?

00:44:02.440 --> 00:44:03.800
And how much do they have today?

00:44:03.880 --> 00:44:07.600
The belly of the market, Nikhil,
is still very mass, right?

00:44:07.680 --> 00:44:10.200
-So, mass and masstige.
-Exactly.

00:44:10.280 --> 00:44:14.760
So, while a L'Oréal Paris
and a Maybelline play in that segment,

00:44:15.480 --> 00:44:19.760
it is still a Lakmē
and a Maybelline that dominate.

00:44:19.840 --> 00:44:23.720
So, Lakmē is still sitting on the top
of the colour cosmetics charts.

00:44:23.800 --> 00:44:26.200
-Exactly.
-There's Lakmē, Maybelline, and MAC.

00:44:26.280 --> 00:44:30.600
But do you think people look at Minimalist
as a nationalistic Indian brand,

00:44:30.680 --> 00:44:32.920
or it seemed foreign to begin with?

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:37.000
-And they never spoke about their story.
-It's a good question.

00:44:37.080 --> 00:44:41.000
They didn't do that many interviews.
Nobody associated a name with the founder.

00:44:41.080 --> 00:44:42.360
[Shantanu] Post exit--

00:44:42.440 --> 00:44:46.480
I think, all of that aside,
I think what Minimalist did really well,

00:44:46.560 --> 00:44:48.680
and, of course,
they're part of the Unilever portfolio,

00:44:48.760 --> 00:44:50.160
so I love them as well.

00:44:50.240 --> 00:44:53.800
But I think their products,
they really focused on good quality.

00:44:53.880 --> 00:44:55.760
They were, I think,
one of the first brands who said...

00:44:55.840 --> 00:44:58.880
Like, even if you go to their labs
or their manufacturing units,

00:44:58.960 --> 00:45:02.160
it's high-quality ingredients,
high-quality products.

00:45:02.240 --> 00:45:05.280
That, I think, was the first time
that consumers were like,

00:45:05.360 --> 00:45:08.640
"Okay, we are being shared transparency."

00:45:08.720 --> 00:45:12.720
They really led the kind of growth
in India on ingredient-led

00:45:12.800 --> 00:45:14.720
and really educating the customer.

00:45:14.800 --> 00:45:19.160
Give me a tip here. I'm starting a brand.
I'm 20 years old or 25 years old.

00:45:19.240 --> 00:45:20.520
I have great quality,

00:45:20.600 --> 00:45:23.040
but how do I tell people
I have great quality?

00:45:23.120 --> 00:45:26.200
-Or how do I show them?
-How quickly do you want to scale?

00:45:26.280 --> 00:45:29.200
-How much time do you have?
-As quickly as I can.

00:45:29.280 --> 00:45:31.680
How much money do you have?

00:45:31.760 --> 00:45:33.720
Say, two crore rupees.

00:45:33.800 --> 00:45:35.880
They started with that much, no?
Minimalist?

00:45:35.960 --> 00:45:39.160
-Two crores, three crores?
-They were very capital-efficient.

00:45:39.240 --> 00:45:40.440
-Yeah.
-They didn't raise a lot.

00:45:40.520 --> 00:45:43.680
They had their own manufacturing unit.
That was a big up.

00:45:43.760 --> 00:45:46.200
But it doesn't cost a lot
to put the manufacture--

00:45:46.280 --> 00:45:49.200
It wasn't very capex-intensive.
It was a small lab--

00:45:49.280 --> 00:45:51.640
See, a lot of people
can hack good quality.

00:45:51.720 --> 00:45:54.200
-The question is, how is the story told?
-How do you go to market?

00:45:54.280 --> 00:45:57.320
Of course, good quality
is part one of the equation.

00:45:57.400 --> 00:46:00.560
Then you need phenomenal, like, marketing.

00:46:00.640 --> 00:46:01.800
Of course, with me,

00:46:01.880 --> 00:46:04.680
it was great that we had
that trampoline jump to begin with.

00:46:04.760 --> 00:46:08.480
It is the content creator economy.
It is content, content--

00:46:08.560 --> 00:46:10.480
Like, I tell my team this all the time.

00:46:10.560 --> 00:46:13.520
"We're a product company
and a media company in one."

00:46:13.600 --> 00:46:15.240
If we can do our content--

00:46:15.320 --> 00:46:17.760
That seems to be
what everybody tells me today.

00:46:17.840 --> 00:46:20.040
-Not just in your industry.
-Yeah.

00:46:20.120 --> 00:46:22.400
-You have to.
-Including him.

00:46:22.480 --> 00:46:25.120
He's a media company
as much as he's a product company.

00:46:25.200 --> 00:46:27.840
No, we're not a media company,
but we do a lot of...

00:46:27.920 --> 00:46:30.200
distribution of content
through channels that we own.

00:46:30.280 --> 00:46:32.240
As opposed to buying media
of off inventory.

00:46:32.320 --> 00:46:35.240
-Yeah, yeah.
-As is Tira now?

00:46:35.320 --> 00:46:37.960
I think Tira is--

00:46:38.040 --> 00:46:40.440
We're also focusing highly on--

00:46:40.520 --> 00:46:43.520
I think content is one end,
but community is on the other.

00:46:43.600 --> 00:46:46.600
Right? And I think that you have to--

00:46:46.680 --> 00:46:49.200
You can be a great content creator,

00:46:49.280 --> 00:46:52.080
but if you don't have a community
that is authentic,

00:46:52.160 --> 00:46:55.000
that has been built on a shared value,

00:46:55.080 --> 00:46:58.520
you're not really
going to be able to maximise it.

00:46:58.600 --> 00:47:03.560
So I think that what I would start with
is a hero product.

00:47:03.640 --> 00:47:06.040
You need to have one solid product,

00:47:06.120 --> 00:47:09.160
and you need to be able to solve
a real problem.

00:47:09.240 --> 00:47:10.840
I think that's one thing.

00:47:10.920 --> 00:47:13.320
So, even if it's good quality,
I think that's one.

00:47:13.400 --> 00:47:16.720
-And then you can go and--
-Give me an example, hero product?

00:47:16.800 --> 00:47:20.400
My favourite example actually
is Mamaearth on this.

00:47:20.480 --> 00:47:22.240
Because their hero products changed,
but they were real...

00:47:22.320 --> 00:47:24.360
-Onion something.
-No.

00:47:24.440 --> 00:47:26.920
Do you guys remember what
Mamaearth's first big hero product was

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:29.280
when they were doing five crores a month
at a total level?

00:47:30.520 --> 00:47:32.720
Take a wild guess. I love this--

00:47:32.800 --> 00:47:34.240
I know the onion hair shampoo.

00:47:34.320 --> 00:47:36.880
Onion one was, like,
maybe when they were doing 10-12 crores.

00:47:36.960 --> 00:47:38.600
-Baby something?
-Yeah, something for kids.

00:47:38.680 --> 00:47:40.240
-Baby, yeah?
-No, but what?

00:47:41.200 --> 00:47:42.320
Diapers?

00:47:42.400 --> 00:47:43.720
They were best mosquito repellent
for kids.

00:47:43.800 --> 00:47:45.240
-[Diipa] Oh, my God.
-Wow.

00:47:45.320 --> 00:47:47.720
It was an outstanding product.
Because it smelled good and...

00:47:47.800 --> 00:47:49.720
I literally ordered it
on Blinkit yesterday.

00:47:49.800 --> 00:47:52.240
-For kids?
-The same mosquito repellent, Mamaearth.

00:47:52.320 --> 00:47:54.720
So Mamaearth was doing
four or five crores a month.

00:47:54.800 --> 00:47:56.720
And they were doing
three crores of mosquito repellent.

00:47:56.800 --> 00:47:58.920
-Good problem to solve.
-It was All Out and Goodknight.

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:01.240
And then they went from that to the onion.
And then, of course, they had--

00:48:01.320 --> 00:48:03.200
But I think also Mamaearth
was the first wave.

00:48:03.280 --> 00:48:05.720
But I think what Bhakti is saying about
community right now--

00:48:05.800 --> 00:48:08.160
Giving an example of her, right?
Champi Hair Oil.

00:48:08.240 --> 00:48:10.560
She has that one product, which...

00:48:10.640 --> 00:48:13.800
And a lot of the story
really works on that.

00:48:13.880 --> 00:48:16.520
So, she picked that product.
She had a story which was nostalgia.

00:48:16.600 --> 00:48:18.520
-But it's the community that made it.
-Exactly.

00:48:18.600 --> 00:48:21.960
So, I think, like, in today's day and age,
you can copy product, right?

00:48:22.040 --> 00:48:26.320
You can copy branding, marketing.
You can copy that.

00:48:26.400 --> 00:48:28.440
You cannot copy a community.

00:48:28.520 --> 00:48:33.240
It would take you so long to build
the community at a level that we've built.

00:48:33.320 --> 00:48:35.240
-How do I build it?
-How is it built?

00:48:35.320 --> 00:48:37.720
-How do I build it?
-How do you build?

00:48:37.800 --> 00:48:39.320
I'm 25, I'm starting.

00:48:39.400 --> 00:48:43.240
I want all the questions that I will need
answered to start tomorrow.

00:48:43.320 --> 00:48:47.240
You start small.
My first community event had 14 people.

00:48:47.320 --> 00:48:50.240
-Is it by hosting event?
-It is by hosting events.

00:48:50.320 --> 00:48:51.720
Is it more offline than online?

00:48:51.800 --> 00:48:54.680
But what if this founder does not
want to be the face, right?

00:48:54.760 --> 00:48:58.760
I think there are people who may not
want to be the face of their--

00:48:58.840 --> 00:49:01.200
We spoke about Minimalist.

00:49:01.280 --> 00:49:03.720
-You can still build the community.
-Yeah, exactly.

00:49:03.800 --> 00:49:06.200
But I think finding the shared values.

00:49:06.280 --> 00:49:08.200
So, finding other creators

00:49:08.280 --> 00:49:11.720
who would have the same shared values
as you or your brand

00:49:11.800 --> 00:49:14.120
and then really reaching out
to their communities.

00:49:14.200 --> 00:49:16.640
I think that's another way,
and a quicker way,

00:49:16.720 --> 00:49:20.320
because there are people who will believe
in the exact same thing.

00:49:20.400 --> 00:49:22.640
So, if you take something
as simple as acne,

00:49:22.720 --> 00:49:25.320
you're solving for acne.

00:49:25.400 --> 00:49:30.240
You reach out to creators
who've spoken about body image,

00:49:30.320 --> 00:49:34.560
you reach out to creators who've spoken
about changes that they've gone through.

00:49:34.640 --> 00:49:38.120
You know, who talk about their journey.

00:49:38.200 --> 00:49:41.160
Or even experts, right,
who know how to solve this issue.

00:49:41.240 --> 00:49:45.480
And then, reach out to their communities
versus putting yourself out there as well.

00:49:45.560 --> 00:49:47.680
-That's--
-And offline helps.

00:49:47.760 --> 00:49:50.400
-But a lot can be done online as well.
-I think online is huge.

00:49:50.480 --> 00:49:53.120
-Okay, I'm starting with two crore rupees.
-Yeah.

00:49:53.200 --> 00:49:54.720
-I'm trying to build a community.
-Yeah.

00:49:54.800 --> 00:49:56.680
Where are you playing first?
That's the first question.

00:49:56.760 --> 00:49:58.800
-On a-- I have some questions on market.
-Yeah, channel.

00:49:58.880 --> 00:50:02.240
-So, for me, like, I always--
-D2C, I guess, no?

00:50:02.320 --> 00:50:03.720
Yeah.

00:50:03.800 --> 00:50:06.320
I think GTM will be--
D2C will be interested.

00:50:06.400 --> 00:50:09.080
For example, the market is, by the way,

00:50:09.160 --> 00:50:12.920
haircare is seven to eight billion,
skin is six billion.

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:15.240
But you're talking about also--
Haircare as personal care.

00:50:15.320 --> 00:50:17.880
-You're talking personal.
-So, now, this is...

00:50:17.960 --> 00:50:19.720
-We play in the other--
-[Nikhil] Haircare is seven billion?

00:50:19.800 --> 00:50:21.720
-Skincare is...
-Haircare is seven to eight billion.

00:50:21.800 --> 00:50:25.200
-Of which majority is oil, by the way.
-You're confusing us.

00:50:25.280 --> 00:50:28.240
You're talking about haircare
or personal care haircare?

00:50:28.320 --> 00:50:29.720
You said BPC, right?
Beauty and personal care.

00:50:29.800 --> 00:50:31.240
-Yeah.
-Or are you saying only beauty?

00:50:31.320 --> 00:50:34.240
No, I want to know the break-up
of skincare, makeup, hair, fragrance.

00:50:34.320 --> 00:50:36.920
You said skincare, right?
So, hair is seven to eight billion,

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:39.240
of which majority is oil, by the way.
The rest is shampoo, conditioner.

00:50:39.320 --> 00:50:41.240
-Parachute.
-Parachute and Vatika.

00:50:41.320 --> 00:50:44.240
-Champi is coming for you.
-Champi, all of that.

00:50:44.320 --> 00:50:46.720
If you are looking
at the skincare, fragrance...

00:50:46.800 --> 00:50:49.240
-How big is skincare?
-Six to seven billion.

00:50:49.320 --> 00:50:51.720
Skincare will be about 30%.

00:50:51.800 --> 00:50:54.240
Okay, how big is makeup? Colour cosmetics.

00:50:54.320 --> 00:50:56.720
-Three billion.
-Makeup is also similar, 30%.

00:50:56.800 --> 00:50:58.240
-Three billion?
-[Bhakti] Yeah. You can take,

00:50:58.320 --> 00:51:00.440
actually, skincare as about 20%,

00:51:00.520 --> 00:51:03.640
makeup as about 25-30%.

00:51:03.720 --> 00:51:06.960
Fragrance is actually
significantly high, 30%.

00:51:07.040 --> 00:51:10.720
-Particularly in the prestige section.
-But of what? Of the total market?

00:51:10.800 --> 00:51:13.720
I'm talking about the beauty market only,
which is 40-45%.

00:51:13.800 --> 00:51:15.720
I think there's a little bit
of confusion here.

00:51:15.800 --> 00:51:18.320
She keeps talking about beauty.
You talk about beauty and personal care.

00:51:18.400 --> 00:51:19.720
He talks about BPC, exactly.

00:51:19.800 --> 00:51:23.040
So, at a personal care level,
hair is seven to eight billion

00:51:23.120 --> 00:51:26.240
which includes Vatika,
Dabur Amla, all of that.

00:51:26.320 --> 00:51:28.240
And Champi from indē wild...

00:51:28.320 --> 00:51:31.000
-Makeup is three?
-Skincare is six billion,

00:51:31.080 --> 00:51:32.720
which includes, by the way, Dove, Ponds...

00:51:32.800 --> 00:51:34.240
-Everything.
-Dettol.

00:51:34.320 --> 00:51:36.640
All the stuff that you were talking about.
Moisturisers--

00:51:36.720 --> 00:51:38.320
-Glow &amp; Lovely, everything.
-[Nikhil] Okay.

00:51:38.400 --> 00:51:40.720
Then beauty is three billion, of which...

00:51:40.800 --> 00:51:42.560
-I think the--
-What is beauty?

00:51:42.640 --> 00:51:46.480
Beauty would be colour cosmetics.
Now, there will be some...

00:51:46.560 --> 00:51:48.320
Now, I don't know where...
Minimalist will either sit in

00:51:48.400 --> 00:51:51.960
-skincare or beauty. I think...
-Will lie in beauty.

00:51:52.040 --> 00:51:54.280
-Because it's skincare.
-It's three billion.

00:51:54.360 --> 00:51:56.720
-And fragrances is three billion.
-Okay.

00:51:56.800 --> 00:51:59.120
So, beauty is growing faster
than personal care

00:51:59.200 --> 00:52:03.560
which is everything FMCG
other than these four categories.

00:52:03.640 --> 00:52:05.840
And, as I said, even in haircare,
there's a difference.

00:52:05.920 --> 00:52:09.560
So, there's certain--
And this is a forever...

00:52:09.640 --> 00:52:12.680
There is no right answer
to how you segregate this, right?

00:52:12.760 --> 00:52:15.800
Every report has a different answer.

00:52:15.880 --> 00:52:18.400
-There's a few products that are grey.
-Exactly.

00:52:18.480 --> 00:52:22.040
Like, you know, the Glow &amp; Lovely,
we consider it BPC.

00:52:22.120 --> 00:52:24.480
We wouldn't consider them in beauty, pure,

00:52:24.560 --> 00:52:27.080
but, technically, they're a moisturiser.
You know what I mean?

00:52:27.160 --> 00:52:30.240
So, there's a few, I guess,
those conglomerate brands,

00:52:30.320 --> 00:52:33.040
and the ones who have
really been, like, legacy brands

00:52:33.120 --> 00:52:36.560
but mass, we consider them part of BPC.

00:52:36.640 --> 00:52:40.280
The skincare--
Like a Minimalist wouldn't be BPC.

00:52:40.360 --> 00:52:42.400
-That would be beauty.
-Okay, let me rephrase my question.

00:52:42.480 --> 00:52:44.800
Tell me which category
is growing the fastest?

00:52:44.880 --> 00:52:47.480
-Skincare. Yes.
-Fragrance?

00:52:47.560 --> 00:52:49.840
-Fragrance?
-I think fragrance is growing really fast.

00:52:49.920 --> 00:52:51.600
I think fragrance is gonna grow
really fast.

00:52:51.680 --> 00:52:53.280
Fragrance is growing really fast.
It's crazy.

00:52:53.360 --> 00:52:55.280
And fast, you mean, like, 15%?

00:52:55.360 --> 00:52:57.360
-No, I think.
-No, skincare between--

00:52:57.440 --> 00:53:03.280
So, they're all growing between 10-13%
because beauty is growing at a 10-11%--

00:53:03.360 --> 00:53:07.760
If you were to start today,
start in a place where there is a lot...

00:53:07.840 --> 00:53:09.560
One, there's growth rate.
The second is disruption.

00:53:09.640 --> 00:53:11.000
-Yeah.
-I agree with her.

00:53:11.080 --> 00:53:13.280
I think fragrance
is seeing insane disruption.

00:53:13.360 --> 00:53:14.880
-100%.
-[Nikhil] Explain.

00:53:14.960 --> 00:53:18.000
Because, why is, if you look at
the Indian fragrance market right now,

00:53:18.080 --> 00:53:19.200
there's one of two things.

00:53:19.280 --> 00:53:22.960
You have the really expensive
Chanel, Tom Fords,

00:53:23.040 --> 00:53:27.200
blah, blah, blah, above 10,000.
15,000, but original.

00:53:27.280 --> 00:53:31.400
Then you have dupes, which I don't know
the brand names fully,

00:53:31.480 --> 00:53:34.520
but they literally sell dupes of, say,

00:53:34.600 --> 00:53:37.920
the best-selling Gio, Acqua di Parmas,
blah, blah, blah, blah.

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:40.280
-599, 699, 799.
-I know this brand.

00:53:40.360 --> 00:53:42.800
-Bella Vita. We do it.
-Bella Vita.

00:53:42.880 --> 00:53:45.600
-We do it. A lot of people do it.
-And that's really mass.

00:53:45.680 --> 00:53:52.640
This entire segment, basically,
between 1,000 to 10,000,

00:53:52.720 --> 00:53:55.800
-for the grabs. Like, it's empty.
-Yeah.

00:53:55.880 --> 00:53:57.360
Also, there's a lot happening
with fragrances.

00:53:57.440 --> 00:53:59.280
There's something called
perfume wardrobing that's happening.

00:53:59.360 --> 00:54:01.080
-Yeah, layering.
-Explain.

00:54:01.160 --> 00:54:03.600
So, earlier-- So, one is layering.
Second is perfume wardrobing.

00:54:03.680 --> 00:54:04.800
So, when I grew up...

00:54:04.880 --> 00:54:06.360
-Different occasions.
-[Bhakti] Different moods.

00:54:06.440 --> 00:54:09.080
My dad and mom or I had
like one or two fragrances...

00:54:09.160 --> 00:54:11.000
-Yeah.
-...perfumes, at any given time.

00:54:11.080 --> 00:54:15.040
Today, a 25-year-old Bombay Shaving
Company employee has...

00:54:15.120 --> 00:54:16.800
Is buying three new fragrances a month.

00:54:16.880 --> 00:54:20.600
So, now you're buying
10ml, 15ml, 20ml SKUs,

00:54:20.680 --> 00:54:22.880
packs of four, packs of six,
packs of eight.

00:54:22.960 --> 00:54:26.000
It's selling like soan papdi in Reliance.

00:54:26.080 --> 00:54:27.800
Literally, it's kind of kept
stacked one on...

00:54:27.880 --> 00:54:29.800
So, people are putting three-four things
on at the same time?

00:54:29.880 --> 00:54:32.800
-No, no. That is layering.
-That's one trend. That's layering,

00:54:32.880 --> 00:54:35.840
where you, like, layer different
to make a whole new fragrance

00:54:35.920 --> 00:54:37.320
that's unique to you.

00:54:37.400 --> 00:54:39.480
-[Nikhil] Do you do that?
-Do I do that?

00:54:39.560 --> 00:54:41.440
-A little bit. Yeah, a little bit.
-[Nikhil] Do you do that?

00:54:41.520 --> 00:54:43.600
Like, you pick your favourite,
like, Jo Malone.

00:54:43.680 --> 00:54:45.720
You pick your favourite, like,
Tom Ford, and mix it.

00:54:45.800 --> 00:54:47.280
And then it's, like, your fragrance.

00:54:47.360 --> 00:54:49.760
-And it's also different on you 'cause--
-That's what Shah Rukh Khan said, no?

00:54:49.840 --> 00:54:51.280
He puts-- Sorry I interrupted you.

00:54:51.360 --> 00:54:52.640
No, I said it's different on you,

00:54:52.720 --> 00:54:56.800
'cause everyone has a different smell
that they have, a particular one.

00:54:56.880 --> 00:55:00.280
Yeah. But what he's talking about
is fragrance wardrobing

00:55:00.360 --> 00:55:03.280
where, now, also for every mood-- Oh, wow.

00:55:03.360 --> 00:55:06.400
For every mood, like, date night,
I want this fragrance.

00:55:06.480 --> 00:55:08.840
Work-me wants this fragrance.

00:55:08.920 --> 00:55:11.560
Like, evening,
chilling with my girlfriends,

00:55:11.640 --> 00:55:12.920
I want this fragrance.

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:14.800
-So, you have, like, a different...
-Also, on the go, right?

00:55:14.880 --> 00:55:16.800
-You're carrying it in your bag.
-On the go, yeah.

00:55:16.880 --> 00:55:18.360
On the go, refillables.

00:55:18.440 --> 00:55:21.880
I also think, in fragrance,
one more thing that's really...

00:55:21.960 --> 00:55:28.360
exploding is the...
like, the cleanness of ingredients.

00:55:28.440 --> 00:55:31.200
Because I think, for so long,
beauty, in general,

00:55:31.280 --> 00:55:33.320
people are becoming
more conscious of ingredients

00:55:33.400 --> 00:55:34.680
and how clean they are.

00:55:34.760 --> 00:55:38.440
But, in fragrance,
specifically, under the name,

00:55:38.520 --> 00:55:40.720
parfum or fragrance in your INCI list.

00:55:40.800 --> 00:55:44.200
INCI list is the...
How do I explain INCI list?

00:55:44.280 --> 00:55:47.640
-The percentage of all your---
-Yeah, INCI list is, like, you know,

00:55:47.720 --> 00:55:49.680
the thing that you have to write
on your label.

00:55:49.760 --> 00:55:51.920
-Regulatory.
-They're all the regulatory ingredients.

00:55:52.000 --> 00:55:55.200
So, with perfume, you can literally just
say, parfum and get away with it.

00:55:55.280 --> 00:55:57.280
But what people have found out

00:55:57.360 --> 00:56:00.040
is that there's a lot
of endocrine-disrupting ingredients,

00:56:00.120 --> 00:56:04.680
like, phthalates, and this-that,
within perfumes, that get in,

00:56:04.760 --> 00:56:06.560
that people have been selling for so long,

00:56:06.640 --> 00:56:08.200
and a lot of the infertility rates,

00:56:08.280 --> 00:56:09.640
and all of that stuff is increasing

00:56:09.720 --> 00:56:12.880
because of these phthalates,

00:56:12.960 --> 00:56:14.720
that people want clean ingredients.

00:56:14.800 --> 00:56:17.680
So, "clean fragrance", another huge trend.
Thank you.

00:56:17.760 --> 00:56:19.200
So, in India, I think...

00:56:19.280 --> 00:56:21.680
By clean fragrance, you mean,
like, vanilla, cherries, something?

00:56:21.760 --> 00:56:24.200
-No, that's a...
-No.

00:56:24.280 --> 00:56:26.680
-"Clean" means what?
-[Shantanu] Chemical.

00:56:26.760 --> 00:56:28.200
Chemicals like phthalates--

00:56:28.280 --> 00:56:30.320
-I think you'll need a whole day with us.
-Vanilla, cherries.

00:56:30.400 --> 00:56:32.800
Nikhil, vanilla and cherries is gourmand.

00:56:32.880 --> 00:56:34.440
-Yeah, gourmand.
-That's, like, you eat that.

00:56:34.520 --> 00:56:36.200
-That's a microtrend.
-[Nikhil] Okay.

00:56:37.760 --> 00:56:39.200
Clean, you mean, like,
it won't harm me, right?

00:56:39.280 --> 00:56:40.680
-Ingredient.
-Yeah.

00:56:40.760 --> 00:56:44.680
Just the purity of the ingredients,
the percentage of the ingredients--

00:56:44.760 --> 00:56:46.680
The transparency.

00:56:46.760 --> 00:56:49.680
Give me an example of a perfume brand
which does very clean.

00:56:49.760 --> 00:56:54.600
In India, I don't know.
In the West, there is... Josie Maran.

00:56:54.680 --> 00:56:56.600
It's this brand, like, a body care brand

00:56:56.680 --> 00:56:59.720
that now have done this
really strong movement on their...

00:56:59.800 --> 00:57:03.200
No alcohol as a base,
which is what majority of fragrances have.

00:57:03.280 --> 00:57:04.560
So, they've reduced the alcohol,

00:57:04.640 --> 00:57:06.560
because it's, like,
drying for your skin and hair.

00:57:06.640 --> 00:57:09.800
And their entire fragrance
is 100% natural,

00:57:09.880 --> 00:57:11.680
as in, essential oil fragrances.

00:57:11.760 --> 00:57:14.440
-And do they last as long?
-It doesn't.

00:57:14.520 --> 00:57:16.200
-It doesn't last as long.
-India is a hot country.

00:57:16.280 --> 00:57:17.680
It wears off.

00:57:17.760 --> 00:57:19.240
The issue with Indian longevity
of fragrances

00:57:19.320 --> 00:57:21.200
is that the Western climate
is different from the Indian climate.

00:57:21.280 --> 00:57:22.520
-It is.
-So, we struggle.

00:57:22.600 --> 00:57:24.680
For Indian consumers,
their number one concern is...

00:57:24.760 --> 00:57:26.680
-So that won't work in India.
-...long-lasting.

00:57:26.760 --> 00:57:28.200
It will, you need a stronger fragrance.

00:57:28.280 --> 00:57:31.040
That's why we like fragrances
that have a lot more scent, right?

00:57:31.120 --> 00:57:33.840
Like, the concentration of...

00:57:33.920 --> 00:57:35.440
-[Diipa] The eau de parfum.
-Exactly.

00:57:35.520 --> 00:57:37.280
It has to be significantly higher.

00:57:37.360 --> 00:57:40.200
They like strong-smelling perfumes
versus--

00:57:40.280 --> 00:57:44.200
But even this-- The gourmand fragrances
is a two-year-old trend.

00:57:44.280 --> 00:57:47.200
-So, you'll see vanilla, croissant--
-And that's working?

00:57:47.280 --> 00:57:49.680
-Yeah. Pistachio.
-Today, Fraganote got funded.

00:57:49.760 --> 00:57:54.480
Sol de Janeiro is the biggest brand
in beauty right now,

00:57:54.560 --> 00:57:56.800
-it's all gourmand fragrances.
-All.

00:57:56.880 --> 00:57:59.680
Every single one of them is you
just smell it and you want to eat it.

00:57:59.760 --> 00:58:02.280
-Eat it.
-I actually use perfumes like that.

00:58:02.360 --> 00:58:05.800
-Like, I have coriander and...
-Coriander is a good one.

00:58:05.880 --> 00:58:07.760
-Good note.
-And that's another one.

00:58:07.840 --> 00:58:10.160
Like, now, everything in beauty
is all about food.

00:58:10.240 --> 00:58:14.120
If you see, like, that's such
a big thing that's happening.

00:58:14.200 --> 00:58:17.640
It's like if you can eat it,
you can put it on your face as well.

00:58:17.720 --> 00:58:19.080
But that's a big trend.

00:58:19.160 --> 00:58:22.200
Whether it's on content,
whether it's on colour,

00:58:22.280 --> 00:58:24.320
whether it's on marketing, storytelling.

00:58:24.400 --> 00:58:28.680
It's all about, like, you know--
Cherry was the big trend.

00:58:28.760 --> 00:58:30.440
If you think of it, psychologically,

00:58:30.520 --> 00:58:32.200
food, it's such a nice place
in your brain.

00:58:32.280 --> 00:58:34.680
Exactly. And then, it triggers that.

00:58:34.760 --> 00:58:36.880
Doughnuts or, like, our lip balm.

00:58:36.960 --> 00:58:39.200
Like, one of our lip balm flavours
is glazed jalebi.

00:58:39.280 --> 00:58:41.640
And it does insanely well.

00:58:41.720 --> 00:58:45.440
It's because you get this happy emotion
subconsciously with jalebi.

00:58:45.520 --> 00:58:47.200
And you're like, "Oh, I'm gonna
put this in my lip balm."

00:58:47.280 --> 00:58:48.680
-And lip is like you're tasting it.
-Yeah.

00:58:48.760 --> 00:58:50.680
-Exactly.
-Also, it's nostalgic, right?

00:58:50.760 --> 00:58:52.200
-Yeah.
-So, Mango Bite, for example,

00:58:52.280 --> 00:58:55.080
is now like a fragrance that people
are really looking for.

00:58:55.160 --> 00:58:56.680
-Keyword searches for Mango Bite--
-You make that?

00:58:56.760 --> 00:58:59.200
-No, we don't make it.
-You make Mango Bite fragrance?

00:58:59.280 --> 00:59:01.680
-We don't yet. We will.
-There's a pistachio.

00:59:01.760 --> 00:59:03.200
Pistachio has done well.

00:59:03.280 --> 00:59:05.480
Kayali has these fragrances.

00:59:05.560 --> 00:59:07.800
Kayali, it's by Mona Kattan.

00:59:07.880 --> 00:59:09.840
It's a Dubai-based brand.

00:59:09.920 --> 00:59:11.920
And she has done all, like,

00:59:12.000 --> 00:59:13.880
she has really caught
onto the gourmand trend.

00:59:13.960 --> 00:59:16.200
-And...
-Pistachio, I saw someone else--

00:59:16.280 --> 00:59:18.200
-Pistachio gelato.
-Matcha.

00:59:18.280 --> 00:59:21.200
-Everyone's doing matcha now.
-That smells bad.

00:59:21.280 --> 00:59:23.200
-No.
-But they make it smell good.

00:59:23.280 --> 00:59:25.800
-They can make it smell good.
-[Diipa] They can make it smell good.

00:59:25.880 --> 00:59:28.200
-Good and bad is so subjective.
-Mochi.

00:59:28.280 --> 00:59:31.680
Mochi. But, yeah,
fragrance is going to-- I think it--

00:59:31.760 --> 00:59:33.680
Who is going to make
the first laddu fragrance?

00:59:33.760 --> 00:59:36.200
Yeah, besan ka laddu. Like a nostalgia--

00:59:36.280 --> 00:59:38.280
Okay, I'm going to summarise
a bit of what you said.

00:59:38.360 --> 00:59:42.440
You said the category,
overall, is about 21 billion.

00:59:42.520 --> 00:59:46.640
"Skincare, six. makeup, three.
Hair, seven. Fragrance, three.

00:59:46.720 --> 00:59:49.680
Fastest-growing is skincare
and fragrance."

00:59:49.760 --> 00:59:51.200
Yeah.

00:59:51.280 --> 00:59:55.160
"Making deals with salons when you're
starting a brand might be a good idea.

00:59:55.240 --> 00:59:56.680
Old products--"

00:59:56.760 --> 00:59:58.440
-For haircare.
-For haircare.

00:59:58.520 --> 01:00:00.440
Yeah, that's--
And professional haircare, right?

01:00:00.520 --> 01:00:06.840
Like, if you're looking to work with...
with professional-grade products.

01:00:06.920 --> 01:00:10.640
So you need to be able to call your brand
a professional brand to be...

01:00:10.720 --> 01:00:12.200
actually be able to work with them.

01:00:12.280 --> 01:00:15.200
"Old products made cooler,
nostalgia sells."

01:00:16.240 --> 01:00:23.240
You said Western, better, still sells,
but the trend is shifting.

01:00:23.320 --> 01:00:27.840
"Shifting faster in premium and prestige
and slower in mass.

01:00:27.920 --> 01:00:31.160
Mass is below 1,000, premium is 1,000,
prestige is 2,300."

01:00:31.240 --> 01:00:33.080
-Yeah?
-But I want to ask you a little bit.

01:00:33.160 --> 01:00:34.720
Sorry. Complete your thought.

01:00:34.800 --> 01:00:36.760
"All product companies
are media companies.

01:00:36.840 --> 01:00:39.240
You need to run a media company
if you want to sell a product."

01:00:39.320 --> 01:00:41.360
-And community.
-Community.

01:00:41.440 --> 01:00:46.320
You said community,
but we didn't finish the thought on...

01:00:46.400 --> 01:00:49.800
You hinted at offline
might be better than online.

01:00:49.880 --> 01:00:53.240
-Or you need to have offline.
-No, I don't think so.

01:00:53.320 --> 01:00:56.560
-And then we moved on to influencers.
-We can go back to community.

01:00:56.640 --> 01:00:58.720
So, I think community...

01:00:58.800 --> 01:01:00.760
Again, what Bhakti said,
it's a buzzword today.

01:01:00.840 --> 01:01:03.240
Everybody's like, "Community,
community, community."

01:01:03.320 --> 01:01:05.680
But I think I can only speak for us.

01:01:05.760 --> 01:01:09.720
But at indē wild, everything we do
starts and ends with community.

01:01:09.800 --> 01:01:11.320
And I mean in every aspect.

01:01:11.400 --> 01:01:14.840
Like, before we launched the brand,
we had surveys

01:01:14.920 --> 01:01:19.120
that were written by 16,000
of my followers

01:01:19.200 --> 01:01:20.840
that really set everything.

01:01:20.920 --> 01:01:24.320
I had 13 focus groups
before the brand even existed.

01:01:24.400 --> 01:01:27.920
Asking them, "What do you care about?
What is your skincare concerns?

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:30.840
What is it not in the market?"
You know, really figuring it out.

01:01:30.920 --> 01:01:34.640
Even in our bio till today, it says,
"Co-created by you."

01:01:34.720 --> 01:01:36.680
So that is pre-brand launch.

01:01:36.760 --> 01:01:40.120
Once the brand launched,
you know, we really interact--

01:01:40.200 --> 01:01:42.640
Like, even the way
our customer service is done,

01:01:42.720 --> 01:01:45.640
it's not like a, "Oh, order misplaced.
Okay, here's your number.

01:01:45.720 --> 01:01:47.280
Go figure it out."

01:01:47.360 --> 01:01:52.200
We really, genuinely talk to them,
like, we'd say educated besties.

01:01:52.280 --> 01:01:54.120
Like, you are their bestie.
You talk to them.

01:01:54.200 --> 01:01:55.680
You keep the conversation going.

01:01:55.760 --> 01:01:57.680
It's not just, like, "Finish order. done."

01:01:57.760 --> 01:02:02.240
And so, in every aspect of indē wilde,
community is infused.

01:02:02.320 --> 01:02:04.960
It almost sounds like you're saying,
"Listen to your followers,

01:02:05.040 --> 01:02:06.720
and speak to them constantly."

01:02:06.800 --> 01:02:08.240
-Exactly.
-Is that community?

01:02:08.320 --> 01:02:10.720
Because I don't know what-- Community
is sounding like spirituality to me.

01:02:10.800 --> 01:02:12.720
I don't think it's about--

01:02:12.800 --> 01:02:14.240
We all mean different things.

01:02:14.320 --> 01:02:17.720
I think it's in--
It's everything, together.

01:02:17.800 --> 01:02:20.120
What's the best community?
Who runs the best community?

01:02:20.200 --> 01:02:22.000
I mean, I think if you take his example,

01:02:22.080 --> 01:02:25.960
it is about-- Like, there is
a whole community of people

01:02:26.040 --> 01:02:28.600
who like to take care of their beards.

01:02:28.680 --> 01:02:34.040
It's a small one, but there is a whole
community that looks at it as self-care

01:02:34.120 --> 01:02:37.720
versus just looking at it as, you know,

01:02:37.800 --> 01:02:40.000
something you have to do
on a day-to-day level.

01:02:40.080 --> 01:02:43.160
Now, that community
is very different from people

01:02:43.240 --> 01:02:45.760
who use the product
as personal grooming products.

01:02:45.840 --> 01:02:47.720
They actually--
And I have a friend in London

01:02:47.800 --> 01:02:49.240
who really takes--

01:02:49.320 --> 01:02:53.640
who has a three to four step
grooming routine for his beard.

01:02:53.720 --> 01:02:56.040
He lives in London,
so he has a Turkish barber

01:02:56.120 --> 01:02:59.440
who he goes to every month
to take care of his beard.

01:02:59.520 --> 01:03:03.040
It's his ritual,
and it's his self-care ritual, right?

01:03:03.120 --> 01:03:04.560
-And now, there may be a...
-[Nikhil] I suspect

01:03:04.640 --> 01:03:06.920
-Shantanu is a bit like that.
-Sorry?

01:03:07.000 --> 01:03:09.120
No, I said I suspect
you might be a bit like that.

01:03:09.200 --> 01:03:11.240
You have your barber
who does everything and stuff.

01:03:11.320 --> 01:03:14.720
Yeah, so we have a whole group of barbers
who kind of work with us.

01:03:14.800 --> 01:03:18.000
And that is exactly a community.

01:03:18.080 --> 01:03:20.120
So, is that a community
or a group of people

01:03:20.200 --> 01:03:22.720
-who have something in common?
-No.

01:03:22.800 --> 01:03:24.240
How do you translate that
into a community?

01:03:24.320 --> 01:03:27.800
Yeah, so it is about 'cause
they have a shared value, right?

01:03:27.880 --> 01:03:31.680
So, I think-- If I have to simplify
what a community is,

01:03:31.760 --> 01:03:35.720
it is a group of people
who have certain shared values

01:03:35.800 --> 01:03:37.840
that they can come together
and speak about.

01:03:37.920 --> 01:03:43.280
So, as I said, if you have acne concerns,
that's a community.

01:03:43.360 --> 01:03:46.840
And you may have a micro-community
in that saying,

01:03:46.920 --> 01:03:51.160
"I'm 15 years old," and then,
there is these young teenage...

01:03:52.880 --> 01:03:56.200
I've just grown out of--
Or mums, for example.

01:03:56.280 --> 01:03:58.920
I have two nieces,

01:03:59.000 --> 01:04:02.560
and they're now in the 11-13 age bracket.

01:04:02.640 --> 01:04:06.520
And they're the most impressionable
age group now.

01:04:06.600 --> 01:04:08.120
And they're also the most exposed.

01:04:08.200 --> 01:04:11.200
I don't think when I was 11 or 12,
I really cared about skincare.

01:04:11.280 --> 01:04:13.720
My mom just said, "Wash your face."
And that's about it.

01:04:13.800 --> 01:04:16.200
They know every single brand
that's trending,

01:04:16.280 --> 01:04:18.600
whenever they go to a Tira store,
my nieces would be like,

01:04:18.680 --> 01:04:22.240
"We saw that, you launched Fenty,
you launched that brand."

01:04:22.320 --> 01:04:25.720
They know everything. They told me,
like, "Why don't you have this brand?"

01:04:25.800 --> 01:04:27.880
They know it a lot more.

01:04:27.960 --> 01:04:31.760
So there's exposure, but with that
comes a lot more pressure as well.

01:04:31.840 --> 01:04:34.360
Right? Now, their mums are a community

01:04:34.440 --> 01:04:36.720
-because they're trying to figure out--
-Mothers are big communities.

01:04:36.800 --> 01:04:40.040
My sister's always asking me,
"Listen, what can I use

01:04:40.120 --> 01:04:43.240
if she's having an acne break-out?"

01:04:43.320 --> 01:04:46.720
I think also what happens
with community is if--

01:04:46.800 --> 01:04:49.920
When you're truly a community of a brand,
you have a choice,

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:51.280
you could go to any other brand.

01:04:51.360 --> 01:04:54.200
They could buy hair oil
from any other brand.

01:04:54.280 --> 01:04:59.280
But the fact that they choose to come back
to indē wild every time,

01:04:59.360 --> 01:05:02.200
that, to me, is a community,
and how you make it.

01:05:02.280 --> 01:05:05.720
I mean, I leave it to the creative lens
of the teams as well.

01:05:05.800 --> 01:05:07.720
-So, is community an emotion?
-[Shantanu] Yes.

01:05:07.800 --> 01:05:09.240
It's definitely an emotion.

01:05:09.320 --> 01:05:12.880
So, you pick one emotion, stay consistent,

01:05:12.960 --> 01:05:15.240
then you listen
and speak to your followers

01:05:15.320 --> 01:05:17.720
-while re-iterating that emotion.
-Yes.

01:05:17.800 --> 01:05:19.720
-And you're the custodian of the emotion.
-[Diipa] Yeah.

01:05:19.800 --> 01:05:21.720
How do I pick what emotion
for my community?

01:05:21.800 --> 01:05:24.120
That's a very good question.
That's a very good question.

01:05:24.200 --> 01:05:27.680
I think you have done six,
seven years of community building

01:05:27.760 --> 01:05:29.880
followed by brand building
on the back of the community.

01:05:29.960 --> 01:05:32.320
So what is that emotion
for indē wild, for example?

01:05:32.400 --> 01:05:34.240
Is it you? Are you the emotion?

01:05:34.320 --> 01:05:35.880
No, I think it's bigger than me.

01:05:35.960 --> 01:05:39.240
-I think the real emotion of indē wild--
-Hot girl.

01:05:39.320 --> 01:05:41.720
-What did he say?
-Hot girl.

01:05:41.800 --> 01:05:43.240
[laughter]

01:05:43.320 --> 01:05:45.720
-I mean, that could be an emotion.
-It could. It could. Absolutely.

01:05:45.800 --> 01:05:48.360
-The more basic, the stronger it is.
-Identity, vulnerability.

01:05:48.440 --> 01:05:51.000
I think our community's real thing,

01:05:51.080 --> 01:05:54.240
honestly, I think in... There's pride.

01:05:54.320 --> 01:05:55.880
Definitely, there's pride.

01:05:55.960 --> 01:05:58.320
Like, indē wild being
that first global Indian brand,

01:05:58.400 --> 01:06:00.720
there's that pride to it, like,
"This is ours."

01:06:00.800 --> 01:06:03.080
-Are you selling patriotism?
-Yes.

01:06:03.160 --> 01:06:05.240
-You have "I-N-D" in the name.
-Definitely.

01:06:05.320 --> 01:06:09.240
There's... indē wild is purely
a very-proud-of-our-culture brand.

01:06:09.320 --> 01:06:11.640
Is that working more?
Patriotism is selling?

01:06:11.720 --> 01:06:14.440
-[Bhakti] For sure.
-Especially if the West is also like,

01:06:14.520 --> 01:06:17.920
"Wow. Champi. Wow, indē wild."

01:06:18.000 --> 01:06:21.920
Then India is like, "What? Our Champi?"
Like, our indē wild?"

01:06:22.000 --> 01:06:25.760
And so, I think there's definitely pride
and patriotism there.

01:06:25.840 --> 01:06:27.520
But there's also this...

01:06:27.600 --> 01:06:29.960
There is indeed that "cool girl" effect,
what you said.

01:06:30.040 --> 01:06:32.520
Like, indē wild users are a certain type.

01:06:32.600 --> 01:06:35.080
Like, Rhode is a great example
of that as well.

01:06:35.160 --> 01:06:38.720
If you use Rhode, subconsciously,
you're like, "I'm part of the It Girl.

01:06:38.800 --> 01:06:41.240
I'm an It Girl because I use Rhode."

01:06:41.320 --> 01:06:43.720
And how do I show that? The first few...

01:06:43.800 --> 01:06:46.160
-Content.
-...community members I have

01:06:46.240 --> 01:06:48.240
have to be good-looking girls as well?

01:06:48.320 --> 01:06:50.680
Not good-looking, necessarily.
It's more...

01:06:50.760 --> 01:06:52.640
What does a confident girl exuberate?

01:06:52.720 --> 01:06:54.280
It's confidence.

01:06:54.360 --> 01:06:56.360
It's your-- Dress well,
you're sure of yourself.

01:06:56.440 --> 01:06:59.120
Like, it doesn't have to
necessarily be "hot",

01:06:59.200 --> 01:07:01.240
but it can also be imperfectly beautiful.

01:07:01.320 --> 01:07:03.880
-Let's actually do this.
-It's also a lifestyle, right?

01:07:03.960 --> 01:07:08.520
You talk about the lifestyle
that comes with being the It Girl.

01:07:08.600 --> 01:07:14.240
So, my circle of friends, my,
you know, buying into the wellness.

01:07:14.320 --> 01:07:17.200
-I go to Pilates in the morning.
-My Sunday matcha with my Pilates.

01:07:17.280 --> 01:07:18.320
My athleisure.

01:07:18.400 --> 01:07:21.800
You're depicting affluence
by making it about matcha--

01:07:21.880 --> 01:07:23.560
-[Diipa] Yes.
-Right?

01:07:23.640 --> 01:07:25.080
-So, affluence is--
-Affluence and identity.

01:07:25.160 --> 01:07:27.040
Let's do the small experiment
with your company.

01:07:27.120 --> 01:07:29.240
You have two crores.
You know, you want to build a brand.

01:07:29.320 --> 01:07:32.160
-He hasn't said if it's women or men's.
-Women's.

01:07:32.240 --> 01:07:34.560
-Okay.
-I don't want to build for a market...

01:07:34.640 --> 01:07:36.000
-I don't want to.
-He's, like,

01:07:36.080 --> 01:07:38.240
"It's too slow-growing for me."

01:07:38.320 --> 01:07:40.640
-I want scale.
-But if you're gonna build fragrances...

01:07:40.720 --> 01:07:42.360
-Are you building a fragrance?
-Yeah.

01:07:42.440 --> 01:07:44.720
...then the world is moving
towards unisex, by the way.

01:07:44.800 --> 01:07:47.160
-Gourmand fragrances?
-I mean, I want you to tell me.

01:07:47.240 --> 01:07:50.360
-I think gourmand.
-No. I think it can be for every mood.

01:07:50.440 --> 01:07:53.360
So you can have
a whole variety of fragrances.

01:07:53.440 --> 01:07:55.920
I think what you would pick is a hook.

01:07:56.000 --> 01:08:00.840
Like, for example, Jo Malone is based
on these beautiful ingredient stories.

01:08:00.920 --> 01:08:02.720
And they really, really
present it so well.

01:08:02.800 --> 01:08:06.240
-Let's say Nikhil's Fragrance Company.
-Yeah.

01:08:06.320 --> 01:08:09.000
Actually, don't say Nikhil 'cause
I probably have a community.

01:08:09.080 --> 01:08:11.720
-Let's say...
-What The Fragrance.

01:08:11.800 --> 01:08:14.840
-What The Fragrance.
-What The Fragrance.

01:08:14.920 --> 01:08:17.960
-What The also has a community?
-Yeah, that's his whole thing.

01:08:18.040 --> 01:08:19.480
Let's say my name is Dilip.

01:08:20.840 --> 01:08:22.720
And I'm building a perfume company.

01:08:22.800 --> 01:08:25.720
-[laughter]
-First question. What is your emotion?

01:08:25.800 --> 01:08:27.480
I'm 25 years old.

01:08:29.440 --> 01:08:30.640
I live in Bangalore.

01:08:31.800 --> 01:08:35.080
-You have two crore rupees.
-I have two crore rupees that I borrowed.

01:08:36.520 --> 01:08:42.200
I spent the last many years of my life
going to an engineering college.

01:08:42.280 --> 01:08:44.720
But today, AI has come,
and I'm feeling very...

01:08:44.800 --> 01:08:46.240
-Irrelevant.
-...obsolete and irrelevant.

01:08:46.320 --> 01:08:48.760
-First question, what's your why?
-Yeah.

01:08:48.840 --> 01:08:50.240
What's the white space?

01:08:50.320 --> 01:08:52.720
-What's my why, a fragrance company?
-What's your why?

01:08:52.800 --> 01:08:57.240
Why are you, engineer at 25,
wanting to build a fragrance company?

01:08:58.120 --> 01:09:00.720
That's a very good question.
Because there are many reasons why--

01:09:00.800 --> 01:09:06.080
Because I go to an engineering college
in South Bangalore, I used to go.

01:09:06.160 --> 01:09:08.720
And people smell really bad,
and I want to change this.

01:09:08.800 --> 01:09:10.640
-Excellent.
-I actually really like that.

01:09:10.720 --> 01:09:12.440
-That's a good point.
-That's a very good start.

01:09:12.520 --> 01:09:14.240
And why do they smell bad?

01:09:15.440 --> 01:09:17.720
Because they don't use fragrance.

01:09:17.800 --> 01:09:21.240
No, they probably do.
You're smelling them in the evening.

01:09:21.320 --> 01:09:22.720
Sweat.

01:09:22.800 --> 01:09:25.920
-In India, there is dust, wind...
-We have it. We've done it for you.

01:09:26.000 --> 01:09:29.240
Your brand is going to
be India's premium brand

01:09:29.320 --> 01:09:32.760
focused on a technology
that changes sweat,

01:09:32.840 --> 01:09:36.120
that the sweat stink can be altered
or differentiated

01:09:36.200 --> 01:09:38.320
like an odour-fix technology

01:09:38.400 --> 01:09:41.720
that you put as your proprietary
ingredient within your fragrances.

01:09:41.800 --> 01:09:43.600
But you only have two crores
to do all of this.

01:09:43.680 --> 01:09:46.120
-So I would--
-No, two crores to start.

01:09:46.200 --> 01:09:48.360
And then, I'll come to you guys
and raise some money.

01:09:48.440 --> 01:09:50.280
So while you have a problem, I would say,

01:09:50.360 --> 01:09:52.920
"Okay, there may be two or three
or four companies

01:09:53.000 --> 01:09:54.600
already doing what you're doing."

01:09:54.680 --> 01:09:57.360
So, I think, yes, that's your problem.

01:09:57.440 --> 01:10:00.840
But, you know, how would you
kind of solve the white space?

01:10:00.920 --> 01:10:04.360
But I think having a why
is very, very powerful in storytelling.

01:10:04.440 --> 01:10:07.000
And in being authentic and real.

01:10:07.080 --> 01:10:10.360
If you just make a business,
'cause white space, money...

01:10:10.440 --> 01:10:13.160
No, I'm coming from a very, like...

01:10:13.240 --> 01:10:16.840
-very practical mindset as well.
-Of course.

01:10:16.920 --> 01:10:20.720
Because while you have the storytelling,
I think a lot of brands also fail.

01:10:20.800 --> 01:10:24.360
Because they have storytelling,
they have all of these other things--

01:10:24.440 --> 01:10:27.200
Okay, tell me how to build my story now.
Yeah.

01:10:27.280 --> 01:10:32.400
So, I'm here. I've figured that why
is people around me smell horrible,

01:10:32.480 --> 01:10:36.200
they don't use perfumes,
or maybe they do, but it's not working.

01:10:36.280 --> 01:10:39.760
-Diipa suggested that...
-Public service.

01:10:39.840 --> 01:10:43.360
We create an odour-fix technology.
It could go huge.

01:10:43.440 --> 01:10:46.640
Maybe you're an engineering student
who's never...

01:10:46.720 --> 01:10:49.360
From South Bangalore,
but who's never been seen, right?

01:10:49.440 --> 01:10:53.000
Can I market it with the story
of, "Do it for me, not for you?"

01:10:53.080 --> 01:10:55.360
-And you put on the perfume?
-No, absolutely not.

01:10:55.440 --> 01:10:58.840
You cannot can't do that.
You can't market like that.

01:10:58.920 --> 01:11:01.360
You will not build a community,
you will lose it.

01:11:01.440 --> 01:11:03.800
You're using a sarcastic
marketing technique,

01:11:03.880 --> 01:11:05.840
-which is also very out there.
-Yeah, that is true.

01:11:05.920 --> 01:11:08.360
-There is a market for it.
-Okay, I'm on Instagram.

01:11:08.440 --> 01:11:11.360
-If he's tongue-in-cheek about it, yeah.
-[Bhakti] There's so many brands--

01:11:11.440 --> 01:11:13.040
You have to be consistent for ten years.

01:11:13.120 --> 01:11:15.240
I'm on Instagram, I have 445 followers.

01:11:16.320 --> 01:11:18.280
-Okay?
-Actually, Bhakti, I like that idea.

01:11:18.360 --> 01:11:21.120
Be tongue-in-cheek sarcastic
saying, "You stink.

01:11:21.200 --> 01:11:25.000
Nobody's ever told you you stink.
So, this is my brand for you,

01:11:25.080 --> 01:11:27.480
the person who people
don't say you stink."

01:11:27.560 --> 01:11:31.360
And all of us in the humidity
sweat and stink, right?

01:11:31.440 --> 01:11:34.360
And you always want to
tell that one friend,

01:11:34.440 --> 01:11:37.360
-"Listen, here's the perfume, use it."
-But you don't have the heart to.

01:11:37.440 --> 01:11:39.920
-Now, this brand will do it for you.
-And should I call my perfume "Stench"?

01:11:40.920 --> 01:11:43.000
-Call them what?
-Call my perfume "Stench."

01:11:43.080 --> 01:11:44.840
If you're gonna be a tongue-in-cheek
branding overall.

01:11:44.920 --> 01:11:46.360
No!

01:11:46.440 --> 01:11:48.360
You can't break category code
so much also.

01:11:48.440 --> 01:11:49.440
-Yeah.
-No?

01:11:49.520 --> 01:11:52.120
You want it to be positively reinforcing
in some way, right?

01:11:52.200 --> 01:11:54.840
-Like, "Oh, I'm going to use this."
-Yeah, Stench is a bit far.

01:11:54.920 --> 01:11:56.360
Every perfume and deodorant and--

01:11:56.440 --> 01:12:00.360
-How about I call it "Gutter"?
-[Diipa] No.

01:12:00.440 --> 01:12:02.720
-You can.
-[laughter]

01:12:03.920 --> 01:12:05.840
[Diipa] Stick to fintech.

01:12:07.440 --> 01:12:09.360
I'm glad this is on paper.

01:12:09.440 --> 01:12:12.440
I think Nikhil can take that risk,
Dilip should not.

01:12:12.520 --> 01:12:15.360
-Dilip should follow category--
-I'm definitely not listing it on Tira.

01:12:15.440 --> 01:12:18.560
No? You wouldn't list it if there
was a perfume called Stench,

01:12:18.640 --> 01:12:20.360
if people asked for it.

01:12:21.280 --> 01:12:23.360
-No.
-Beauty is about making people feel...

01:12:23.440 --> 01:12:25.840
Feel good about themselves.

01:12:25.920 --> 01:12:27.360
But everybody is doing that.

01:12:27.440 --> 01:12:29.840
-But, again, it's about...
-For a reason, no?

01:12:29.920 --> 01:12:33.320
Your marketing can be tongue-in-cheek.
Your content can be tongue-in-cheek.

01:12:33.400 --> 01:12:36.440
That can be a bit sarcastic.
That can be funny.

01:12:36.520 --> 01:12:38.400
-Why call it Gutter or Stench?
-Yeah, don't do that.

01:12:38.480 --> 01:12:39.680
That's not what the product is.

01:12:39.760 --> 01:12:41.840
But then you're saying the opposite
of what your product is doing.

01:12:41.920 --> 01:12:44.720
And that's the first thing
that people see, right?

01:12:44.800 --> 01:12:46.320
Like, that's the first relation they make.

01:12:46.400 --> 01:12:48.840
What's the name of your product?
What's the story you're telling?

01:12:48.920 --> 01:12:51.520
-Okay, so what do I call it?
-Anything else.

01:12:51.600 --> 01:12:54.360
-Like, something positive.
-For example?

01:12:54.440 --> 01:12:55.840
I Got You.

01:12:55.920 --> 01:12:58.720
For example, Nikhil,
let's take a step back.

01:12:58.800 --> 01:13:00.600
What are the big trends?
Like, one is gourmand.

01:13:00.680 --> 01:13:02.840
-Second is oud.
-Yeah.

01:13:02.920 --> 01:13:04.360
-Oud is a trend?
-Oud is big.

01:13:04.440 --> 01:13:07.840
Third is-- Kannauj is now
the Mecca of fragrances.

01:13:07.920 --> 01:13:09.360
So, Dilip should go to Kannauj--

01:13:09.440 --> 01:13:10.840
What is Kannauj?

01:13:10.920 --> 01:13:13.120
It's like the Grasse of India.

01:13:13.200 --> 01:13:14.480
-[Bhakti] Yeah.
-It's like this perfume--

01:13:14.560 --> 01:13:16.360
Oh, like that wet sand smell--

01:13:16.440 --> 01:13:18.360
-No, the perfumeries.
-No, no, it's a place

01:13:18.440 --> 01:13:20.360
-where they make perfume.
-Perfumers there...

01:13:20.440 --> 01:13:22.880
-Right. Where is this place?
-...who, like, in the thousands.

01:13:22.960 --> 01:13:24.840
Kannauj is UP, I think.

01:13:24.920 --> 01:13:26.360
I'm gonna write down "go to Kannauj".

01:13:26.440 --> 01:13:28.840
-Kannauj. K-A-N-N-A-U-J.
-What else?

01:13:28.920 --> 01:13:31.840
I think also going back to what Diipa
said about nostalgia,

01:13:31.920 --> 01:13:34.160
there are so many beautiful Indian...

01:13:34.240 --> 01:13:37.240
you know, fragrances
that are native to India.

01:13:37.320 --> 01:13:40.960
And that's a big trend
that's, you know, picking up now.

01:13:41.040 --> 01:13:44.600
And people are kind of
also giving that, you know,

01:13:44.680 --> 01:13:47.160
alluding to Indian fragrances
as well, right?

01:13:47.240 --> 01:13:49.640
Jasmine is so powerful, but it's...

01:13:49.720 --> 01:13:51.800
It's never found that rooting...

01:13:51.880 --> 01:13:55.360
We've never kind of overly commercialised
it from a beauty perspective.

01:13:55.440 --> 01:13:57.200
But, craziest thing...

01:13:57.280 --> 01:14:01.080
Chanel No. 5--
Everybody knows Chanel No. 5,

01:14:01.160 --> 01:14:03.360
their two main key notes is from India.

01:14:03.440 --> 01:14:06.480
-Yeah.
-It's the jasmine and the rose from India.

01:14:06.560 --> 01:14:09.640
In their documentary,
they literally showcase,

01:14:09.720 --> 01:14:11.840
like, "The Indian Jasminica."

01:14:11.920 --> 01:14:13.360
And they're like...

01:14:13.440 --> 01:14:17.160
Literally from India, and a French brand
has used it for centuries now.

01:14:17.240 --> 01:14:19.840
And... Yeah. Time to take ownership.

01:14:19.920 --> 01:14:22.120
I also feel like the other big trend
in fragrances is that

01:14:22.200 --> 01:14:24.000
there is gender neutrality
happening there.

01:14:24.080 --> 01:14:26.360
-Like... people are--
-[Bhakti] Yeah.

01:14:26.440 --> 01:14:27.840
The strong fragrances...

01:14:27.920 --> 01:14:30.200
-My husband and I share fragrances.
-Yeah.

01:14:30.280 --> 01:14:32.360
Very easily. Fruit--

01:14:32.440 --> 01:14:34.360
We do fragrance shopping
together, actually.

01:14:34.440 --> 01:14:37.400
-Fruit is becoming very common.
-No wonder Tejas smells feminine.

01:14:38.920 --> 01:14:41.320
I don't only wear feminine fragrances--

01:14:41.400 --> 01:14:43.520
And then, also,
to the whole layering bit, right?

01:14:43.600 --> 01:14:45.200
So you can have a floral fragrance

01:14:45.280 --> 01:14:48.160
and then pair it with something
extremely musky.

01:14:48.240 --> 01:14:50.320
-Yeah.
-Then you have a fragrance

01:14:50.400 --> 01:14:54.520
that's not too feminine,
but just enough that you like it--

01:14:54.600 --> 01:14:57.160
And it's masculine on your spectrum.

01:14:57.240 --> 01:14:58.840
There's a spectrum in fragrance,

01:14:58.920 --> 01:15:02.160
but I think there will always be
a differentiation between men and women.

01:15:02.240 --> 01:15:05.320
I take issue of this layering thing.
I feel like...

01:15:06.240 --> 01:15:10.640
So, brands themselves, by the way,
now sell perfumes layered together.

01:15:10.720 --> 01:15:12.520
Why do you find that an issue?

01:15:13.240 --> 01:15:17.640
I'm paying a brand for their taste.

01:15:17.720 --> 01:15:20.400
-For their nose to do the job.
-Yeah.

01:15:20.480 --> 01:15:25.160
Why would I pay Chanel's perfumer
or gourmand or whatever he's called,

01:15:25.240 --> 01:15:27.880
money for his taste in his nose,

01:15:27.960 --> 01:15:30.160
and then I take it
and try to make it in my own?

01:15:30.240 --> 01:15:33.160
But it's like your saying you'll buy
all your clothes from the same brand.

01:15:33.240 --> 01:15:37.480
No. I will not go to say,
Tom Ford, and say,

01:15:37.560 --> 01:15:40.680
"Okay, now, stitch a flower over here
and then cut this part off

01:15:40.760 --> 01:15:43.160
-and make it in a certain way.
-I think it's just creativity.

01:15:43.240 --> 01:15:44.640
-About self-expression.
-It's individuality.

01:15:44.720 --> 01:15:46.160
Yeah, self-expression.

01:15:46.240 --> 01:15:49.200
Minimalist's first brand
was actually this whole...

01:15:49.280 --> 01:15:51.280
You remember that, right?
Minimalist's first brand was,

01:15:51.360 --> 01:15:53.360
these guys said,
"You tell me all the ingredients you want

01:15:53.440 --> 01:15:54.560
and all the stuff you want done,

01:15:54.640 --> 01:15:57.640
and we'll put it together
and give you a personalised sample."

01:15:57.720 --> 01:16:00.360
But that happens in the US a lot.

01:16:00.440 --> 01:16:02.640
It may not be everything you want,

01:16:02.720 --> 01:16:05.640
but, in skincare,
they will create a special...

01:16:05.720 --> 01:16:07.680
-Questionnaire and all that.
-Questionnaire.

01:16:07.760 --> 01:16:09.160
You know, based on your skin type--

01:16:09.240 --> 01:16:11.160
-How does that business model work?
-Very hard.

01:16:11.240 --> 01:16:13.360
-I've tried that. It's a pain in the ass.
-[Diipa] It's crazy.

01:16:13.440 --> 01:16:15.960
I mean, your supply chain
just goes for a toss.

01:16:16.040 --> 01:16:19.320
But I think that people have tried it.

01:16:19.400 --> 01:16:23.480
Hyper-personalised skincare.
That's there now.

01:16:23.560 --> 01:16:26.560
Remember we were talking about
how beauty has been through those phases?

01:16:26.640 --> 01:16:29.160
Beauty is in this self-expression phase.

01:16:29.240 --> 01:16:32.320
So, while it's a shared value,
community is also driving beauty,

01:16:32.400 --> 01:16:33.480
it's still you.

01:16:33.560 --> 01:16:35.280
There is a "you" and an "us",

01:16:35.360 --> 01:16:37.640
and the "you" part of you
is driving all of these movements.

01:16:37.720 --> 01:16:41.560
But you know what?
I think, for your business,

01:16:41.640 --> 01:16:44.400
the layering part can actually be
a part of your offering.

01:16:44.480 --> 01:16:46.120
Because, in fragrances, it's a lot easier.

01:16:46.200 --> 01:16:48.160
It's much easier
to mix fragrances together.

01:16:48.240 --> 01:16:51.160
But I'm a 25-year-old guy,
I've lost my job.

01:16:51.240 --> 01:16:52.640
I don't know what to do in life.

01:16:52.720 --> 01:16:54.640
I don't want to have ten bottles
and I'm layering--

01:16:54.720 --> 01:16:56.160
[overlapping conversations]

01:16:56.240 --> 01:16:59.640
-You're confusing who the customer is.
-You're cross-selling.

01:16:59.720 --> 01:17:02.480
-Is it for yourself or to women?
-I'm telling--

01:17:02.560 --> 01:17:05.160
You started off saying women.
Then why do you keep thinking of Dilpreet?

01:17:06.240 --> 01:17:07.640
-Dilip.
-Dilip.

01:17:08.720 --> 01:17:10.160
-What did you call him?
-Dilpreet.

01:17:11.080 --> 01:17:15.640
No, but, tell me one thing.
You want to build a fragrance brand...

01:17:15.720 --> 01:17:17.160
Yeah. For women.

01:17:17.240 --> 01:17:21.200
Your issue is that you don't want them
to go to, like, ten fragrances,

01:17:21.280 --> 01:17:22.640
and buy Bella Vita--

01:17:22.720 --> 01:17:24.160
No, I don't want that.

01:17:24.240 --> 01:17:27.160
-But you can yourself create--
-You can do it.

01:17:27.240 --> 01:17:30.200
You sell it to the consumers
saying, "Hey, you take this fragrance.

01:17:30.280 --> 01:17:32.040
Great, you like it on its own. Amazing.

01:17:32.120 --> 01:17:33.560
But you take this plus this,

01:17:33.640 --> 01:17:35.720
and now you've got a fragrance,
especially for you.

01:17:35.800 --> 01:17:37.640
And I'm telling you
how to create it." So...

01:17:37.720 --> 01:17:39.200
You remember the big moment
with fragrance?

01:17:39.280 --> 01:17:40.560
The big aha moment in layering?

01:17:40.640 --> 01:17:41.920
-You know when it happened?
-I don't know.

01:17:42.000 --> 01:17:46.040
There was an Instagram reel which had
20 Bollywood actresses saying,

01:17:46.120 --> 01:17:50.160
"I just love how Shah Rukh Khan smells."
He will smoke--

01:17:50.240 --> 01:17:51.640
-He does smell good.
-But he smells amazing.

01:17:51.720 --> 01:17:54.440
There's Kareena Kapoor
and Priyanka Chopra and Katrina.

01:17:54.520 --> 01:17:57.800
All the women who men aspire to, like,

01:17:57.880 --> 01:18:00.120
date someone like her
or marry someone like her,

01:18:00.200 --> 01:18:02.640
saying, "This dude smells so good."

01:18:02.720 --> 01:18:04.720
And then, there's a separate video
of Shah Rukh Khan saying,

01:18:04.800 --> 01:18:06.640
"I layer two fragrances,

01:18:06.720 --> 01:18:08.760
Diptyque something
and something, something."

01:18:08.840 --> 01:18:13.080
And then, there are 20 Dilips in India
who combined these two fragrances,

01:18:13.160 --> 01:18:15.160
made a SKU and just sold it on Myntra.

01:18:15.240 --> 01:18:17.920
You know what he does?
He doesn't spray perfume on himself.

01:18:18.000 --> 01:18:20.640
He takes his jacket, holds it like this,
and he sprays.

01:18:20.720 --> 01:18:22.640
-Really?
-Like 20 times.

01:18:22.720 --> 01:18:24.640
-How do you know that?
-Because I've seen him do it.

01:18:26.240 --> 01:18:28.160
Some people also spray and walk into it.

01:18:28.240 --> 01:18:30.640
Yeah, that's, like, you do and then...

01:18:30.720 --> 01:18:33.720
Does any of that make a difference?
I'm not still selling this, guys.

01:18:33.800 --> 01:18:35.640
Like, Dilip has no own business
going right now.

01:18:36.720 --> 01:18:39.160
-You need to believe, Dilip.
-You need to have--

01:18:39.240 --> 01:18:41.160
[laughter]

01:18:41.240 --> 01:18:42.640
It's not working out.

01:18:42.720 --> 01:18:44.640
Dilip is not delusional enough
to be an entrepreneur.

01:18:44.720 --> 01:18:47.400
Fine, you want to do fragrances,
but you don't want to do the layering bit.

01:18:47.480 --> 01:18:50.160
-Yeah.
-Okay, fair. That's-- You don't--

01:18:50.240 --> 01:18:51.600
Okay, first thing,
I'm building for the mass,

01:18:51.680 --> 01:18:53.160
premium, or prestige category?

01:18:53.240 --> 01:18:55.160
I think three digit price point.

01:18:55.240 --> 01:18:58.640
I would say entry-premium,
because there's a great segment.

01:18:58.720 --> 01:19:00.640
-What price am I selling it?
-Above 1,000.

01:19:00.720 --> 01:19:03.640
-Yeah.
-But below 2,000.

01:19:03.720 --> 01:19:06.000
-No, that's too expensive.
-[Diipa] There are so many.

01:19:06.080 --> 01:19:10.160
You are very mass.
There's too many players under 1,000.

01:19:10.240 --> 01:19:12.160
I would say between
the 1,000 to 2,000 space.

01:19:12.240 --> 01:19:14.880
-1,000 to 2,000 is empty.
-That's not possible. How?

01:19:14.960 --> 01:19:16.640
How big-- Sorry, can I talk in Hindi?

01:19:16.720 --> 01:19:19.160
-Yeah.
-How big do you want the business to be?

01:19:19.240 --> 01:19:22.160
-500 crores.
-That's it? That's your upper limit?

01:19:22.240 --> 01:19:26.160
Then you can... I think that can be--
This can be much bigger with 1,000...

01:19:26.240 --> 01:19:27.640
That's it? Where have you come from?

01:19:27.720 --> 01:19:31.440
Zara is doing fragrances at 1,000 rupees.

01:19:31.520 --> 01:19:33.760
-How much does Zara sell?
-I'm just saying... entry price point.

01:19:33.840 --> 01:19:35.600
That becomes entry price point.

01:19:35.680 --> 01:19:38.640
-Because anything under that is...
-Too mass.

01:19:39.720 --> 01:19:42.160
My view is you should be able to give
value and aspiration.

01:19:42.240 --> 01:19:46.280
100%. But today,
when you're looking at a fragrance

01:19:46.360 --> 01:19:49.600
that is a Dior or a Chanel
or even lower, right?

01:19:49.680 --> 01:19:51.480
Everyone wants to aspire there.

01:19:51.560 --> 01:19:54.720
So, when you're talking about fragrance,

01:19:54.800 --> 01:19:57.240
you want to also make it
a little bit more aspirational.

01:19:57.320 --> 01:20:00.920
So, you can start small. So, you can say,
"Okay, I'll have a 50ml at 1,000.

01:20:01.000 --> 01:20:04.640
And then maybe a 30ml at 400 or 500."

01:20:04.720 --> 01:20:06.680
If you want to give them
good-quality perfume,

01:20:06.760 --> 01:20:10.160
if you look at a 599, 499,
you want a 80% margin--

01:20:10.240 --> 01:20:11.640
No, I was thinking more 999.

01:20:11.720 --> 01:20:13.160
Okay, that is 1,000.

01:20:13.240 --> 01:20:15.160
-That's 1,000.
-But not 1,000 to 2,000.

01:20:15.240 --> 01:20:16.640
999 is a very nice price point.

01:20:16.720 --> 01:20:18.440
But even that 80% margin,

01:20:18.520 --> 01:20:21.320
then, like, the quality of ingredients
you're gonna have

01:20:21.400 --> 01:20:24.560
are not gonna be as good
as the quality of ingredients

01:20:24.640 --> 01:20:26.640
that a proper perfume would have.

01:20:26.720 --> 01:20:28.640
And this is very true
in a market like beauty--

01:20:28.720 --> 01:20:31.120
Clean. I'm talking clean fragrances.

01:20:31.200 --> 01:20:35.160
No, just going to this point of margin
and everything.

01:20:35.240 --> 01:20:38.600
-As opposed to odour-free--
-The $200 product versus a $20 product,

01:20:38.680 --> 01:20:40.960
-there is a big difference.
-There is?

01:20:41.040 --> 01:20:43.560
Yeah, significantly,
because of the quality of ingredients.

01:20:43.640 --> 01:20:46.160
So, this is one industry
where you're, like,

01:20:46.240 --> 01:20:49.640
you know, particularly
in the efficacy of ingredients.

01:20:49.720 --> 01:20:51.160
But if he doesn't care about that...

01:20:51.240 --> 01:20:54.360
So, it doesn't mean that
you won't get the same results.

01:20:54.440 --> 01:20:58.160
But there is a difference in selling...

01:20:58.240 --> 01:21:01.440
You're not selling the same thing
at $20 and $200.

01:21:01.520 --> 01:21:03.680
The results can be the same

01:21:03.760 --> 01:21:06.520
because you're using
different kinds of ingredients.

01:21:06.600 --> 01:21:10.640
But, in an industry like beauty,
yes, there is mark-up, there is margin.

01:21:10.720 --> 01:21:14.160
I thought perfumes are like bottled water.
There's no difference between $200 and $2.

01:21:14.240 --> 01:21:17.640
Huge difference.
Just, if you would go to--

01:21:17.720 --> 01:21:20.440
-Don't they operate at 90% margin?
-Yeah, they do.

01:21:20.520 --> 01:21:23.160
So, nobody is spending more than,
like, 50 bucks in making the product.

01:21:23.240 --> 01:21:25.640
They do. But packaging makes
a big difference. Glass versus plastic.

01:21:25.720 --> 01:21:27.640
Forget packaging,
I'm talking about quality of product.

01:21:27.720 --> 01:21:29.960
It does.
Like, there's the weight of the oil.

01:21:30.040 --> 01:21:32.120
If you use pure saffron oil
versus if you use

01:21:32.200 --> 01:21:34.160
a synthetic saffron oil, huge difference.

01:21:34.240 --> 01:21:36.840
How much will it cost me
to make a 100ml perfume

01:21:36.920 --> 01:21:40.160
with pure, good, clean ingredients?
Less than 1,000.

01:21:40.920 --> 01:21:42.640
I think you can get it done
for 500 or 600.

01:21:42.720 --> 01:21:44.640
Okay, none of us have a fragrance brand.

01:21:44.720 --> 01:21:47.160
So, we can't really give you
that much detail.

01:21:47.240 --> 01:21:51.160
-And we won't be, like, accurate.
-Absolutely accurate about it.

01:21:51.240 --> 01:21:54.160
We just launched a 999 fragrance.

01:21:54.240 --> 01:21:57.080
Oh, he does have. Okay.
You can give him the details.

01:21:57.160 --> 01:21:59.160
We just launched, like, a week back.

01:21:59.920 --> 01:22:02.840
-Under which brand?
-Bombay Shaving Company.

01:22:02.920 --> 01:22:06.160
So, it's called Toxic Fruit
and Little Beach.

01:22:06.240 --> 01:22:08.160
-By Bombay Shav-- Fruit.
-You call your fragrance toxic?

01:22:08.240 --> 01:22:10.160
-Oh, like the forbidden fruit.
-Yeah.

01:22:10.240 --> 01:22:12.440
And Little Beach.
So, it's kind of rebellious.

01:22:12.520 --> 01:22:15.000
It's like Bombay Shaving Company
in a way, at 999.

01:22:15.080 --> 01:22:17.160
-So, it's a big price point for us.
-Online, offline?

01:22:17.240 --> 01:22:19.160
-Both.
-It's doing good?

01:22:19.240 --> 01:22:20.640
-Omnichannel.
-Start is good.

01:22:20.720 --> 01:22:22.840
-We are at 100 DRR now.
-[Diipa] Wow.

01:22:22.920 --> 01:22:25.640
We're selling 100 units per day.
But, it's good. People will try.

01:22:25.720 --> 01:22:28.160
Is that a non-negotiable? Omnichannel?

01:22:28.240 --> 01:22:30.400
-Yeah.
-I think, yeah. Today, omnichannel.

01:22:30.480 --> 01:22:33.640
If you want to grow at scale,
omnichannel is the way to go.

01:22:33.720 --> 01:22:37.200
And that's where multi-brand
retailers like us come in, right?

01:22:37.280 --> 01:22:40.160
Because if you're talking
about a D2C brand, yes,

01:22:40.240 --> 01:22:44.200
you can start your own website,
but I already have captive audience.

01:22:44.280 --> 01:22:45.880
I already have the customer.

01:22:45.960 --> 01:22:47.880
I had an idea, actually. There's a whole--

01:22:47.960 --> 01:22:50.440
-For Dilip or for me?
-For Dilip.

01:22:50.520 --> 01:22:52.360
We were thinking about community.
Like, for example,

01:22:53.360 --> 01:22:56.880
there's a huge opportunity to build out
the fraghead community of India.

01:22:56.960 --> 01:22:58.880
-Explain. I don't even know--
-Fragheads are people who--

01:22:58.960 --> 01:23:00.360
-Like sneakerheads.
-Like sneakerheads.

01:23:00.440 --> 01:23:03.440
But fragheads are people who understand--
So, they're called "noses."

01:23:03.520 --> 01:23:06.400
So, if you're a nose, you can distinguish
between multiple notes.

01:23:06.480 --> 01:23:08.640
And there is, like,
in a group of five friends,

01:23:08.720 --> 01:23:12.160
the nose has become
like this status symbol that you're--

01:23:12.240 --> 01:23:15.360
It's like a good wine-taster
in a group of people who like wine.

01:23:15.440 --> 01:23:18.000
-For example.
-Like, a sneakerhead is cool.

01:23:18.080 --> 01:23:20.360
A sommelier is cool.
I don't know about fragheads.

01:23:20.440 --> 01:23:21.640
That's what he's saying, build it up.

01:23:21.720 --> 01:23:22.960
-[Shantanu] Build it up.
-Make it cool.

01:23:23.040 --> 01:23:24.880
-That becomes a common purpose.
-How we made the champi cool.

01:23:24.960 --> 01:23:27.360
-And that's a community.
-Then, it's a community.

01:23:27.440 --> 01:23:30.080
Now, you can also make insane content
about this community.

01:23:30.160 --> 01:23:33.360
You get fragheads into your podca--
Whatever. To your Bangalore home.

01:23:33.440 --> 01:23:35.880
I can go around smelling celebrities...

01:23:35.960 --> 01:23:37.360
-Yeah.
-...and making expressions.

01:23:37.440 --> 01:23:40.160
Have smelling events. Bring them together.

01:23:40.240 --> 01:23:42.880
Let them create their own
signature perfume.

01:23:42.960 --> 01:23:44.880
And then you can have food
associated with it.

01:23:44.960 --> 01:23:47.760
Can I tell you a funny story?

01:23:47.840 --> 01:23:50.720
So, I rented this place some time ago.

01:23:50.800 --> 01:23:53.760
And I've had a few house managers
along the way.

01:23:53.840 --> 01:23:57.520
One of them--
For three months of the year,

01:23:57.600 --> 01:24:00.840
the area smells like dead fish.

01:24:00.920 --> 01:24:05.160
One of them joined. I was not in town.
I spend, like, a week a month here.

01:24:05.240 --> 01:24:09.640
One of them joined and quit
even before he could ever meet me.

01:24:09.720 --> 01:24:13.360
And he said this area smells so bad
that he can't survive.

01:24:13.440 --> 01:24:14.880
-Wow!
-Wow!

01:24:14.960 --> 01:24:17.880
-So, smell is a big--
-He had a very strong nose, yeah.

01:24:17.960 --> 01:24:19.880
So, smell is a problem.

01:24:21.120 --> 01:24:28.040
But good smell is not equally proportional
as an incentive to do a trigger.

01:24:28.120 --> 01:24:29.880
To be a trigger event.

01:24:29.960 --> 01:24:31.360
No, it is. In what way?

01:24:31.440 --> 01:24:35.680
Like, I feel like I can sell fear
around bad smell

01:24:35.760 --> 01:24:38.880
much more than I can sell
the incentive of good smell.

01:24:38.960 --> 01:24:41.120
-No, no, no. I totally disagree with you.
-[Bhakti and Diipa] No!

01:24:41.200 --> 01:24:44.160
-No?
-Because good smell triggers--

01:24:44.240 --> 01:24:45.720
Again, we spoke about emotion.

01:24:45.800 --> 01:24:49.000
It triggers that emotion in you,
it triggers a memory.

01:24:49.080 --> 01:24:50.440
It triggers something.

01:24:50.520 --> 01:24:54.360
It takes you back to some moment
in your life.

01:24:54.440 --> 01:24:56.880
-It also triggers a memory.
-The same way, makeup,

01:24:56.960 --> 01:24:59.240
like, when women put it on,

01:24:59.320 --> 01:25:00.920
they feel almost like this...

01:25:01.000 --> 01:25:04.920
more confident versions of themselves,
perfume has the power to do that, too.

01:25:05.000 --> 01:25:07.720
The second you smell
an incredible perfume--

01:25:07.800 --> 01:25:11.000
Like, I can feel suddenly
more stronger in myself.

01:25:11.080 --> 01:25:14.720
Or you can armour yourself or something.
Or you feel more sophisticated.

01:25:14.800 --> 01:25:18.360
Or you feel more... It's like another--
like, putting on clothes.

01:25:18.440 --> 01:25:19.880
It's sensual as well.

01:25:19.960 --> 01:25:21.920
Yeah, it's like another part
of your identity you can put on.

01:25:22.000 --> 01:25:24.360
-Some people...
-Big time. It's happening a lot.

01:25:24.440 --> 01:25:26.520
Some people can have the same fragrance
for many years.

01:25:26.600 --> 01:25:28.880
Like, Old Spice, my dad. Like, forever--

01:25:28.960 --> 01:25:31.360
-I love Old Spice.
-That generation...

01:25:31.440 --> 01:25:32.880
I love everything that smells
like a barber shop.

01:25:32.960 --> 01:25:35.360
Oh, why doesn't Dilip make Old Spice
in a new way?

01:25:35.440 --> 01:25:38.880
Nostalgia, plus a smell
that everyone remembers.

01:25:38.960 --> 01:25:40.360
-Like, spicy.
-[Shantanu] Layer it up, right?

01:25:40.440 --> 01:25:42.880
I think it's a fantastic idea.

01:25:42.960 --> 01:25:45.880
-And throw in a Cool Water.
-Mixed with--

01:25:45.960 --> 01:25:48.280
-Oh, wait for this, whiskey smoke.
-Yeah.

01:25:48.360 --> 01:25:53.360
-Or Old Spice, plus, like, Danish--
-He's like, "Mmm!"

01:25:53.440 --> 01:25:56.360
That could work.
Old Spice with a vegetable?

01:25:56.440 --> 01:25:59.360
-No, I think bakery.
-You make it so un-sexy so quickly.

01:25:59.440 --> 01:26:02.360
I think, by the end of this,
we are never going to want to...

01:26:02.440 --> 01:26:04.880
-Cabbage?
-...create a fragrance brand.

01:26:05.960 --> 01:26:08.000
-Old Spice jalebis?
-Yeah.

01:26:08.080 --> 01:26:10.360
-I think that'll do really well.
-You can make an entire--

01:26:10.440 --> 01:26:11.880
Old Spice and sweet is like a very nice--

01:26:11.960 --> 01:26:15.360
...a bath and body range
as well with that.

01:26:17.440 --> 01:26:19.680
I think step one, for you,
is to find a good nose.

01:26:19.760 --> 01:26:22.600
Because cabbage and Old Spice--
Let them do it.

01:26:22.680 --> 01:26:24.360
You can develop it, I think.

01:26:24.440 --> 01:26:26.880
-No, I don't think--
-He cannot develop this.

01:26:26.960 --> 01:26:29.360
Your bathroom, there's some
really nice fragrances, by the way.

01:26:29.440 --> 01:26:31.880
-That doesn't mean he's a good nose.
-I'm assuming you have...

01:26:31.960 --> 01:26:34.360
-You have to be unbiased.
-...had some say on--

01:26:34.440 --> 01:26:37.680
I've had no say on anything in life,
pretty much.

01:26:37.760 --> 01:26:40.360
But... let's say Old Spice.

01:26:40.440 --> 01:26:41.880
What did we say with?

01:26:41.960 --> 01:26:43.360
-Danish pastry, I think?
-Cabbage.

01:26:44.960 --> 01:26:46.960
-I think... With bakery.
-Old Spice with jalebi.

01:26:47.040 --> 01:26:49.360
-With bakery or jalebi.
-Jalebis are not sexy.

01:26:49.440 --> 01:26:51.880
-Basque cheesecake.
-Jalebis are sexy?

01:26:51.960 --> 01:26:53.560
-Old Spice with leather.
-You'll be amazed, Nikhil...

01:26:53.640 --> 01:26:55.360
-...how much--
-Do you wanna make it for men or women?

01:26:55.440 --> 01:26:56.880
-Women.
-Women.

01:26:56.960 --> 01:26:58.880
Old Spice with something
gourmand, yeah? Vanilla.

01:26:58.960 --> 01:27:00.360
-Vanilla.
-Vanilla.

01:27:00.440 --> 01:27:03.360
We'll have men for that.
We'll have men takers for that.

01:27:03.440 --> 01:27:06.640
-Yeah, I like vanilla-smelling perfumes.
-Yeah.

01:27:06.720 --> 01:27:09.360
Vanilla is one of the most popular
scent profiles.

01:27:09.440 --> 01:27:10.880
I don't know.

01:27:10.960 --> 01:27:13.560
I don't know if this is selling,
but we'll come back to this, okay?

01:27:14.720 --> 01:27:16.800
So, community offline helps.

01:27:16.880 --> 01:27:18.280
Online also helps.

01:27:18.360 --> 01:27:22.360
Offline, I think, has an impact
which is exponential in nature.

01:27:22.440 --> 01:27:25.200
I don't know why, with most communities,
I've found that.

01:27:25.280 --> 01:27:26.960
When I bring a bunch of people together

01:27:27.040 --> 01:27:30.200
who see each other physically
and touch each other--

01:27:30.280 --> 01:27:34.360
-"Touch each other." I think it kind of...
-You sound like a cult.

01:27:35.960 --> 01:27:37.880
No, but if you're doing offline--

01:27:37.960 --> 01:27:40.200
Like, making content around it

01:27:40.280 --> 01:27:42.360
and distributing it on
fraghead communities--

01:27:42.440 --> 01:27:43.880
Yeah, exactly.
There is a dual effect for that.

01:27:43.960 --> 01:27:46.040
-And, I agree, patriotism is selling.
-Yeah.

01:27:46.120 --> 01:27:48.360
And Trump has four years left.

01:27:48.440 --> 01:27:51.400
-Three, three and a half.
-It'll sell more up until then.

01:27:52.440 --> 01:27:53.440
His tariffs affecting you?

01:27:54.440 --> 01:27:56.200
Big time. You were asking...

01:27:56.280 --> 01:27:58.760
One of your first questions was
your share in business, right?

01:27:58.840 --> 01:28:01.360
Um, US used to be 60%.

01:28:01.440 --> 01:28:02.880
-Uh-huh.
-And, in the last year,

01:28:04.160 --> 01:28:05.800
thanks to people like Tira,

01:28:05.880 --> 01:28:08.560
our retail has grown 500% in India.

01:28:08.640 --> 01:28:11.360
And now, India is 60% and US is 40%.

01:28:11.440 --> 01:28:14.360
So, back then, US was 40,
and India was, uh--

01:28:14.440 --> 01:28:16.880
US was 60, India was 40.
Now, it's flipped.

01:28:17.840 --> 01:28:19.360
This is another thing that India has done.

01:28:19.440 --> 01:28:20.880
Where do you manufacture?

01:28:20.960 --> 01:28:25.000
Um, I'm one of those really
product-obsessed people.

01:28:25.080 --> 01:28:26.840
We go wherever the best manufacturing is.

01:28:26.920 --> 01:28:28.160
It's not-- My husband hates it

01:28:28.240 --> 01:28:30.360
'cause he does the ops and finance part.

01:28:30.440 --> 01:28:32.480
-You guys work together?
-We do.

01:28:32.560 --> 01:28:34.360
-Wow.
-We're co-founders, yeah.

01:28:34.440 --> 01:28:35.880
-[Shantanu] Wow.
-So, where do you manufacture?

01:28:35.960 --> 01:28:39.160
So, we manufacture, um,
like, Champi is in India, obviously.

01:28:39.240 --> 01:28:40.840
But like, our lip balms are in Korea,

01:28:40.920 --> 01:28:43.000
'cause I found the best lab there for it.

01:28:43.080 --> 01:28:44.560
Our eye cream is Japan.

01:28:44.640 --> 01:28:48.360
Again, Indian ingredients,
but manufactured in Japan.

01:28:48.440 --> 01:28:49.880
So, tariffs are hitting you,
but not at 50%.

01:28:49.960 --> 01:28:51.880
Every corner. Every side.

01:28:51.960 --> 01:28:53.600
This might be an opportunity in itself.

01:28:53.680 --> 01:28:56.360
Make Indian products
outside of India to beat tariffs.

01:28:56.440 --> 01:28:57.800
Yeah.

01:28:57.880 --> 01:28:58.880
-I'm--
-Sorry,

01:28:58.960 --> 01:29:00.880
-make Indian products where?
-Outside of India.

01:29:00.960 --> 01:29:02.360
-Why?
-Make Indian products

01:29:02.440 --> 01:29:03.480
-outside of India.
-There is a demand

01:29:03.560 --> 01:29:05.480
for Indian products,
and you don't have to pay 50%.

01:29:05.560 --> 01:29:07.280
And sell them there. Yeah.

01:29:07.360 --> 01:29:09.360
For the American market.
I'm not suggesting that.

01:29:09.440 --> 01:29:10.880
It's a bad idea.

01:29:10.960 --> 01:29:13.000
A lot of Indian companies
have now created US subsidiaries

01:29:13.080 --> 01:29:15.040
-because of TikTok shop.
-Yeah.

01:29:15.120 --> 01:29:17.400
-TikTok shop is huge.
-It's huge.

01:29:18.440 --> 01:29:20.480
A lot of people,
when I was researching this,

01:29:20.560 --> 01:29:21.560
told me that...

01:29:22.280 --> 01:29:26.040
Instagram is content created by brands.

01:29:26.120 --> 01:29:28.880
-And TikTok is more UGC.
-Yes. That's--

01:29:28.960 --> 01:29:32.360
I mean, there is TikTokification happening
of Instagram as well.

01:29:32.440 --> 01:29:34.880
-I don't think it's managed to crack it.
-What is it called? Perfume talk.

01:29:34.960 --> 01:29:37.360
-Perfume talk, yeah.
-Perfume talk, yeah. Perfume talk.

01:29:37.440 --> 01:29:39.680
There's every talk.
Like, in TikTok, there is every talk...

01:29:39.760 --> 01:29:41.800
-Skin talk, hair talk, hair oiling talk.
-Frag talk, perfume talk.

01:29:41.880 --> 01:29:43.920
This talk, that talk, every talk.

01:29:44.000 --> 01:29:46.040
And TikTok is insane.

01:29:46.120 --> 01:29:48.360
I hope we get it to India soon. Um...

01:29:48.440 --> 01:29:50.360
No, buddy. Have you seen...

01:29:50.440 --> 01:29:52.960
But recently, we saw some news, right?
China, India were shaking hands.

01:29:53.040 --> 01:29:54.840
I met a Unilever guy who heads China.

01:29:56.160 --> 01:29:57.840
So, we hear all these numbers, no?

01:29:57.920 --> 01:29:59.840
I was blown away.
I don't know whether you know this.

01:29:59.920 --> 01:30:02.520
Douyin, which is TikTok, is 40% of retail.

01:30:03.440 --> 01:30:05.720
It has broken
every marketing rule possible

01:30:05.800 --> 01:30:07.080
for one reason.

01:30:07.160 --> 01:30:10.400
It's because there's now
so much content for consumers,

01:30:10.480 --> 01:30:13.880
they're doing four hours of research
before they buy a face wash.

01:30:14.520 --> 01:30:16.360
So, now this whole thing
that if you're creating a brand,

01:30:16.440 --> 01:30:17.880
then just tell me one message
for ten years...

01:30:17.960 --> 01:30:20.360
But it's gone out of the window.
You have to tell everything.

01:30:20.440 --> 01:30:22.480
But you're still buying more than
you would have bought,

01:30:22.560 --> 01:30:24.120
-if not for TikTok.
-Consumption goes up,

01:30:24.200 --> 01:30:25.760
but it becomes very noisy.

01:30:25.840 --> 01:30:26.880
Very noisy.

01:30:26.960 --> 01:30:28.400
-So brands--
-But net-net good only, no?

01:30:29.680 --> 01:30:31.720
But the question then is,
why doesn't TikTok

01:30:31.800 --> 01:30:33.280
create their white-labelled products

01:30:33.360 --> 01:30:36.360
if they know what sells
and they can influence it?

01:30:36.440 --> 01:30:37.880
'Cause that's not the game
they're playing in.

01:30:37.960 --> 01:30:39.480
It's like Amazon
not making private labels.

01:30:39.560 --> 01:30:41.080
-Why would they?
-Eventually, the Chinese companies

01:30:41.160 --> 01:30:42.880
tend to do everything, right?

01:30:42.960 --> 01:30:44.880
I don't think they need to.

01:30:44.960 --> 01:30:46.360
Like, Amazon does that.

01:30:46.440 --> 01:30:47.960
Now they have TikTok shops

01:30:48.040 --> 01:30:50.920
where they keep a percentage
of every sale every brand does.

01:30:51.000 --> 01:30:52.880
So, they're already making so much.

01:30:54.440 --> 01:30:57.040
And ad sales on top of that.
And shop sales.

01:30:57.120 --> 01:30:59.880
So, like, they have enough
revenue... streams.

01:30:59.960 --> 01:31:04.200
But making globally relevant fragrances
will be a good idea for Dilip.

01:31:04.920 --> 01:31:07.200
-Coming back to...
-Dilip.

01:31:07.280 --> 01:31:08.280
You might be Dilip.

01:31:09.280 --> 01:31:11.200
I think building from India
for the world...

01:31:13.280 --> 01:31:14.440
is something that--

01:31:14.520 --> 01:31:16.200
We have to start doing
a lot more of what she does.

01:31:16.280 --> 01:31:17.680
What indē wild is doing.

01:31:17.760 --> 01:31:19.800
-Yeah.
-100%. I think the world's ready.

01:31:19.880 --> 01:31:23.040
Like, we've had Korean skincare, beauty,

01:31:23.120 --> 01:31:25.040
obviously, explode in the world.

01:31:25.120 --> 01:31:27.800
-Japanese skincare, beauty.
-Japanese.

01:31:27.880 --> 01:31:29.800
We've had fragrances from France.

01:31:29.880 --> 01:31:31.400
We've had skincare from France.

01:31:31.480 --> 01:31:32.480
Like, it's all happened.

01:31:33.120 --> 01:31:34.480
-It's time--
-It's time for India.

01:31:34.560 --> 01:31:36.680
It's time for India.
And indē wild doing that.

01:31:36.760 --> 01:31:39.560
And we've done it with Ayurveda.

01:31:39.640 --> 01:31:40.840
-We've done a bunch of exporting.
-Yeah.

01:31:40.920 --> 01:31:43.280
But still, the UK-- Still, like--
If you look at Kama, Forest,

01:31:43.360 --> 01:31:44.680
they're only in the UK.

01:31:44.760 --> 01:31:47.800
-Like, nobody really dominated the US.
-I feel like that's a big step, right?

01:31:47.880 --> 01:31:53.320
For a brand to go outside of India,
have this stunning presence,

01:31:53.400 --> 01:31:54.800
and for people to kind of

01:31:54.880 --> 01:31:56.840
-bench it on global...
-Yeah.

01:31:56.920 --> 01:31:59.560
...uh, you know, with global brands.

01:31:59.640 --> 01:32:01.400
And take their names in the same breath.

01:32:01.480 --> 01:32:05.160
And I think we would have never
imagined that, like, ten years ago.

01:32:05.240 --> 01:32:06.680
And I think that just goes back
to what you said...

01:32:06.760 --> 01:32:08.280
-So, the fact that--
-[Shantanu] But we've done it.

01:32:08.360 --> 01:32:09.800
...patriotism, pride.

01:32:09.880 --> 01:32:11.480
But even ten years ago,
when I was growing up,

01:32:11.560 --> 01:32:14.760
I would never imagine Sephora,
the Sephora,

01:32:14.840 --> 01:32:18.680
take an Indian brand like indē wild,
and build a global partnership.

01:32:18.760 --> 01:32:20.200
-Yeah.
-I mean, Sephora America

01:32:20.280 --> 01:32:24.040
is, like, the World Cup of beauty.

01:32:24.120 --> 01:32:26.240
Like, there's nothing bigger
than Sephora North America.

01:32:26.320 --> 01:32:29.360
And for them to be like, "indē wild,
we want you to come launch with us,"

01:32:29.440 --> 01:32:30.520
is... Yeah.

01:32:30.600 --> 01:32:33.680
And Ayurveda and Indian beauty, for sure.

01:32:33.760 --> 01:32:35.200
We haven't celebrated enough.

01:32:35.280 --> 01:32:38.200
Ayurveda is hugely, like,
popular right now.

01:32:38.280 --> 01:32:42.120
You know the supermarket store,
Erewhon, right, in LA?

01:32:42.200 --> 01:32:44.200
-So, this time, I went there.
-You get $40 smoothies there,

01:32:44.280 --> 01:32:46.200
-by the way.
-I like going there.

01:32:46.280 --> 01:32:49.280
It's so good.
But it's expensive, but it's good.

01:32:49.360 --> 01:32:50.680
But if you look at their shelves,

01:32:50.760 --> 01:32:54.160
everything, shilajit, shatavari,
turmeric, ashwagandha.

01:32:54.240 --> 01:32:56.280
Like, there is a craze,

01:32:56.360 --> 01:32:59.200
in, at least, the wellness, like,
and of longevity--

01:32:59.280 --> 01:33:01.280
-And there's a lot of sea moss.
-Sea moss.

01:33:01.360 --> 01:33:03.440
Yeah, but that's not Indian.
I'm focusing on the Indian ones.

01:33:03.520 --> 01:33:05.200
That's the main thing in the store.

01:33:05.280 --> 01:33:06.800
I think it's a way of life, right?

01:33:06.880 --> 01:33:09.720
And I think that, to your point,
when we were talking about

01:33:09.800 --> 01:33:11.920
what we got from the West, right?

01:33:12.000 --> 01:33:14.960
I think now,
Indians are kind of understanding

01:33:15.040 --> 01:33:19.640
the longstanding traditions
and heritage that India comes with.

01:33:19.720 --> 01:33:21.560
And kind of... We've always had it.

01:33:21.640 --> 01:33:23.760
I think we're just now
extremely proud of it.

01:33:23.840 --> 01:33:26.960
And I think Indian beauty
is a way of life.

01:33:27.040 --> 01:33:28.560
-Wellness.
-Yeah.

01:33:28.640 --> 01:33:31.240
I think it's wellness, like, with Ayurveda

01:33:31.320 --> 01:33:35.040
has really been, like,
intricately woven into India for so long,

01:33:35.120 --> 01:33:37.240
that we ourselves
didn't give it enough credit.

01:33:37.320 --> 01:33:40.640
Like, if you look at yoga, meditation,
breathwork, mindfulness,

01:33:40.720 --> 01:33:42.080
we've all had it, you know.

01:33:42.160 --> 01:33:44.200
It took the West to be like, "Wow!"

01:33:44.920 --> 01:33:47.240
Scientifically prove it,
and now, we're like,

01:33:47.320 --> 01:33:49.680
"Oh, my God,
we should be nervous system reset."

01:33:50.520 --> 01:33:52.200
Kapalbhati, you know?

01:33:52.280 --> 01:33:56.240
Do you think a high-end
boutique hotel, like Aman,

01:33:56.320 --> 01:34:00.680
with Indian yoga, breathwork,
turmeric, all of that will do well?

01:34:00.760 --> 01:34:02.680
-It will...
-Like, insane.

01:34:02.760 --> 01:34:04.440
-Insane.
-Insane.

01:34:04.520 --> 01:34:06.680
I think Kapil is doing that with Postcard
in a way, no?

01:34:06.760 --> 01:34:08.920
-It's all about longevity...
-That's more India, inward-looking.

01:34:09.000 --> 01:34:10.200
I'm talking outside of India.

01:34:10.280 --> 01:34:13.040
-And outside, it will work even better.
-Even better.

01:34:13.120 --> 01:34:15.360
He has something in Bhutan.
I think he's going outside now.

01:34:15.440 --> 01:34:16.800
He wants to build
the best hotel in the world.

01:34:16.880 --> 01:34:19.480
-But, guys, like, the longevity...
-But that's not so much around wellness.

01:34:19.560 --> 01:34:21.680
Postcard is more take a home,
retain the aesthetic.

01:34:21.760 --> 01:34:23.200
Postcard is more... Yeah, exactly that.

01:34:23.280 --> 01:34:24.680
Clean.

01:34:24.760 --> 01:34:26.680
There's no yoga. There's no breathwork.

01:34:26.760 --> 01:34:28.920
-There's no wellness.
-[Diipa] No.

01:34:29.000 --> 01:34:31.200
It's not pivoted on wellness.

01:34:31.280 --> 01:34:35.000
I think the searches in the pandemic
for, like, ingredients like ghee.

01:34:35.080 --> 01:34:37.400
Like, all the fitness bros now
cook in ghee.

01:34:37.480 --> 01:34:40.240
You know? Because, like,
the smoke point is really high,

01:34:40.320 --> 01:34:41.720
and it's super healthy.

01:34:41.800 --> 01:34:44.280
-Our dadi was like, "Cook in ghee."
-Desi ghee.

01:34:44.360 --> 01:34:45.920
"It's the best,"
and we never believed her.

01:34:46.000 --> 01:34:48.800
But now, indeed, they're all
getting scientifically backed,

01:34:48.880 --> 01:34:50.200
and it's growing a lot.

01:34:50.280 --> 01:34:51.920
What about influence?

01:34:52.680 --> 01:34:53.920
I'm starting a brand.

01:34:55.760 --> 01:34:58.280
I have figured out, maybe,

01:34:58.360 --> 01:35:01.960
how to make a deal with salons,
if it's in hair.

01:35:02.040 --> 01:35:06.040
I figured out a old product
I can bring back and sell nostalgia.

01:35:06.920 --> 01:35:11.360
I have added the Indian narrative to it.

01:35:11.440 --> 01:35:13.600
Patriotism. I have found a emotion.

01:35:13.680 --> 01:35:15.040
I have doubled down on the emotion.

01:35:15.120 --> 01:35:17.920
I talk to the people who follow me,
the few people.

01:35:18.000 --> 01:35:20.400
I listen and I speak to them often.

01:35:21.920 --> 01:35:22.920
And I have figured out that

01:35:23.000 --> 01:35:25.120
I have one hero product
that I'm starting with.

01:35:25.200 --> 01:35:28.880
That product is, let's say, a moisturiser.

01:35:28.960 --> 01:35:30.480
Okay, for the lack of a better word.

01:35:32.120 --> 01:35:33.680
Omnichannel. I'm on Tira.

01:35:33.760 --> 01:35:36.960
I'm in some physical stores.
I'm selling online, all of that.

01:35:37.880 --> 01:35:42.120
Now, I have come to a point
where I've realised that

01:35:42.760 --> 01:35:45.000
all of this is only taking it so far,

01:35:45.080 --> 01:35:48.560
and I need to figure out
my influencing and marketing piece.

01:35:48.640 --> 01:35:49.640
How do I do that?

01:35:49.720 --> 01:35:50.880
Are you sure the product works?

01:35:50.960 --> 01:35:54.360
-The 100--
-The hero product question.

01:35:54.440 --> 01:35:57.360
The 100 people I'm speaking to
right now are buying it.

01:35:57.440 --> 01:35:58.880
-So, your repeat rates are 70-80%.
-Yeah.

01:35:59.920 --> 01:36:02.800
Then... then my view is...

01:36:02.880 --> 01:36:04.400
My view has always been, like,

01:36:04.480 --> 01:36:08.080
the best influencers
are your current customers.

01:36:08.160 --> 01:36:10.360
-And the best--
-Not celebrities who I...

01:36:10.440 --> 01:36:12.600
Not-- not early on, no?

01:36:12.680 --> 01:36:15.920
My view is just take the product
and start sending it to celebrities.

01:36:16.000 --> 01:36:18.000
-And see who starts liking it.
-Can I do that?

01:36:18.080 --> 01:36:19.360
Just send it to them and they'll post it?

01:36:19.440 --> 01:36:20.880
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:36:20.960 --> 01:36:23.320
-Has a celebrity posted it for you?
-Oh, plenty of times.

01:36:23.400 --> 01:36:24.880
-Just by sending it to them?
-Yeah, plenty of times.

01:36:24.960 --> 01:36:26.360
-[Diipa] That's lovely.
-Who?

01:36:26.440 --> 01:36:29.000
Men. Multiple.
So, we send it to Rannvijay.

01:36:29.080 --> 01:36:30.360
We send it to Ashwin.

01:36:30.440 --> 01:36:32.880
-We send it to...
-[Diipa] Who's Ashwin?

01:36:32.960 --> 01:36:35.360
The off-spinner. The Indian cricketer.

01:36:35.440 --> 01:36:37.360
If she's asking who,
there's a problem with the celebrity.

01:36:39.520 --> 01:36:41.760
-The cricketer.
-It's a different-- different demographic.

01:36:41.840 --> 01:36:42.960
Legend cricketer.

01:36:44.720 --> 01:36:47.800
When we launched the head shaver,
we had sent it to Raghu and Rajiv.

01:36:47.880 --> 01:36:48.880
-Uh...
-[Diipa] Oh!

01:36:48.960 --> 01:36:50.480
-They posted?
-Uh-huh.

01:36:50.560 --> 01:36:52.360
-Raghu and Rajiv. In fact--
-Just on--

01:36:52.440 --> 01:36:53.960
-They're legends.
-Yeah.

01:36:54.040 --> 01:36:55.680
-Handwritten note from the founder.
-Wow.

01:36:55.760 --> 01:36:56.960
Handwritten note from the founder.

01:36:57.040 --> 01:36:59.320
Someone from the team
getting in touch for the address.

01:36:59.400 --> 01:37:02.480
Like, you have to make the effort
to make the person feel special.

01:37:02.560 --> 01:37:05.120
Perhaps it was less cluttered then?

01:37:05.200 --> 01:37:07.360
-Were you the first one?
-There's no head shaver.

01:37:07.440 --> 01:37:10.440
With Ashwin, it was with trimmers.

01:37:10.520 --> 01:37:12.360
With Rannvijay also, it was trimmers.

01:37:12.440 --> 01:37:14.800
-Because when did you start the brand?
-2016.

01:37:14.880 --> 01:37:17.040
Okay, so it was
a less cluttered market. No?

01:37:17.120 --> 01:37:20.960
-Which one? Trimmers?
-In men grooming, skincare...

01:37:21.040 --> 01:37:23.840
It was a smaller market,
but it was getting cluttered quickly.

01:37:23.920 --> 01:37:25.880
There were, like, some legacy players.
This is similar.

01:37:25.960 --> 01:37:27.320
Tell me some conversion rates.

01:37:27.400 --> 01:37:30.680
How many celebrities did you send it to,
and how many posted?

01:37:30.760 --> 01:37:32.480
What was the cost of that exercise?

01:37:35.200 --> 01:37:38.760
Till date, we have probably sent
10,000-12,000...

01:37:40.120 --> 01:37:44.760
free samplers to micro influencers,
macro influencers, creators,

01:37:44.840 --> 01:37:47.720
and then cricketers, actors,
television, et cetera.

01:37:48.720 --> 01:37:50.520
We've probably had 500 organic.

01:37:51.160 --> 01:37:52.880
500 organic. 5%.

01:37:52.960 --> 01:37:56.360
Is it more the product or your letter
that is getting the trigger?

01:37:56.440 --> 01:37:57.720
It's a combination.

01:37:57.800 --> 01:38:00.760
I think as I have also
built a public profile,

01:38:00.840 --> 01:38:02.200
people also know that, "Okay,

01:38:03.160 --> 01:38:05.120
this can be like a give-and-take thing."

01:38:05.200 --> 01:38:06.880
And then, the conversion
has gone up as a brand.

01:38:06.960 --> 01:38:09.880
So, they post and you repost
and that gets them distribution.

01:38:09.960 --> 01:38:12.880
-Post, repost--
-But I don't have that as a new person.

01:38:12.960 --> 01:38:14.360
I don't think any celebrity will...

01:38:14.440 --> 01:38:17.360
So, I'm keeping quiet,
'cause I love influencer marketing

01:38:17.440 --> 01:38:20.280
and topic, like, we do it very well.

01:38:20.360 --> 01:38:23.480
But, indeed, if you're telling me
the person is starting

01:38:23.560 --> 01:38:24.960
-with no following...
-Mmm.

01:38:25.960 --> 01:38:28.200
...it is a harder game, indeed.

01:38:28.280 --> 01:38:31.760
A lot of people like our...
We send about, per launch,

01:38:31.840 --> 01:38:35.360
say, 500 to 600 influencer boxes
for any launch.

01:38:36.960 --> 01:38:38.960
-50% post us.
-Yeah.

01:38:39.040 --> 01:38:41.440
50%, because they're like,
"Diipa will repost.

01:38:41.520 --> 01:38:42.640
Diipa will look at it."

01:38:42.720 --> 01:38:45.360
Or I think that's an aspect,

01:38:45.440 --> 01:38:49.680
and second aspect I think is
indē wild is such a loved brand

01:38:49.760 --> 01:38:51.600
that they look forward to the PR box.

01:38:51.680 --> 01:38:53.760
'Cause every time a PR box
is an experience,

01:38:53.840 --> 01:38:57.320
it's like-- and so, for a young girl
to get an amazing box

01:38:57.400 --> 01:39:00.800
where you open it and it looks
super pretty and the product is there,

01:39:00.880 --> 01:39:04.040
they want to show the content
to their following as well.

01:39:04.120 --> 01:39:08.160
So, it becomes like
a content piece for them, altogether.

01:39:08.240 --> 01:39:11.920
So we have
a really high organic love

01:39:12.000 --> 01:39:16.120
and kind of push for packages and gifting,

01:39:16.200 --> 01:39:20.800
but if I didn't have a following,
I don't know. It's a hard one.

01:39:20.880 --> 01:39:22.800
I would say, indeed,
you start with micros then.

01:39:22.880 --> 01:39:25.360
Start with nanos and micros who,

01:39:25.440 --> 01:39:28.680
even if they have 2,000
or 5,000 followers,

01:39:28.760 --> 01:39:31.600
you start with them and start
building them into a community,

01:39:31.680 --> 01:39:33.560
the word that we keep saying.

01:39:33.640 --> 01:39:37.640
And then, start from there,
and then start levelling up slowly.

01:39:39.000 --> 01:39:41.640
And that's where I think that
shared purpose or value comes, right?

01:39:41.720 --> 01:39:43.840
That you find those creators

01:39:43.920 --> 01:39:45.320
-who align with your brand.
-The key ones.

01:39:45.400 --> 01:39:46.800
Who are the fragheads or--

01:39:46.880 --> 01:39:50.160
And they grow with you
because I think that's the beauty of it.

01:39:51.760 --> 01:39:56.800
If you don't have that much money,
you will have about 20 of them versus--

01:39:56.880 --> 01:40:00.200
And I truly believe
that the nanos and the micros

01:40:00.280 --> 01:40:02.280
get you a lot more traction.

01:40:02.360 --> 01:40:03.400
-Organic reach.
-And conversion.

01:40:03.480 --> 01:40:04.920
-And conversion.
-Yeah.

01:40:05.000 --> 01:40:07.440
Versus, you know, using mega influencers.

01:40:07.520 --> 01:40:10.800
You use mega influencers
for the awareness.

01:40:10.880 --> 01:40:13.320
And the problem with mega is
they are very used to getting paid.

01:40:13.400 --> 01:40:14.800
-Exactly.
-So, because they're so used to

01:40:14.880 --> 01:40:17.800
getting paid, and they get
1,000 packages a month

01:40:17.880 --> 01:40:20.200
from all the different brands
in the world,

01:40:20.280 --> 01:40:23.200
for an unknown small brand,
they're less likely to open it,

01:40:23.280 --> 01:40:24.320
so it goes to waste.

01:40:24.400 --> 01:40:26.400
-And they charge a lot.
-And they charge a lot.

01:40:26.480 --> 01:40:28.920
It's all brand collab--
paid brand collaboration.

01:40:30.280 --> 01:40:31.480
By the way, Meta...

01:40:31.560 --> 01:40:34.960
Instagram is now bigger than WhatsApp
in India on daily active.

01:40:35.040 --> 01:40:36.560
It's a crazy number.
Did you guys know this?

01:40:36.640 --> 01:40:38.720
-[Diipa] No.
-Instagram, like, two weeks back,

01:40:38.800 --> 01:40:40.960
has gone ahead of WhatsApp
on daily actives.

01:40:41.040 --> 01:40:42.480
And creator partnerships are becoming big.

01:40:42.560 --> 01:40:46.440
The thing with micro influencers is
that they will do it for you

01:40:46.520 --> 01:40:48.960
even if you're a small brand,
with two expectations.

01:40:49.040 --> 01:40:52.160
One, that I might become
a brand ambassador

01:40:52.240 --> 01:40:53.400
or I could get an influencer deal

01:40:53.480 --> 01:40:55.520
if I do a good piece of content
to start with.

01:40:55.600 --> 01:40:59.080
Two, is my friends will think
that I'm now getting paid for content.

01:40:59.880 --> 01:41:02.720
So, you start signalling
that you're an influencer also.

01:41:02.800 --> 01:41:03.920
That's what I said.

01:41:04.000 --> 01:41:06.320
Like, indeed, they feel like
they can use this for content.

01:41:06.400 --> 01:41:07.560
Like, it becomes like, "Oh,

01:41:07.640 --> 01:41:09.600
-brands work with me now."
-Yeah.

01:41:10.400 --> 01:41:13.080
So, if I'm trying to build
influence or marketing,

01:41:13.160 --> 01:41:17.960
I should definitely send it to celebrities
bottom-up, start with micro.

01:41:19.400 --> 01:41:24.080
With the gift box, should have
a heartfelt handwritten letter.

01:41:24.160 --> 01:41:26.320
-And I need to repost if they share.
-Yes.

01:41:26.400 --> 01:41:28.440
And if it can be unique, cherry on top.

01:41:28.520 --> 01:41:31.080
Like, not like every other box
that they are getting,

01:41:31.160 --> 01:41:32.440
but think of something outside the box.

01:41:32.520 --> 01:41:34.760
Can you give it to them in a...

01:41:34.840 --> 01:41:37.160
in a... I don't know, a tin box?

01:41:37.240 --> 01:41:40.160
Can you give it to them in a--
with fresh flowers?

01:41:40.240 --> 01:41:41.320
Is there something unique?

01:41:41.400 --> 01:41:44.320
I was going to say that if you have
some element of storytelling...

01:41:44.400 --> 01:41:46.320
Yeah, or a surprise and delight.

01:41:46.400 --> 01:41:49.800
...that goes far enough,
and then, you create that unboxing moment.

01:41:49.880 --> 01:41:54.360
So, again, you're telling the consumers
about the brand in that moment, right?

01:41:54.440 --> 01:41:59.200
So, again, we were talking about that
how do consumers interact

01:41:59.280 --> 01:42:02.080
for the first time, through influencers,
in that moment.

01:42:02.160 --> 01:42:05.120
So, you kind of think
of that entire piece together.

01:42:05.200 --> 01:42:07.400
Oh, they're unboxing the brand.

01:42:07.480 --> 01:42:09.280
They're seeing the brand
for the first time.

01:42:09.360 --> 01:42:13.320
So, that kind of is as much
for the consumer as for the creator.

01:42:13.400 --> 01:42:15.800
-Yeah.
-So, you think of it that way as well.

01:42:15.880 --> 01:42:18.040
I also think sampling distribution
is a huge opportunity

01:42:18.120 --> 01:42:19.320
which we don't do well enough on.

01:42:19.400 --> 01:42:20.800
-Explain.
-[Bhakti] 100%.

01:42:20.880 --> 01:42:24.320
Like, for example, my favourite example
of sampling distribution is Uncle Chipps.

01:42:25.160 --> 01:42:26.800
Uncle Chipps distributors would go with

01:42:26.880 --> 01:42:29.400
big garlands of Uncle Chipps
around their neck

01:42:29.480 --> 01:42:30.960
and go into a village
and the kid would, like--

01:42:31.040 --> 01:42:32.480
-Did they?
-Yeah. The kids would just come.

01:42:32.560 --> 01:42:34.640
And you'd feed a chip here,
feed a chip there,

01:42:34.720 --> 01:42:36.280
suddenly, kids are buying, moms are there.

01:42:36.360 --> 01:42:37.800
That is full guerrilla marketing.
I love it.

01:42:37.880 --> 01:42:39.520
Yeah, so with fragrances--

01:42:39.600 --> 01:42:41.360
Like, going into a college fest,
for example,

01:42:41.440 --> 01:42:45.800
with, like, a whole suitcase
of your perfumeric innovations,

01:42:45.880 --> 01:42:47.320
yourself smelling really great.

01:42:47.400 --> 01:42:50.320
What is the word you used for this?
Sampling?

01:42:50.400 --> 01:42:52.800
-Sampling.
-Yeah, sampling, like...

01:42:52.880 --> 01:42:55.840
You basically get a sachet
of something or a trial,

01:42:55.920 --> 01:42:56.920
not even a trial pack.

01:42:57.000 --> 01:43:00.480
It's a small sampling...
sample that you can use

01:43:00.560 --> 01:43:04.320
for maybe two or three washes
or two or three moisturising.

01:43:04.400 --> 01:43:07.320
You can also do it really well
with a Tira,

01:43:07.400 --> 01:43:08.400
where you say, "Hey, Tira,

01:43:08.480 --> 01:43:10.760
I am going to give you 100,000 samples."

01:43:10.840 --> 01:43:12.320
Put it in every order.

01:43:12.400 --> 01:43:14.320
But that doesn't work.
That never worked for me.

01:43:14.400 --> 01:43:15.800
-You don't think so?
-It's not-- Blink...

01:43:15.880 --> 01:43:17.800
Tira, I don't know,
but Blinkit does not work.

01:43:17.880 --> 01:43:20.320
But the thing is, I think it really
depends on who the customer is.

01:43:20.400 --> 01:43:22.800
-We did a lot.
-Who your target is.

01:43:22.880 --> 01:43:24.480
We did a lot in terms of...
is it correlated or not,

01:43:24.560 --> 01:43:25.720
is KitKat going after a buyer or not?

01:43:25.800 --> 01:43:28.320
Everything was done, yet,
the repeats are just not there.

01:43:28.400 --> 01:43:31.280
I think it works if you do it correctly.

01:43:31.360 --> 01:43:33.320
-It's great for even upselling, right?
-Maybe we've done a bad job.

01:43:33.400 --> 01:43:36.560
So, if you want to convert
a mass brand into...

01:43:36.640 --> 01:43:37.800
You want to convert a consumer

01:43:37.880 --> 01:43:40.520
who is shopping in mass
for haircare to masstige.

01:43:40.600 --> 01:43:42.720
Then you will send them
that masstige sample,

01:43:42.800 --> 01:43:44.400
and I will upsell them.

01:43:44.480 --> 01:43:46.240
Especially if the product has been getting

01:43:46.320 --> 01:43:47.920
-a lot of buzz in social.
-Exactly.

01:43:48.000 --> 01:43:51.600
And people are hesitant to buying it
because, say, price or whatever,

01:43:51.680 --> 01:43:54.080
and then they get that sample.
They're so happy.

01:43:54.160 --> 01:43:56.360
Especially if it's a deluxe sample.

01:43:56.440 --> 01:43:58.600
And they get to try it once in their hair.

01:43:58.680 --> 01:44:00.360
Or, like, try it on their face
two, three times.

01:44:00.440 --> 01:44:02.400
And they're like, "Oh, I've been dying.
Now I got this.

01:44:02.480 --> 01:44:03.920
Now I'm going to buy full size."

01:44:04.000 --> 01:44:05.360
And that's where minis come in.

01:44:05.440 --> 01:44:09.120
In beauty, the mini
and travel size is just...

01:44:09.200 --> 01:44:11.280
It's a whole business on its own.

01:44:11.360 --> 01:44:15.040
And, in fact, this-- A Bobbi Brown
area manager told me this, that...

01:44:16.320 --> 01:44:18.480
India is a mini capital of the world.

01:44:18.560 --> 01:44:21.800
Like, global brands have produced
their best sellers,

01:44:21.880 --> 01:44:23.280
particularly for India,

01:44:23.360 --> 01:44:25.680
because they know that
India is a value market.

01:44:25.760 --> 01:44:29.760
Value, I don't mean that
we move from price consciousness to...

01:44:29.840 --> 01:44:33.320
to saying that I will pay for the product
if I find value in it.

01:44:33.400 --> 01:44:36.880
So, to cross that barrier, they're like,
"Okay, we'll give you a mini."

01:44:36.960 --> 01:44:39.920
You still pay for it
after having "sampled" it.

01:44:40.000 --> 01:44:41.840
There is that, you know, that bridge.

01:44:41.920 --> 01:44:43.680
So, you buy a mini
of our best-selling product.

01:44:43.760 --> 01:44:45.720
If you like it,
then you will buy the full size.

01:44:45.800 --> 01:44:48.320
So, they've built that bridge,
particularly,

01:44:48.400 --> 01:44:50.920
to get you from a masstige
to a premium brand.

01:44:51.000 --> 01:44:52.920
And you may not even
move into the full size.

01:44:53.000 --> 01:44:54.320
You sell the mini,
or do you just give it away?

01:44:54.400 --> 01:44:55.800
-You sell the mini.
-[Diipa] You sell it.

01:44:55.880 --> 01:44:57.320
-So, like, Estée Lauder...
-Which is a great SKU.

01:44:57.400 --> 01:44:59.920
-Estée Lauder, specifically...
-With MAC.

01:45:00.000 --> 01:45:01.800
...did a phenomenal mini job with MAC.

01:45:01.880 --> 01:45:03.800
Like, for India, specifically,

01:45:03.880 --> 01:45:06.640
they made their lipsticks--
lipstick in a mini form.

01:45:06.720 --> 01:45:08.280
It was like a tiny lipstick.

01:45:08.360 --> 01:45:09.800
Killed it.

01:45:09.880 --> 01:45:11.320
Because they don't want
to wardrobe it, no?

01:45:11.400 --> 01:45:15.320
And their best-selling shades,
not the ones that don't sell too much.

01:45:15.400 --> 01:45:17.960
-Same with the moisture surge minis.
-Exactly. Minis.

01:45:18.040 --> 01:45:20.280
Everything is like, "Oh, I want luxury,

01:45:20.360 --> 01:45:23.080
but give it to me in an affordable price
so I can try it.

01:45:23.160 --> 01:45:24.800
And then, I'll buy the full thing."

01:45:24.880 --> 01:45:26.440
But it's the whole
wardrobing thing, right?

01:45:26.520 --> 01:45:28.720
If I'm gonna keep 30,
I don't want 30 100mls or whatever.

01:45:28.800 --> 01:45:29.800
I want to have 30...

01:45:29.880 --> 01:45:31.240
Are you talking fragrance or skincare?

01:45:31.320 --> 01:45:32.320
Both, I think.

01:45:32.400 --> 01:45:34.120
Skincare people wouldn't wardrobe, no?

01:45:34.200 --> 01:45:36.800
-With colour, for example?
-Yeah, makeup. Yeah.

01:45:36.880 --> 01:45:38.320
You will want brown one day.

01:45:38.400 --> 01:45:39.880
For example, a mascara runs out...

01:45:39.960 --> 01:45:42.320
If you open it, in six months,
you have to finish it,

01:45:42.400 --> 01:45:44.160
or else you should not be using it.

01:45:44.240 --> 01:45:47.760
So, I only buy mini mascaras
because I'm like, "Okay, great.

01:45:47.840 --> 01:45:48.960
I only use that much.

01:45:49.040 --> 01:45:50.800
So, I will only buy a mini mascara."

01:45:50.880 --> 01:45:53.800
Is that true for perfume?
You shouldn't use it after six months?

01:45:53.880 --> 01:45:55.800
-[Bhakti] No.
-There is expiry dates of perfumes.

01:45:55.880 --> 01:45:59.800
Expiry, but it's-- Yeah, for perfumes.
For mascaras, it just clumps after...

01:45:59.880 --> 01:46:01.320
Yeah, mascaras, for sure.

01:46:01.400 --> 01:46:02.680
I think supermarkets do this right

01:46:02.760 --> 01:46:05.680
where I feel like the sampling
works better in person.

01:46:06.280 --> 01:46:08.680
When you give somebody
something in person,

01:46:08.760 --> 01:46:10.800
it may be a Tira store or a supermarket.

01:46:10.880 --> 01:46:12.360
We have a vending machine that,

01:46:12.440 --> 01:46:14.760
when you enter, even if you don't walk out

01:46:14.840 --> 01:46:16.520
with anything that you've purchased,

01:46:16.600 --> 01:46:19.320
you walk out with a sample
because, you know, we've made it...

01:46:19.400 --> 01:46:20.400
We've gamified it.

01:46:20.480 --> 01:46:25.840
You know, you put in your number
and, uh, you know, your email address.

01:46:25.920 --> 01:46:29.400
And you select which sample
you want for that.

01:46:29.480 --> 01:46:33.240
You know, you'll have fragrance sample,
a skincare sample, and a makeup sample,

01:46:33.320 --> 01:46:34.440
and you select which one you want.

01:46:34.520 --> 01:46:37.080
And we let you take
one sample in two months.

01:46:37.160 --> 01:46:38.880
So, every two months
when you come to our store,

01:46:38.960 --> 01:46:40.520
you get something to take back.

01:46:40.600 --> 01:46:44.680
And we work with brands
to really utilise this to,

01:46:44.760 --> 01:46:45.960
again, for sampling.

01:46:46.040 --> 01:46:48.760
So, again, you gamified it.
You've created a moment.

01:46:48.840 --> 01:46:52.320
And offline is all about experiences.
So you've created that experience.

01:46:52.400 --> 01:46:56.560
The two greatest sampling successes
from a brand standpoint

01:46:56.640 --> 01:47:00.480
was Lifebuoy at Kumbh Mela
in COVID 2020 or 2021?

01:47:01.200 --> 01:47:04.360
Where they gave Lifebuoy
to everyone who was eating roti,

01:47:04.440 --> 01:47:07.200
so that before you eat, you use Lifebuoy.

01:47:07.280 --> 01:47:09.200
The second one was Paper Boat
in Indigo Airlines.

01:47:10.080 --> 01:47:13.120
Paper Boat was built as a brand,
again, nostalgic taste,

01:47:13.800 --> 01:47:15.720
by distributing as samples
on Indigo Airlines,

01:47:15.800 --> 01:47:17.800
and then it became something--
a part of the menu and then...

01:47:17.880 --> 01:47:20.800
This nostalgia keeps coming back,
the more I think about it.

01:47:20.880 --> 01:47:22.320
Paper Boat was about nostalgic flavours.

01:47:22.400 --> 01:47:23.800
I think you might be
bang-on with your Champi.

01:47:23.880 --> 01:47:26.800
-Yeah. Especially with Gen Z.
-Is that what it's called? Champi?

01:47:26.880 --> 01:47:28.920
-Champi Hair Oil. Yeah.
-Mm.

01:47:29.000 --> 01:47:31.160
Even the name, I had to fight in my team.

01:47:31.240 --> 01:47:33.360
They were like, "No, but, like,
don't call it that.

01:47:33.440 --> 01:47:35.040
We all have a bad connotation with it."

01:47:35.120 --> 01:47:38.520
I'm like, "No, it's gonna work."
Because it's-- it's a ritual.

01:47:38.600 --> 01:47:41.880
You're literally putting
the name of what we all know.

01:47:41.960 --> 01:47:43.240
-It's a household name.
-Yeah.

01:47:43.320 --> 01:47:44.800
On a bottle. It's gonna work.

01:47:45.400 --> 01:47:47.160
Could a brand of just minis work?

01:47:47.880 --> 01:47:51.320
Yes. I think in the category...
or in fragrances, yes, I think so.

01:47:51.400 --> 01:47:52.720
-Yeah.
-[Nikhil] Yeah?

01:47:52.800 --> 01:47:53.800
Fragrances, for sure.

01:47:53.880 --> 01:47:56.800
-Like, it is...
-It's also expensive to make minis.

01:47:56.880 --> 01:47:58.800
Yeah. That's true.
The margins are not as good.

01:47:58.880 --> 01:48:00.880
Yeah. The margins are not great in minis,

01:48:00.960 --> 01:48:03.720
because you have to make
that much product.

01:48:03.800 --> 01:48:07.200
And your packaging
still costs the same, so...

01:48:07.280 --> 01:48:09.320
I actually was going to ask you--

01:48:09.400 --> 01:48:11.640
That's just from the limited
knowledge that I have that,

01:48:11.720 --> 01:48:14.800
you know, brands don't like minis
as much as consumers.

01:48:14.880 --> 01:48:16.320
Correct. That's true.

01:48:16.400 --> 01:48:18.280
I was actually gonna ask you
whether sustainability is something

01:48:18.360 --> 01:48:20.800
Dilip cares about a lot,
because that's another Gen Z trend.

01:48:20.880 --> 01:48:23.320
I don't think that's a trend right now.
It was a trend yesterday.

01:48:23.400 --> 01:48:27.320
No, it's a bare minimum.
I think you have to care about it.

01:48:27.400 --> 01:48:28.800
-[Nikhil] Yeah?
-But I don't know.

01:48:28.880 --> 01:48:30.800
-Do you think that...
-I think, again, maybe...

01:48:30.880 --> 01:48:32.800
-Do you think something sells more--
-Sustainability is also

01:48:32.880 --> 01:48:34.800
-a little bit of affluence.
-Yeah.

01:48:34.880 --> 01:48:37.000
Does something sell more
because it's sustainable?

01:48:37.080 --> 01:48:39.440
Maybe in India, not as much yet.

01:48:39.520 --> 01:48:43.360
But I think, again, the Gen Z value
is starting to become more important.

01:48:43.440 --> 01:48:47.000
And for me, as a founder,
I don't want to clutter the market more.

01:48:47.080 --> 01:48:49.920
Like, if you look at even
just sustainable in every measure,

01:48:50.000 --> 01:48:52.320
they say, you know,
our packaging is mostly glass,

01:48:52.400 --> 01:48:53.760
so it can be recycled better.

01:48:53.840 --> 01:48:56.520
We have six SKUs
in three and a half years.

01:48:56.600 --> 01:48:59.720
We're not in the business
of building 200 SKUs, 300 SKUs,

01:48:59.800 --> 01:49:00.800
clutter the market.

01:49:00.880 --> 01:49:03.960
We really are, like,
hero product strategy only.

01:49:04.040 --> 01:49:06.000
Talk to the consumers. What do they want?

01:49:06.080 --> 01:49:07.400
Build it for them.

01:49:07.480 --> 01:49:10.280
And then really put all your
marketing might in six SKUs,

01:49:10.360 --> 01:49:12.680
instead of, "Which one am I picking here?"

01:49:12.760 --> 01:49:14.960
Like, am I playing-- you know,
you're gambling then.

01:49:15.040 --> 01:49:18.800
So, I think sustainability, for me,
as a founder, is very important.

01:49:18.880 --> 01:49:20.160
Do you put it on every product?

01:49:20.880 --> 01:49:22.960
That we're sustainable? No.
Because it's a given.

01:49:23.040 --> 01:49:25.320
Like, I don't...
I don't need to scream about it.

01:49:25.400 --> 01:49:26.800
I agree with that.
That's why I don't think

01:49:26.880 --> 01:49:28.320
-putting sustainability will sell.
-No.

01:49:28.400 --> 01:49:29.800
No, so, I'll tell you
where I'm coming from.

01:49:29.880 --> 01:49:34.400
The reason is, I think today's Gen Z,
whether it comes to food or personal care,

01:49:34.480 --> 01:49:36.160
actually cares about
the product inside the bottle,

01:49:36.240 --> 01:49:37.320
not the bottle so much.

01:49:37.400 --> 01:49:38.800
They're way too smart for that.

01:49:38.880 --> 01:49:41.000
And if you make that
a point of your communication,

01:49:41.080 --> 01:49:46.000
you don't need to spend 30% of your COGS
on a glass bottle that looks great.

01:49:46.080 --> 01:49:49.320
You can get away with a product
that is much cheaper.

01:49:49.400 --> 01:49:50.800
It could be an idea for Dilip.

01:49:50.880 --> 01:49:54.320
Yeah. And then, you actually focus
all the money on the product inside.

01:49:54.400 --> 01:49:56.920
It can be a plain black bottle,

01:49:57.000 --> 01:49:59.320
and my marketing can be
not about the bottle.

01:49:59.400 --> 01:50:02.000
-For Dilip?
-Ordinary is all about that.

01:50:02.080 --> 01:50:04.200
You know, have you seen
those Ordinary billboards

01:50:04.280 --> 01:50:05.520
all over the place where they're like,

01:50:05.600 --> 01:50:06.960
-I'm marketing--
-Ordinary eggs.

01:50:07.040 --> 01:50:09.200
Yeah, people told us
we should hire celebrities,

01:50:09.280 --> 01:50:12.920
but we put all our marketing money
into building the best product ever.

01:50:13.880 --> 01:50:15.200
They said "Make better packaging,"

01:50:15.280 --> 01:50:17.320
but we put all the money
into the formulations.

01:50:17.400 --> 01:50:18.800
Yeah.

01:50:18.880 --> 01:50:20.760
"Not about the bottle" is a good line.

01:50:21.360 --> 01:50:22.800
-Do you think?
-Yeah.

01:50:22.880 --> 01:50:24.400
-Yeah?
-Yeah.

01:50:24.480 --> 01:50:26.800
-Because fragrance is always--
-Dilip is starting to feel better slowly.

01:50:28.400 --> 01:50:29.960
But, for sustainability,

01:50:30.040 --> 01:50:33.800
I think the thought leaders
of the world today

01:50:34.760 --> 01:50:37.480
are moving away from sustainability.

01:50:38.080 --> 01:50:42.160
And hence, I think it will trickle down,
permeate down to the consumer as well.

01:50:42.240 --> 01:50:46.760
If you hear a Trump talk
about bring plastic straws back,

01:50:46.840 --> 01:50:47.960
drill, baby, drill.

01:50:48.600 --> 01:50:49.800
I was doing a--

01:50:49.880 --> 01:50:52.320
You mean, you're saying
it's going to get backwards.

01:50:52.400 --> 01:50:53.800
Regressing. Yeah. We're regressing.

01:50:53.880 --> 01:50:55.640
The novelty around sustainability
has gone, I think.

01:50:55.720 --> 01:50:58.360
It was really big two years ago,
in my opinion.

01:51:00.880 --> 01:51:02.800
-No, we get a lot of push.
-I don't think so.

01:51:02.880 --> 01:51:05.080
-You don't think so?
-I think the young consumers care.

01:51:05.160 --> 01:51:07.560
Yeah. India, for sure.
Globally, I don't know.

01:51:08.240 --> 01:51:09.680
India, for sure, young consumers.

01:51:09.760 --> 01:51:12.320
Urban, young, affluent consumers
will care.

01:51:12.400 --> 01:51:13.800
-They care.
-[Nikhil] I don't know.

01:51:13.880 --> 01:51:14.880
It'll be a differentiator.

01:51:15.720 --> 01:51:18.880
If it were, Diipa would have
"sustainable" on her packaging.

01:51:20.400 --> 01:51:23.160
No, because they know
what a conscious brand I'm building.

01:51:23.240 --> 01:51:27.920
When I speak to... The content I make
is about we are sustainable,

01:51:28.000 --> 01:51:29.000
we are vegan,

01:51:29.080 --> 01:51:31.440
but we're not screaming about it
because that's a no-brainer for us.

01:51:31.520 --> 01:51:32.920
You know, being vegan, being this.

01:51:33.000 --> 01:51:35.280
-It's like the table stakes.
-Cruelty-free-- Table stakes.

01:51:35.360 --> 01:51:36.920
-This is how we stand out.
-But it's also...

01:51:37.000 --> 01:51:38.800
I feel like the word "sustainability"

01:51:38.880 --> 01:51:42.320
has been used around in very many ways

01:51:42.400 --> 01:51:46.480
and people also have
some amount of doubt around it,

01:51:46.560 --> 01:51:48.600
that what is actually sustainable.

01:51:48.680 --> 01:51:51.600
So, I think brands also
do stay away from--

01:51:51.680 --> 01:51:53.280
for the fear of getting called out.

01:51:53.360 --> 01:51:55.600
Because anything you say today
that's sustainable,

01:51:55.680 --> 01:51:57.560
you will still get
called out for it, right?

01:51:57.640 --> 01:52:00.240
So, I think there's a little bit
of fear as well

01:52:00.320 --> 01:52:04.160
on what the consumer
really believes you stand for.

01:52:04.240 --> 01:52:08.720
So, I think it's kind of not being able
to distil those sustainable values,

01:52:08.800 --> 01:52:11.800
what sustainability in beauty
really stands for.

01:52:11.880 --> 01:52:15.000
Like, right now,
if we talk about sustainability,

01:52:15.080 --> 01:52:16.960
technically, it's less consumption, right?

01:52:17.040 --> 01:52:18.520
But now, there's refillable.

01:52:18.600 --> 01:52:20.920
So, that's a step in the right direction.

01:52:21.000 --> 01:52:23.760
But is it 100% sustainable? No.

01:52:23.840 --> 01:52:27.080
But you're still kind of-- again,
it's all about creating that lifestyle.

01:52:27.160 --> 01:52:29.800
So, I think it's still about
the lifestyle.

01:52:29.880 --> 01:52:31.240
I think being honest about that,

01:52:31.320 --> 01:52:34.880
I think, also, with founders
who are a little sustainable,

01:52:34.960 --> 01:52:38.520
nobody can be all the way sustainable
because, then, you don't have a brand.

01:52:38.600 --> 01:52:39.600
If you're gonna be...

01:52:39.680 --> 01:52:41.080
Like, be honest about,
"These are the areas

01:52:41.160 --> 01:52:42.720
we're working on our sustainability.

01:52:42.800 --> 01:52:46.200
These are areas that we cannot yet,
until we get scale

01:52:46.280 --> 01:52:47.800
or until we can, you know..."

01:52:47.880 --> 01:52:49.000
The refillable programme.

01:52:49.080 --> 01:52:50.160
-Or there's a way to do it.
-Exactly.

01:52:50.240 --> 01:52:51.800
Because, sometimes, there's no way out.

01:52:51.880 --> 01:52:53.800
Just be honest.
I think that's the main thing.

01:52:53.880 --> 01:52:56.600
Because you said "honest" so many times,

01:52:56.680 --> 01:53:01.160
like, I am as far removed
an expert in this industry

01:53:01.240 --> 01:53:02.560
as anyone can be.

01:53:03.080 --> 01:53:05.240
But looking from afar,

01:53:05.320 --> 01:53:12.120
it feels like the sustainable,
organic, natural movement

01:53:12.200 --> 01:53:13.520
happened when...

01:53:14.560 --> 01:53:17.560
Was it Jessica Alba
started The Honest Company?

01:53:17.640 --> 01:53:20.800
-Which was six, seven years ago?
-Long back. Ten years back.

01:53:20.880 --> 01:53:22.800
-Ten years ago?
-If you say so, yeah.

01:53:22.880 --> 01:53:24.520
-I feel like--
-Goop, Gwyneth Paltrow.

01:53:24.600 --> 01:53:26.040
-Yeah.
-Yeah. Goop.

01:53:26.120 --> 01:53:29.800
I feel like the wave after that
was the wave of actives.

01:53:29.880 --> 01:53:31.320
-Yeah.
-Yes.

01:53:31.400 --> 01:53:33.320
Which was, maybe, a couple of years ago.

01:53:33.400 --> 01:53:34.800
Mm-hmm.

01:53:34.880 --> 01:53:38.520
And most companies that I looked at,
which did really well,

01:53:38.600 --> 01:53:41.800
were companies that caught on
to a change in cycle

01:53:41.880 --> 01:53:43.440
before the cycle changed.

01:53:43.520 --> 01:53:45.800
I think Minimalist was exactly
in that spot.

01:53:46.880 --> 01:53:52.360
So, my question to you guys is,
if the active cycle is midway,

01:53:53.120 --> 01:53:54.680
what comes next?

01:53:54.760 --> 01:53:57.320
And what can I build
to catch on to the next cycle

01:53:57.400 --> 01:53:59.760
-before the others scale?
-I don't think it's about sustainability.

01:54:00.360 --> 01:54:03.840
I think the Gen Z younger consumers,
are actually,

01:54:03.920 --> 01:54:06.200
what we are now starting to realise
are Skinimalists.

01:54:07.040 --> 01:54:09.320
-Just give me what I need.
-What is this now?

01:54:09.400 --> 01:54:11.640
-[Bhakti] Skin-Minimalism.
-Skin-Minimalism.

01:54:11.720 --> 01:54:13.280
So just, like,
Minimalist is a classic example.

01:54:13.360 --> 01:54:16.800
Just give me these three molecules.
I don't need the jazz around it.

01:54:16.880 --> 01:54:18.640
I don't need a 10-step skincare routine.

01:54:18.720 --> 01:54:21.240
So, if that is what they're thinking,
why should I have three molecules?

01:54:21.320 --> 01:54:24.800
Why can't I have the combination of three
in a way which is effective?

01:54:24.880 --> 01:54:26.320
That's what we do.

01:54:26.400 --> 01:54:29.400
So, like, the whole six SKU thing
I was talking about earlier,

01:54:29.480 --> 01:54:32.240
our whole play was,
we're not going to be a Minimalist.

01:54:32.320 --> 01:54:34.360
We're not gonna be a Plum or a Mamaearth.

01:54:34.440 --> 01:54:36.800
-We're not gonna do the whole thing.
-Assortment, yeah.

01:54:36.880 --> 01:54:40.600
We're gonna do one serum
with twelve serums in it,

01:54:40.680 --> 01:54:43.320
with an expert who does it for you.

01:54:43.400 --> 01:54:45.520
We're gonna do one evening ritual.

01:54:45.600 --> 01:54:48.080
For the mom on the go,
for the college student,

01:54:48.160 --> 01:54:52.280
for the one who doesn't have time
for a 12-step skincare routine.

01:54:52.360 --> 01:54:54.800
-And I think--
-That's very progressive, actually.

01:54:54.880 --> 01:54:58.080
And we did this already
two and a half years ago,

01:54:58.160 --> 01:54:59.400
where everybody was only buying

01:54:59.480 --> 01:55:01.840
the 700-rupee vitamin C from Ordinary
or this,

01:55:01.920 --> 01:55:04.240
and I'm like,
"Wait, they're gonna get there."

01:55:04.320 --> 01:55:07.080
At one point, 'cause we saw it
in the West as well,

01:55:07.160 --> 01:55:10.640
it was The Ordinary that led the way,
and then it was the Drunk Elephants.

01:55:10.720 --> 01:55:13.320
-It was the...
-Youth To The People.

01:55:13.400 --> 01:55:15.400
Youth To The People,
all the other brands that

01:55:15.480 --> 01:55:17.600
really brought them together,
that people are like,

01:55:17.680 --> 01:55:19.800
"Okay, one, that's it,
I don't need anything else."

01:55:19.880 --> 01:55:22.160
And this is moving
even into makeup, right?

01:55:22.240 --> 01:55:27.120
So, you want skinification of makeup,
so, anything to--

01:55:27.200 --> 01:55:29.360
You don't want to put anything
on your skin that harms it.

01:55:29.440 --> 01:55:33.000
So, skincare ingredients
in makeup products,

01:55:33.080 --> 01:55:34.640
and layered with an SPF.

01:55:34.720 --> 01:55:37.720
So, imagine that you're just putting that
one product on the go.

01:55:37.800 --> 01:55:39.760
So if I don't have time,
but I'm coming here.

01:55:39.840 --> 01:55:41.280
And I just have that one product.

01:55:41.360 --> 01:55:43.200
-It should do the job.
-Everything for me.

01:55:43.280 --> 01:55:45.360
It moisturises my skin.
It protects me from the sun.

01:55:45.440 --> 01:55:46.520
And it allows me to have

01:55:46.600 --> 01:55:49.280
a good amount of coverage,
my "no makeup" look.

01:55:49.360 --> 01:55:52.320
Yeah, multi-purpose, multi-active--

01:55:52.400 --> 01:55:54.120
-On the go.
-On the go.

01:55:54.200 --> 01:55:55.400
That's what the consumer wants.

01:55:55.480 --> 01:55:58.640
Do you think the next wave
could be that, in my bathroom,

01:55:58.720 --> 01:56:00.240
I have three bottles.

01:56:00.320 --> 01:56:02.680
One which says morning,
one that says afternoon,

01:56:02.760 --> 01:56:05.320
-one that says...
-Afternoon, what do you need for?

01:56:05.400 --> 01:56:07.320
Yeah, then two bottles?

01:56:07.400 --> 01:56:08.920
-Two, yeah.
-Yeah?

01:56:09.880 --> 01:56:11.320
And sunscreen.

01:56:11.400 --> 01:56:13.800
So, the two bottles would be
like your actives, like your serums.

01:56:13.880 --> 01:56:15.800
The morning will have the sunscreen.

01:56:15.880 --> 01:56:18.320
Okay, fine. Then you're fine, yeah.

01:56:18.400 --> 01:56:20.240
You can put the sunscreen
together with it.

01:56:20.320 --> 01:56:24.520
Another big trend in Gen Z, I think,
is also around stress management.

01:56:24.600 --> 01:56:27.600
So, skincare, like skinification of hair,
for example.

01:56:27.680 --> 01:56:29.680
A skincare that helps you sleep better.

01:56:29.760 --> 01:56:33.840
It's hugely-- Like, magnesium roll-ons
have, like, exploded.

01:56:33.920 --> 01:56:36.240
-It helps you sleep better.
-Is that like a...

01:56:37.400 --> 01:56:39.480
-Sleep well, clean gut and great skin.
-...dramatising something?

01:56:39.560 --> 01:56:42.320
I mean, I could eat
the magnesium pill as well, but...

01:56:42.400 --> 01:56:44.320
Yeah. So, great skin...

01:56:44.400 --> 01:56:46.400
There's some studies shown

01:56:46.480 --> 01:56:49.120
that the magnesium
is absorbed by, like, skin

01:56:49.200 --> 01:56:51.880
better than your gut,
takes it away or something.

01:56:51.960 --> 01:56:52.960
There were some studies.

01:56:53.040 --> 01:56:56.680
I think doctors would still say
you can do the pills.

01:56:56.760 --> 01:57:01.280
I take the pills, but indeed,
magnesium lotion, magnesium oil,

01:57:01.360 --> 01:57:02.920
and magnesium... because, apparently,

01:57:03.000 --> 01:57:04.920
it gets into your bloodstream
more from your skin.

01:57:05.000 --> 01:57:07.320
Isn't that more a magnesium thing
than a skincare thing?

01:57:07.400 --> 01:57:09.240
-Where did magnesium come from?
-Yeah.

01:57:09.320 --> 01:57:11.800
Two, three years ago,
nobody spoke about it.

01:57:11.880 --> 01:57:13.920
But, for example,
if you're building a fragrance brand,

01:57:14.000 --> 01:57:16.800
a pillow fragrance would be
a very critical new-age skincare.

01:57:16.880 --> 01:57:18.680
-Like a lavender.
-That helps you...

01:57:18.760 --> 01:57:21.280
I've had, like, sleep fragrances.

01:57:22.600 --> 01:57:24.520
You never remember to use them, right?

01:57:24.600 --> 01:57:26.800
I don't feel like it's a habit.
It's not like brushing your teeth.

01:57:26.880 --> 01:57:28.920
-But you keep it on your bedside.
-It's just one of those products

01:57:29.000 --> 01:57:30.440
that's great to have,
but you never use it.

01:57:30.520 --> 01:57:31.840
Every hotel gives it to you now.

01:57:31.920 --> 01:57:33.800
But how often do you actually use it?

01:57:33.880 --> 01:57:36.640
-That's very true.
-It's a habit. If one friend uses it...

01:57:36.720 --> 01:57:38.320
Or if your girlfriend-- Like, something--

01:57:38.400 --> 01:57:40.320
I also feel we do,
because we don't use it.

01:57:40.400 --> 01:57:42.800
You use products
that others can see you use.

01:57:42.880 --> 01:57:44.760
-No, no.
-Or there's some effect of it.

01:57:44.840 --> 01:57:46.800
You'll feel it. You'll feel it.

01:57:46.880 --> 01:57:47.880
-Would you feel?
-Yeah.

01:57:47.960 --> 01:57:49.320
With the lavender spray, you sleep better?

01:57:49.400 --> 01:57:52.800
-Oh, magnesium is really improving.
-What about the lavender spray?

01:57:52.880 --> 01:57:54.800
Lavender spray, I don't know.
But magnesium will...

01:57:54.880 --> 01:57:57.120
-Magnesium works, yeah.
-I'm using my morning serum,

01:57:57.200 --> 01:57:59.720
whatever is in this one bottle
which has everything.

01:58:00.400 --> 01:58:01.800
That's the indē wild vitamin C.
You need that one.

01:58:01.880 --> 01:58:04.320
[Bhakti] But then you still need
a moisturiser.

01:58:04.400 --> 01:58:06.200
It has everything together.
It has vitamin C.

01:58:06.280 --> 01:58:07.800
It has moisturiser. It has sunscreen.

01:58:07.880 --> 01:58:10.680
Niacinamide, hyaluronic acid, everything.

01:58:10.760 --> 01:58:12.400
-All in one bottle.
-So you've got moisture,

01:58:12.480 --> 01:58:13.800
brightening, acne...

01:58:13.880 --> 01:58:16.840
You can be creative with the bottle.
Maybe the bottle has three sections.

01:58:16.920 --> 01:58:19.080
-You go one, two, three or something.
-Oh, cool.

01:58:19.160 --> 01:58:21.800
Or like a triphasic
that you mix and like...

01:58:21.880 --> 01:58:22.920
-Mix it and...
-Yeah.

01:58:23.000 --> 01:58:24.320
So, say form factor can change
of the bottle.

01:58:24.400 --> 01:58:25.800
Yeah. Yeah.

01:58:27.880 --> 01:58:31.040
But again, these are all areas
which are category-creating,

01:58:31.120 --> 01:58:32.800
and hence, community matters.

01:58:34.520 --> 01:58:35.520
Right.

01:58:36.200 --> 01:58:38.440
So. I think the trend,
the next wave you were asking,

01:58:38.520 --> 01:58:40.800
skin-minimalism, definitely.

01:58:40.880 --> 01:58:42.320
[Bhakti] Skinification of makeup.

01:58:42.400 --> 01:58:43.600
I think nostalgia is not really a trend,

01:58:43.680 --> 01:58:45.640
but I think it will always
come back in life.

01:58:45.720 --> 01:58:47.920
Whether it's fashion,
whether it's beauty.

01:58:48.000 --> 01:58:52.280
I think we, as human beings,
go after things we know.

01:58:52.360 --> 01:58:54.320
There is a familiarity.

01:58:54.400 --> 01:58:56.120
There is something that's familiar,

01:58:56.200 --> 01:58:59.560
but then, something that's new
is the best way we digest it.

01:58:59.640 --> 01:59:03.240
Like, if you look at music,
the remixes of really old songs

01:59:03.320 --> 01:59:05.640
with something new are the ones
we immediately are like,

01:59:05.720 --> 01:59:07.800
"Oh, that is... I like this."

01:59:07.880 --> 01:59:09.800
-Gen Z is getting in ghazals now.
-It feels familiar.

01:59:09.880 --> 01:59:11.320
-Exactly.
-It's insane.

01:59:11.400 --> 01:59:13.760
There are, like, so many Instagram singers

01:59:13.840 --> 01:59:16.320
who are not getting into, like,
Mehdi Hassan and I was like,

01:59:16.400 --> 01:59:17.920
"Wow, that's-- that's incredible."

01:59:18.000 --> 01:59:20.720
And I think if you can
package nostalgia and identity

01:59:20.800 --> 01:59:24.200
and India pride-ness, again,
I'm going to say that.

01:59:24.280 --> 01:59:29.800
But for a new India and for the world,
I think that is the next big wave.

01:59:29.880 --> 01:59:30.880
-For sure.
-That's very well put.

01:59:30.960 --> 01:59:32.800
-And minimalism.
-Yeah, that I already said.

01:59:32.880 --> 01:59:35.320
Nostalgia, minimalism.
Okay, I'm now taking notes.

01:59:35.400 --> 01:59:37.320
-Nostalgia, minimalism.
-He's like... my next brand.

01:59:38.400 --> 01:59:40.320
-We're getting into it.
-I also think

01:59:40.400 --> 01:59:43.240
there's a huge pick up of microtrends.

01:59:43.320 --> 01:59:45.600
So, that's changed
every three to six months.

01:59:45.680 --> 01:59:48.600
So, brands that kind of catch on to that,

01:59:48.680 --> 01:59:50.920
or figure a way
of how to catch on to that trend,

01:59:51.000 --> 01:59:53.760
then you show the product
in a different light.

01:59:53.840 --> 01:59:55.760
For example, glass skin, right?

01:59:55.840 --> 01:59:57.800
-So, that came out of Korea.
-Korean, right?

01:59:57.880 --> 02:00:00.960
Yeah. But it's not... It's just that--

02:00:01.040 --> 02:00:05.440
That's all the Korean brands,
even if they were not talking about it,

02:00:05.520 --> 02:00:08.280
or brands that are inspired
by Korean ingredients

02:00:08.360 --> 02:00:13.360
started using that trend as a viral moment
to resell their product.

02:00:13.440 --> 02:00:17.280
The same product that has,
as she said, repackaged and sold.

02:00:17.360 --> 02:00:19.800
You're talking about the mob-wife look.

02:00:19.880 --> 02:00:21.200
-If I go to Korea...
-Yeah.

02:00:21.280 --> 02:00:22.760
...I find a person

02:00:22.840 --> 02:00:24.520
-willing to white label...
-Yeah.

02:00:24.600 --> 02:00:26.440
...and bring back
a whole bunch of products.

02:00:26.520 --> 02:00:29.360
Because this is a country
with better skin and not a celebrity,

02:00:29.440 --> 02:00:31.800
so, they're probably being
a bit more honest,

02:00:31.880 --> 02:00:34.800
-will it work in India?
-Yes, it will.

02:00:34.880 --> 02:00:36.440
-[Diipa] Brands are doing it.
-It will be too expensive.

02:00:36.520 --> 02:00:37.920
-Brands are doing it.
-I don't know.

02:00:38.000 --> 02:00:39.440
ClayCo, d'you, right?

02:00:39.520 --> 02:00:41.400
I think they're all Korean-inspired.

02:00:41.480 --> 02:00:43.320
They're all Indian wrappers
in Korean brands?

02:00:43.400 --> 02:00:45.000
-d'you is--
-So, what they do, like,

02:00:45.080 --> 02:00:46.400
the best way to-- I don't know.

02:00:46.480 --> 02:00:49.360
I think there's two
differentiations, right?

02:00:49.440 --> 02:00:51.920
So, you're using...
You're getting Korean...

02:00:52.000 --> 02:00:53.800
-Manufacturers.
-You're getting brands made--

02:00:53.880 --> 02:00:57.400
manufactured in Korea
without any of the Korean inspiration.

02:00:57.480 --> 02:01:04.080
Or you're using Korean-origin ingredients,
and then packaging it as a Korean brand,

02:01:04.160 --> 02:01:05.800
getting glass skin and then--

02:01:05.880 --> 02:01:07.800
What if I'm just taking
a Korean product...

02:01:07.880 --> 02:01:09.800
-Yeah.
-...putting a different wrapper on it

02:01:09.880 --> 02:01:11.760
-and selling it in India?
-It's 90% water.

02:01:11.840 --> 02:01:13.320
Why will you transport it all the way?

02:01:13.400 --> 02:01:15.320
-[Diipa] It's not...
-It will work.

02:01:15.400 --> 02:01:17.000
It's about product, right?

02:01:17.080 --> 02:01:19.560
I mean, my lip balm,
the main ingredient is ghee,

02:01:19.640 --> 02:01:21.720
but I'm making it in Korea. Why?

02:01:21.800 --> 02:01:23.000
Because they are--

02:01:23.080 --> 02:01:26.800
The texture and the sensorialism
in their ingredients is far superior...

02:01:26.880 --> 02:01:28.680
No, but I think he's saying,
"I'll just get a Korean product."

02:01:28.760 --> 02:01:29.920
So, Korean brand, and then...

02:01:30.000 --> 02:01:31.600
What I'm saying is,
it will work because they're--

02:01:31.680 --> 02:01:33.640
I think they're manufacturing--
At this point,

02:01:33.720 --> 02:01:37.120
I think India is coming up there.
Like, our manufacturing is getting better.

02:01:37.200 --> 02:01:40.920
But, at this point,
Korea has certain textures and ingredients

02:01:41.000 --> 02:01:42.400
in the way they mix it together--

02:01:42.480 --> 02:01:43.800
-They are far ahead of the game.
-Yeah.

02:01:43.880 --> 02:01:46.800
-So, I think that just--
-We can't mix Korean beauty here in India?

02:01:46.880 --> 02:01:48.440
-Yes, you can.
-[Diipa] You can.

02:01:48.520 --> 02:01:51.600
But I think we're talking
from a quality perspective,

02:01:51.680 --> 02:01:54.320
from technology perspective,
from innovation perspective, right?

02:01:54.400 --> 02:01:56.800
-Hygiene...
-Innovation is huge here.

02:01:56.880 --> 02:01:59.920
I think what they're saying is...
Can you make a Ferrari in India?

02:02:00.000 --> 02:02:03.320
-Yes. But it won't be Ferrari, right?
-Wow.

02:02:03.400 --> 02:02:04.800
But Ferrari and beauty is very different.

02:02:04.880 --> 02:02:07.320
No, it sounds complicated.
Like, beauty is not...

02:02:07.400 --> 02:02:10.600
Beauty is not just mixing things
in a pot and doing it.

02:02:10.680 --> 02:02:13.120
Like, there's so many emulsifiers,
so many steps.

02:02:13.200 --> 02:02:14.680
Like, you've got to cool it,
you've got to heat it.

02:02:14.760 --> 02:02:17.600
And then, I think,
the way Korean chemists, specifically,

02:02:17.680 --> 02:02:19.520
the manufacturing,
I think you can still do in India

02:02:19.600 --> 02:02:22.080
because you can reverse engineer
the formula.

02:02:22.160 --> 02:02:26.160
But I think the chemists in Korea,
like, the ingredients they use like PDRN,

02:02:26.240 --> 02:02:29.000
Like, the salmon sperm.

02:02:29.080 --> 02:02:32.520
Salmon sperm is the trendiest ingredient
in skincare today.

02:02:32.600 --> 02:02:34.040
-Yeah.
-That came from Korea.

02:02:34.120 --> 02:02:37.200
And they literally
create ingredients like that.

02:02:37.280 --> 02:02:41.240
And because they have this branding
of having better skincare,

02:02:41.320 --> 02:02:43.200
people, as consumers, accept it.

02:02:43.280 --> 02:02:45.520
Is it always better? One can argue.

02:02:45.600 --> 02:02:48.160
I know someone who got it
injected into his knees

02:02:48.240 --> 02:02:51.040
because the logic was
salmon sperm will help...

02:02:51.120 --> 02:02:52.520
-Who injected that?
-My brother.

02:02:52.600 --> 02:02:54.560
So, we were travelling somewhere recently.

02:02:54.640 --> 02:02:58.040
He got it into his knees.
He got an IV into his body.

02:02:58.120 --> 02:02:59.520
Did it help?

02:02:59.600 --> 02:03:01.520
It put him on a wheelchair
for four or five days.

02:03:01.600 --> 02:03:03.520
-Oh, dear.
-Yeah.

02:03:03.600 --> 02:03:05.920
So, caution for salmon sperm then.

02:03:06.000 --> 02:03:08.120
But there's also a lot
of information out there.

02:03:08.200 --> 02:03:10.760
So I think, you know,
it's also about understanding.

02:03:10.840 --> 02:03:12.440
That's why going back to experts.

02:03:12.520 --> 02:03:13.920
So, while it's all about influencing,

02:03:14.000 --> 02:03:17.360
it's also about understanding
what your skin type is, right?

02:03:17.440 --> 02:03:18.920
And I think that's something that

02:03:19.000 --> 02:03:21.480
I would tell anyone
who's starting a brand there.

02:03:21.560 --> 02:03:24.520
Understand who your audience is
and who you're creating for.

02:03:24.600 --> 02:03:29.160
So, if it's a concern-based solve,
particularly for skincare,

02:03:29.240 --> 02:03:31.680
make sure that you also have experts

02:03:31.760 --> 02:03:34.560
who back your brand
or have them as advisors

02:03:34.640 --> 02:03:37.520
to kind of tell you
this is the right thing to do.

02:03:37.600 --> 02:03:40.640
But I think country, you know,
if you look at different countries,

02:03:40.720 --> 02:03:42.960
like, what you started off earlier saying,

02:03:43.040 --> 02:03:44.680
that when you look at Italy or Germany,

02:03:44.760 --> 02:03:47.320
you know they would have
good colour, good makeup.

02:03:47.400 --> 02:03:49.800
You look at France, of course,
French pharmacy,

02:03:49.880 --> 02:03:52.520
you already, subconsciously,
are like, French skincare.

02:03:52.600 --> 02:03:54.040
-Quality.
-It must be good.

02:03:54.120 --> 02:03:56.240
-Yes.
-Like, all the La Roche-Posays

02:03:56.320 --> 02:03:58.440
and the Caudalies,
like, they must be good.

02:03:58.520 --> 02:04:00.360
Korea is this new one that's come on,

02:04:00.440 --> 02:04:02.720
where, subconsciously,
because they have good skin,

02:04:02.800 --> 02:04:04.760
we all are like, "They must be good."

02:04:04.840 --> 02:04:06.960
India, I think, has that,
globally, for hair.

02:04:07.040 --> 02:04:08.080
Yeah.

02:04:08.160 --> 02:04:11.280
Anyone thinks of Indians, they're like,
they have some secret to hair...

02:04:11.360 --> 02:04:12.360
Great point.

02:04:12.440 --> 02:04:14.040
...that the world needs to know.

02:04:14.120 --> 02:04:16.280
And that's why even Ayurveda, right?

02:04:16.360 --> 02:04:18.640
Like, I think it's so unique to India.

02:04:18.720 --> 02:04:22.360
It's the entire lifestyle
that we're kind of, you know,

02:04:22.440 --> 02:04:25.840
putting out there and anything
from India about Ayurveda

02:04:25.920 --> 02:04:28.040
-really moves the needle.
-[Shantanu] Yeah.

02:04:28.120 --> 02:04:31.280
So you're saying a product
that says Indian hair oil

02:04:31.360 --> 02:04:33.040
-could do well in the West.
-Yeah.

02:04:34.600 --> 02:04:36.040
-For sure.
-Champi.

02:04:36.120 --> 02:04:37.200
It does, yeah. And it will.

02:04:37.280 --> 02:04:39.040
And I think... I think--

02:04:39.120 --> 02:04:40.520
What else are Indians known for?

02:04:40.600 --> 02:04:42.040
What else are Indians known for?

02:04:42.120 --> 02:04:44.040
-Weddings?
-Yoga. Yoga.

02:04:44.120 --> 02:04:45.440
Spirituality, wellness.

02:04:46.120 --> 02:04:48.120
-I think just their--
-Food?

02:04:48.200 --> 02:04:50.800
Their-- their warmth and love for food.

02:04:50.880 --> 02:04:52.040
I think that's another one.

02:04:52.120 --> 02:04:54.040
-Food's a biggie, yeah.
-Food is huge.

02:04:54.120 --> 02:04:56.280
-Bollywood.
-Just colour.

02:04:56.360 --> 02:04:59.280
So, we have to build on those things
when we build a brand.

02:04:59.360 --> 02:05:00.800
If you want to build a global brand.

02:05:00.880 --> 02:05:01.960
Because it's subconscious.

02:05:02.040 --> 02:05:04.440
Like, I think, what then...
it's like the winds are behind you

02:05:04.520 --> 02:05:05.520
and it's helping you.

02:05:05.600 --> 02:05:08.680
Like, with Koreans, any Korean brand
can launch something now.

02:05:08.760 --> 02:05:12.680
And we're all like, "Ah, Korean skincare.
Like, let's put it all over us."

02:05:12.760 --> 02:05:14.120
So, like, go wear something,

02:05:14.200 --> 02:05:16.600
because consumers already
are thinking of you with that.

02:05:16.680 --> 02:05:20.400
So, then you don't have to, like,
train them to change their minds.

02:05:20.480 --> 02:05:23.320
You're like, "Okay.
Do you think Indians do good haircare?

02:05:23.400 --> 02:05:26.720
Here, an exhibit A, my mom,
who has hair down to her ankles,

02:05:26.800 --> 02:05:28.280
and she's 63 years old."

02:05:28.360 --> 02:05:29.800
-Does she?
-She does. Yeah.

02:05:29.880 --> 02:05:31.960
She has really, really long hair.

02:05:32.040 --> 02:05:34.600
Um, and so, it's, like,
you give that exhibit.

02:05:34.680 --> 02:05:37.560
And, like, the same way
shea butter came from Africa.

02:05:37.640 --> 02:05:42.480
Shea Marie is a brand in the US
that sells, like, insane.

02:05:42.560 --> 02:05:44.240
It's one of the best
haircare brands there.

02:05:44.320 --> 02:05:45.560
And the story is,

02:05:45.640 --> 02:05:47.440
the grandmother, on the side of the road,

02:05:47.520 --> 02:05:49.040
sold shea butter.

02:05:49.120 --> 02:05:51.480
And look at her hair
and how amazing it made.

02:05:51.560 --> 02:05:54.400
And that story,
they've kind of built over the last,

02:05:54.480 --> 02:05:56.480
I think, two or three decades.

02:05:56.560 --> 02:05:58.280
And it's this amazing...

02:05:58.360 --> 02:06:02.280
And now, shea butter is really, you know,
the ingredient for moisture.

02:06:02.360 --> 02:06:03.800
And you've seen this
happen in India, by the way.

02:06:03.880 --> 02:06:05.960
Indians are known for hair.
Also, what else?

02:06:06.040 --> 02:06:07.280
Weddings?

02:06:07.360 --> 02:06:09.800
-Weddings. We said food.
-Yeah, I think just--

02:06:09.880 --> 02:06:11.800
-Animals.
-Their--

02:06:11.880 --> 02:06:13.800
-Animals.
-Animals?

02:06:13.880 --> 02:06:15.280
-I think, family--
-Tigers?

02:06:15.360 --> 02:06:17.240
Whenever I speak to a foreigner
about India,

02:06:17.320 --> 02:06:21.240
they have a mental image of,
like, tigers and snakes and all of that.

02:06:21.880 --> 02:06:23.280
Elephants?

02:06:23.360 --> 02:06:24.480
I think family.

02:06:24.560 --> 02:06:27.280
-Like, there's a lot of, like--
-Asian culture.

02:06:27.360 --> 02:06:30.600
Asian culture, right?
Warmth, vibrancy, like, just...

02:06:30.680 --> 02:06:33.280
-And, yeah. I think...
-Music. Music.

02:06:33.360 --> 02:06:35.280
-Music.
-Classical music, yeah.

02:06:35.360 --> 02:06:36.960
-Punjabi music also.
-Punjabi music.

02:06:37.040 --> 02:06:40.360
And it's stereotyping,
but I feel like India's very vibrant

02:06:40.440 --> 02:06:42.280
in terms of its colour palette, right?

02:06:42.360 --> 02:06:44.280
So, you always expect an Indian brand
to be colourful.

02:06:44.360 --> 02:06:46.000
-I think of, like, Jaipur.
-Yeah.

02:06:46.080 --> 02:06:48.200
Like Udaipur. Yeah, yeah. That's true.

02:06:48.280 --> 02:06:52.280
Palaces, palatial, that stuff, yeah.

02:06:52.360 --> 02:06:54.240
We've actually seen
what she's saying, right?

02:06:54.320 --> 02:06:55.800
-Religion.
-New-age brands?

02:06:55.880 --> 02:06:58.800
Spirituality.
More than religion, I'd say spirituality.

02:06:58.880 --> 02:07:00.400
-Really?
-Yeah.

02:07:00.480 --> 02:07:02.800
-Hinduism, yeah.
-Two different things.

02:07:02.880 --> 02:07:04.040
We're saying two different things.

02:07:04.120 --> 02:07:06.800
I don't think they look at India
purely as Hinduism,

02:07:06.880 --> 02:07:08.680
because they don't know
enough about Ganesh

02:07:08.760 --> 02:07:09.760
and, like, all of that.

02:07:09.840 --> 02:07:12.360
But they look at Indians being
very spiritual people.

02:07:14.240 --> 02:07:17.360
We do our morning meditations.

02:07:17.440 --> 02:07:19.960
None of us do. But they think we do.

02:07:20.040 --> 02:07:21.800
My husband wakes up at 5:45.

02:07:21.880 --> 02:07:23.280
He does it?

02:07:23.360 --> 02:07:25.280
We're more pious.
Yeah, we're a pious generation.

02:07:25.360 --> 02:07:27.280
-Yeah.
-It's not fun, but...

02:07:27.360 --> 02:07:28.400
What else?

02:07:28.480 --> 02:07:29.480
Because you live there,

02:07:30.200 --> 02:07:32.280
you're a better person
to answer this question as well.

02:07:33.000 --> 02:07:35.800
This is a funny one.
I always say in my friend group now,

02:07:35.880 --> 02:07:37.920
but, of late, CEOs.

02:07:38.000 --> 02:07:40.240
It's, like, every multinational

02:07:40.320 --> 02:07:41.760
-is an Indian CEO.
-Smarts.

02:07:41.840 --> 02:07:44.800
Yeah, intellect. Intellect. Intelligence.

02:07:44.880 --> 02:07:46.280
-Education.
-IT. Computer.

02:07:46.360 --> 02:07:50.280
Everyone in the West has that
one Indian friend who's highly educated...

02:07:50.360 --> 02:07:51.800
Doctors, engineers.

02:07:51.880 --> 02:07:53.280
...who's just doing really well
in their career.

02:07:53.360 --> 02:07:55.480
-IT, I think.
-So, if I'm building a community,

02:07:55.560 --> 02:07:58.560
I should pick something from weddings,

02:07:58.640 --> 02:08:01.960
culture, colourful, palaces,
religion, spirituality,

02:08:02.040 --> 02:08:04.400
yoga, CEOs, smart,
and build on top of that?

02:08:05.360 --> 02:08:06.640
-It's a good start.
-And food.

02:08:06.720 --> 02:08:08.800
-I think food.
-Food, don't forget, food bonds us all.

02:08:08.880 --> 02:08:13.120
Because food and--
I think even native florals, right?

02:08:13.200 --> 02:08:15.280
-There's--
-Food, masala, like that?

02:08:15.360 --> 02:08:18.280
-No, I think--
-It's cultural consumption, no?

02:08:18.360 --> 02:08:20.280
-Yeah.
-Chicken tikka masala.

02:08:20.360 --> 02:08:23.280
Like, that could be a perfume.
Chicken Tikka Masala.

02:08:24.360 --> 02:08:25.800
-Dilip?
-Like, Jalebi,

02:08:25.880 --> 02:08:29.800
she's launched jalebi
and chai lip balms. So, again...

02:08:29.880 --> 02:08:31.800
I wouldn't launch Chicken Tikka Masala.

02:08:31.880 --> 02:08:34.280
I'm not sure. That's one of the stuff--

02:08:34.360 --> 02:08:36.280
-It doesn't sit right.
-Okay.

02:08:36.360 --> 02:08:38.960
Yeah, I think what she said
touched on florals as well, I think.

02:08:39.040 --> 02:08:42.760
And maybe the West doesn't know it enough,
but that is something we can scream about.

02:08:42.840 --> 02:08:44.680
-Our flowers.
-[Nikhil] Really?

02:08:44.760 --> 02:08:46.760
The jasmine, the champaka,
the firangi paani.

02:08:46.840 --> 02:08:47.880
Rajnigandha.

02:08:47.960 --> 02:08:49.400
-[Bhakti] The rose.
-Rajnigandha.

02:08:50.360 --> 02:08:53.800
These are... And they have roots in India.

02:08:53.880 --> 02:08:56.040
And I'm not saying
they're only native to India,

02:08:56.120 --> 02:08:58.000
but they have
a huge amount of storytelling.

02:08:58.080 --> 02:08:59.800
-And history here.
-And history here.

02:08:59.880 --> 02:09:00.880
How about temples?

02:09:03.000 --> 02:09:05.880
Temple smell?
What if Dilip sells temple scent?

02:09:05.960 --> 02:09:07.360
That ittar.

02:09:07.440 --> 02:09:09.360
-Phool?
-Phool and ittar.

02:09:09.440 --> 02:09:10.880
That Phool thing is used temple flowers.

02:09:10.960 --> 02:09:12.840
What if Dilip's perfume brand
is called Temple?

02:09:13.960 --> 02:09:15.960
-Cute, I like it.
-Yeah?

02:09:16.960 --> 02:09:19.920
Agarbatti is like a very, very...
Makes the house smell aromatic.

02:09:20.000 --> 02:09:21.480
Agarbatti needs to be disrupted.

02:09:22.520 --> 02:09:24.800
But we're saying
bring back the old in a new way.

02:09:24.880 --> 02:09:25.880
Yeah.

02:09:25.960 --> 02:09:27.920
So, Temple, maybe,
has a hint of agarbatti somewhere.

02:09:28.000 --> 02:09:29.040
The perfume "Temple".

02:09:29.120 --> 02:09:30.920
But you can also make it,
"Your body is your temple."

02:09:31.000 --> 02:09:32.440
It has camphor.

02:09:32.520 --> 02:09:33.920
-Exactly.
-Agarbatti, for example...

02:09:34.000 --> 02:09:36.920
And the smell, actually,
is about cleansing the home.

02:09:37.000 --> 02:09:38.520
-Mm.
-That's what the Indian home does.

02:09:38.600 --> 02:09:40.840
-Sage.
-And camphor's also about, like,

02:09:40.920 --> 02:09:41.960
you know, good energy,

02:09:42.040 --> 02:09:44.440
and making sure that
you are purifying your space.

02:09:44.520 --> 02:09:46.440
Dilip is starting to feel better.

02:09:46.520 --> 02:09:47.680
[Diipa] That's great.

02:09:47.760 --> 02:09:50.880
Is there a tech play here
to identify which product?

02:09:50.960 --> 02:09:55.200
Let's say we are doing morning, night.

02:09:55.320 --> 02:09:56.320
There's two products.

02:09:56.400 --> 02:09:59.480
Morning has sunscreen,
plus moisturiser, plus niacinamide,

02:09:59.560 --> 02:10:01.680
plus vitamin C.

02:10:01.760 --> 02:10:06.000
-Night has... peptides...
-Magnesium.

02:10:06.080 --> 02:10:08.320
...magnesium and retinol?

02:10:08.400 --> 02:10:09.600
-[Bhakti] Yeah.
-Okay.

02:10:09.680 --> 02:10:11.200
-Good.
-And if we combine--

02:10:11.280 --> 02:10:13.200
If we have two bottles in the bathroom,

02:10:13.280 --> 02:10:15.920
A, I would love that,
'cause it removes so much clutter.

02:10:18.480 --> 02:10:20.920
Is there a tech play to figure out

02:10:21.000 --> 02:10:23.520
Diipa's morning is different
from Nikhil's morning?

02:10:24.520 --> 02:10:26.640
And Bhakti's night is different
from Shantanu's?

02:10:27.520 --> 02:10:29.920
-Using AI?
-[Nikhil] Using anything. AI.

02:10:30.000 --> 02:10:31.920
If you have enough data, for sure.

02:10:32.000 --> 02:10:38.560
Just about taking a picture of your face
and asking a genetic AI to tell you

02:10:38.640 --> 02:10:39.880
which product to use.

02:10:39.960 --> 02:10:42.040
Which, either pick
morning one or morning two.

02:10:42.120 --> 02:10:45.640
I mean, there's a lot of advances in that.
My only concern with that then is,

02:10:45.720 --> 02:10:48.280
are you going to the model
of hyper-personalisation?

02:10:48.360 --> 02:10:51.440
Because then, operationally,
I don't know how that's going to work.

02:10:51.520 --> 02:10:52.920
That's what we were saying, right?

02:10:53.000 --> 02:10:55.440
It's just too many
permutations, combinations.

02:10:55.520 --> 02:10:57.400
What if you only have three SKUs?

02:10:57.480 --> 02:10:59.440
Three mornings and three nights?

02:10:59.520 --> 02:11:01.400
-Okay. Then, it can work.
-One is right for me.

02:11:01.480 --> 02:11:02.920
-One is right for her.
-Then you come on the website.

02:11:03.000 --> 02:11:04.440
You come on the website,

02:11:04.520 --> 02:11:05.920
-you show--
-Give you a quiz.

02:11:06.000 --> 02:11:07.440
Take a photo, do a quiz,
give your details.

02:11:07.520 --> 02:11:08.920
No quiz, nothing, no questions.

02:11:09.000 --> 02:11:10.520
-Just photo?
-Just photo.

02:11:10.600 --> 02:11:12.280
That's fine as well. We can tell you...

02:11:12.360 --> 02:11:14.440
There's skin analysers that'll tell you...

02:11:14.520 --> 02:11:17.080
The thing with that is you're not
giving it your environment.

02:11:17.160 --> 02:11:19.440
Are you hot, humid, cold?
Are you living in Canada?

02:11:19.520 --> 02:11:22.920
You can add that layer as well.
I can figure out your location.

02:11:23.000 --> 02:11:25.520
No, you can take a--
You can put in your location.

02:11:27.040 --> 02:11:29.160
-So, just one picture.
-Yeah.

02:11:30.520 --> 02:11:34.760
So, you walk into a website,
one picture that you take there.

02:11:34.840 --> 02:11:38.920
And then, you say
morning two is right for you

02:11:39.000 --> 02:11:40.280
and night three is right for you.

02:11:40.360 --> 02:11:41.440
Send it. Done.

02:11:41.520 --> 02:11:43.440
And age, the picture has to calculate?

02:11:43.520 --> 02:11:46.040
Because the physical age
does not matter with skin age.

02:11:46.120 --> 02:11:48.400
-If you have three SKUs...
-And you can do a try-before-you-buy.

02:11:48.480 --> 02:11:51.760
Saying, "Okay, try it, if you like it,
I mean, and you, uh...

02:11:51.840 --> 02:11:52.960
You know, you pre-book it.

02:11:53.040 --> 02:11:55.400
If you don't like it,
you can send it back to me

02:11:55.480 --> 02:11:56.960
and I'll give you your money back."

02:11:57.040 --> 02:11:58.440
-Wow, Bhakti.
-So you can absolutely do that.

02:11:58.520 --> 02:11:59.920
I'm just saying, for a brand--

02:12:00.000 --> 02:12:02.280
Because a brand, Il Makiage,
has just done this.

02:12:02.360 --> 02:12:04.000
So, they have the try-before-you-buy.

02:12:04.080 --> 02:12:07.840
And they've also built their tech platform
called Oddity

02:12:07.920 --> 02:12:09.480
which is all about, again,

02:12:10.400 --> 02:12:14.200
really predicting what shade
will match you.

02:12:14.280 --> 02:12:16.440
So, they, sometimes,
will send you three shades.

02:12:16.520 --> 02:12:20.200
In colour, I see this work very well
because now you have lipstick try-ons.

02:12:20.280 --> 02:12:21.560
-You have...
-Virtual try-ons.

02:12:21.640 --> 02:12:23.080
Everything in colour.

02:12:23.160 --> 02:12:24.800
But even with skincare,
because if you have tech

02:12:24.880 --> 02:12:29.040
that's good enough to kind of
give you at least 96 to 98% accuracy.

02:12:29.120 --> 02:12:31.840
If they can indeed, like,
zoom in and analyse, "Oh, he has pores,

02:12:31.920 --> 02:12:34.960
or he has under-eye circles
or he has acne,

02:12:35.040 --> 02:12:37.200
then he needs these and these ingredients.

02:12:37.280 --> 02:12:41.440
Or he looks a bit older, so he needs
more, like, peptides and that stuff."

02:12:41.520 --> 02:12:44.960
And we can change the form factor
of the bottle to have 1, 2, 3.

02:12:45.040 --> 02:12:47.440
-Yeah.
-So you put 1 on, then 2 on, then 3 on.

02:12:47.520 --> 02:12:49.440
-You love your 1, 2, 3.
-1, 2.

02:12:49.520 --> 02:12:50.960
No, but if you're gonna have fewer SKUs...

02:12:51.040 --> 02:12:53.440
I hate looking at clutter,
and each time I go into my bathroom...

02:12:53.520 --> 02:12:55.640
But if you have fewer SKUs,
then you don't need tech.

02:12:56.560 --> 02:12:59.440
I think the juice
is not worth the squeeze at all.

02:12:59.520 --> 02:13:01.440
No, he's saying tech so that the customer
knows what they should know.

02:13:01.520 --> 02:13:03.680
He basically doesn't want
to interact with anyone.

02:13:03.760 --> 02:13:04.960
-[Nikhil] Yes.
-He's like, "This is it."

02:13:05.040 --> 02:13:06.760
No, but that,
the customer will figure it out.

02:13:06.840 --> 02:13:08.560
The tech is when what she's saying is--

02:13:08.640 --> 02:13:09.840
No, customer figuring out is very hard.

02:13:09.920 --> 02:13:11.960
-How will the customer figure it out?
-I don't know what I should use.

02:13:12.040 --> 02:13:14.960
The brand has three SKUs.
They'll figure it out.

02:13:15.040 --> 02:13:17.440
[Diipa] But, for sure,
how would a customer know?

02:13:17.520 --> 02:13:19.440
You believe the customer knows everything.

02:13:19.520 --> 02:13:21.960
If they don't have any information...

02:13:22.040 --> 02:13:23.960
Can I tell you?
I have no clue what is good for my skin.

02:13:24.040 --> 02:13:25.440
You knew peptides, though.

02:13:25.520 --> 02:13:26.720
Yeah.

02:13:27.680 --> 02:13:30.760
But I have no clue what I should use,
when I should use,

02:13:30.840 --> 02:13:31.960
if something is right for me.

02:13:32.040 --> 02:13:34.960
If you want to solve that problem,
then you can't have a three-SKU business.

02:13:35.040 --> 02:13:37.040
-Sorry?
-You can't have a three-SKU business.

02:13:37.120 --> 02:13:39.720
-Why?
-Because you're super-blending everything.

02:13:39.800 --> 02:13:41.960
We are not believing
that this is the right product.

02:13:42.040 --> 02:13:44.240
Your premise is, "I'm gonna
mix everything and give it to you."

02:13:44.320 --> 02:13:46.960
And then, you're like,
"Okay, I've mixed everything..."

02:13:48.040 --> 02:13:50.040
-Choose one.
-I think what he is saying is...

02:13:50.120 --> 02:13:52.440
Not every active ingredient...

02:13:52.520 --> 02:13:54.920
He's saying one becomes
a supersonic brightening one.

02:13:55.000 --> 02:13:57.720
One becomes a supersonic anti-ageing one.

02:13:57.800 --> 02:13:59.960
One becomes a supersonic acne one.

02:14:00.040 --> 02:14:04.000
And then, people whose skin
is more prone to one or the other...

02:14:04.080 --> 02:14:05.440
-They'll know, no?
-...they get that.

02:14:05.520 --> 02:14:08.440
-How will they know all this?
-The acne guy will know.

02:14:08.520 --> 02:14:11.440
-I don't know.
-You don't have acne. You don't need it.

02:14:11.520 --> 02:14:14.440
We're also super-simplifying it.

02:14:14.520 --> 02:14:15.960
I don't think you can have three SKUs.

02:14:16.040 --> 02:14:19.080
One element that we are also missing
is, while all of this is great,

02:14:19.160 --> 02:14:24.480
consumers, today, still buy 80% of beauty
for the first time in a store,

02:14:24.560 --> 02:14:25.880
in an offline environment,

02:14:25.960 --> 02:14:29.320
because the emotional touch-feel factor

02:14:29.400 --> 02:14:32.440
is still so huge in beauty, right?
That you want to--

02:14:32.520 --> 02:14:34.840
80%? That's a shocking stat.

02:14:34.920 --> 02:14:41.440
By 2028, beauty will be 33% online
and 67% offline.

02:14:41.520 --> 02:14:43.440
But the trend is going more online.

02:14:43.520 --> 02:14:47.360
It is, but I feel like offline
will still dominate significantly.

02:14:47.440 --> 02:14:50.440
-There will still be a healthy mix--
-I think for first purchase.

02:14:50.520 --> 02:14:51.960
First purchase.

02:14:52.040 --> 02:14:53.960
Second purchase is definitely online.

02:14:54.040 --> 02:14:57.200
But that's why offline is moving
to being all about experiences.

02:14:57.280 --> 02:14:58.680
It's all about experiential marketing.

02:14:58.760 --> 02:15:02.440
It's all about creating your stores
as experience centres.

02:15:02.520 --> 02:15:07.560
Because for people who travel a lot,
like, I travel incessantly.

02:15:07.640 --> 02:15:10.280
I've been travelling
for the last three months.

02:15:10.360 --> 02:15:12.960
I'm not going to carry
ten bottles with me.

02:15:13.040 --> 02:15:15.960
-But minis, you can carry...
-But we agree.

02:15:16.040 --> 02:15:18.440
Skin-minimalism is the thing.

02:15:18.520 --> 02:15:20.360
-I think also for supplements.
-Yeah.

02:15:20.440 --> 02:15:22.960
I'm not going to carry ten boxes of...

02:15:23.040 --> 02:15:25.040
Like what AG1... Do you know AG1?

02:15:25.120 --> 02:15:28.200
What AG1 did with supplementation
was phenomenal.

02:15:28.280 --> 02:15:30.880
Like, I was waiting
for that my whole life.

02:15:30.960 --> 02:15:36.040
And now, Perelel is another supplement
brand in the US, UV-backed as well.

02:15:36.120 --> 02:15:38.840
And they put all your supplements
in one packet.

02:15:38.920 --> 02:15:40.000
So, it's, like...

02:15:40.080 --> 02:15:42.680
You just have to open the packet
and just take it in the morning.

02:15:42.760 --> 02:15:44.440
Or why not even in one pill?

02:15:44.520 --> 02:15:47.960
I think because active ingredients
can interact with each other.

02:15:48.040 --> 02:15:51.960
Like an omega-3 is oil-based,
but, like, vitamin C is a powder-base.

02:15:52.040 --> 02:15:53.160
Yeah.

02:15:53.240 --> 02:15:56.440
-But I think simplifying time...
-Yeah.

02:15:56.520 --> 02:15:59.840
...and simplifying life by optimising
for time is a great idea.

02:15:59.920 --> 02:16:00.960
Bathroom break?

02:16:01.040 --> 02:16:03.960
I think they want it. I can take one.

02:16:04.040 --> 02:16:05.960
-Yeah, I don't mind.
-Yeah, I don't mind.

02:16:06.040 --> 02:16:08.960
-Take a bathroom break.
-You guys hungry?

02:16:09.880 --> 02:16:11.800
I like your tattoos. What do they say?

02:16:13.280 --> 02:16:18.440
So, my job is that of a trader
in the stock market. It's my primary job.

02:16:18.520 --> 02:16:22.840
So, "delay gratification" is a reminder
not to sell stuff fast,

02:16:22.920 --> 02:16:24.280
which I tend to do a lot.

02:16:25.360 --> 02:16:27.600
Without the tattoo, you would forget?

02:16:27.680 --> 02:16:30.080
-[Bhakti] Be patient.
-I don't remember with the tattoo, so...

02:16:31.520 --> 02:16:33.120
"Be here now" is not...

02:16:35.280 --> 02:16:37.000
I have a tendency to procrastinate.

02:16:37.080 --> 02:16:40.920
I spent a lot of my life thinking
what will happen five years from now,

02:16:41.000 --> 02:16:43.040
ten years from now. That.

02:16:43.880 --> 02:16:48.800
This says, "Do unto others as you would
have others do unto you."

02:16:49.920 --> 02:16:56.160
Which I feel like is a simple model,
if you had to pick one to live by.

02:16:57.440 --> 02:16:59.200
And this is my handwriting.

02:16:59.280 --> 02:17:02.720
I like that. And all together
or in different moments in life?

02:17:02.800 --> 02:17:04.800
-Different moments in life.
-That's really nice.

02:17:04.880 --> 02:17:06.200
Very cool.

02:17:06.280 --> 02:17:08.200
And the date of when I got it
is also there.

02:17:08.280 --> 02:17:10.720
See, this is 2013.

02:17:10.800 --> 02:17:12.720
Very cool.

02:17:12.800 --> 02:17:15.400
-Do you have tattoos?
-Yeah, a bunch.

02:17:15.480 --> 02:17:16.960
This one is the funniest.

02:17:17.040 --> 02:17:20.320
Back then, tattoos used to be quite thick.

02:17:20.400 --> 02:17:22.360
Now you can make them
really thin and beautiful.

02:17:22.440 --> 02:17:24.400
But these are bleeding
a little into each other.

02:17:24.480 --> 02:17:27.480
But it's Roman,
and it's like a conversation starter.

02:17:27.560 --> 02:17:29.360
Every time someone is like,
"What does your tattoo say?"

02:17:29.440 --> 02:17:31.200
I'm like, "Decode it."

02:17:32.080 --> 02:17:37.720
But it basically is Roman numerals
for the letter G,

02:17:37.800 --> 02:17:39.920
it's the 11th letter in the alphabet.

02:17:40.000 --> 02:17:41.720
R-I-T.

02:17:41.800 --> 02:17:44.600
So, when I was in my
final year in high school,

02:17:44.680 --> 02:17:48.720
I did a thesis on
what makes people successful.

02:17:48.800 --> 02:17:51.280
I think it was my social psychology
class or something.

02:17:51.360 --> 02:17:54.000
I was obsessed with
how do people become successful?

02:17:54.080 --> 02:17:56.920
What is it that makes them
different from everybody else?

02:17:57.000 --> 02:18:01.160
And long story short,
the end answer was grit.

02:18:01.240 --> 02:18:03.600
That, whether you have money or not,

02:18:03.680 --> 02:18:07.440
whether you're beautiful or not,
whether you have the right people,

02:18:07.520 --> 02:18:08.720
if you just have grit,

02:18:08.800 --> 02:18:11.720
that was a common denominator
in every successful person.

02:18:11.800 --> 02:18:14.160
And so, I was like,
"I need to tattoo that."

02:18:14.240 --> 02:18:16.680
What is the biggest thing
you have going for you?

02:18:16.760 --> 02:18:18.720
Why is Diipa successful?

02:18:19.800 --> 02:18:21.720
"Why is Diipa successful?"

02:18:23.280 --> 02:18:25.000
Can I have multiple answers?

02:18:25.080 --> 02:18:26.520
One.

02:18:26.600 --> 02:18:27.760
Grit.

02:18:29.640 --> 02:18:31.680
In the face of adversity?

02:18:31.760 --> 02:18:33.200
Yeah.

02:18:33.280 --> 02:18:34.680
Adversity being?

02:18:34.760 --> 02:18:40.280
I mean, as an entrepreneur, as a founder,
you're hit with, like, the velocity

02:18:40.360 --> 02:18:44.080
and the amount of shit
that hits you on a daily basis,

02:18:44.160 --> 02:18:47.920
and whether it's rejections
or noes or things not working out.

02:18:48.000 --> 02:18:51.400
And a good founder and entrepreneur
is the one who's able to take that

02:18:51.480 --> 02:18:53.960
and come on the other side
over and over and over again.

02:18:54.040 --> 02:18:58.040
Even when you think, "Finally,
I'm on the other side, the sun is shining,

02:18:58.120 --> 02:19:00.960
the sales are great,
something else will come around."

02:19:01.040 --> 02:19:03.600
So, I think people
who can really withstand that

02:19:03.680 --> 02:19:07.680
will end up being good entrepreneurs,
according to me.

02:19:08.560 --> 02:19:12.680
-And pre-entrepreneurship?
-Pre-entrepreneurship...

02:19:14.760 --> 02:19:19.760
I think I just really wanted to be
somebody that did something with her life.

02:19:19.840 --> 02:19:22.240
I wanted to be-- like, leave a mark.

02:19:22.320 --> 02:19:27.960
I know it sounds a bit cliché,
but my biggest fear was to die ordinary.

02:19:28.040 --> 02:19:32.640
I'm like, "What if... what if I don't
become an anybody or nobody?"

02:19:32.720 --> 02:19:35.560
Like, you get this one life
to live, make it count.

02:19:35.640 --> 02:19:38.400
You know, so that was something
that always kept me going as a child.

02:19:38.480 --> 02:19:42.680
Make sure you do something worthwhile.
Make sure your life means something.

02:19:42.760 --> 02:19:45.400
And make sure it also means
something bigger than yourself.

02:19:45.480 --> 02:19:47.080
Interesting.

02:19:47.160 --> 02:19:49.240
Digressing from our subject for a second,

02:19:49.320 --> 02:19:52.120
you didn't tell us about
how you started Tira.

02:19:52.200 --> 02:19:54.560
And you didn't finish
what happened after McKinsey.

02:19:54.640 --> 02:19:57.240
Maybe we do a little bit of your lives.

02:19:57.320 --> 02:19:58.400
-[Bhakti] Yeah.
-You want to go first?

02:19:58.480 --> 02:20:02.760
Okay. So, I had nothing to do with beauty.

02:20:02.840 --> 02:20:05.240
I started, you know...

02:20:05.320 --> 02:20:09.560
did my undergrad in
psychology and communication,

02:20:09.640 --> 02:20:13.480
graduated and got my first job at Macy's.

02:20:13.560 --> 02:20:16.680
-Cool.
-But, as a management trainee,

02:20:16.760 --> 02:20:21.880
and then in fashion, you weren't really
going to get anything post your OPT.

02:20:21.960 --> 02:20:26.080
So, my dad was like,
"Come home and figure it out."

02:20:26.160 --> 02:20:28.120
So, I had no plan.

02:20:28.200 --> 02:20:33.920
I think I've always kind of been,
I like to say, good at many things,

02:20:34.000 --> 02:20:39.120
and, you know,
I was average at a lot of things.

02:20:39.200 --> 02:20:40.400
I was good at a lot of things.

02:20:40.480 --> 02:20:43.280
And I think I was always
trying to find that one purpose,

02:20:43.360 --> 02:20:47.920
that kind of, you know,
what is it that will make me feel,

02:20:48.000 --> 02:20:49.720
"Oh, wow, I've got it as well."

02:20:49.800 --> 02:20:52.040
You know, because you
keep looking at other people,

02:20:52.120 --> 02:20:55.880
and everyone has something about them
or they know what they want to do.

02:20:55.960 --> 02:20:58.880
And I think it can't be easy
having a dad like your dad.

02:20:58.960 --> 02:21:01.400
Yeah. But I don't think...

02:21:01.480 --> 02:21:02.880
I feel the opposite is true.

02:21:02.960 --> 02:21:04.880
-Yeah.
-It can or it can't be easy?

02:21:04.960 --> 02:21:06.400
I think it depends on the kid.

02:21:06.480 --> 02:21:08.640
The unhappiest people I know

02:21:08.720 --> 02:21:13.840
are people who have these really,
really large figures as their parents

02:21:13.920 --> 02:21:15.720
because happiness is always relative.

02:21:15.800 --> 02:21:20.400
And you get your validation when you
get something beyond what they have.

02:21:20.480 --> 02:21:22.680
-But--
-And if you start at that scale,

02:21:22.760 --> 02:21:25.720
like, I could have gone from A to B
and got validated.

02:21:25.800 --> 02:21:27.880
She has to go from Z to Z-plus.

02:21:27.960 --> 02:21:30.440
-Yeah.
-But I don't think... I...

02:21:30.520 --> 02:21:33.600
What I liked about my childhood was,

02:21:33.680 --> 02:21:36.680
yeah, I grew up
in a conservative household.

02:21:36.760 --> 02:21:38.640
My parents were strict, you know.

02:21:38.720 --> 02:21:39.760
Follow deadlines.

02:21:39.840 --> 02:21:42.440
I wasn't allowed to be out till 1:00 a.m.

02:21:42.520 --> 02:21:43.880
My dad always opened the door.

02:21:43.960 --> 02:21:47.120
Even, you know, didn't have the keys
to my house, even when I grew up.

02:21:47.200 --> 02:21:50.240
But I think that the one thing
that I am very grateful for

02:21:50.320 --> 02:21:52.800
is that I grew up without pressure.
I grew up--

02:21:52.880 --> 02:21:55.520
Sweet, but that's probably
because people were trying to kidnap you.

02:21:55.600 --> 02:21:57.200
[laughter]

02:21:57.280 --> 02:21:58.720
Okay, but go ahead...

02:21:58.800 --> 02:22:00.080
[Diipa] KGB.

02:22:00.160 --> 02:22:03.280
I think that's what...
That trend has kind of followed me.

02:22:03.360 --> 02:22:08.280
I graduated and then came here,
and as a 21-year-old,

02:22:08.360 --> 02:22:11.760
was very enamoured with
this whole retail side, right?

02:22:11.840 --> 02:22:14.000
And Reliance Brands had just started up.

02:22:14.080 --> 02:22:19.760
And my first ever gig was when...

02:22:19.840 --> 02:22:21.720
Darshan told me, he's like,

02:22:21.800 --> 02:22:24.720
"Okay, you want to work in retail,
then you need to know how to sell."

02:22:24.800 --> 02:22:29.720
So, my first job was selling shoes
on the Timberland's store-front.

02:22:29.800 --> 02:22:33.160
He said, "You will be allowed
to enter my office after you want to...

02:22:33.240 --> 02:22:36.200
after you've actually sold something."

02:22:36.280 --> 02:22:38.080
And I was like, "Okay, cool, I'll do it."

02:22:38.160 --> 02:22:41.960
So I've done the...
the six-to-eight-month...

02:22:43.920 --> 02:22:48.920
shopfront associate, sales associate job,
when I was selling Timberland shoes,

02:22:49.000 --> 02:22:51.760
and in Mumbai,
where the weather is completely

02:22:51.840 --> 02:22:54.560
not accustomed to selling winter wear.

02:22:54.640 --> 02:22:57.200
And I learnt something.

02:22:57.280 --> 02:23:00.520
I learnt this one rule
from my boss at that time,

02:23:00.600 --> 02:23:02.800
where he said that
it's a rule in the retail industry

02:23:02.880 --> 02:23:07.480
that for-- particularly for footwear,
so if someone's coming to buy...

02:23:07.560 --> 02:23:10.320
buy one pair of shoes,
you bring out three for them.

02:23:10.400 --> 02:23:12.440
Because if you don't--
They don't like that one,

02:23:12.520 --> 02:23:15.160
you sell them,
you make them try the other two.

02:23:15.240 --> 02:23:16.760
-That's very good.
-So, it was a three-box rule.

02:23:16.840 --> 02:23:21.360
And, for me,
I remember I told my sister, my dad,

02:23:21.440 --> 02:23:24.120
that, "Oh, we're having
an end-of-season sale."

02:23:24.200 --> 02:23:28.880
And my mom and him came and they bought
that one pair of shoes just to...

02:23:28.960 --> 02:23:33.560
it was that, that really, also,
again, validated that...

02:23:33.640 --> 02:23:37.040
To that 21-year-old, meant a lot,

02:23:37.120 --> 02:23:41.120
because for me, that was like, "Oh, wow,
I've done that thing for myself."

02:23:41.200 --> 02:23:45.360
And then, I worked in retail
for about, I had...

02:23:45.440 --> 02:23:51.960
You're talking about
having this larger than life...

02:23:52.040 --> 02:23:53.480
figure.

02:23:53.560 --> 02:23:55.320
I think I used--
I turned that as an opportunity.

02:23:55.400 --> 02:23:59.480
I got access to opportunity,
and I never took it to waste.

02:23:59.560 --> 02:24:04.440
I believed that I had access,
and I really, really used it.

02:24:04.520 --> 02:24:07.000
I feel like I've overcompensated,
at times.

02:24:07.080 --> 02:24:09.600
I would sometimes be
the last one to stay back,

02:24:09.680 --> 02:24:12.800
and I wanted to always prove
that I could do it.

02:24:12.880 --> 02:24:15.920
And, at some point, I just embraced it,
"Yes, this is who I am,

02:24:16.000 --> 02:24:20.400
and I'm going to make use of everything
that I have and I'm going to do it."

02:24:20.480 --> 02:24:23.280
I didn't know what I was
going to do when I was 21,

02:24:23.360 --> 02:24:26.280
but I worked through multiple roles
and I still was figuring it out.

02:24:26.360 --> 02:24:29.200
I worked in fashion for eight years.

02:24:29.280 --> 02:24:33.240
I did buying, I worked at AJIO,
and when I got married

02:24:33.320 --> 02:24:36.120
after working in Reliance Brands
for about five years,

02:24:36.200 --> 02:24:38.680
I moved to AJIO and I did
something completely different,

02:24:38.760 --> 02:24:40.000
which was inventory planning.

02:24:40.080 --> 02:24:44.200
My boss at that time asked me that,
"Yes, you can do marketing

02:24:44.280 --> 02:24:47.440
or do something completely different
and learn inventory planning."

02:24:47.520 --> 02:24:50.640
So I learnt all about
couponing, discounting,

02:24:50.720 --> 02:24:53.880
how do you manage inventory,
how do you look at...

02:24:53.960 --> 02:24:57.320
how do you calculate everything
when it comes to e-commerce?"

02:24:57.400 --> 02:24:58.480
I learnt the basics then.

02:24:58.560 --> 02:25:01.760
And I think I'm grateful
for the opportunities

02:25:01.840 --> 02:25:05.040
and also the people that I met
through that time to kind of...

02:25:05.960 --> 02:25:12.280
kind of give me that confidence that,
"Okay, I got a varied...

02:25:12.360 --> 02:25:16.960
just multitudes of opportunity
that I would have not gotten."

02:25:17.040 --> 02:25:19.200
I'm so grateful, super grateful for that.

02:25:19.280 --> 02:25:21.520
And after that,
I was in fashion for so many years.

02:25:21.600 --> 02:25:25.160
I was like, that's when that,
"Oh, I want to do something on my own."

02:25:25.240 --> 02:25:27.600
I believed that I could do a lot more.

02:25:27.680 --> 02:25:30.640
And I was like, "Okay, I want to now
get out and do my own thing."

02:25:30.720 --> 02:25:33.720
And I was like, "Okay, I think
I want to go to school again."

02:25:33.800 --> 02:25:37.960
I always thought that I wanted to go back
to school and do something

02:25:38.040 --> 02:25:40.520
that was completely different
from what I had done.

02:25:40.600 --> 02:25:43.120
And I wanted to then
be in the fashion space.

02:25:43.200 --> 02:25:48.080
I applied to Parsons for their AAS degree,

02:25:48.160 --> 02:25:51.000
which is for people
who want to change careers.

02:25:51.080 --> 02:25:54.520
So, I had friends who were lawyers,
who were doctors,

02:25:54.600 --> 02:25:56.120
who all wanted to get
into the fashion space.

02:25:56.200 --> 02:26:00.360
So, you basically take a four-year course,
condense it into a two-year course.

02:26:00.440 --> 02:26:02.520
And I got married, moved to Bangalore.

02:26:02.600 --> 02:26:05.640
And after one year, I decided just
to move to New York for two years.

02:26:05.720 --> 02:26:10.320
So, I did long-distance marriage
and studied for those two years,

02:26:10.400 --> 02:26:14.200
purely out of passion to--
wanting to build something for myself.

02:26:14.280 --> 02:26:16.120
It really works, no?
Long-distance marriage.

02:26:16.200 --> 02:26:17.200
It's great.

02:26:19.000 --> 02:26:24.960
I think that I give so much credit
to my husband, my partner, Tejas,

02:26:25.040 --> 02:26:31.000
because I think that there was no
conversation about, "You are allowed,"

02:26:31.080 --> 02:26:33.320
which, you know, kind of stems,
these conversation stems.

02:26:33.400 --> 02:26:35.080
"Yeah, I'm allowing you to go.

02:26:35.160 --> 02:26:36.680
You should do this."

02:26:36.760 --> 02:26:38.760
It was always like, "You want to do this?"

02:26:38.840 --> 02:26:42.000
"Let's figure it out,
and you have my entire support."

02:26:42.080 --> 02:26:47.520
So, I think that kind of set the bar
for me on what I expected.

02:26:47.600 --> 02:26:49.760
And I think that...

02:26:49.840 --> 02:26:53.320
I don't think my parents ever asked me
once that, "Are you guys okay?"

02:26:53.400 --> 02:26:55.800
Just purely out of when anyone saw.

02:26:55.880 --> 02:27:00.120
And it's not like we didn't have
our fair share of fights and quarrels.

02:27:00.200 --> 02:27:04.520
But never for a moment did trust walk out.

02:27:04.600 --> 02:27:09.120
And he knew, he's like,
"You made the move to Bangalore for me,

02:27:09.200 --> 02:27:12.920
and it's only fair that I do that for you
because you want to do this."

02:27:13.000 --> 02:27:15.920
Because, imagine, if he had to go to MBA,
it would be easy that,

02:27:16.000 --> 02:27:18.320
"Oh, Bhakti will go with him."

02:27:18.400 --> 02:27:20.960
No one would say anything.

02:27:21.040 --> 02:27:24.120
If it's the opposite...
and people still gave him a lot of credit,

02:27:24.200 --> 02:27:26.200
which I do as well.
But I also went, right?

02:27:26.280 --> 02:27:29.200
So, that kind of gets lost
in the whole process.

02:27:29.280 --> 02:27:34.400
But I think we've kind of been okay
with letting that limelight go.

02:27:34.480 --> 02:27:37.080
But I think... Then when it was COVID,

02:27:37.160 --> 02:27:40.440
we lived in New York for one year
after my two-year degree

02:27:40.520 --> 02:27:42.400
because I was like,
"Okay, I'm not coming back.

02:27:42.480 --> 02:27:45.000
I have a couple of more months at school."

02:27:45.080 --> 02:27:48.840
And he took the last flight out
and came to New York

02:27:48.920 --> 02:27:51.280
and we were stuck in the pandemic
for an entire year.

02:27:51.360 --> 02:27:55.520
And it was the best time that we had
in our bubble, just figuring it out.

02:27:55.600 --> 02:28:01.080
That was that one year where I did
not work since I started working.

02:28:01.160 --> 02:28:03.280
And I was like,
"Okay, what do I want to do?"

02:28:03.360 --> 02:28:06.120
I wanted to, at that point,
start my own athleisure brand.

02:28:06.200 --> 02:28:10.000
So, I was making all my plans,
speaking to my dad, saying, "Okay, great."

02:28:10.080 --> 02:28:12.360
So, putting all my plans together.

02:28:12.440 --> 02:28:15.360
And plans never go
the way they're meant to.

02:28:15.440 --> 02:28:19.600
I moved back to India and I started again,

02:28:19.680 --> 02:28:24.080
working a little bit
on the design side with Trends

02:28:24.160 --> 02:28:28.040
because the entire fashion and lifestyle
business is in Bangalore.

02:28:28.120 --> 02:28:33.320
So, I was trying to see how I could
actually put my skills to... test.

02:28:33.400 --> 02:28:36.120
So, I was working on
designing a small collection,

02:28:36.200 --> 02:28:40.000
and then beauty just happened
to be a conversation

02:28:40.080 --> 02:28:43.240
that I was part of as a consumer.

02:28:43.320 --> 02:28:46.920
And then, it was... Nothing was planned.

02:28:47.000 --> 02:28:49.080
I had to... I remember having
this conversation with Isha

02:28:49.160 --> 02:28:51.240
where I told her, I said,
"I'm just going to--

02:28:51.320 --> 02:28:54.280
I'll be around and I definitely
want to do my own thing."

02:28:54.360 --> 02:28:57.000
She's like, "Yeah, of course,
you go ahead and it'll all work out."

02:28:57.080 --> 02:28:58.160
And that was the plan.

02:28:58.240 --> 02:29:01.040
And then, there was no set moment.

02:29:01.120 --> 02:29:03.720
It was... We named Tira together.

02:29:03.800 --> 02:29:05.480
We had about two days
to name Tira together.

02:29:05.560 --> 02:29:07.800
I know that me and her
have this Google sheet

02:29:07.880 --> 02:29:09.920
where we came up with names
like Sorbet, Blush.

02:29:10.000 --> 02:29:11.160
-And then...
-Why Tira?

02:29:11.240 --> 02:29:12.760
That's what... I'll get to that.

02:29:12.840 --> 02:29:18.280
And then, and it was
such a easy flow in that...

02:29:18.360 --> 02:29:19.800
We started from there.

02:29:19.880 --> 02:29:24.240
So, we named it Tira because we were
thinking of what are some of the best...

02:29:24.320 --> 02:29:27.600
the genesis of some of the most
powerful brand names?

02:29:27.680 --> 02:29:32.320
And if you think there's Nike,
which is from Greek mythology.

02:29:32.400 --> 02:29:34.040
Nike is a goddess of power.

02:29:34.120 --> 02:29:36.520
Sephora is from the goddess Zephyrus.

02:29:36.600 --> 02:29:38.640
So, everything was rooted.

02:29:38.720 --> 02:29:42.120
These brands were
rooted in Greek mythology.

02:29:42.200 --> 02:29:44.000
So, we're like, "We're in India.

02:29:44.080 --> 02:29:45.920
We have so much history, so much culture.

02:29:46.000 --> 02:29:48.560
Let's go back to Hindu mythology."

02:29:48.640 --> 02:29:52.720
And then we looked up
some of the Indian goddesses

02:29:52.800 --> 02:29:57.120
and goddess Rati, who is the goddess
of love, passion, and beauty.

02:29:57.200 --> 02:30:01.560
And we're like, can we make...
Tira is an anagram of goddess Rati.

02:30:01.640 --> 02:30:05.600
And the entire idea
is that when any person

02:30:05.680 --> 02:30:09.000
looks at themselves in the mirror,
they see...

02:30:09.080 --> 02:30:13.840
Every person has a unique superpower
because goddesses have superpowers.

02:30:13.920 --> 02:30:19.320
And that unique superpower on the inside
helps you feel beautiful in the outside.

02:30:19.400 --> 02:30:21.480
-And Tira celebrates that superpower.
-[Diipa] That's beautiful.

02:30:21.560 --> 02:30:24.720
So, I think...
And we didn't use an agency.

02:30:24.800 --> 02:30:27.720
You light up when you speak about Tira.
It's so nice.

02:30:27.800 --> 02:30:30.200
Why didn't you keep it Rati?
And why did you change it around?

02:30:30.280 --> 02:30:32.440
-I think it's also...
-[Diipa] It's somewhat modern.

02:30:32.520 --> 02:30:34.640
Yeah. We wanted to also let...

02:30:34.720 --> 02:30:38.080
We were making it for the Indian consumer,
but also for the--

02:30:38.160 --> 02:30:41.280
We wanted to be a global retailer
for the Indian consumer.

02:30:41.360 --> 02:30:42.440
I think we were both...

02:30:42.520 --> 02:30:47.360
I think the beauty of it is that we always
looked at the brand as consumers of beauty

02:30:47.440 --> 02:30:49.880
and what we wanted the Indian...

02:30:49.960 --> 02:30:53.680
what we wanted to have
that shopping experience in India.

02:30:53.760 --> 02:30:57.120
So, every decision we made
was from that perspective versus

02:30:57.200 --> 02:31:00.960
saying, "Okay, let's look at what else
is happening out in India."

02:31:01.040 --> 02:31:06.200
I think that gave such a fresh perspective
to what we were trying to do at Tira.

02:31:06.280 --> 02:31:08.320
What's cool about Bhakti also,

02:31:08.400 --> 02:31:11.000
whenever we run into each other
in a function,

02:31:11.080 --> 02:31:15.080
I gravitate towards her and her husband,
and I hang out with them.

02:31:17.520 --> 02:31:19.960
I couldn't quite put my finger on why,

02:31:20.040 --> 02:31:25.840
but if I asked the question I asked her
to people in her shoes,

02:31:25.920 --> 02:31:30.240
nine out of ten would be
masking insecurity

02:31:30.320 --> 02:31:33.200
with some form of ego saying,
"I did this."

02:31:35.920 --> 02:31:38.720
It takes a certain amount of...

02:31:38.800 --> 02:31:43.360
evolution to not do that.

02:31:43.440 --> 02:31:46.200
Compliment her father, then her husband

02:31:46.280 --> 02:31:50.720
and place credit elsewhere
and not take any.

02:31:50.800 --> 02:31:52.840
-[Bhakti] Thank you.
-Which is nice.

02:31:55.200 --> 02:31:57.200
I don't know how to take that,
but thank you.

02:31:57.280 --> 02:32:00.560
The Rati-Tira story,
I think more people should hear about it.

02:32:00.640 --> 02:32:02.200
-It's really beautiful.
-Thank you.

02:32:02.280 --> 02:32:08.720
That happened without an agency
and our tagline is "Tira for every you."

02:32:08.800 --> 02:32:12.720
So, we're not... When we spoke about
beauty is self-expression.

02:32:12.800 --> 02:32:16.160
I think, for us,
it's celebrating every journey,

02:32:16.240 --> 02:32:17.880
every part of your beauty journey

02:32:17.960 --> 02:32:20.680
and also just kind of alluding to the fact

02:32:20.760 --> 02:32:23.880
that wherever you are in your life,
even if it's a bad time,

02:32:23.960 --> 02:32:26.880
we got you and we want to celebrate
that version of you.

02:32:26.960 --> 02:32:28.680
We don't want you to evolve.

02:32:28.760 --> 02:32:31.280
We want you to be in that moment
'cause we are with you.

02:32:31.360 --> 02:32:36.240
And I think that kind of came from,
as women, what we feel on a daily basis.

02:32:36.320 --> 02:32:39.520
That we want someone to just tell us,
"You are enough."

02:32:39.600 --> 02:32:44.200
And I think that really
is very personal to me.

02:32:44.280 --> 02:32:50.280
And I would like to also...
if we're talking about, like, what...

02:32:50.360 --> 02:32:53.840
why Tira is so special
to both Isha and I...

02:32:53.920 --> 02:32:59.440
I think from a perspective of championing
what women leaders can be,

02:32:59.520 --> 02:33:02.480
and beauty is a space
where we've been able to do that.

02:33:02.560 --> 02:33:08.440
We have 60% women leaders and we have
one of the highest diversity ratios.

02:33:08.520 --> 02:33:13.520
We have... I have 100% success rate
in women having every...

02:33:13.600 --> 02:33:16.120
anyone who comes to Tira has a baby,

02:33:16.200 --> 02:33:18.760
goes into their maternity leave
and comes back.

02:33:18.840 --> 02:33:21.280
And I think we've... I'm so happy.

02:33:21.360 --> 02:33:23.520
I didn't know that I was
so passionate about it.

02:33:23.600 --> 02:33:24.600
But when I started this,

02:33:24.680 --> 02:33:28.720
I saw what a difference we made
to women leaders,

02:33:28.800 --> 02:33:30.720
and when people were coming back
from maternity,

02:33:30.800 --> 02:33:32.960
taking a break and coming back

02:33:33.040 --> 02:33:38.680
and seeing those leaders and the kind of
hunger they have has just been...

02:33:41.520 --> 02:33:47.240
an unknowing success that
I feel more proud of than anything else.

02:33:47.320 --> 02:33:49.680
That we've been able to do that.

02:33:49.760 --> 02:33:52.000
And I understood the power of, like...

02:33:52.080 --> 02:33:56.000
When so many women come together,
what they can put together.

02:33:56.080 --> 02:33:59.120
So I think that has been
the most special part about Tira,

02:33:59.200 --> 02:34:00.960
that it has this amazing energy,

02:34:01.040 --> 02:34:04.040
that there's everyone
who kind of wants to do something.

02:34:04.120 --> 02:34:07.360
Like, they also want to find themselves
and prove themselves.

02:34:07.440 --> 02:34:10.200
And I think that has resonated
a lot with me.

02:34:10.280 --> 02:34:13.760
If I build my brand, Dilip the Fragrance

02:34:13.840 --> 02:34:18.640
or me with morning and night
skincare product,

02:34:18.720 --> 02:34:21.040
-how do I pitch?
-Is that going to be Nikhil Kamath's line?

02:34:21.120 --> 02:34:22.760
-Yeah, why not?
-[Diipa] Morning and night, yeah.

02:34:22.840 --> 02:34:24.200
How do I pitch it to you?

02:34:27.160 --> 02:34:29.400
To Tira, particularly?

02:34:29.480 --> 02:34:33.520
I think that the one thing that
we, at Tira,

02:34:33.600 --> 02:34:36.840
in terms of our mission and vision,

02:34:36.920 --> 02:34:41.080
we've said that we want to be
affordable yet aspirational,

02:34:41.160 --> 02:34:44.000
and whether we're selling
a 200-rupee lipstick

02:34:44.080 --> 02:34:47.320
or a 2,000-rupee lipstick,
we want the consumer...

02:34:47.400 --> 02:34:50.080
consumer experience to be premium.

02:34:50.160 --> 02:34:53.640
So, whether it's the UI-UX
that's clutter-free

02:34:53.720 --> 02:34:56.880
or whether it's not really throwing
the constant

02:34:56.960 --> 02:35:00.360
discounting in your face
or leading with education,

02:35:00.440 --> 02:35:02.160
having an editorial approach.

02:35:02.240 --> 02:35:06.880
I think that has really been
a differentiator for us.

02:35:06.960 --> 02:35:10.880
I think when it comes to a brand,
particularly homegrown brands,

02:35:10.960 --> 02:35:12.200
we want to champion them.

02:35:12.280 --> 02:35:15.240
For us, it would mean
that have a good brand story,

02:35:15.320 --> 02:35:17.120
have a solid product, and...

02:35:18.480 --> 02:35:21.440
we really enjoy working with founders
as well.

02:35:21.520 --> 02:35:24.200
So, I think, for us, it would be...
for me, particularly,

02:35:24.280 --> 02:35:27.200
would be to have great product
and fit into that ecosystem.

02:35:27.280 --> 02:35:32.520
So, we're not being picky about a brand.

02:35:32.600 --> 02:35:34.640
I feel like if you're entering
into the brand,

02:35:34.720 --> 02:35:38.200
even if you're a young brand,
we would definitely want to work with you.

02:35:38.280 --> 02:35:42.200
-How do I reach out to you?
-You email us.

02:35:42.280 --> 02:35:46.080
So, the number of people who reach out
to me on LinkedIn is also insane.

02:35:46.160 --> 02:35:47.680
And even if I can't reply,

02:35:47.760 --> 02:35:50.920
I will connect you
to the merchandising team.

02:35:51.000 --> 02:35:53.160
And they, at least, have the convos.

02:35:53.240 --> 02:35:56.360
There will be times
when you've not reached a certain scale

02:35:56.440 --> 02:35:59.720
and you're just starting to distribute.

02:35:59.800 --> 02:36:03.000
Sometimes, that,
you can also get lost in the entire...

02:36:03.080 --> 02:36:05.160
the number of brands that we have.

02:36:05.240 --> 02:36:08.800
So, I think when you've got a little,
when you just started,

02:36:08.880 --> 02:36:12.240
I think it's gained
a little bit of traction,

02:36:12.320 --> 02:36:13.760
like, we've worked with very small brands.

02:36:13.840 --> 02:36:15.280
Like, we spoke about ClayCo.

02:36:15.360 --> 02:36:17.600
You know, I think it's about discovery.

02:36:17.680 --> 02:36:20.480
You want to have more brands
to lead discovery.

02:36:20.560 --> 02:36:23.240
And I feel like, as a platform with scale,

02:36:23.320 --> 02:36:27.280
it is a little bit of our duty
to kind of also set that platform.

02:36:27.360 --> 02:36:29.200
So, I think, for us, it's important.

02:36:29.280 --> 02:36:31.200
So, as long as you're a brand
with solid product...

02:36:31.280 --> 02:36:33.480
Is there a product
you're looking for right now?

02:36:33.560 --> 02:36:35.200
The odds would be higher if I build that?

02:36:36.040 --> 02:36:39.080
No, I don't think so.
See, we're a retailer.

02:36:39.160 --> 02:36:43.400
We want to be able to give
the variety to the audience.

02:36:43.480 --> 02:36:45.720
-[Diipa] That's your job.
-Yeah, that's your job.

02:36:45.800 --> 02:36:50.320
I think what our job is to make sure that
your brand is going to the right consumer.

02:36:50.400 --> 02:36:52.280
So, we spoke about hyper-personalisation.

02:36:52.360 --> 02:36:59.240
So, if I understand who my consumer is,
and if that consumer is your consumer,

02:36:59.320 --> 02:37:00.840
then I'm doing right by you.

02:37:00.920 --> 02:37:03.200
And then it makes sense for you to list
with me. And then I would want you.

02:37:03.280 --> 02:37:07.880
So, I think, for us, it is about
having a large portfolio of brands,

02:37:07.960 --> 02:37:10.120
but also then making sure
that the right brand is going

02:37:10.200 --> 02:37:12.640
to the right...
we're connecting to the right consumer.

02:37:12.720 --> 02:37:14.720
That is all about the personalisation.

02:37:14.800 --> 02:37:21.200
If I build my morning and night,
one form factor which does it all...

02:37:21.280 --> 02:37:22.720
Correct.

02:37:22.800 --> 02:37:26.760
...and I build a tech layer on top of it
which is housed in Tira, for example,

02:37:27.920 --> 02:37:29.240
and it does really well,

02:37:30.680 --> 02:37:34.720
at some point, won't Bhakti think,
"Why don't I just do this myself?"

02:37:34.800 --> 02:37:36.640
Yes.

02:37:36.720 --> 02:37:38.200
-Naturally.
-Absolutely. Naturally.

02:37:38.280 --> 02:37:42.720
But that's a disincentive for me
to then sell on Tira, right?

02:37:42.800 --> 02:37:44.560
No, I don't think so.

02:37:44.640 --> 02:37:46.800
I think, first and foremost,
we are a retailer, right?

02:37:46.880 --> 02:37:51.680
So, I think that we will always make sure
that we will always support the brand

02:37:51.760 --> 02:37:55.280
and if we are getting into something,
it's great for the consumer

02:37:55.360 --> 02:37:59.760
because you are giving the consumer choice
and they can decide what they want to.

02:37:59.840 --> 02:38:02.320
I think it's pure retail.
So, I don't think it's about...

02:38:02.400 --> 02:38:06.040
There's so many different ways now
of working with brands.

02:38:06.120 --> 02:38:08.240
There's collaborations,
there's exclusivity.

02:38:08.320 --> 02:38:11.360
So, if you tell me
that I'm going to be exclusive to you,

02:38:11.440 --> 02:38:13.400
and, you know, we get into...

02:38:13.480 --> 02:38:16.280
I make money off your brand,
then I'm like, "Great."

02:38:16.360 --> 02:38:19.560
Because it also takes
that much amount of time and effort

02:38:19.640 --> 02:38:21.040
to create another brand.

02:38:21.120 --> 02:38:23.720
So, I would also want to create a brand

02:38:23.800 --> 02:38:26.040
in a wide space that I know
is going to win quickly.

02:38:26.120 --> 02:38:27.920
You guys have done that, right?

02:38:28.000 --> 02:38:32.240
With a few of the celebrities,
and also the recent Ayurvedic one.

02:38:32.320 --> 02:38:33.760
Just launched a brand called Puraveda.

02:38:33.840 --> 02:38:35.760
Are celebrity brands working?

02:38:37.680 --> 02:38:39.760
I think that...

02:38:40.800 --> 02:38:42.440
I think they are working, yes.

02:38:42.520 --> 02:38:46.560
But I feel like not the way
they were working in the past.

02:38:46.640 --> 02:38:49.480
I think that you need to have
solid product.

02:38:49.560 --> 02:38:50.960
You need to still have...

02:38:51.040 --> 02:38:55.240
You need to have that hook
that links you to the consumer today.

02:38:55.320 --> 02:39:01.440
It's not just about slapping your photo
on a product.

02:39:01.520 --> 02:39:03.360
Those days are gone.

02:39:03.440 --> 02:39:06.240
You need to be able to connect
with the consumers.

02:39:06.320 --> 02:39:10.280
The consumer buys the product
for you and also for the quality.

02:39:10.360 --> 02:39:12.680
So, you need to have story...

02:39:12.760 --> 02:39:17.640
a very strong storyline that depicts
what you kind of stand for,

02:39:17.720 --> 02:39:20.320
and they take a little bit
of your thought, a piece of you,

02:39:20.400 --> 02:39:22.040
or something that you stand for.

02:39:22.120 --> 02:39:25.240
So, it is very important
for a celebrity to be authentic.

02:39:25.320 --> 02:39:26.400
I think... Exactly.

02:39:26.480 --> 02:39:28.920
-The entitlement that sometimes...
-Is moved away.

02:39:29.000 --> 02:39:30.480
...really famous people have.

02:39:30.560 --> 02:39:33.720
If I just promote something,
it should be fine.

02:39:33.800 --> 02:39:36.360
I think that has really, really shifted

02:39:36.440 --> 02:39:39.440
because we've all mentioned
consumers are very smart today.

02:39:39.520 --> 02:39:42.960
They want value, they want quality,
they want good ingredients

02:39:43.040 --> 02:39:45.720
and just slapping a celebrity face
doesn't cut it anymore.

02:39:45.800 --> 02:39:47.760
-There's so many--
-Which brand are you thinking of?

02:39:47.840 --> 02:39:49.760
I'm not going to mention the name.

02:39:50.680 --> 02:39:52.160
I'm not going to mention the name,

02:39:52.240 --> 02:39:54.760
but there are so many
celebrity brands in India that...

02:39:54.840 --> 02:39:56.480
I think I know which you are thinking of.

02:39:56.560 --> 02:39:59.200
-And globally.
-And globally, of course,

02:39:59.280 --> 02:40:03.680
that have started and then,
if you're just not into it enough,

02:40:03.760 --> 02:40:05.680
like, for example,
if you come on and somebody...

02:40:05.760 --> 02:40:08.640
You're doing a live or you're doing
a video and somebody is like,

02:40:08.720 --> 02:40:10.360
"What ingredients does your product have?"

02:40:10.440 --> 02:40:14.120
And you're like,
"Oh, my moisturiser moisturises."

02:40:14.200 --> 02:40:15.800
We're not dumb.

02:40:15.880 --> 02:40:18.120
We can see you don't know enough about it.

02:40:18.200 --> 02:40:21.840
And then, you ask another founder
who really is deeply involved,

02:40:21.920 --> 02:40:24.000
whether that's Rare Beauty,

02:40:24.080 --> 02:40:25.960
whether that's Fenty.

02:40:26.040 --> 02:40:28.560
You could literally wake them up
in the middle of the night

02:40:28.640 --> 02:40:31.160
and be like, 'What is the name
of your blush and shade?

02:40:31.240 --> 02:40:33.320
"What ingredient does it have?"

02:40:33.400 --> 02:40:35.920
I think they're so deeply... For me, 100%.

02:40:36.000 --> 02:40:38.560
Like, I would know, for sure,
anything you ask me,

02:40:38.640 --> 02:40:41.480
even the name of our warehouse
in the US or UK or whatever.

02:40:41.560 --> 02:40:42.760
I would know those things,

02:40:42.840 --> 02:40:46.120
because we're so deeply involved
and I think they see that.

02:40:46.200 --> 02:40:48.440
They see that involvement.

02:40:48.520 --> 02:40:50.840
They see that love and they see that care.

02:40:50.920 --> 02:40:52.880
And I think that translates to sales.

02:40:52.960 --> 02:40:55.760
And if a celebrity can do that,
it still works.

02:40:55.840 --> 02:40:58.880
If they cannot because they're really busy
being actresses

02:40:58.960 --> 02:41:02.760
or influencers or whatever else,
then I don't think it works.

02:41:02.840 --> 02:41:06.360
What are some of the examples
of celebrity brands that have worked?

02:41:06.440 --> 02:41:09.040
-And what did they get right?
-Not necessarily in beauty. Anything.

02:41:09.760 --> 02:41:10.760
India.

02:41:10.840 --> 02:41:13.040
Latest one I really like is Underneat.

02:41:13.120 --> 02:41:14.440
What is Underneat?

02:41:14.520 --> 02:41:17.120
Underneat is Kusha Kapila's
lingerie brand.

02:41:17.200 --> 02:41:20.240
SuperYou by Ranveer.
Very good start. Very good start.

02:41:20.320 --> 02:41:23.800
What celebrity should start what brand?

02:41:23.880 --> 02:41:26.280
What celebrity should start what--
Give me a name.

02:41:27.200 --> 02:41:30.080
-Shah Rukh Khan.
-[all] Fragrance.

02:41:30.160 --> 02:41:31.280
100%.

02:41:31.360 --> 02:41:32.800
Fragrance.

02:41:32.880 --> 02:41:35.280
-100%.
-We all said it.

02:41:35.360 --> 02:41:36.800
We will all invest in it.

02:41:36.880 --> 02:41:39.400
So, me, Dilip, should try and pitch him
to be the partner.

02:41:39.480 --> 02:41:42.080
Oh, for sure. Give him 30%.
That's half your job done.

02:41:42.160 --> 02:41:44.280
For sure.
And get Prashanth to invest in it.

02:41:44.360 --> 02:41:46.800
Your two crores gets to 25,
and you're home.

02:41:46.880 --> 02:41:49.120
-So, Prashanth, the friend you met.
-[Diipa] Yeah.

02:41:49.960 --> 02:41:53.800
He founded a venture capital
company called Accel.

02:41:53.880 --> 02:41:55.280
Oh.

02:41:55.360 --> 02:41:57.280
So, they have been the first cheque in...

02:41:57.360 --> 02:41:58.800
Flipkart.

02:41:58.880 --> 02:42:00.800
Flipkart, Swiggy, Ola.
All the tech companies.

02:42:00.880 --> 02:42:02.280
I think we spoke to them. Yeah.

02:42:02.360 --> 02:42:04.040
Very good. Very savvy investors.

02:42:04.120 --> 02:42:05.920
I think even they are looking
at some beauty brands.

02:42:06.000 --> 02:42:07.280
He would have had some insights.

02:42:07.360 --> 02:42:09.800
-MyGlamm.
-MyGlamm.

02:42:09.880 --> 02:42:12.280
-That's not doing too well.
-MyGlamm is...

02:42:12.360 --> 02:42:14.400
I think the Kardashians
are amazing examples

02:42:14.480 --> 02:42:16.800
of what it means to create a brand.

02:42:16.880 --> 02:42:18.000
-But also--
-[Nikhil] Everything.

02:42:18.080 --> 02:42:21.120
What I find they are also really good at
is even if something fails,

02:42:21.200 --> 02:42:23.280
they just push it under the rug
and start the next one.

02:42:23.360 --> 02:42:26.080
Yeah. They don't care about failure.

02:42:26.160 --> 02:42:28.800
They are like, "Okay, that didn't work.
Fine. Let's start the next one."

02:42:28.880 --> 02:42:30.560
SKIMS. I think Kim has...

02:42:30.640 --> 02:42:33.800
She lives, breathes,
and really, really buys into...

02:42:33.880 --> 02:42:35.280
-Who?
-SKIMS.

02:42:35.360 --> 02:42:40.800
SKIMS has again taken not just beauty,
taken a category and really--

02:42:40.880 --> 02:42:43.240
But again, I think we need
to mention the operator.

02:42:43.320 --> 02:42:44.920
Emma Grede... And like the product.

02:42:45.000 --> 02:42:47.280
Like, the product of SKIMS is phenomenal.

02:42:47.360 --> 02:42:48.800
-Is it?
-[Bhakti] Yeah.

02:42:48.880 --> 02:42:49.960
So, people come back for it.

02:42:50.040 --> 02:42:53.880
I think celebrity influencers were
a great, like, trampoline, like I said.

02:42:53.960 --> 02:42:56.280
-But the product will bring you back.
-I agree with you.

02:42:56.360 --> 02:42:57.800
The marketing, the branding, the product.

02:42:57.880 --> 02:43:00.040
-Product is still king, right?
-Yeah.

02:43:00.120 --> 02:43:02.720
If you don't have product,
you can build a brand,

02:43:02.800 --> 02:43:04.320
but you are not really going to--

02:43:04.400 --> 02:43:06.800
-You won't have any repeat.
-Yeah. Exactly.

02:43:06.880 --> 02:43:10.920
But I think, in beauty,
both Rare and Fenty are, I think,

02:43:11.000 --> 02:43:12.800
gold standards for being able to--

02:43:12.880 --> 02:43:14.280
-Rhode.
-Rhode.

02:43:14.360 --> 02:43:18.760
But I still think
when it comes to a storytelling...

02:43:18.840 --> 02:43:22.920
I think that Rare
with the mental health impact

02:43:23.000 --> 02:43:26.480
and Rihanna with inclusivity and diversity

02:43:26.560 --> 02:43:30.600
and really championing
those two causes has made it...

02:43:30.680 --> 02:43:32.240
-Absolutely.
-It's gone beyond the founder.

02:43:32.320 --> 02:43:35.280
So, now that cause and the brand
has gotten related.

02:43:35.360 --> 02:43:37.520
The singular thing
that creates a community.

02:43:37.600 --> 02:43:40.320
Yes. And they have built communities.

02:43:40.400 --> 02:43:42.120
And that's what I think has driven it.

02:43:42.200 --> 02:43:45.600
They have made themselves
relevant as people,

02:43:45.680 --> 02:43:48.320
moved away from the celebrity status

02:43:48.400 --> 02:43:51.640
and kind of championed something
that is core to all of us.

02:43:51.720 --> 02:43:53.280
And I think that is what they've sold.

02:43:53.360 --> 02:43:56.280
And I think that's what a lot of
Indian celebrities have seen,

02:43:56.360 --> 02:44:00.640
where they're like...
after their relevance as a pop star

02:44:00.720 --> 02:44:02.440
or as an actress died out,

02:44:02.520 --> 02:44:04.600
they're still staying relevant
with the business,

02:44:04.680 --> 02:44:05.680
"Let's do it, too."

02:44:05.760 --> 02:44:08.240
And I think that's the wrong intention
to start a business

02:44:08.320 --> 02:44:12.240
just for the... "Oh, I'll be in the buzz
and I'll make a quick buck."

02:44:12.320 --> 02:44:15.800
But I think if you truly start for,
like we said, with the cause, the why.

02:44:15.880 --> 02:44:18.200
What was my first question to you?
What's your why?

02:44:18.280 --> 02:44:22.040
If that's really strong, then the business
will become bigger than you.

02:44:22.120 --> 02:44:23.800
-It will sustain.
-Yeah.

02:44:23.880 --> 02:44:26.800
I think HRX did a very good job
because I think Hrithik was involved.

02:44:26.880 --> 02:44:28.600
-[Bhakti] Yeah, HRX.
-I think the product was good,

02:44:28.680 --> 02:44:30.880
and I think the distribution with Myntra
was outstanding.

02:44:30.960 --> 02:44:32.280
They did such a good job with that brand.

02:44:32.360 --> 02:44:33.800
-HRX is a good celebrity brand.
-Yeah.

02:44:33.880 --> 02:44:35.280
Yeah.

02:44:35.360 --> 02:44:37.800
So, I have to figure out the product first
and then find the celebrity.

02:44:37.880 --> 02:44:39.840
And then the distribution.

02:44:39.920 --> 02:44:41.440
Coming to you with the brand.

02:44:43.240 --> 02:44:44.680
It's going to be Nikhil123.

02:44:46.400 --> 02:44:48.120
-Dilip123.
-[Diipa] Yeah.

02:44:51.400 --> 02:44:52.840
What was your why?

02:44:52.920 --> 02:44:54.680
You just spoke about "why".

02:44:55.720 --> 02:45:00.360
My why was truly to create
India's first global beauty brand

02:45:00.440 --> 02:45:05.200
and to be on the shelves of Sephora
that I never saw growing up.

02:45:05.280 --> 02:45:08.680
It was all French brands,
it was all American brands,

02:45:08.760 --> 02:45:10.880
and I didn't feel seen in that.

02:45:10.960 --> 02:45:14.320
And I think creating a brand
with so much pride

02:45:14.400 --> 02:45:15.680
from where we come from

02:45:15.760 --> 02:45:19.560
and being able to stand on those
global shelves is uncharted territory,

02:45:19.640 --> 02:45:22.480
and, honestly,
freaks the shit out of me to do it.

02:45:22.560 --> 02:45:25.640
It really does,
to really take on the US market

02:45:25.720 --> 02:45:28.160
which is a beast of a beauty market,

02:45:28.240 --> 02:45:31.920
with sitting next to brands
like all these ones that we mentioned

02:45:33.480 --> 02:45:35.000
But that is the why.

02:45:35.080 --> 02:45:37.480
It's like we need to build something
from our country

02:45:37.560 --> 02:45:40.120
that can do that and truly be global.

02:45:40.200 --> 02:45:45.040
And have that... like,
have us Indians be proud of our skin,

02:45:45.120 --> 02:45:49.160
our skin type, our ingredients,
and everything that we come from.

02:45:50.360 --> 02:45:53.440
If I were to ask you "Why?"
enough number of times,

02:45:53.520 --> 02:45:57.840
and you don't have a filter on,
you'll go back to first principles?

02:45:57.920 --> 02:45:58.920
Identity?

02:46:02.240 --> 02:46:04.680
My own identity?

02:46:05.760 --> 02:46:07.480
Perhaps.

02:46:07.560 --> 02:46:09.000
Yeah.

02:46:09.080 --> 02:46:13.160
But, in that, mirrored the identity
of the community that I built, I think.

02:46:14.760 --> 02:46:17.040
Ultimately, yes,
I'm really proud of it too,

02:46:17.120 --> 02:46:19.840
and I think there's definitely
an identity piece there,

02:46:19.920 --> 02:46:22.600
but I think it just makes...

02:46:22.680 --> 02:46:25.920
It's a national pride, in a way, as well.

02:46:26.840 --> 02:46:31.360
And I think the community of the women
that I've built so far together,

02:46:31.440 --> 02:46:35.160
I think we've all had these very clear
friction points where...

02:46:35.240 --> 02:46:38.560
I think I told Bhakti when I was first
pitching indē wild to her as well.

02:46:38.640 --> 02:46:42.320
It's like there's this-- On the one hand,
we love where we come from.

02:46:42.400 --> 02:46:45.000
We love being Indian.
We love our food, the culture,

02:46:45.080 --> 02:46:46.920
all the lists that we made. We love it.

02:46:47.000 --> 02:46:50.040
But, at the same time,
we're not our mums and grandmothers.

02:46:50.120 --> 02:46:55.120
We're modern Indian women
who want to talk about sex if we do,

02:46:55.200 --> 02:46:58.080
we want to, like, stay with somebody
before we marry them.

02:46:58.160 --> 02:47:00.200
We believe in science and fact,

02:47:00.280 --> 02:47:04.080
and there's almost this dichotomy
and a friction between us.

02:47:04.160 --> 02:47:07.240
And there was no brand
that brought them together.

02:47:07.320 --> 02:47:11.200
So, indē wild is an identity
of that friction point in a bottle.

02:47:11.280 --> 02:47:14.280
It is Ayurveda and everything
Mum and Grandmum said.

02:47:14.360 --> 02:47:16.120
"Use ghee. Use turmeric."

02:47:16.200 --> 02:47:20.040
But it's cutting-edge, clinical,
vitamin C, niacinamide,

02:47:20.120 --> 02:47:21.400
put together in a bottle.

02:47:21.480 --> 02:47:23.840
So, that's me, Diipa. I see that.

02:47:23.920 --> 02:47:27.160
That is my... that's me.
So, I can identify with it.

02:47:27.240 --> 02:47:28.680
The name is brilliant, by the way.

02:47:28.760 --> 02:47:30.680
indē wild? Yeah. Thank you.

02:47:30.760 --> 02:47:33.400
I suspect you will do...
you're already doing well,

02:47:33.480 --> 02:47:36.160
but after this,
I think you'll do exponentially well.

02:47:36.240 --> 02:47:37.680
That's very kind.

02:47:37.760 --> 02:47:42.680
You come across as a great spokesperson
for an Indian woman.

02:47:42.760 --> 02:47:44.160
Thank you. Thank you.

02:47:44.240 --> 02:47:46.680
And you own so many things,
which is also nice.

02:47:47.760 --> 02:47:49.160
White man, okay.

02:47:50.240 --> 02:47:52.680
Once you meet him, you will love him.

02:47:52.760 --> 02:47:54.160
He's more Indian than Diipa.

02:47:54.240 --> 02:47:55.680
-Thank you.
-[Nikhil] Really?

02:47:55.760 --> 02:47:59.680
I was just going to say that.
He's literally... he's Indian inside.

02:47:59.760 --> 02:48:02.600
Like he, his entire life,
even though he's as white,

02:48:02.680 --> 02:48:04.320
blonde, blue-eyed as they get,

02:48:04.400 --> 02:48:09.040
like, literally Scandi vibes,
he has always been eastward-looking.

02:48:09.120 --> 02:48:13.160
I think he was in his past life,
in his last life, I think he was Indian.

02:48:13.240 --> 02:48:16.640
He literally just...
I'll get you to meet him.

02:48:16.720 --> 02:48:18.680
You'll see what I mean. You'll love him.

02:48:18.760 --> 02:48:20.680
I should have met him
day before yesterday, right?

02:48:20.760 --> 02:48:22.080
-Yeah.
-I missed it.

02:48:26.240 --> 02:48:29.600
When we spoke about
categories first, we said...

02:48:29.680 --> 02:48:32.920
"What is mass? What is premium?
And what is prestige?"

02:48:34.480 --> 02:48:38.600
Is there a case to be made
for premiumisation happening fast?

02:48:38.680 --> 02:48:40.560
Which category is growing faster?

02:48:41.960 --> 02:48:44.360
Is there a case? 100%.

02:48:44.440 --> 02:48:47.880
Are you saying the 2,300 prestige category
is growing fastest?

02:48:47.960 --> 02:48:49.360
-Yes.
-It is growing.

02:48:49.440 --> 02:48:51.880
-Yeah?
-Premium to prestige is growing.

02:48:51.960 --> 02:48:53.360
Premium to prestige is growing.

02:48:53.440 --> 02:48:54.920
-The fastest.
-Mass is plateauing.

02:48:55.000 --> 02:48:56.160
Yeah.

02:48:56.240 --> 02:48:58.960
And even mass brands
are looking to premiumise.

02:48:59.040 --> 02:49:01.480
So, I think it's about premiumisation
at every level.

02:49:01.560 --> 02:49:04.760
While prestige is growing
because it's such a small market,

02:49:06.080 --> 02:49:08.880
at every level, we are premiumising.

02:49:08.960 --> 02:49:13.320
Mainly because multiple--
India has a lot...

02:49:13.400 --> 02:49:18.200
Indian-- The target audience
has a lot more disposable income,

02:49:18.280 --> 02:49:21.720
and there's the expansion
into Tier 2, Tier 3 cities

02:49:21.800 --> 02:49:23.800
and breakout of online, right?

02:49:23.880 --> 02:49:27.440
So, there is reachability
and awareness and access.

02:49:27.520 --> 02:49:30.400
So, people want better, they want quality.

02:49:30.480 --> 02:49:32.440
So, at every level, you premiumise.

02:49:32.520 --> 02:49:34.480
So, people want that aspiration
to move up.

02:49:34.560 --> 02:49:36.400
It's not just there, it's at every level.

02:49:36.480 --> 02:49:38.760
So, I think it's premiumisation
across the board

02:49:38.840 --> 02:49:40.880
versus just in that segment,

02:49:40.960 --> 02:49:42.840
-if I have to put it.
-Yeah, agreed.

02:49:44.080 --> 02:49:47.320
I think wealth equals,
"I want better quality,

02:49:47.400 --> 02:49:49.880
I want better things..."

02:49:49.960 --> 02:49:51.200
Are you seeing that in society?

02:49:51.280 --> 02:49:55.240
That discretionary spending power
is going up at such a pace?

02:49:56.560 --> 02:49:57.880
Why are you building in mass, then?

02:49:57.960 --> 02:49:59.600
So, the two are very different questions.

02:49:59.680 --> 02:50:02.520
I think the first question is around
discretionary spending power going up.

02:50:02.600 --> 02:50:05.960
I think it's concentrated in the top 1-5%.

02:50:08.480 --> 02:50:11.360
Beyond the next five--
From 5-100% per cent,

02:50:11.440 --> 02:50:13.760
it's going up because people
are not buying homes enough.

02:50:14.680 --> 02:50:16.160
So, you now have a lot more money
in your hand

02:50:16.240 --> 02:50:17.360
because you don't have a loan to pay off.

02:50:18.440 --> 02:50:21.280
That's global also, India also.

02:50:21.360 --> 02:50:22.840
So, that's why people
are able to spend more

02:50:22.920 --> 02:50:24.200
because they're saving less.

02:50:24.280 --> 02:50:26.920
The savings rate has come down
by, like, thousand bips.

02:50:27.920 --> 02:50:29.360
-From 14%.
-In the last five years.

02:50:29.440 --> 02:50:31.360
For the Gen Z,
is all about experiences, right?

02:50:32.200 --> 02:50:35.240
So, now, your experience,
like, those experience,

02:50:35.320 --> 02:50:36.880
hence, you know, coffee shops and...

02:50:36.960 --> 02:50:38.680
-We rent and...
-Yeah.

02:50:38.760 --> 02:50:41.480
This concept of small luxuries,
I don't know,

02:50:41.560 --> 02:50:45.240
like, the Labubu
is just an example of that, right?

02:50:45.320 --> 02:50:48.280
That you're getting
a piece of a small luxury,

02:50:48.360 --> 02:50:51.440
like, you may not be able to buy
a handbag of that brand,

02:50:51.520 --> 02:50:53.360
but you can buy a small beauty product.

02:50:53.440 --> 02:50:55.360
-And beauty is the biggest one of that.
-Exactly.

02:50:55.440 --> 02:50:56.880
Yeah.

02:50:56.960 --> 02:50:59.240
So, it's about getting a little piece
of that next thing.

02:50:59.320 --> 02:51:01.240
You may not be able to take a big holiday,

02:51:01.320 --> 02:51:04.680
but you can get that fragrance
that reminds you of it.

02:51:04.760 --> 02:51:09.320
So, I think that small little luxuries
is another trend that's going...

02:51:09.400 --> 02:51:11.640
that's kind of feeding
into this premiumisation.

02:51:11.720 --> 02:51:15.120
And I think women entering the workforce,
like a generation before,

02:51:15.200 --> 02:51:16.640
women did not enter,

02:51:16.720 --> 02:51:18.880
it was looked down upon in a family
if a woman would work,

02:51:18.960 --> 02:51:22.920
and I think women entering the workforce,
young women entering the workforce,

02:51:23.000 --> 02:51:25.800
having that disposable income,
but still live with their parents.

02:51:25.880 --> 02:51:28.400
So, their entire salary is,
"Let's go shopping."

02:51:29.480 --> 02:51:32.320
So, I think a lot of these changes
in society are,

02:51:32.400 --> 02:51:34.400
especially for the beauty industry,

02:51:34.480 --> 02:51:38.560
really, really strong kind of trends
to help grow that.

02:51:38.640 --> 02:51:41.200
And then they have social media,
let's not forget,

02:51:41.280 --> 02:51:43.040
where they look at global brands.

02:51:43.120 --> 02:51:47.120
They look at global trends, they're like,
"I want that niacinamide as well."

02:51:47.200 --> 02:51:50.360
Or, "I want that face mask as well."

02:51:50.440 --> 02:51:51.680
And then, there's a demand.

02:51:51.760 --> 02:51:52.920
-We have 500 million...
-Yeah.

02:51:53.000 --> 02:51:54.840
...social media users in India.

02:51:57.120 --> 02:52:01.160
If I were to, like,
project an average Indian girl

02:52:01.240 --> 02:52:07.880
who is 25 years old and is making, say,
$10,000 a year in income...

02:52:08.920 --> 02:52:12.920
how has the beauty category of my spend,

02:52:13.000 --> 02:52:16.480
discretionary spend,
changed in the last five years?

02:52:17.440 --> 02:52:19.360
In the last five years?

02:52:19.440 --> 02:52:20.880
Has it, like, doubled?

02:52:20.960 --> 02:52:26.000
Do I spend today 20% of my income,
and five years ago, it was 10%, or 30%?

02:52:26.920 --> 02:52:28.360
I don't know, actually.

02:52:29.440 --> 02:52:32.440
-Beauty, I wouldn't know.
-I think it's more about awareness.

02:52:34.200 --> 02:52:39.240
An average Indian probably spends
about $10 on beauty

02:52:39.320 --> 02:52:42.760
versus now,
with platforms and brands coming in,

02:52:42.840 --> 02:52:48.320
that has gone anywhere up to...
$80 in our offline stores.

02:52:48.400 --> 02:52:52.360
And even though we're looking at
premium to prestige,

02:52:52.960 --> 02:52:57.240
online, it's still, if you say,
a consumer's purchasing twice a year,

02:52:57.320 --> 02:53:02.800
still about 3,600 to 4,000 rupees
in the year that they're spending,

02:53:02.880 --> 02:53:06.440
even if it's just someone
who's freshly out of college,

02:53:06.520 --> 02:53:08.840
they will wait to buy
that one Dior lipstick

02:53:08.920 --> 02:53:11.760
or they will build their entire
skincare routine in that 4,000 rupees.

02:53:11.840 --> 02:53:14.280
But the good thing is,
there is availability to do that now.

02:53:14.360 --> 02:53:15.800
Earlier, there wasn't.

02:53:15.880 --> 02:53:19.000
So, it's also about moving
that wallet share there.

02:53:19.080 --> 02:53:20.480
So, I think that has happened.

02:53:20.560 --> 02:53:23.800
And as I said, at every level,
there's been premiumisation.

02:53:23.880 --> 02:53:27.240
So, it's not so much about doubling it,
but it's about getting--

02:53:27.320 --> 02:53:30.360
spending a little bit more
because of availability as well.

02:53:30.440 --> 02:53:33.280
Like, from my perspective,
I only know indē wild data.

02:53:33.360 --> 02:53:36.480
But if you look at our AOV year on year,
it's been increasing.

02:53:36.560 --> 02:53:38.680
Year on year, in the last three years,

02:53:38.760 --> 02:53:42.200
our AOV in Indie has just gone bigger
and bigger, the basket size.

02:53:42.280 --> 02:53:43.960
So, people are able to spend more.

02:53:44.040 --> 02:53:46.840
And even back to,
sorry to sound like a broken record,

02:53:46.920 --> 02:53:48.800
but the Champi example...

02:53:48.880 --> 02:53:51.800
Nobody would have given me
five cents for the idea,

02:53:51.880 --> 02:53:55.000
"Let's launch a hair oil
in the country of hair oils,

02:53:55.920 --> 02:53:59.280
price it 950 rupees for 50ml,"

02:53:59.360 --> 02:54:01.800
and that you're going to do well.

02:54:01.880 --> 02:54:03.240
Imagine.

02:54:03.320 --> 02:54:04.960
Five years ago,

02:54:05.040 --> 02:54:08.000
when, in the country of every hair oil
you can possibly imagine,

02:54:08.080 --> 02:54:11.240
you're going to price it at 950
and sell it at 50ml.

02:54:11.320 --> 02:54:12.920
And they were like,
"It's not going to work."

02:54:13.000 --> 02:54:14.360
Like, "Who are you to sell a hair oil?"

02:54:14.440 --> 02:54:16.720
People accept it. They want that.

02:54:16.800 --> 02:54:21.200
They want it because they know it works.
They believe in the quality.

02:54:21.280 --> 02:54:23.320
They like the packaging.
They like the story.

02:54:23.400 --> 02:54:25.360
They just... They have the money.

02:54:25.440 --> 02:54:27.360
-Can I ask a question?
-...market is still mass.

02:54:27.440 --> 02:54:29.720
-So, what he's saying.
-How big?

02:54:29.800 --> 02:54:32.520
-How big is...
-Okay, so the biggest pie is still mass.

02:54:32.600 --> 02:54:35.880
But the fastest-growing
is the category you're saying.

02:54:35.960 --> 02:54:37.360
But the baseline is very low.

02:54:37.440 --> 02:54:39.880
Yeah, but also, you guys have
a lot more competition as well.

02:54:39.960 --> 02:54:41.840
And mass, there's so many...

02:54:41.920 --> 02:54:44.880
It's a crowded market as well.

02:54:44.960 --> 02:54:47.360
Depends. So, soap, yes.
Shaving, not at all.

02:54:47.440 --> 02:54:48.880
Shaving, okay.

02:54:48.960 --> 02:54:50.360
I'll give you an example in my world.

02:54:50.440 --> 02:54:52.560
There are 30 crore shavers in the country.

02:54:52.640 --> 02:54:55.240
Thirty crore.
300 million people who shave.

02:54:55.320 --> 02:54:57.640
Fifteen crore of them
use one-rupee blades.

02:54:57.720 --> 02:54:59.920
Fifteen crore.
Half the market uses one-rupee blades.

02:55:01.960 --> 02:55:05.400
Seven to eight crore people
go to barber shops.

02:55:06.400 --> 02:55:09.200
Five crore people use disposable blades.

02:55:09.280 --> 02:55:12.240
One crore people use premium blades.

02:55:12.320 --> 02:55:14.320
Out of 30 crore. 3%.

02:55:14.400 --> 02:55:16.600
All of us will assume MACH3
is like the biggest.

02:55:16.680 --> 02:55:18.480
It's a crown jewel brand, globally.

02:55:18.560 --> 02:55:20.160
And Gillette is the best.

02:55:20.240 --> 02:55:22.720
I respect that company like crazy.

02:55:22.800 --> 02:55:26.320
Their inability to take someone
buying a one-rupee blade

02:55:26.400 --> 02:55:27.440
or a 20-rupee disposable,

02:55:27.520 --> 02:55:31.400
to a 200-rupee MACH3 is...
They just can't do it.

02:55:31.480 --> 02:55:32.760
We are not premiumised.

02:55:32.840 --> 02:55:35.600
Look at Colgate.
It's a 6,000-crore company.

02:55:35.680 --> 02:55:36.720
50% market share.

02:55:36.800 --> 02:55:39.520
The most successful
penetration brand possible.

02:55:39.600 --> 02:55:42.800
70% of the business comes
from 10 to 12-rupee toothpaste.

02:55:42.880 --> 02:55:45.360
And they have
outstanding premium products.

02:55:45.440 --> 02:55:47.360
So you will have a Perfora here.
Sensodyne is a good example.

02:55:47.440 --> 02:55:49.880
But the thing, Shantanu,
is also that, right?

02:55:49.960 --> 02:55:51.880
It's not just... It's not that--

02:55:51.960 --> 02:55:54.040
As we said, that sector is small.

02:55:54.120 --> 02:55:56.640
But it's premiumisation at every level.

02:55:56.720 --> 02:55:58.840
So, now that 10-12 rupees
will be 15-16 rupees.

02:55:58.920 --> 02:56:00.200
Where is that happening?

02:56:00.280 --> 02:56:02.960
-I'm saying that is the trend, right?
-It's very difficult.

02:56:03.040 --> 02:56:06.480
Wouldn't that happen in general
because of inflation and the price?

02:56:06.560 --> 02:56:07.880
Net of inflation.

02:56:07.960 --> 02:56:09.080
-So, net of inflation.
-Okay.

02:56:09.160 --> 02:56:10.400
Large markets.

02:56:10.480 --> 02:56:15.280
So, every CEO here,
Priya or Prabha or, you know, Gaurav...

02:56:15.360 --> 02:56:17.280
Everyone says we need to premiumise.

02:56:17.360 --> 02:56:19.880
Whether it's a Dettol or a Durex,
everyone wants to do it.

02:56:19.960 --> 02:56:20.960
Yeah.

02:56:21.040 --> 02:56:24.120
I feel like it's happening in pockets.
It's not happening in a linear way.

02:56:24.200 --> 02:56:26.200
Yeah, it's not happening homogeneously,
it will take time.

02:56:26.280 --> 02:56:28.480
Your core will still remain mass,

02:56:28.560 --> 02:56:32.760
but you will have a valorised product
for that mass brand for the consumer,

02:56:32.840 --> 02:56:35.200
so, you don't also lose
the consumer, right?

02:56:35.280 --> 02:56:36.840
That's the thing,
their tastes are changing.

02:56:36.920 --> 02:56:39.320
So, I want to keep that
consumer in my brand.

02:56:39.400 --> 02:56:42.520
So I'll be like, "Okay, I also have to
have something that I can upsell.

02:56:42.600 --> 02:56:45.360
Otherwise, it'll move to another brand.
And I've lost my consumer."

02:56:45.440 --> 02:56:48.480
-In beauty, at the mass level...
-100%.

02:56:48.560 --> 02:56:51.120
...which are the brands that have scaled
above a thousand crores?

02:56:51.200 --> 02:56:53.880
-Lakmē is...
-[Diipa] Mama.

02:56:53.960 --> 02:56:56.200
Mamaearth... Would you put it in beauty
or would you put it in skincare?

02:56:56.280 --> 02:56:57.440
-Beauty, no?
-Yeah.

02:56:57.520 --> 02:56:59.640
Mamaearth? Mamaearth is as...

02:56:59.720 --> 02:57:01.600
What do you mean beauty, skincare?

02:57:01.680 --> 02:57:03.880
-Beauty is the higher one.
-Minimalist.

02:57:03.960 --> 02:57:05.640
-The colour cosmetics or whatever.
-Okay.

02:57:05.720 --> 02:57:07.360
-We need to teach these men.
-Lakmē.

02:57:07.440 --> 02:57:09.360
Lakmē is the biggest example
of valorisation.

02:57:09.440 --> 02:57:11.720
You're talking about mass.
You're asking for premium brand, right?

02:57:11.800 --> 02:57:13.560
-Which premium brand is it?
-I'm just saying, yeah,

02:57:13.640 --> 02:57:16.880
premium brands that have scaled
to a large, like, 500 crores.

02:57:16.960 --> 02:57:18.080
I think it's starting.

02:57:18.160 --> 02:57:20.760
I don't think a premium
has hit thousand yet.

02:57:20.840 --> 02:57:22.880
But I think in the years to come, it will.

02:57:22.960 --> 02:57:27.280
MAC has taken time, but it's the number
three colour cosmetic brand on the...

02:57:27.360 --> 02:57:31.360
-you know, when you look at...
-Do you think they do thousand a year?

02:57:31.440 --> 02:57:33.360
Is that premium or prestige?

02:57:33.440 --> 02:57:35.360
-That's premium.
-Premium, for sure.

02:57:35.440 --> 02:57:37.840
-Like, I see, for example--
-So, how big is that market, Shantanu?

02:57:37.920 --> 02:57:40.360
How big is the prestige market?
How big is the premium market?

02:57:40.440 --> 02:57:42.760
I think it's really small.
I feel it's still very small.

02:57:42.840 --> 02:57:46.360
The prestige market is 0.8 billion USD.

02:57:46.440 --> 02:57:47.880
In what? In what category?

02:57:47.960 --> 02:57:49.080
-In beauty.
-In beauty.

02:57:49.160 --> 02:57:50.360
Yeah.

02:57:50.440 --> 02:57:53.080
And I think it's growing faster
than we expect.

02:57:53.160 --> 02:57:54.560
-We have 10%...
-Only the beauty market.

02:57:54.640 --> 02:57:56.080
-I have a feeling it taps out.
-That's my issue.

02:57:56.160 --> 02:57:57.400
So, it'll still be significantly small.

02:57:57.480 --> 02:57:59.560
All of us have this feeling because
we live in that... We live in this world.

02:57:59.640 --> 02:58:00.960
But, you know, I think with India,

02:58:01.040 --> 02:58:02.880
what we need to always
look at is India's...

02:58:02.960 --> 02:58:05.400
like, consumers and as a country,

02:58:05.480 --> 02:58:08.040
I feel like it lives in many different
centuries at the same time.

02:58:08.120 --> 02:58:10.680
Like, yes,
the premium market is not as big,

02:58:10.760 --> 02:58:12.760
but I just think the middle class

02:58:12.840 --> 02:58:17.000
and the luxury consumer
is growing at a very fast rate.

02:58:17.080 --> 02:58:19.760
It's not as big as mass, I agree.

02:58:20.480 --> 02:58:23.440
The pie there is way bigger,
but I see it from my own brand.

02:58:23.520 --> 02:58:25.560
If I look at my pricing,

02:58:25.640 --> 02:58:28.960
couple of years ago,
people would just find that very expensive

02:58:29.040 --> 02:58:31.560
for an Indian brand, and it's working.

02:58:31.640 --> 02:58:35.400
So, for example, to aid your argument,
I would say, "Okay, fine."

02:58:35.480 --> 02:58:38.120
Mercedes, for example,
is a 25,000 crore company in India.

02:58:38.200 --> 02:58:41.560
It's four times the size of Colgate.
But they just have to sell 25,000 cars.

02:58:41.640 --> 02:58:44.320
-Yeah, that's true.
-It's 25,000 cars, 25,000 crores.

02:58:44.400 --> 02:58:45.880
If you have to sell a small volume,

02:58:45.960 --> 02:58:48.560
you can have a large
premium luxury business.

02:58:48.640 --> 02:58:51.080
But in beauty,
I think it's a volume game also.

02:58:51.160 --> 02:58:53.040
-I really, really believe...
-It's a volume game.

02:58:53.120 --> 02:58:56.920
I believe in the consumer.
I think the consumer wants quality.

02:58:57.000 --> 02:58:58.840
I think the consumer
wants good ingredients,

02:58:58.920 --> 02:59:00.720
and when you truly can give it--

02:59:00.800 --> 02:59:04.080
indē wild wouldn't exist otherwise.
They really do.

02:59:04.160 --> 02:59:06.560
Do you think to get to a thousand crores,
you don't have to compromise on price?

02:59:06.640 --> 02:59:09.720
-You can do it at a 950-rupee hair oil?
-Yeah.

02:59:09.800 --> 02:59:11.240
You'll get to a thousand crores?

02:59:11.320 --> 02:59:13.960
Yeah. I mean,
we also have the US, luckily.

02:59:14.040 --> 02:59:16.200
-No, no, in India.
-In India, purely?

02:59:16.280 --> 02:59:17.680
Eventually.

02:59:17.760 --> 02:59:21.080
I don't think in the next three years,
but I think, eventually, yes.

02:59:22.640 --> 02:59:26.000
It's also about how much...
if you can build a thousand-crore brand

02:59:26.080 --> 02:59:28.280
if you're putting in, like,
crazy amounts of money,

02:59:28.360 --> 02:59:31.320
-but to do it purely on organic...
-Sustainable.

02:59:32.080 --> 02:59:37.840
Building it with an organic mindset
and doing it sustainably will take time.

02:59:37.920 --> 02:59:41.080
It's not easy to build a thousand crore.

02:59:41.160 --> 02:59:44.440
Which is a high volume prestige game
that has happened in India?

02:59:44.520 --> 02:59:46.560
-The last five years...
-I think Minimalist came close.

02:59:46.640 --> 02:59:49.280
I mean, look at Forest Essentials
and Kama Ayurveda.

02:59:49.360 --> 02:59:50.560
How big is Forest Essentials?

02:59:50.640 --> 02:59:53.560
It's not about big. It's about them
being able to capture market share

02:59:53.640 --> 02:59:56.560
-in their market.
-Then you're saying market is small.

02:59:56.640 --> 02:59:59.080
Yeah. Of course the market is small.

02:59:59.160 --> 03:00:01.080
-How big are Kama and Forest?
-Today, it's 4%.

03:00:01.160 --> 03:00:02.680
It must be around 400-500 crores.

03:00:02.760 --> 03:00:05.080
Sub-500 crores. Plum is--

03:00:05.160 --> 03:00:08.840
Today, prestige is only 4%
of the beauty market.

03:00:08.920 --> 03:00:12.080
As I was telling him, it'll be 10%
in the next three to four years.

03:00:12.160 --> 03:00:13.240
We all feel like...

03:00:13.320 --> 03:00:16.280
Even I made that huge mistake
of launching very premium,

03:00:16.360 --> 03:00:19.560
and then realising that
it will remain a niche business.

03:00:19.640 --> 03:00:22.840
But, no, I don't agree
with your definition of premium.

03:00:22.920 --> 03:00:24.360
Premium is not one thing, right?

03:00:24.440 --> 03:00:27.320
What is premium to me
may not be premium to him.

03:00:27.400 --> 03:00:30.120
Yes, there's a definition of premium
on classification.

03:00:30.200 --> 03:00:33.120
By category, you can make out.
A vehicle, for example, is 40 lakhs.

03:00:33.200 --> 03:00:36.480
You're still premiumising in mass.
You're still staying in mass.

03:00:36.560 --> 03:00:38.880
So, that is what I'm talking about,
is the trend.

03:00:38.960 --> 03:00:40.200
Yes, that I agree.

03:00:40.280 --> 03:00:42.280
That's exactly what I'm saying.
That your 10-12 rupee Colgate,

03:00:42.360 --> 03:00:46.520
you will maybe create a product
that is ten rupees more expensive.

03:00:46.600 --> 03:00:48.440
-You're not going far.
-But that didn't happen.

03:00:48.520 --> 03:00:50.600
Look at biscuits. Look at chips.

03:00:50.680 --> 03:00:52.600
Grammage has reduced, price is ten bucks.

03:00:52.680 --> 03:00:54.760
I'm not saying it's happened.
It is happening. That's where--

03:00:54.840 --> 03:00:56.600
Everyone is saying that as well, right?

03:00:57.320 --> 03:00:59.400
Everyone is saying
that I have a huge question mark on it

03:00:59.480 --> 03:01:00.640
because of inequity.

03:01:00.720 --> 03:01:03.720
I just feel all the money gets
concentrated in a small number of people.

03:01:03.800 --> 03:01:04.800
Fair.

03:01:04.880 --> 03:01:06.840
And then we fool ourselves into believing
this is a consumption story.

03:01:06.920 --> 03:01:08.600
We're seeing it getting stagnant
for the last three years now.

03:01:08.680 --> 03:01:11.320
But there is that new, like,
women entering the workforce.

03:01:11.400 --> 03:01:13.160
That is a new variable.

03:01:13.240 --> 03:01:14.600
And young women having
that disposable income--

03:01:14.680 --> 03:01:17.800
We have the highest unemployment
rate of women in the world.

03:01:17.880 --> 03:01:20.120
Our employment rate in women
is reducing, not increasing.

03:01:20.800 --> 03:01:24.720
I think you're always looking at it
from the lens of, like, Tier 2, Tier 3,

03:01:24.800 --> 03:01:27.920
and I think we're always looking at it
from the lens of Tier 1.

03:01:28.000 --> 03:01:29.600
-I agree.
-Metro, I think that's the big difference.

03:01:29.680 --> 03:01:33.400
But even in metro, in metro,
how much of Bombay do you think is Tier 1?

03:01:33.480 --> 03:01:34.480
In terms of income?

03:01:37.200 --> 03:01:41.120
-Under five-- 100%...
-I 100% agree with you.

03:01:41.200 --> 03:01:43.520
So, for that small number of that--
For that one-crore people,

03:01:43.600 --> 03:01:45.600
-you can do a million things.
-Yeah, absolutely.

03:01:45.680 --> 03:01:49.200
And we're not... I don't think any of us
are creating for that one crore.

03:01:49.280 --> 03:01:51.760
They will-- They have the ability to buy
whatever they want,

03:01:51.840 --> 03:01:53.120
travel wherever they want.

03:01:53.200 --> 03:01:54.600
-That's the ultra luxury.
-Yeah.

03:01:54.680 --> 03:01:58.040
We are creating
for a large, large audience.

03:01:58.120 --> 03:02:01.560
And I think that you are creating
for the largest audience.

03:02:01.640 --> 03:02:04.320
And I think, at Reliance,
we do also everything at scale.

03:02:04.400 --> 03:02:06.120
You have to do it
for the majority of India.

03:02:06.200 --> 03:02:07.840
I just feel like if you want
to build a large business...

03:02:07.920 --> 03:02:10.800
You have to do it.
It's the belly of the market. 100%.

03:02:10.880 --> 03:02:12.160
Your price will have to start eroding.

03:02:12.240 --> 03:02:14.120
And what according to you
is the definition of a large business?

03:02:14.200 --> 03:02:17.640
So, let's talk oils. Let's say Parachute
is, what, 5,000-4,000 crores?

03:02:17.720 --> 03:02:20.120
-The largest oil business?
-Yeah.

03:02:20.200 --> 03:02:21.600
In terms of beauty oils?

03:02:21.680 --> 03:02:24.280
-But what would...
-If you want to get to 25% of Parachute...

03:02:24.360 --> 03:02:30.600
Your average order value will have
to come from 950 to 400, in my view.

03:02:30.680 --> 03:02:32.800
But what would make it
a successful business?

03:02:32.880 --> 03:02:36.040
If I hit 1,000 crore,
you'd be like, "That's successful."

03:02:36.120 --> 03:02:37.840
No, no. That's totally up to you.

03:02:37.920 --> 03:02:40.240
You can totally say that,
"Boss, I want to build a..."

03:02:40.320 --> 03:02:42.760
Like, Forest Essentials promoter will say
that they're the most successful business,

03:02:42.840 --> 03:02:44.120
because they built a great brand.

03:02:44.200 --> 03:02:46.640
And it is the scale at which it is.

03:02:46.720 --> 03:02:48.920
But I think like, for example,

03:02:49.000 --> 03:02:51.280
if you want people
to become entrepreneurs,

03:02:51.360 --> 03:02:54.360
you have to aim for the stars,
and then be okay to fall on the moon.

03:02:54.440 --> 03:02:57.240
So, large markets
with large outcome possibilities

03:02:57.320 --> 03:02:59.920
should be a starting point fairly,
in my view.

03:03:00.000 --> 03:03:05.400
I feel that the illusion of scale
in large price points,

03:03:05.480 --> 03:03:07.600
because it is aspirational, is very high.

03:03:07.680 --> 03:03:12.040
Do you think, ironically enough,
you need a larger capital pie

03:03:12.120 --> 03:03:15.120
to go after the mass market
and a smaller one for the premium market?

03:03:15.200 --> 03:03:17.480
It is very expensive
to go after the mass market.

03:03:17.560 --> 03:03:21.200
It is very expensive because it's...
we have five million retailers.

03:03:21.280 --> 03:03:23.680
And it is capex-heavy
to go after five million retailers.

03:03:23.760 --> 03:03:25.600
And you would rather go
top-down than bottom-up?

03:03:25.680 --> 03:03:27.560
I think with quick commerce,
it has changed a little.

03:03:27.640 --> 03:03:29.040
So, earlier, you could build a...

03:03:29.120 --> 03:03:31.480
At 100 crores, you would say,
"Okay, at 100 crores, now, a beauty,

03:03:31.560 --> 03:03:35.400
or an apparel or a food-- F&amp;B brand
has to go into stores."

03:03:35.480 --> 03:03:36.720
Today, that number is now 500.

03:03:36.800 --> 03:03:40.320
You can build a good 500-crore business,
80% online,

03:03:40.400 --> 03:03:43.400
and some amount in modern trade,
and still do well.

03:03:43.480 --> 03:03:44.600
We are 500 crores.

03:03:44.680 --> 03:03:47.200
Do you think the pathway
would be to build a premium brand

03:03:47.280 --> 03:03:48.600
and then trickle down or...

03:03:48.680 --> 03:03:51.240
Yes. To an extent, yes.
Because you set aspiration

03:03:51.320 --> 03:03:54.320
and then you can kind of sub-brand it out
or make more product.

03:03:54.400 --> 03:03:57.480
That's how I feel, like,
Mamaearth has done a good job with that.

03:03:57.560 --> 03:03:58.800
But I just feel you have to do it

03:03:58.880 --> 03:04:01.080
or you acquire a brand
or you become more...

03:04:01.160 --> 03:04:03.120
Or you start a sub-brand
which is accessible.

03:04:03.200 --> 03:04:04.800
I think, for us... I see so--

03:04:04.880 --> 03:04:07.920
I have invested, also,
in so many entrepreneurs who think big,

03:04:08.000 --> 03:04:11.960
and then they just see the market
just fall off a cliff.

03:04:12.040 --> 03:04:13.960
That universe becomes so limited.

03:04:14.040 --> 03:04:16.000
Additional customer acquisition
becomes so expensive.

03:04:16.080 --> 03:04:18.240
But do we fear
a lot of what we are discussing today

03:04:18.320 --> 03:04:20.120
is what Indian brands
can sell outside of India?

03:04:20.200 --> 03:04:22.600
-Fair. That's a very different story.
-Global brands.

03:04:22.680 --> 03:04:24.120
I think that's a fair point to add.

03:04:24.200 --> 03:04:25.920
I think that's how it should be.

03:04:26.000 --> 03:04:28.200
You know, we should inspire people

03:04:28.280 --> 03:04:31.720
to build brands not just for India,
but outside of it.

03:04:31.800 --> 03:04:33.600
Very Indian-in-nature brands.

03:04:33.680 --> 03:04:35.600
India has the ability to do it as well.

03:04:35.680 --> 03:04:38.280
We are the largest
motorcycle seller in Africa.

03:04:38.360 --> 03:04:42.120
Bajaj has beaten
Chinese motorcycle players.

03:04:42.200 --> 03:04:44.080
Scooters, three-wheelers, all of that.

03:04:44.160 --> 03:04:48.440
But that's because the really large
Western markets or Chinese markets

03:04:48.520 --> 03:04:50.120
are not two-wheeler heavy, right?

03:04:50.200 --> 03:04:51.600
[Shantanu] Yes.

03:04:51.680 --> 03:04:53.160
Also true.

03:04:53.240 --> 03:04:55.280
So, I think we have figured that out.

03:04:55.360 --> 03:04:58.600
I think, for example, indē wild,
huge opportunity in the US.

03:04:58.680 --> 03:05:00.280
-Huge.
-[Diipa] Absolutely.

03:05:00.360 --> 03:05:03.120
-With oils and, like...
-And GCC as well. UK as well.

03:05:03.200 --> 03:05:04.880
-Even for us.
-UK, we're already there, but...

03:05:04.960 --> 03:05:07.760
When we were told...
when we started, we were like,

03:05:07.840 --> 03:05:09.240
"I want to build a global brand
from India,

03:05:09.320 --> 03:05:11.160
it has to have global appeal..."

03:05:11.240 --> 03:05:13.000
So, one of my friends from Unilever,

03:05:13.080 --> 03:05:14.600
I told him, "Tell me some name options

03:05:14.680 --> 03:05:16.440
which is Indian in nature
and has global appeal."

03:05:16.520 --> 03:05:18.600
He did some research
and he came back after a few days

03:05:18.680 --> 03:05:20.600
and he was like, "You have four options.

03:05:20.680 --> 03:05:23.200
Himalaya, Taj, Gandhi, Bombay."

03:05:23.280 --> 03:05:25.360
These are the four words
which you can have...

03:05:25.440 --> 03:05:28.600
which are Indian in nature
and have global appeal.

03:05:28.680 --> 03:05:32.560
Himalaya and Taj were taken. Gandhi,
he said, will be political suicide.

03:05:32.640 --> 03:05:35.480
So, Bombay is what you have to do,
and then we built out Bombay.

03:05:35.560 --> 03:05:38.400
One of the first things
you want to build a global business.

03:05:38.480 --> 03:05:40.880
You know, indē wild, for example,
is something you came up with.

03:05:40.960 --> 03:05:43.600
-Yeah.
-But starting point was that.

03:05:43.680 --> 03:05:47.040
Are Tier 2s an opportunity?
I know Purplle is doing well there.

03:05:47.120 --> 03:05:48.600
-[Bhakti] Yes.
-Beyond metros?

03:05:48.680 --> 03:05:50.120
-I think it's there.
-[Bhakti] Huge.

03:05:50.200 --> 03:05:51.600
-Yeah.
-Huge.

03:05:51.680 --> 03:05:53.600
How does one hit that market?

03:05:53.680 --> 03:05:57.400
I think, for example,
I really think you should just kind of

03:05:57.480 --> 03:06:01.600
go with marketplaces
who are building out infrastructure.

03:06:01.680 --> 03:06:04.600
Do you find that Tier 2
is going to Purplle, not coming to Tira?

03:06:04.680 --> 03:06:06.720
No, Tier 2 is coming as well.

03:06:06.800 --> 03:06:10.840
I think it's about... as I said,
it is about premiumisation at every lever.

03:06:10.920 --> 03:06:12.880
We are-- We're really...

03:06:12.960 --> 03:06:18.200
I don't think that we are only speaking
to the metro audience.

03:06:19.120 --> 03:06:20.760
I think what we wanted to create

03:06:20.840 --> 03:06:25.200
is a platform
for the Indian consumer of today, right?

03:06:25.280 --> 03:06:27.160
And that consumer
is not just sitting in Tier 1,

03:06:27.240 --> 03:06:29.880
they are sitting in Tier 2 and Tier 3.

03:06:29.960 --> 03:06:34.920
In fact, there is at least 5x times
headroom to grow

03:06:35.000 --> 03:06:40.720
in terms of acquisition,
and even premiumisation, like...

03:06:40.800 --> 03:06:44.920
A huge amount of prestige sales
come from Tier 2 and Tier 3 cities.

03:06:45.000 --> 03:06:48.560
So, we should not assume
that those consumers are buying value.

03:06:48.640 --> 03:06:51.560
They have the ability, they have the...

03:06:53.040 --> 03:06:57.560
They also have the wallet share
to be able to spend on those things.

03:06:57.640 --> 03:07:02.920
So, there is huge amount
of untapped revenue acquisition

03:07:03.000 --> 03:07:04.800
in all in... all beyond metros.

03:07:04.880 --> 03:07:08.880
Because those consumers...
There is aspiration at every level.

03:07:08.960 --> 03:07:11.720
As I said, there's aspiration
and premiumisation at every level,

03:07:11.800 --> 03:07:14.120
and there's so much
untapped potential there.

03:07:14.200 --> 03:07:15.560
We should actually make the distinction

03:07:15.640 --> 03:07:17.960
between income India one,
India two, India three,

03:07:18.040 --> 03:07:20.080
and urban-rural India one,
India two, India three.

03:07:20.160 --> 03:07:21.760
So, Tier 2 India,

03:07:21.840 --> 03:07:24.400
if you, in fact, look at the top 5%
households in a Ludhiana

03:07:24.480 --> 03:07:26.120
or a Nashik or a Coimbatore,

03:07:26.200 --> 03:07:28.320
will probably have much
higher disposable income

03:07:28.400 --> 03:07:31.200
than the top 5% in a, let's say
Pune or an Ahmedabad.

03:07:31.280 --> 03:07:33.080
Because the cost of living
is so much lower,

03:07:33.160 --> 03:07:35.120
you end up saving
and you will want to have Tira.

03:07:35.200 --> 03:07:37.200
But I wanted to ask you,
are you thinking quick?

03:07:38.000 --> 03:07:41.120
Like, Blinkit is out in 200 cities
and they're, like, expanding.

03:07:41.200 --> 03:07:44.000
And in Tier 2, for example,
the good part about Tier 2 India

03:07:44.080 --> 03:07:47.120
is you need only two Blinkit stores
to serve the whole city.

03:07:47.200 --> 03:07:50.120
I know a friend who's starting
quick commerce specifically for beauty.

03:07:50.200 --> 03:07:54.160
-Quick commerce for X has now become...
-Quick commerce for fashion.

03:07:54.240 --> 03:07:55.440
Goodness! So much money.

03:07:55.520 --> 03:07:58.080
-Quick commerce for this.
-For food.

03:07:58.160 --> 03:08:00.280
-Fashion is crazy.
-Quick commerce for food?

03:08:00.360 --> 03:08:02.160
-Yeah, five minutes.
-But that's Zomato.

03:08:02.240 --> 03:08:05.760
No. Zomato has Bistro or café whatever.

03:08:05.840 --> 03:08:08.480
You know what the offering is?

03:08:08.560 --> 03:08:10.840
Two-minute cook time,
eight-minute delivery time.

03:08:10.920 --> 03:08:12.600
In two minutes, food is being made,
eight minutes...

03:08:12.680 --> 03:08:14.200
-Who is cooking?
-[Bhakti] Who is doing this cooking?

03:08:14.280 --> 03:08:16.600
-Some cloud kitchen with ready stuff.
-Yeah.

03:08:16.680 --> 03:08:18.840
So, couple of weeks ago,
I was interviewing Dara,

03:08:18.920 --> 03:08:21.080
the Uber CEO, in the US.

03:08:21.160 --> 03:08:23.440
He had a very interesting take on this.

03:08:23.520 --> 03:08:27.520
The American markets
skipped quick commerce

03:08:27.600 --> 03:08:29.440
because they had big box retail.

03:08:30.480 --> 03:08:37.040
And he said quick commerce can work
in very densely populated societies.

03:08:37.120 --> 03:08:41.480
But the distinction is,
how many people in that society

03:08:41.560 --> 03:08:44.400
are willing to pay...

03:08:44.480 --> 03:08:49.760
a dollar, two dollars, five dollars a day
in perpetuity

03:08:49.840 --> 03:08:52.080
because the labour arbitrage comes in.

03:08:53.160 --> 03:08:57.720
If this building
has 30 houses or 50 houses,

03:08:57.800 --> 03:09:00.800
and we all use quick commerce
a couple of times a day

03:09:00.880 --> 03:09:02.840
and we're spending
a few thousand rupees...

03:09:04.240 --> 03:09:08.520
At some point, it gets to the point
where people start thinking,

03:09:08.600 --> 03:09:12.720
"Okay, a few thousand rupees a day
is a few lakh rupees a month.

03:09:12.800 --> 03:09:16.560
Should we hire five boys who will not
only go and bring the grocery,

03:09:16.640 --> 03:09:18.600
but they'll also do errands at home?"

03:09:20.760 --> 03:09:26.440
It works in high...
high cost of labour societies somehow.

03:09:26.520 --> 03:09:28.000
In India, I don't know.

03:09:28.080 --> 03:09:29.440
I don't know what the TAM is.

03:09:29.520 --> 03:09:32.400
I don't think it's much more
than 50, 60 million people.

03:09:33.480 --> 03:09:35.600
-If with all the...
-That's a large TAM.

03:09:35.680 --> 03:09:37.320
-But not more.
-Five crore people are a large TAM.

03:09:37.400 --> 03:09:40.080
Well, these companies have
two lakh, three lakh crore market caps.

03:09:41.760 --> 03:09:44.040
So, TAM is reciprocal of that, right?

03:09:45.720 --> 03:09:47.880
I don't know. It's a tough question.
I've never bought.

03:09:47.960 --> 03:09:49.600
All of them are my friends,
but I've never bought.

03:09:49.680 --> 03:09:51.080
You've never bought from quick commerce?

03:09:51.160 --> 03:09:53.200
I've never invested
in a quick commerce company.

03:09:53.280 --> 03:09:55.200
-But you have ordered.
-Yeah, I have ordered.

03:09:55.280 --> 03:09:56.680
It's now becoming a feature.

03:09:56.760 --> 03:10:00.080
So, for example, Nykaa is now doing some
two-hour delivery in Bombay and Bangalore.

03:10:00.160 --> 03:10:03.280
For D2C brands, there are now companies
that do quick commerce.

03:10:03.360 --> 03:10:06.360
They will say, "Hey, for these PIN codes,
we'll deliver in six hours."

03:10:06.440 --> 03:10:08.080
You'll just... we'll have...

03:10:08.160 --> 03:10:10.080
But I'll tell you,
this is again labour arbitrage.

03:10:10.160 --> 03:10:14.720
Uber does this exact same thing
where their riders are not employees.

03:10:14.800 --> 03:10:16.240
They can't have unions.

03:10:16.320 --> 03:10:20.600
They don't get pensions and medical
and this, that, and the other.

03:10:22.880 --> 03:10:25.320
When seven, eight players
come into the foray

03:10:25.400 --> 03:10:28.840
and they start unionising
and they start asking for benefits,

03:10:28.920 --> 03:10:34.640
at some point,
that cost to convenience math...

03:10:34.720 --> 03:10:36.600
will get skewed and not for the better.

03:10:36.680 --> 03:10:39.080
But that's what happened
with Uber and Ola in India.

03:10:39.160 --> 03:10:42.200
-The market tapped out very quickly.
-Yeah.

03:10:42.280 --> 03:10:44.600
And then all that supply of cars
became problematic.

03:10:44.680 --> 03:10:48.600
Rapido is, like, the upcoming thing
from Bangalore.

03:10:48.680 --> 03:10:50.920
Bombay? I only use Rapido now.

03:10:51.000 --> 03:10:53.040
-Rapido?
-Only Rapido.

03:10:53.120 --> 03:10:55.040
Gurgaon, Bombay, Bangalore, only Rapido.

03:10:56.080 --> 03:10:59.080
Pradeep will kill me for saying this,
but Uber is too expensive.

03:10:59.160 --> 03:11:00.600
Who's Pradeep?

03:11:00.680 --> 03:11:02.680
Pradeep was Asia head for Uber,

03:11:02.760 --> 03:11:05.600
is now working in Dara's team,
I think, on their enterprise.

03:11:06.680 --> 03:11:08.080
He's one of my investors.

03:11:12.000 --> 03:11:13.640
Ayurveda.

03:11:13.720 --> 03:11:16.520
Ayurveda was a novelty a few years ago.

03:11:16.600 --> 03:11:17.600
Is it still?

03:11:19.600 --> 03:11:20.960
I don't think it's a novelty.

03:11:21.040 --> 03:11:22.800
I think, as she said, it's about...

03:11:23.680 --> 03:11:25.200
In the pre-actives era.

03:11:25.280 --> 03:11:27.080
Right now, it's all actives, right?

03:11:27.160 --> 03:11:30.080
Now, it's about how do you...
if you can take Ayurveda and...

03:11:30.160 --> 03:11:31.600
Hybrid.

03:11:31.680 --> 03:11:35.160
...and actives and put it together
and get the benefit.

03:11:35.240 --> 03:11:39.080
As you said, the natural, the holistic...

03:11:39.160 --> 03:11:42.360
So, in beauty,
there's always been two lanes.

03:11:42.440 --> 03:11:48.120
There's people who like clean,
which is all natural, herbal...

03:11:48.200 --> 03:11:52.120
And then, there's clinical,
which is the dermats, the actives.

03:11:52.200 --> 03:11:57.280
And I think there's a new trend or phase
that's coming up, where it's cleanical.

03:11:57.360 --> 03:12:00.360
So, it's the clean and the clinical,
AKA hybrid.

03:12:00.440 --> 03:12:04.080
And I think Ayurveda
is having that phase now.

03:12:04.160 --> 03:12:08.640
So, I think the brands like Kama, Forest,
that are pure Ayurveda, are there.

03:12:08.720 --> 03:12:11.720
But I think it's a different demographic
that they serve.

03:12:11.800 --> 03:12:15.120
And I think brands like indē wild,
which are cleanical,

03:12:15.200 --> 03:12:19.320
Ayurvedistry is the term we coined,
like Ayurveda meets chemistry.

03:12:20.160 --> 03:12:22.600
Is that how you would describe indē wild?

03:12:22.680 --> 03:12:26.240
Yeah, that's the main, I think, bucket,
is that we formulate

03:12:26.320 --> 03:12:28.480
and we kind of do everything
under Ayurvedistry,

03:12:28.560 --> 03:12:31.120
which even is that friction point
I was talking about earlier

03:12:31.200 --> 03:12:33.160
where the consumer is Ayurvedistry.

03:12:33.240 --> 03:12:35.720
You can have food that's Ayurvedistry,

03:12:35.800 --> 03:12:40.200
which basically just means fusion
of Ayurveda and the chemistry

03:12:40.280 --> 03:12:41.560
or the science-backed things.

03:12:42.720 --> 03:12:47.600
And I think that is easily acceptable
to the new consumer.

03:12:47.680 --> 03:12:50.600
-Did you just raise a round?
-Did, yeah.

03:12:50.680 --> 03:12:52.600
Who was the investor? Unilever?

03:12:52.680 --> 03:12:54.600
They led it, but we had two more.

03:12:54.680 --> 03:12:57.400
Ventures or, like, Unilever from--

03:12:57.480 --> 03:13:00.120
-No, no, no, Ventures.
-Ventures. In India?

03:13:00.200 --> 03:13:01.600
No, in the global office.

03:13:01.680 --> 03:13:04.600
-How large was the round?
-We raised five.

03:13:04.680 --> 03:13:06.480
-Million?
-Yeah.

03:13:06.560 --> 03:13:07.840
At, like, a...

03:13:08.680 --> 03:13:10.080
That...

03:13:11.160 --> 03:13:12.760
...4x, 5x.

03:13:15.160 --> 03:13:16.600
Ish, yeah.

03:13:16.680 --> 03:13:20.600
And you are selling eight to ten...
No, 12 million now.

03:13:20.680 --> 03:13:23.600
This year, we're gonna to hit 12
in net, yeah.

03:13:25.680 --> 03:13:28.120
The company really has grown a lot
in the last 12 months,

03:13:28.200 --> 03:13:32.280
thanks to...
India is just exploding for us.

03:13:33.080 --> 03:13:34.360
US is doing really well,

03:13:34.440 --> 03:13:37.400
but we are only on dotcom in the US
at this point.

03:13:37.480 --> 03:13:39.160
UK, we are dotcom and Sephora,

03:13:39.240 --> 03:13:42.440
but Sephora is tiny there,
it's seven stores.

03:13:42.520 --> 03:13:44.440
And India is just...

03:13:44.520 --> 03:13:48.600
It's the retail side,
it's our dotcom side, it's just really...

03:13:48.680 --> 03:13:50.600
How much is direct-to-customer?

03:13:53.400 --> 03:13:58.600
I'd say we still do 40% direct,
and 60% is between all our retailers,

03:13:59.520 --> 03:14:00.680
but changing.

03:14:00.760 --> 03:14:05.080
Retail is taking the pie, like,
every month more, yeah.

03:14:06.200 --> 03:14:07.200
Very interesting.

03:14:08.440 --> 03:14:10.120
Would you be open to someone coming in

03:14:10.200 --> 03:14:13.080
and getting equity in your company,
like, significant equity?

03:14:13.160 --> 03:14:16.080
-Do you mean you?
-Me or anyone watching this?

03:14:16.160 --> 03:14:18.720
I mean, right now,
I don't think we're fundraising,

03:14:18.800 --> 03:14:21.760
but I think we'll probably
do Series A next year.

03:14:21.840 --> 03:14:25.080
But right now, we're good. Yeah.

03:14:25.160 --> 03:14:27.600
But, yes, always come meet me,
have coffee.

03:14:27.680 --> 03:14:29.800
Always welcome for that.

03:14:29.880 --> 03:14:32.240
You know, sometimes, with these things,

03:14:32.320 --> 03:14:34.400
before you get into a marriage,
you need to court.

03:14:34.480 --> 03:14:37.080
So, we're always happy to have coffee.

03:14:37.160 --> 03:14:38.600
Yeah.

03:14:40.160 --> 03:14:41.280
Interesting.

03:14:42.920 --> 03:14:45.200
Your story after McKinsey,
we didn't get there.

03:14:45.920 --> 03:14:48.400
How did you get to here from there?

03:14:49.160 --> 03:14:52.480
I think I was a part
of the cohort of branding.

03:14:52.560 --> 03:14:54.960
There was a lot of infrastructural things
happening in India at that time, right?

03:14:55.040 --> 03:14:59.840
We had Jio and Airtel and Xiaomi
and iPhones and Samsung

03:14:59.920 --> 03:15:02.200
putting phones and Internet
in people's hands.

03:15:02.280 --> 03:15:05.080
But Amazon, Flipkart, Facebook, Google,

03:15:05.160 --> 03:15:09.360
giving us ability to market products
and store them.

03:15:10.160 --> 03:15:12.280
And we had a consumer base
that was truly changing

03:15:12.360 --> 03:15:16.200
because of Virat and Ranveer at that time
with beards and expression, right?

03:15:16.280 --> 03:15:20.600
So, masculine trends were
really taking off in terms of styling.

03:15:20.680 --> 03:15:23.360
And hair removal
was going from cheek-to-chin

03:15:23.440 --> 03:15:25.280
and ankle-to-thigh waxing,

03:15:25.360 --> 03:15:28.120
and cheek-to-chin shaving
to, like, whole body hair removal.

03:15:28.200 --> 03:15:31.120
So, there was infrastructure.
There was distribution.

03:15:31.200 --> 03:15:33.080
And then there was consumer
which was changing.

03:15:33.160 --> 03:15:35.960
So, for us, I think there
was a whole host of brands.

03:15:36.040 --> 03:15:39.280
So, boAt, Mamaearth, Plum,
Bombay Shaving Company,

03:15:39.360 --> 03:15:41.400
all of us was a part of that
ten years ago.

03:15:41.480 --> 03:15:44.360
We are now all 10, 12,
8-year-old businesses today.

03:15:44.440 --> 03:15:46.080
-Thank you so much.
-Thank you.

03:15:46.160 --> 03:15:48.600
This is, like, protein powder and yogurt.

03:15:49.680 --> 03:15:51.520
You're really spoiling us.
Everything has been so delicious.

03:15:51.600 --> 03:15:53.600
-It's really clean food.
-[Shantanu] Thank you so much.

03:15:53.680 --> 03:15:56.040
Pragati is cooking, and she's really good.

03:15:56.120 --> 03:15:59.560
-This has creatine, protein powder...
-[Diipa] Wow.

03:16:00.800 --> 03:16:02.680
...dark chocolate plus some nuts.

03:16:02.760 --> 03:16:04.600
Wow. You're really
in your longevity journey.

03:16:04.680 --> 03:16:07.080
-Trying.
-I like that.

03:16:07.160 --> 03:16:09.080
-Is there magnesium in it?
-No.

03:16:10.680 --> 03:16:12.520
So, we started as
a premium shaving business.

03:16:12.600 --> 03:16:14.480
We thought that we can build
a good shaving brand.

03:16:14.560 --> 03:16:17.080
It became very niche.
Went into men's grooming.

03:16:17.160 --> 03:16:18.400
And then, after COVID,

03:16:18.480 --> 03:16:20.440
we realised that hair removal
is a big place.

03:16:20.520 --> 03:16:21.720
We went into trimmers.

03:16:21.800 --> 03:16:23.800
We went into women with our brand Bombay.

03:16:24.520 --> 03:16:27.400
And today, we are now 500 crores net.

03:16:27.480 --> 03:16:29.600
Profitable. EBITDA and PAT both.

03:16:29.680 --> 03:16:31.080
I love that we speak in net. I like that.

03:16:31.160 --> 03:16:32.520
Yeah. Cash positive.

03:16:33.280 --> 03:16:35.840
Over the last 3-4 months,
cash balances are going up.

03:16:35.920 --> 03:16:37.600
Good investor base.

03:16:37.680 --> 03:16:41.680
And 170-180 people
with 99% of our business in India,

03:16:41.760 --> 03:16:43.120
which is something we want to change now.

03:16:43.200 --> 03:16:45.520
We do believe that there is
a brand pull that is significant

03:16:45.600 --> 03:16:48.200
outside the country for us,
especially amongst Indian consumers.

03:16:50.080 --> 03:16:51.960
So, we are very focused that...

03:16:52.040 --> 03:16:55.720
if we are in the universe
which removes hair off your body,

03:16:55.800 --> 03:16:58.400
in that ten minutes
when you go into the bathroom,

03:16:58.480 --> 03:17:01.040
brush your teeth, take a shave,
use the loo, take a shower,

03:17:01.120 --> 03:17:03.200
come out, put on a fragrance,
after-shave, and leave,

03:17:03.280 --> 03:17:06.640
in that 10-15 minutes,
we want to be a big part of your life.

03:17:07.600 --> 03:17:09.960
And that's the brand.
And that's what we do.

03:17:10.040 --> 03:17:12.040
It's very simple.
We don't do rocket science.

03:17:12.120 --> 03:17:13.840
We are an unremarkable company that way.

03:17:13.920 --> 03:17:15.480
But we do the small thing very well.

03:17:16.680 --> 03:17:19.080
But it's crazy scale.
So, it's super impressive.

03:17:19.160 --> 03:17:20.880
Yeah.

03:17:20.960 --> 03:17:23.280
To give you a sense, in COVID, 2021...

03:17:23.360 --> 03:17:25.880
So, we will do more EBITDA this year
than the revenue in 2021.

03:17:26.680 --> 03:17:28.240
-Wow.
-Congratulations.

03:17:28.320 --> 03:17:31.960
Yeah. So, that's the five-year journey.

03:17:32.040 --> 03:17:34.240
First five years
was struggle and discovery.

03:17:34.320 --> 03:17:36.000
Next five years have been good scale.

03:17:36.080 --> 03:17:37.480
But still, 500 crores is nothing.

03:17:37.560 --> 03:17:39.640
Like, I don't think
it's a large-scale business yet.

03:17:39.720 --> 03:17:41.080
Gillette is 2,500 crores.

03:17:41.160 --> 03:17:43.600
Philips trimmers is 1,000 crores.

03:17:43.680 --> 03:17:46.760
But can you take a second
and believe that you've built it,

03:17:46.840 --> 03:17:48.360
like, from ground-up?

03:17:48.440 --> 03:17:50.080
-So, I think that is something...
-It's very nice.

03:17:50.160 --> 03:17:51.600
Yeah, that's commendable.

03:17:51.680 --> 03:17:53.080
No, no, for sure. I think...

03:17:53.160 --> 03:17:55.080
-And a sustainable...
-Yeah.

03:17:55.160 --> 03:17:57.600
...you know, profitable business
is what...

03:17:57.680 --> 03:17:59.080
-Everybody wants.
-Yeah.

03:17:59.160 --> 03:18:01.200
No, no, I'm very proud
of what the team has done.

03:18:01.280 --> 03:18:03.080
I think the brand is very good.

03:18:03.160 --> 03:18:05.760
I genuinely feel like
we are a brand that...

03:18:05.840 --> 03:18:07.200
People will think that we are premium

03:18:07.280 --> 03:18:08.800
when they see our logo
or when they see our product.

03:18:08.880 --> 03:18:11.000
But when they see the price,
they'll go, "This is pretty cheap."

03:18:11.080 --> 03:18:13.880
Like, you know, you'll get, like,
a 20-rupee razor.

03:18:13.960 --> 03:18:17.960
So, our brand goes from one-rupee blades
to 7,000-rupee trimmers.

03:18:18.040 --> 03:18:20.680
-The width is pretty large.
-One-rupee blades?

03:18:20.760 --> 03:18:22.200
Yeah, we sell the one-rupee blades,

03:18:22.280 --> 03:18:23.560
which you sharpen your pencil with
in school.

03:18:23.640 --> 03:18:25.280
-Wow.
-Yeah. It's called Sharpmaxx.

03:18:25.360 --> 03:18:26.840
Bombay Shaving Company, Sharpmaxx.

03:18:26.920 --> 03:18:29.600
Pack of ten, 100 rupees--
Like, pack of 100, 100 rupees.

03:18:30.560 --> 03:18:32.600
Yeah, which barbers use, and so on.

03:18:32.680 --> 03:18:34.600
And who's your average customer?

03:18:34.680 --> 03:18:38.920
So, we've realised over a period of time,
for men, we've realised that...

03:18:39.000 --> 03:18:41.080
We started with older consumers.

03:18:41.160 --> 03:18:44.200
But we realised that we're taking
sharp metal to your face.

03:18:44.280 --> 03:18:45.880
So, if you've used Gillette
for a long time,

03:18:45.960 --> 03:18:47.560
it's unlikely you're going to change.

03:18:48.320 --> 03:18:50.720
So, men are hard to engage,
easy to please.

03:18:50.800 --> 03:18:52.440
Women are easy to engage, hard to please.

03:18:53.560 --> 03:18:55.600
The fundamental difference in consumption.

03:18:55.680 --> 03:18:58.080
-So, we realised...
-All of life is like that.

03:18:58.160 --> 03:18:59.680
-It's too difficult...
-[Bhakti] I'm stealing that.

03:18:59.760 --> 03:19:02.720
Yeah. It's too difficult
to, like, you know...

03:19:02.800 --> 03:19:04.320
But women are easy to engage,

03:19:04.400 --> 03:19:06.040
but then the product
has to be really good.

03:19:06.120 --> 03:19:07.720
But men, you put a good shaving foam,

03:19:07.800 --> 03:19:10.000
does the job, they're happy,
they keep repeating, right?

03:19:10.080 --> 03:19:13.040
So, then we realised
the idea is actually to get in early.

03:19:13.120 --> 03:19:14.920
So, when you're going to shave,
shave for the first time,

03:19:15.000 --> 03:19:16.280
or you're going to trim,

03:19:16.360 --> 03:19:19.000
you're 15 years old,
you have a small moustache,

03:19:19.080 --> 03:19:20.800
sideburns, you want to take it off.

03:19:20.880 --> 03:19:22.240
Like, that's when...

03:19:22.320 --> 03:19:25.440
So, our brand has become a lot younger
for 16, 17-year-old.

03:19:25.520 --> 03:19:27.080
How do you find them?

03:19:28.160 --> 03:19:29.640
So, we do a lot.

03:19:29.720 --> 03:19:32.000
So, Instagram and social
for young consumers.

03:19:32.080 --> 03:19:33.920
We do a lot of college activations.

03:19:34.000 --> 03:19:37.440
Like, very Red Bull approach to, like--

03:19:37.520 --> 03:19:39.600
We run the barber shop for young people.

03:19:39.680 --> 03:19:41.080
-Very young DG.
-Very.

03:19:41.880 --> 03:19:45.000
First time you shave...
So, the first product a man would buy

03:19:45.080 --> 03:19:46.840
in our age group, or all of our age group

03:19:46.920 --> 03:19:49.080
would probably be
a 25-rupee razor at the age of 18.

03:19:49.160 --> 03:19:51.080
-How old are all of us?
-I'm 37.

03:19:51.160 --> 03:19:53.080
-34.
-35.

03:19:53.160 --> 03:19:55.320
38. The oldest.

03:19:55.400 --> 03:19:57.400
So, in all of our age groups, we would...

03:19:57.480 --> 03:20:01.320
the first product a man would buy would be
a 25-rupee razor at the age of 18.

03:20:01.400 --> 03:20:04.760
But the first product a boy is buying
is a 500-rupee trimmer at the age of 14.

03:20:05.480 --> 03:20:07.640
And Gillette is not in trimmers.

03:20:07.720 --> 03:20:10.600
So, we have a four-year runway
before they can get into Bombay.

03:20:10.680 --> 03:20:12.760
So, we have 15% market share
in trimmers, all India.

03:20:12.840 --> 03:20:14.320
We sell 7,000 trimmers a day.

03:20:14.400 --> 03:20:16.120
7,000 trimmers a day, all India.

03:20:16.200 --> 03:20:17.360
-That's amazing.
-Yeah.

03:20:17.440 --> 03:20:19.000
At a 1,000-rupee price point.

03:20:19.080 --> 03:20:21.600
That's why the... like, the price point
becomes so important for me.

03:20:21.680 --> 03:20:23.560
Like, you know, if I can premiumise.

03:20:23.640 --> 03:20:26.080
So, the idea is, "You come with me."

03:20:26.160 --> 03:20:27.200
When you buy your first razor,

03:20:27.280 --> 03:20:29.440
at least you'll use a trimmer
for some four years,

03:20:29.520 --> 03:20:30.680
you'll choose Bombay Shaving Company.

03:20:30.760 --> 03:20:34.240
But if you're 25, 27, 28,
you've used Gillette for ten years,

03:20:34.320 --> 03:20:35.720
you're used to it,
there's no way you're changing.

03:20:35.800 --> 03:20:38.000
There's no way. It's too good a product.

03:20:38.080 --> 03:20:39.080
Gillette's too good.

03:20:41.520 --> 03:20:43.080
Mm-hmm.

03:20:43.160 --> 03:20:44.600
-So, that's the idea.
-[Diipa] Thank you.

03:20:44.680 --> 03:20:46.160
-I've got chocolate all over me.
-Yeah.

03:20:48.320 --> 03:20:49.680
-Sorry.
-Yeah.

03:20:49.760 --> 03:20:50.920
-[Diipa] Oh, sorry.
-There you go.

03:20:51.000 --> 03:20:52.080
Thank you.

03:20:52.160 --> 03:20:55.560
You guys are serving us
the wrong food for a podcast.

03:20:55.640 --> 03:20:57.080
-[Shantanu] Yeah.
-It's yum, though, right?

03:20:57.160 --> 03:20:59.600
-Yeah, but noodles and chocolate...
-Me and Diipa are...

03:20:59.680 --> 03:21:02.080
It's like slurping the noodle up.

03:21:03.080 --> 03:21:04.080
But, yeah.

03:21:04.840 --> 03:21:06.600
And we are still, like--

03:21:07.240 --> 03:21:10.080
We did the whole GT thing, by the way.
We went into offline stores.

03:21:12.680 --> 03:21:14.680
Boss, you need to really
be prepared for this stuff.

03:21:14.760 --> 03:21:16.840
And we have Colgate-Palmolive
and Reckitt Benckiser,

03:21:16.920 --> 03:21:21.080
two successful global offline businesses
as investors, who taught us how to do it.

03:21:21.160 --> 03:21:23.720
-Wow. Good.
-But until the brand pull is there,

03:21:23.800 --> 03:21:26.200
assortment sharpness is there,
and pricing is right,

03:21:26.280 --> 03:21:28.920
anyone watching this,
general trade, just be super careful.

03:21:29.000 --> 03:21:32.640
Start in a small city
around a dark store that's doing well.

03:21:32.720 --> 03:21:34.520
Try that in one or two neighbourhoods.

03:21:34.600 --> 03:21:37.600
Then only you can take a look there.
But, yeah. That's where we are.

03:21:38.960 --> 03:21:40.760
Okay. Last part of today.

03:21:43.480 --> 03:21:44.760
We need step two.

03:21:44.840 --> 03:21:46.880
Now, Dilip has figured
out his fragrance brand.

03:21:46.960 --> 03:21:48.560
Back to Dilip.

03:21:50.440 --> 03:21:51.880
-That story was not really...
-I think we should...

03:21:51.960 --> 03:21:53.680
Four of us should create
this fragrance brand.

03:21:53.760 --> 03:21:55.360
[Diipa] Oh, my God. It would be so good.

03:21:55.440 --> 03:21:57.040
-Yeah. It would be fun.
-[Shantanu] Yeah.

03:21:58.920 --> 03:22:01.920
Okay. Dilip Fragrance or Diipa's...

03:22:02.600 --> 03:22:07.440
I don't know.
Keepa has started a new kind of hair oil.

03:22:07.520 --> 03:22:09.640
Or somebody started a marketplace.

03:22:09.720 --> 03:22:12.360
Or some new men's grooming product
has started.

03:22:13.840 --> 03:22:15.240
What do they do next?

03:22:16.760 --> 03:22:17.800
The idea is here.

03:22:17.880 --> 03:22:20.480
I know what to make. How do I make it?

03:22:23.200 --> 03:22:25.840
Who do I go to? Co-packer?

03:22:25.920 --> 03:22:28.360
How do I sort out manufacturing?

03:22:28.440 --> 03:22:30.680
It's just the idea phase. Just the idea.

03:22:30.760 --> 03:22:32.280
Idea phase, we have crossed now, okay?

03:22:32.360 --> 03:22:33.880
Where is Dilip's idea?

03:22:33.960 --> 03:22:35.360
-It's on paper.
-Yeah.

03:22:35.440 --> 03:22:36.680
25 years old.

03:22:38.120 --> 03:22:41.960
He's going to promote it as,
"Not about the bottle."

03:22:42.040 --> 03:22:43.680
The name of the company is Temple.

03:22:44.800 --> 03:22:48.880
He's going to try and get
fragheads community going.

03:22:48.960 --> 03:22:51.880
Think of flavours like
Old Spice plus agarbatti.

03:22:52.880 --> 03:22:55.160
Vanilla plus some camphor,
temple, something.

03:22:56.080 --> 03:22:57.760
-Stuff like that.
-Solid.

03:22:57.840 --> 03:23:00.360
-So, he's gotten that far.
-Okay.

03:23:00.440 --> 03:23:03.800
And now, he needs to go out
and manufacture the product.

03:23:03.880 --> 03:23:05.080
Where does he go?

03:23:06.480 --> 03:23:07.760
Trade shows.

03:23:07.840 --> 03:23:10.280
Like, there's a huge one in Italy

03:23:10.360 --> 03:23:13.760
that happens every year
in Bologna called Cosmoprof.

03:23:13.840 --> 03:23:15.760
There's also Cosmoprof in India now.

03:23:17.040 --> 03:23:18.720
Every country has their own.

03:23:18.800 --> 03:23:21.840
Like, these manufacturer hubs,
they come from all over the world.

03:23:21.920 --> 03:23:23.800
And you can go there,
walk around for two, three days,

03:23:23.880 --> 03:23:26.360
talk to every manufacturer
about everything.

03:23:26.440 --> 03:23:29.360
And you'll also meet packaging...

03:23:29.440 --> 03:23:30.880
Packaging experts.

03:23:30.960 --> 03:23:33.080
You'll meet contract manufacturers

03:23:33.160 --> 03:23:35.520
who will be like,
"Okay, this is your idea.

03:23:35.600 --> 03:23:37.640
We'll do everything for you end-to-end."

03:23:37.720 --> 03:23:39.520
Sometimes, they even get into branding.

03:23:39.600 --> 03:23:41.280
So they'll be like,
"We'll brand it for you.

03:23:41.360 --> 03:23:44.880
Tell us your idea.
We'll do end-to-end for you."

03:23:45.520 --> 03:23:51.800
And they will touch me if I have,
say, demand for a hundred pieces.

03:23:51.880 --> 03:23:53.360
Few, not all.

03:23:53.440 --> 03:23:57.040
I think few manufacturers
will have a low, like, MOQs.

03:23:57.120 --> 03:23:59.600
So, then you can be, like,
"Only a thousand, I want."

03:23:59.680 --> 03:24:02.480
Or they'll be like,
"No, our minimum is 10,000."

03:24:02.560 --> 03:24:06.880
But for a thousand,
they'll do it more expensive per unit.

03:24:06.960 --> 03:24:09.400
And generally, like, if you're doing...

03:24:09.480 --> 03:24:11.920
There's open moulds and custom moulds.

03:24:12.000 --> 03:24:14.400
So, if you're doing smaller quantities,

03:24:14.480 --> 03:24:17.080
it's very expensive
to make a custom mould.

03:24:17.160 --> 03:24:18.800
So, you want a particular shape.

03:24:18.880 --> 03:24:20.880
So, generally, a lot of young...

03:24:20.960 --> 03:24:23.240
And we discussed,
is that it's not about the bottle anymore.

03:24:23.320 --> 03:24:26.240
So, how do you kind of...
a lot of brands use generic bottles.

03:24:26.320 --> 03:24:29.640
Even, like, bigger brands,
because it is expensive

03:24:29.720 --> 03:24:33.680
and you can't get a huge amount of MOQs,

03:24:33.760 --> 03:24:35.760
you know, say 10,000 or 20,000

03:24:35.840 --> 03:24:38.240
for that one SKU
and then change the mould.

03:24:38.320 --> 03:24:41.560
So, generically,
all of this advice you will get

03:24:41.640 --> 03:24:44.880
from your contract manufacturer
and packaging.

03:24:44.960 --> 03:24:46.960
The good part about India
is because all the contract manufacturing

03:24:47.040 --> 03:24:48.360
is written on the back of the pack.

03:24:48.440 --> 03:24:50.360
-Yeah.
-That's crazy, guys.

03:24:50.440 --> 03:24:52.320
-You know who's who.
-I find that so crazy.

03:24:52.400 --> 03:24:54.240
You'll know every manufacturer
within, like, a day.

03:24:54.320 --> 03:24:55.440
[Bhakti] Yeah, a day.

03:24:55.520 --> 03:24:56.920
And then you can just go
and talk to them because...

03:24:57.000 --> 03:24:59.880
And I think with fragrances, particularly,
I think MOQs are, like, really low.

03:24:59.960 --> 03:25:02.320
That's a really crazy hack
that you're giving everyone.

03:25:02.400 --> 03:25:05.880
But it's insane. You can literally
find out people's manufacturers.

03:25:05.960 --> 03:25:07.360
-You know exactly...
-Actually, that's easy.

03:25:07.440 --> 03:25:09.280
If I like a good product,
I can just call them.

03:25:09.360 --> 03:25:10.360
Yeah.

03:25:10.440 --> 03:25:12.760
Write a sharp brief
and get an 80% answer within a week.

03:25:12.840 --> 03:25:15.720
They should have NDAs
and, like, contracts in place

03:25:15.800 --> 03:25:17.880
that they don't give the formula away.

03:25:17.960 --> 03:25:20.720
-They'll tweak it a little bit.
-Yeah.

03:25:20.800 --> 03:25:23.760
Is there something like
patenting my perfume?

03:25:23.840 --> 03:25:24.880
No.

03:25:25.800 --> 03:25:28.920
Not patent in perfume,
unless, like, the odour technology,

03:25:29.000 --> 03:25:32.040
whatever we're talking about,
that you could probably patent.

03:25:32.120 --> 03:25:36.400
But just purely the notes,
no, you can't patent that.

03:25:36.480 --> 03:25:37.880
-Because there's...
-You can keep it a secret.

03:25:37.960 --> 03:25:39.080
...so many dupes.

03:25:39.160 --> 03:25:41.400
The dupe market
is a whole different market.

03:25:41.480 --> 03:25:42.880
-Yeah.
-[Shantanu] It's insane.

03:25:42.960 --> 03:25:44.080
-Yeah.
-[Diipa] Insane.

03:25:44.160 --> 03:25:45.600
And people are like, people use dupes

03:25:45.680 --> 03:25:48.000
and they say that they use dupes
because they wanna look smart.

03:25:48.080 --> 03:25:50.880
No, and there's a whole community
about telling you which is the best dupe.

03:25:50.960 --> 03:25:53.880
By dupe, you don't mean
like a Chanel is called Chanel.

03:25:53.960 --> 03:25:55.440
-No, it's duplicate.
-No, no.

03:25:55.520 --> 03:25:57.880
It's a Bella Vita.
He says, "This is Chanel No. 5."

03:25:57.960 --> 03:26:00.160
-Yeah.
-It has these two.

03:26:00.240 --> 03:26:02.040
And you can even tell
the manufacturer that,

03:26:02.120 --> 03:26:04.880
"I want to create this,
make it 60% closer to this."

03:26:04.960 --> 03:26:08.200
It's very easy to make anything
that is water or gas-based.

03:26:08.280 --> 03:26:11.240
-Broadly.
-And as you said, everything is inspired.

03:26:11.320 --> 03:26:14.520
So, something has been
inspired from someone.

03:26:14.600 --> 03:26:18.400
So, it's all circular.

03:26:18.480 --> 03:26:21.320
What you can also do is, like,
benchmark a fragrance you like,

03:26:21.400 --> 03:26:24.080
be like, "Make it like this,
but give me more oud

03:26:24.160 --> 03:26:28.760
or give me more woody,
or give me more spice or something."

03:26:28.840 --> 03:26:32.160
And then the manufacturer can, like,
at least use it as a baseline.

03:26:32.240 --> 03:26:35.880
So you're not full copy-copying,
but it's a bit...

03:26:35.960 --> 03:26:40.240
But that's the reason
innovation is so rare in our industry.

03:26:40.320 --> 03:26:45.000
And that's why, you know,
companies like L'Oréal, Estée Lauder,

03:26:45.080 --> 03:26:46.440
they win and they have products

03:26:46.520 --> 03:26:49.000
whose formulations don't change
over 15 to 20 years.

03:26:49.080 --> 03:26:53.160
Because there's hard-coded time and energy

03:26:53.240 --> 03:26:56.400
spent on research and development,
innovation and technology

03:26:56.480 --> 03:27:00.520
that comes together to kind of create
a product that surpasses it.

03:27:00.600 --> 03:27:03.600
Whatever you do,
you will not be able to create that.

03:27:03.680 --> 03:27:06.680
And I think, that,
you can't take that away.

03:27:06.760 --> 03:27:10.240
So, I think when you want
to create something clutter-breaking,

03:27:10.320 --> 03:27:12.880
it's either a great storytelling

03:27:12.960 --> 03:27:15.600
or, you know, an idea like Minimalist,

03:27:15.680 --> 03:27:19.880
or solid product that is innovation-led.

03:27:19.960 --> 03:27:22.040
L'Oréal is so good at innovation,

03:27:22.120 --> 03:27:24.200
-like, out of this world.
-Yeah?

03:27:24.280 --> 03:27:27.040
But they also keep buying over,
like, biotech companies

03:27:27.120 --> 03:27:30.120
and stuff to constantly keep that
innovation wheelhouse going.

03:27:30.200 --> 03:27:32.640
But that's why brands
that are smaller, like us,

03:27:32.720 --> 03:27:37.240
we need to go find that innovation
in a Korea, in a Japan,

03:27:37.320 --> 03:27:39.840
and then take our Indian ingredients
and mix it

03:27:39.920 --> 03:27:44.120
to bring that proprietary kind of
something to the formula, you know?

03:27:44.200 --> 03:27:48.320
That either makes the delivery
of the niacinamide deeper into your skin

03:27:48.400 --> 03:27:52.240
with things like exosomes and stuff
that, like, deliver the ingredient better.

03:27:52.320 --> 03:27:53.800
So you're like,
"Yes, it's still niacinamide,

03:27:53.880 --> 03:27:56.520
but our serum is gonna
deliver it to you stronger."

03:27:56.600 --> 03:28:01.040
Or you do it based on ingredients
or you do it based on the texture itself.

03:28:01.120 --> 03:28:05.080
Like, it's the most unique
sunscreen texture you've ever felt.

03:28:05.160 --> 03:28:07.280
Because in the humidity,
it just melts in your skin.

03:28:07.360 --> 03:28:09.560
So, there's something that I think,

03:28:09.640 --> 03:28:11.280
as a brand, you have to give your customer

03:28:11.360 --> 03:28:15.040
that's then different than
every other kind of cookie-cutter.

03:28:15.120 --> 03:28:19.720
The greatest story in this world
was actually Darshan bhai in 2010-11

03:28:19.800 --> 03:28:21.800
when he said that,
"My perfume lasts longer.

03:28:21.880 --> 03:28:23.720
We don't need this
whole aerosol technology.

03:28:23.800 --> 03:28:26.800
Just put water and gas, give it in a can,
and we call it deodorant."

03:28:26.880 --> 03:28:28.880
And Fogg is a 1,000-crore business

03:28:28.960 --> 03:28:31.360
built off of great marketing
and a product that lasts long.

03:28:31.440 --> 03:28:33.040
-[Diipa] What's he talking about?
-Fogg. F-O-G-G.

03:28:33.120 --> 03:28:35.560
-The deodorant brand.
-Fogg. Oh, yeah.

03:28:35.640 --> 03:28:38.080
Axe was 40% market share,

03:28:38.160 --> 03:28:40.760
Fogg came in, within four years,
and they're at 25% market share.

03:28:40.840 --> 03:28:44.640
HUL brand is losing market share
quarter on quarter on quarter.

03:28:44.720 --> 03:28:46.720
Insane. She's right.

03:28:46.800 --> 03:28:49.560
-One thing, be known for it.
-[Bhakti] Yes, hero product.

03:28:49.640 --> 03:28:55.040
And the same applies
for my Nikhil's skincare

03:28:55.120 --> 03:28:59.560
morning-night supplement business?
Trade shows?

03:28:59.640 --> 03:29:01.560
I think trade shows
is a great start for you

03:29:01.640 --> 03:29:04.440
to be able to meet, see everyone.

03:29:04.520 --> 03:29:06.080
-Brands, manufacturers.
-Build a network.

03:29:06.160 --> 03:29:07.880
-Build a network.
-Which is the next trade show?

03:29:07.960 --> 03:29:09.040
Maybe we'll throw it up.

03:29:09.120 --> 03:29:10.600
-Where, in India?
-Yeah.

03:29:10.680 --> 03:29:12.360
I think India is only
Cosmoprof that happens.

03:29:12.440 --> 03:29:14.080
Yeah. There's Cosmoprof
that happens in India,

03:29:14.160 --> 03:29:16.760
but there's Cosmoprof
that happens in Vegas.

03:29:16.840 --> 03:29:19.200
There's Cosmoprof that happens in Italy.

03:29:19.280 --> 03:29:22.040
-Those are the biggest ones.
-US, Korea and stuff have many.

03:29:22.120 --> 03:29:25.040
Go to Canton also.
Canton is a great place to go.

03:29:25.120 --> 03:29:26.680
-Canton?
-In China.

03:29:26.760 --> 03:29:28.160
-Oh, huh? For packaging?
-Yeah.

03:29:28.240 --> 03:29:29.680
No, in general. For everything.

03:29:29.760 --> 03:29:31.960
Build trimmers, packaging, manufacturers.

03:29:32.040 --> 03:29:33.480
-Merch.
-Yeah.

03:29:33.560 --> 03:29:35.560
Everything.
Canton is, like, the world's...

03:29:35.640 --> 03:29:37.560
Even Korea has, through the year,

03:29:37.640 --> 03:29:39.280
they have many conventions
and trade festivals.

03:29:39.360 --> 03:29:42.000
And it's a great start,
particularly if you don't have it.

03:29:42.080 --> 03:29:43.760
If you don't know anyone in the industry,

03:29:43.840 --> 03:29:46.040
it's great to go build
that contact network.

03:29:46.120 --> 03:29:47.560
-It is fine, yeah.
-Yeah, and also,

03:29:47.640 --> 03:29:50.280
there'll be smaller manufacturers
who you'll want to work with,

03:29:50.360 --> 03:29:53.960
who'll, you know,
be able to suit to your scale

03:29:54.040 --> 03:29:56.080
and help you innovate and take that time.

03:29:56.160 --> 03:29:59.480
And then move to, once you've got it,
"Okay, this is what I'm going to do."

03:29:59.560 --> 03:30:01.800
Indeed, as a small brand,
it's going to be a lot harder

03:30:01.880 --> 03:30:05.120
to go to a really big manufacturer
that builds for the biggest brands,

03:30:05.200 --> 03:30:08.240
because they're like,
"Sorry, but no, you don't have scale."

03:30:08.320 --> 03:30:12.040
But one that's starting up themselves,
then I think that would be a good fit.

03:30:12.120 --> 03:30:13.560
Yeah.

03:30:13.640 --> 03:30:17.400
Okay, last word, guys.
Any advice to somebody starting tomorrow?

03:30:20.640 --> 03:30:25.640
I think mine would be, definitely,
identify your white space.

03:30:25.720 --> 03:30:27.520
Have a hero product strategy.

03:30:27.600 --> 03:30:31.600
And really, I think there's this thing
about, like, perfection, right?

03:30:31.680 --> 03:30:34.640
You want to get everything right.
I think keep...

03:30:34.720 --> 03:30:37.320
keep building that momentum
and getting out there.

03:30:37.400 --> 03:30:40.920
It's not about beauty.
It's just about really keep on going.

03:30:41.000 --> 03:30:43.480
And it's about progress, not perfection.

03:30:43.560 --> 03:30:44.920
So, I think that is something
that really...

03:30:45.000 --> 03:30:47.600
I keep telling myself that,
"Okay, what's the next move?"

03:30:47.680 --> 03:30:48.840
So, be agile.

03:30:48.920 --> 03:30:51.880
And that'll really help you,
because you can adapt.

03:30:51.960 --> 03:30:55.640
So I think, for me,
that's what I would tell anyone

03:30:55.720 --> 03:30:57.360
that, yeah, in beauty,

03:30:57.440 --> 03:31:01.320
definitely white space, storytelling,
and hero product

03:31:01.400 --> 03:31:03.560
are three things, and community too,

03:31:03.640 --> 03:31:05.520
to kind of build your brand.

03:31:05.600 --> 03:31:08.640
And we'll put out Bhakti's email
so people can reach out.

03:31:08.720 --> 03:31:11.480
People find me on LinkedIn and email me.

03:31:11.560 --> 03:31:14.400
So, that, I think, is already happening.

03:31:14.480 --> 03:31:16.160
But you might get a great funnel
of good ideas.

03:31:16.240 --> 03:31:17.240
Absolutely.

03:31:20.240 --> 03:31:23.000
Mine would be...

03:31:23.080 --> 03:31:25.480
remember your why.

03:31:25.560 --> 03:31:28.760
I think, through tough times
and good times, that'll keep you going.

03:31:28.840 --> 03:31:31.240
And as a brand,
especially when you're building...

03:31:31.320 --> 03:31:34.640
-Yeah, it's a good point.
-...it's very much for the community

03:31:34.720 --> 03:31:36.960
and for it to mean something.

03:31:37.040 --> 03:31:40.520
And then, secondly,
I would say build a winning team.

03:31:41.240 --> 03:31:43.720
I think you, as one person,
can do so much.

03:31:43.800 --> 03:31:45.720
But having an incredible team around you.

03:31:45.800 --> 03:31:47.080
-Marry them.
-Yeah.

03:31:47.160 --> 03:31:48.360
-Marry them.
-Yeah.

03:31:48.440 --> 03:31:51.720
Yes. That helps. That's a big one.
Marry them.

03:31:51.800 --> 03:31:53.240
It can't be easy
to work with your husband.

03:31:54.040 --> 03:31:57.360
I know people say that,
but we're one of those crazy couples

03:31:57.440 --> 03:32:00.560
that is-- Bhakti's witnessed it live,

03:32:00.640 --> 03:32:03.240
but we're so happy to be
with each other all the time.

03:32:03.320 --> 03:32:06.680
That even if we...
like, are away for 24 hours,

03:32:06.760 --> 03:32:09.240
we're like, "Oh, I miss you."

03:32:09.320 --> 03:32:13.200
But, I think, from a business perspective,
we have very complementary skill sets.

03:32:13.280 --> 03:32:15.400
He was an ex-diplomat,

03:32:15.480 --> 03:32:20.840
and he's really a kind of
people's collaborative leader.

03:32:20.920 --> 03:32:24.200
And I'm much more, like,
the solo vision kind of leader.

03:32:24.280 --> 03:32:26.120
And I'm much more
marketing and storytelling.

03:32:26.200 --> 03:32:28.360
And it's all in here,
I need to bring it out.

03:32:28.440 --> 03:32:31.760
And he's so much more about, you know,
and it's just really complementary.

03:32:31.840 --> 03:32:34.000
I think, without him,
indē wild wouldn't exist.

03:32:35.080 --> 03:32:36.720
So, yeah, very grateful to work with him.

03:32:36.800 --> 03:32:41.280
But also the team that we built together
is so important.

03:32:41.360 --> 03:32:43.520
-Where is the team based?
-In Bombay.

03:32:43.600 --> 03:32:45.560
Our HQ is Lower Parel.

03:32:45.640 --> 03:32:46.760
-Lovely.
-Come by.

03:32:46.840 --> 03:32:48.280
I would love to. Would love to.

03:32:51.360 --> 03:32:52.920
I think...

03:32:54.560 --> 03:32:59.440
For me, I think the most important thing
for entrepreneurs... is that...

03:32:59.520 --> 03:33:03.520
this will be a decades-long gig.

03:33:03.600 --> 03:33:06.280
It's not going to be a small one.
You've experienced it yourself.

03:33:06.880 --> 03:33:09.320
And if you look at... Mukesh
had actually told me this from Myntra.

03:33:09.400 --> 03:33:11.120
He said very interesting things.

03:33:11.200 --> 03:33:13.280
Look at companies that have
lasted 20 years.

03:33:13.360 --> 03:33:15.760
You'll see 93% of their market value

03:33:15.840 --> 03:33:18.600
is created in the second decade,
only 7% in the first.

03:33:18.680 --> 03:33:20.960
See companies that have lasted
three decades,

03:33:21.040 --> 03:33:23.000
almost 80% is in the third decade,

03:33:23.080 --> 03:33:26.240
15% or 17% in the second,
and only 3% or 4% in the first.

03:33:26.320 --> 03:33:29.960
So, in today's world
of instant gratification...

03:33:30.040 --> 03:33:31.760
Do that many companies
last three decades anymore?

03:33:31.840 --> 03:33:34.080
Amazon. He was giving me
examples of Amazon and Meta,

03:33:34.160 --> 03:33:35.960
and, in India, I think, like...

03:33:36.040 --> 03:33:38.280
Is Meta three decades old already?

03:33:38.960 --> 03:33:41.760
No, Google is three decades.
Meta is probably two decades.

03:33:41.840 --> 03:33:44.080
I think a lot of companies
die in, like, 8-10 years.

03:33:44.840 --> 03:33:49.280
Yeah. But the thing is,
in a world of instant gratification

03:33:49.360 --> 03:33:52.680
and wanting to tell the story
of your startup

03:33:52.760 --> 03:33:54.600
before the startup is even there,

03:33:54.680 --> 03:33:56.240
because we are building communities

03:33:56.320 --> 03:33:57.800
and we are on Instagram
and we want our friends

03:33:57.880 --> 03:33:59.280
to know we are entrepreneurs
and blah, blah, blah.

03:33:59.360 --> 03:34:02.640
At the first sign of failure,
I'm noticing this with, like,

03:34:02.720 --> 03:34:05.080
a cohort of companies
we invested in '21-'22.

03:34:05.160 --> 03:34:06.360
And suddenly, founders are like,

03:34:06.440 --> 03:34:08.200
"It's been three years,
and nothing is happening.

03:34:08.280 --> 03:34:11.000
It's a ten-lakh-month business.
What do we do?"

03:34:11.080 --> 03:34:12.600
Not worth it.

03:34:12.680 --> 03:34:15.200
Shantanu, grit.

03:34:15.280 --> 03:34:18.400
Yeah. So, I think patience
and knowing that this is...

03:34:18.480 --> 03:34:19.560
[Diipa] It is very important.

03:34:19.640 --> 03:34:22.560
There's opportunity cost and there is
a very long zone of frustration

03:34:22.640 --> 03:34:25.920
for most good companies,
even the most successful ones.

03:34:26.480 --> 03:34:27.800
So, just go through it.

03:34:28.360 --> 03:34:30.440
But don't become a zombie company
where you're doing something

03:34:30.520 --> 03:34:32.720
which is totally not worth it,
and there just because you're surviving.

03:34:32.800 --> 03:34:33.800
So, don't do that.

03:34:33.880 --> 03:34:36.240
But going in,
know that this will take 20 years

03:34:36.320 --> 03:34:39.480
at the very least to see the first signs
of something meaningful.

03:34:39.560 --> 03:34:42.040
Fund life cycle, that,
Prashanth is here, he'll know.

03:34:42.120 --> 03:34:45.000
Everyone promises eight-year life cycle.
It's 13-14 years.

03:34:45.080 --> 03:34:48.760
India is a country where you need
15-20 years to find something meaningful.

03:34:48.840 --> 03:34:50.760
-We run all perpetual funds.
-Huh?

03:34:50.840 --> 03:34:53.320
We run all perpetual funds.

03:34:53.400 --> 03:34:54.760
-No fund life.
-Yeah.

03:34:54.840 --> 03:34:58.760
What's your takeaway from
spending three hours with us on beauty?

03:34:58.840 --> 03:35:01.280
-Four hours.
-Four hours?

03:35:01.360 --> 03:35:02.760
Wow.

03:35:03.560 --> 03:35:08.360
A, if there is a Dilip listening,
that idea is yours, you can have it.

03:35:08.440 --> 03:35:09.760
On the fragrance.

03:35:09.840 --> 03:35:12.760
-Before-- Unless we do it first.
-Unless they do it first.

03:35:14.360 --> 03:35:15.920
But...

03:35:18.600 --> 03:35:25.040
I think, tomorrow,
we will care a lot more for how we look

03:35:25.120 --> 03:35:27.040
as a means of getting validation.

03:35:28.600 --> 03:35:31.640
So, anything that aids that
will likely grow,

03:35:31.720 --> 03:35:34.720
both in the mass and the premium segment.

03:35:34.800 --> 03:35:38.240
I think the affluent
will probably adapt faster.

03:35:38.320 --> 03:35:41.640
So, the premium will go
significantly faster than mass.

03:35:42.480 --> 03:35:45.160
So, it feels like a good category
to be in.

03:35:45.240 --> 03:35:48.160
And as an investor,

03:35:48.240 --> 03:35:52.560
strangely enough, there aren't enough
listed Indian players

03:35:52.640 --> 03:35:55.760
which allow you allocation
into this category.

03:35:55.840 --> 03:35:59.000
So, lots of room and potential
for someone to build here.

03:36:01.000 --> 03:36:03.160
Beauty, for example,
so many new companies.

03:36:03.240 --> 03:36:07.840
I see Foxtale and d'you
and Deconstruct and Pilgrim, indē wild,

03:36:07.920 --> 03:36:09.760
large-scale businesses now.

03:36:09.840 --> 03:36:12.760
Look at Minimalist.
They were, like, 3-4 years old.

03:36:12.840 --> 03:36:14.760
-Yeah. I think 4-5.
-Yeah.

03:36:14.840 --> 03:36:16.640
-Wild.
-Crazy.

03:36:16.720 --> 03:36:18.280
Very well done.

03:36:19.120 --> 03:36:20.760
Done. Thank you, guys.

03:36:20.840 --> 03:36:22.360
-Thank you so much.
-Thank you so much.

03:36:22.440 --> 03:36:23.800
So nice to meet both of you as well.

03:36:23.880 --> 03:36:25.920
Four hours went, like, 30 minutes.

03:36:26.000 --> 03:36:28.760
-Yeah.
-Went by super fast.

03:36:28.840 --> 03:36:30.760
When you're having fun
and eating yummy food.

03:36:30.840 --> 03:36:32.280
-Thank you so much.
-Thank you for bringing us together.

03:36:32.360 --> 03:36:33.480
Yeah.

